UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'The Black Forest, in German the Schwarzwald, is the most recognisable landscape of Baden-Württemberg, an upland of dark spruce and silver fir that stretches from the Swiss border near Basel north past Freudenstadt and Baden-Baden to the Murg and Enz valleys and the gates of Pforzheim. Its forested heights are interrupted by glacial cirque lakes such as the Mummelsee, the Titisee, the Schluchsee and the Feldsee, by waterfalls like the Triberg Wasserfälle (the highest cascade in Germany at one hundred and sixty-three metres over seven steps), and by deep narrow valleys including the Kinzig, Murg, Wutach, Höllental, Glottertal and Albtal. The summit of the Feldberg at one thousand four hundred and ninety-three metres is the highest peak of the state and offers winter skiing on the Seebuck and the Grafenmatt, summer hiking on the Westweg long-distance trail, and panoramic views to the Vosges and the Bernese Alps. The Hornisgrinde, Belchen, Schauinsland, Kandel, Hochfirst, Köhlgartenwiese and Herzogenhorn are other classic Schwarzwald summits ringed by cuckoo-clock workshops, cattle pastures and timbered farmhouses with low hipped roofs of the Schauinslandhof and Vogtsbauernhof type. The Vogtsbauernhof open-air museum at Gutach im Schwarzwald preserves historic farmsteads transplanted from Hotzenwald, Kinzigtal, Markgräflerland and the central Black Forest. Black Forest dress, the Bollenhut with its red or black wool pompoms worn over white linen by the women of Gutach, Kirnbach and Reichenbach, has become an emblem of the region, alongside the cuckoo clock from Triberg, Schonach and Furtwangen, whose Deutsches Uhrenmuseum traces three centuries of horological craft from the rooster clocks of Friedrich Eisenlohr through the chalet clocks of Johann Baptist Beha to the precision wristwatches of Glashütte and Pforzheim. Triberg, Schramberg, Furtwangen and Hornberg are clock-making capitals; Schramberg also hosts the Junghans museum at the Stiftung Erbe Junghans, where Bauhaus designer Max Bill''s clocks are exhibited. The Westweg, opened in 1900 by the Schwarzwaldverein, is the oldest waymarked long-distance trail in Europe and runs from Pforzheim to Basel through almost three hundred kilometres of forest. The Schluchtensteig, the Querweg Freiburg-Bodensee and the Mittelweg complete the long-distance network.

Lake Constance, the Bodensee, defines the southern border of Baden-Württemberg with Bavaria, Austria and Switzerland. Konstanz, the largest town on the lake, contains a Romanesque Minster, the Council House where Pope Martin V was elected in 1417 to end the Western Schism, and the harbour with its slowly rotating Imperia statue by Peter Lenk. The island of Mainau, owned by the Bernadotte family from Sweden, is a sub-tropical flower park with palm avenues, orchid houses, a butterfly hall and Italianate gardens around an eighteenth-century Teutonic Order palace. The island of Reichenau, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, holds the Carolingian and Ottonian churches of St. George at Oberzell, St. Peter and Paul at Niederzell, and the abbey church of St. Mary and Mark at Mittelzell, all founded by Benedictine monks who produced the famed Reichenau illuminated manuscripts. The lake-shore towns of Meersburg with its Altes Schloss and Neues Schloss, Überlingen with its Münster St. Nikolaus, Friedrichshafen with the Zeppelin Museum and Dornier Museum, Hagnau, Sipplingen, Bodman and Ludwigshafen am Bodensee all draw cruise traffic from the white fleet. The Pfahlbauten pile dwellings at Unteruhldingen, a UNESCO World Heritage prehistoric site, reconstruct Bronze Age lakeside villages, while the Wallfahrtskirche Birnau, a baroque pilgrimage church above the lake, the Marienschlucht gorge and the Affenberg Salem complete the lake-front itinerary. Salem Castle, formerly a Cistercian monastery, and the medieval town of Salem, the noble boarding school Schule Schloss Salem founded by Kurt Hahn and Prince Max von Baden, lie in the immediate hinterland.

Heidelberg is the romantic essence of the Neckar valley, with the ruined sandstone Heidelberg Castle towering above the Altstadt. The castle complex contains the Friedrichsbau Renaissance facade with statues of the Wittelsbach electors, the Ottheinrichsbau, the Englischer Bau, the Great Heidelberg Tun (a wine cask holding two hundred and twenty thousand litres), the German Apothecary Museum and the Königstuhl funicular. Below, the Alte Brücke crosses the Neckar to the Philosophenweg, the Philosophers'' Walk where Hegel, Schelling, Hölderlin and Max Weber once strolled. Heidelberg University, founded in 1386, is the oldest in Germany and one of the oldest north of the Alps; the Studentenkarzer student prison, the Marstall and the Alte Aula still serve academic life. The Heiliggeistkirche on the marketplace, the Jesuitenkirche, the Karl-Theodor-Brücke and the Kurpfälzisches Museum complete the cultural offer. Mark Twain, Goethe and Schumann all left their mark on the town''s literary identity, and the annual Schlossbeleuchtung fireworks recall the destruction of the castle by French troops in 1693 during the Nine Years'' War. The Königstuhl, the Thingstätte (an open-air amphitheatre on the Heiligenberg), the Bismarckturm and the Bergfriedhof cemetery with the graves of Friedrich Ebert and Robert Bunsen extend the visit.

Stuttgart, the state capital, lies in a basin ringed by vineyards and forested hills. The Schlossplatz forms the heart of the city, with the Neues Schloss, the Altes Schloss, the Stiftskirche, the Königsbau and the Kunstmuseum, a glass cube housing the Otto Dix collection. Nearby the Staatsgalerie Stuttgart by James Stirling holds Picassos, Beckmanns and a Swabian medieval collection, while the Linden-Museum of ethnology and the Landesmuseum Württemberg in the Altes Schloss show regional history. Across the Stadtgarten lies the Württembergische Landesbibliothek and the Stuttgart State Opera with its world-famous Stuttgart Ballet under the legacy of John Cranko and Marcia Haydée. The Solitude Palace, the Rosenstein Palace and the Wilhelma zoological-botanical garden in Bad Cannstatt, the largest combined zoo-botanical garden in Europe, are favourite outings, alongside the Killesberg park, the Grabkapelle on the Württemberg Hill above the family vineyards, and the dignified Schillerplatz with its monument to Friedrich Schiller. The Mercedes-Benz Museum at Untertürkheim, designed by UNStudio in a double-helix spiral, and the Porsche Museum at Zuffenhausen by Delugan Meissl are pilgrimage sites for automotive enthusiasts, exhibiting the Patent-Motorwagen of Karl Benz, the 300SL Gullwing, the Silberpfeil grand-prix cars, the Porsche 356, the 911 series and the Carrera GT. The Stuttgart Fernsehturm, the world''s first reinforced-concrete television tower opened in 1956 by Fritz Leonhardt, the Markthalle Stuttgart art nouveau market hall, and the Cannstatter Wasen festival on the Wasen meadow, often called the Swabian Oktoberfest, complete the city.

Beyond these centres, Baden-Württemberg offers Schwetzingen Palace with its rococo gardens, mosque and theatre; Bruchsal Palace; Ludwigsburg Residential Palace, the largest baroque palace in Germany still in its original condition, with the Blühendes Barock garden; the Hohenlohe palaces of Weikersheim, Bad Mergentheim seat of the Teutonic Order, Schloss Langenburg, Schloss Neuenstein and Jagsthausen of Götz von Berlichingen fame; Hohenzollern Castle on its dramatic crag near Hechingen, ancestral seat of the Prussian royal house; Lichtenstein Castle, the fairy-tale castle inspired by Wilhelm Hauff''s novel; Sigmaringen Castle on the Upper Danube; the romantic ruins of Burg Hohenstaufen and the Hohenstaufen heritage at Lorch monastery and Bad Wimpfen Imperial Palace. Maulbronn Monastery, the most complete Cistercian monastic complex north of the Alps, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site; so are Reichenau, the Pfahlbauten pile dwellings, the upper Germanic-Raetian Limes (passing through Aalen with the Limesmuseum, Welzheim, Lorch and Osterburken), and the prehistoric Caves and Ice Age Art of the Swabian Jura, where the Venus of Hohle Fels, the Löwenmensch of Hohlenstein-Stadel and the earliest known figurative art were excavated. The Cathedral of Speyer faces the BW bank of the Rhine.

Ulm Minster, with the world''s tallest church spire at one hundred and sixty-one and a half metres, dominates the Danube. Its Last Judgment portal, the choir stalls by Jörg Syrlin the Elder, and seven hundred and sixty-eight steps to the viewing platform reward the climber with a view to the Alps. The Fischerviertel fishermen''s quarter, the Schiefes Haus leaning house, the Stadthaus by Richard Meier and the Einstein-Brunnen memorial mark the city of Albert Einstein''s birth. Tübingen, home of Eberhard Karls University founded in 1477, charms with its Neckarfront, the famous Stocherkahn punts on the river, the Hölderlinturm where the poet spent the last thirty-six years of his life, the Stiftskirche St. Georg with the tombs of the Württemberg dukes, and the Schloss Hohentübingen with its archaeological museum. Freiburg im Breisgau, gateway to the southern Black Forest, is famous for its Gothic Münster with the only church tower in Germany completed in the Middle Ages, the Bächle running channels along the streets, the Augustinerplatz and the sustainable Vauban and Rieselfeld quarters. Karlsruhe, planned in 1715 by Margrave Karl Wilhelm around the fan-shaped layout radiating from the palace, contains the ZKM Center for Art and Media in the former munitions factory, the Federal Constitutional Court, the Bundesgerichtshof and the Botanischer Garten. Pforzheim is the city of gold and jewellery, with the Schmuckmuseum.

Baden-Baden, the elegant spa town, has welcomed European nobility for centuries. The Friedrichsbad, a Roman-Irish bathhouse opened in 1877, the modern Caracalla Therme, the Kurhaus with its casino once frequented by Dostoyevsky as he composed The Gambler, the Festspielhaus (Germany''s largest opera and concert hall by capacity), the Trinkhalle drinking hall with frescoes by Jakob Götzenberger, the Lichtentaler Allee park, the Stiftskirche, the Kloster Lichtenthal Cistercian convent and the Frieder Burda Museum next to the Staatliche Kunsthalle give a sense of belle époque grandeur. Other thermal towns include Bad Wildbad with its Sommerberg cable car, Bad Mergentheim, Bad Krozingen, Bad Liebenzell, Bad Buchau on the Federsee, Bad Herrenalb and Bad Säckingen on the Hochrhein.

The history of the territory is rich. The Duchy of Württemberg under the Counts and Dukes from Stuttgart and Württemberg Castle; the Margraviate of Baden and the Grand Duchy of Baden from Karlsruhe; the Hohenzollern principalities of Hechingen and Sigmaringen, ancestral home of the Prussian royal family who would later rule the German Empire; the Imperial Free Cities of Esslingen, Heilbronn, Reutlingen, Schwäbisch Hall with its salt mines, Schwäbisch Gmünd, Heilbronn and Ulm; the Swabian League of Cities; the Peasant War of 1525 that ravaged Weinsberg and Stühlingen and was suppressed at the Battle of Böblingen; the Thirty Years'' War devastation including the Sack of Heidelberg in 1622; the Palatinate Succession War under Louis the Fourteenth which burned Heidelberg, Mannheim and Speyer in 1693; the Napoleonic reorganisation that elevated Württemberg and Baden to kingdom and grand duchy in 1806; the 1848 revolution in Baden led by Friedrich Hecker and Gustav Struve from Konstanz; the foundation of the German Empire in 1871 in which both states participated; the Weimar-era Werkbund Weissenhof estate of 1927 with houses by Le Corbusier, Mies van der Rohe, Walter Gropius, Hans Scharoun and Peter Behrens; and the Hohenzollern abdication. After 1945 the territories south of the Stuttgart-Karlsruhe Autobahn lay in the French zone (South Baden and Württemberg-Hohenzollern from Tübingen), the north in the American zone (Württemberg-Baden from Stuttgart), and in 1952 a referendum merged the three into the present Land Baden-Württemberg, the only German state founded by popular vote. Famous figures associated with the land include Friedrich Schiller from Marbach, Friedrich Hölderlin from Lauffen, Hermann Hesse from Calw, Wilhelm Hauff, Eduard Mörike, Theodor Heuss the first Federal President from Brackenheim, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel from Stuttgart, Albert Einstein from Ulm, Karl Drais of Karlsruhe inventor of the bicycle, Carl Benz of Karlsruhe and Mannheim inventor of the automobile, Robert Bosch from Albeck near Ulm, and Gottlieb Daimler from Schorndorf.

The cuisine of Baden-Württemberg blends Swabian and Badisch traditions. Maultaschen, the so-called Herrgottsbescheißerle (literally meaning Lord-deceivers) supposedly invented by the monks of Maulbronn to conceal meat inside dough during Lent, are large stuffed pasta squares with veal, smoked sausage, spinach and onion, served in beef broth or browned with onions and a fried egg. Spätzle, the soft egg noodles scraped from a board into boiling water with a Spätzlebrett or pressed through a Spätzlepresse, accompany roasts and form the basis of Kässpätzle (with Allgäu cheese and crisp onions) and Linsen mit Spätzle und Saiten (lentils with Spätzle and slim Frankfurter-style sausages, the Saiten meaning strings). Zwiebelrostbraten is a rump steak topped with crisp fried onions and served with Spätzle; Saure Kutteln, sour tripe, persists as a regional speciality. The Schwarzwälder Schinken, smoked over fir branches in Black Forest huts, and the Bauernbrot bread from wood-fired ovens, are exported across Europe. Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte, the Black Forest gâteau, layers chocolate sponge, kirsch-soaked Morello cherries and whipped cream beneath chocolate shavings. Flammkuchen, the thin Alsatian-style flatbread with crème fraîche, onion and lardons, is common in the Baden territory. Brägele (fried potatoes), Bubespitzle (finger-shaped potato dumplings), Dampfnudeln steamed yeast dumplings, Ofenschlupfer bread-and-apple pudding, Spundekäs, Schneckensuppe snail soup of Pfullingen, the Bibliskäs cottage cheese, the Maultaschenpfanne and the Gaisburger Marsch beef stew round out the home kitchen. Spargel asparagus from Schwetzingen, Bruchsal and the Filderkraut white cabbage from the Filder plateau near Stuttgart are protected geographic products.

The state is one of Germany''s principal wine regions. Baden, the warmest German wine area along the Rhine valley facing Alsace, produces Spätburgunder Pinot Noir, Grauburgunder Pinot Gris, Weißburgunder Pinot Blanc, Müller-Thurgau, Riesling and Gutedel Chasselas, with Kaiserstuhl, Markgräflerland, Ortenau, Tuniberg, Tauberfranken and Bodensee being the key Bereiche. Württemberg specialises in Trollinger its signature light red, Lemberger Blaufränkisch, Schwarzriesling Pinot Meunier, Riesling and Kerner, and is unusual for a German region in producing more red than white. The cooperatives of Lauffen, Heuchelberg, the WG Markgräflerland and the Badischer Winzerkeller and estates such as Aldinger, Wöhrwag, Salwey, Bercher, Dr. Heger, Bernhard Huber, Schnaitmann and Karl H. Johner are well known. Black Forest distillers produce Kirschwasser, Williamsbirne, Mirabellenbrand, Zwetschgenwasser and Himbeergeist. Beer brands include Rothaus Tannenzäpfle from the state-owned brewery in the high Black Forest, Stuttgarter Hofbräu, Dinkelacker, Schwaben Bräu, Fürstenberg from Donaueschingen, Alpirsbacher Klosterbräu, Berg Brauerei of Ehingen, Härle and Waldhaus. The Pforzheim Schmuckmuseum and goldsmithing, the Ravensburger toy and Spielwarenfabrik, the Steiff teddy bears of Giengen, and the Märklin model railways of Göppingen complete the artisanal map. Festivals of note include the Stuttgarter Weindorf, the Heilbronner Weindorf, the Stuttgarter Frühlingsfest, the Esslinger Weihnachtsmarkt and Mittelaltermarkt, the Mannheimer Maimarkt, the Fasnet (Swabian-Alemannic Carnival) of Rottweil with its Narrensprung procession, the Lindauer Bregenzer and Konstanzer fasnachten, the Tübinger Stocherkahnrennen punt races, the Heidelberger Schlossbeleuchtung, the Bregenzer Festspiele audience overflow into Lindau and Friedrichshafen, and the Festival of Old Music at Maulbronn.',
    transportation = 'The transport network of Baden-Württemberg is anchored by Stuttgart Airport, IATA code STR and ICAO code EDDS, located at Leinfelden-Echterdingen on the Filder plateau. Stuttgart Airport is Germany''s seventh-busiest commercial airport, handling around twelve million passengers a year in normal traffic and rising. Eurowings, Lufthansa, Lufthansa Cityline, TUI fly, easyJet, SunExpress, Pegasus, Turkish Airlines, Condor, Croatia Airlines, Aegean Airlines and a wide range of Mediterranean and Levantine leisure carriers operate from its three terminals. The airport sits beside the Messe Stuttgart trade fair complex, host of the AMI Auto Mobil International, the CMT Caravan-Motor-Touristik, the Retro Classics, the Bondexpo and the Intergastra trade shows, and is linked to Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof by S-Bahn lines S2 and S3 in around twenty-seven minutes. The under-construction Stuttgart 21 tunnel and the new Wendlingen-Ulm high-speed line will provide direct ICE access to the airport from the planned opening of the Filderbahnhof. Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden Airport, code FKB, at Söllingen on a former Canadian Forces base in the Rhine plain, is the second-largest airport in the state, focused on Ryanair leisure flights to the Mediterranean and to Berlin Brandenburg and Hamburg. Friedrichshafen Airport, FDH, on the Bodensee is the third regional airport, with Lufthansa Cityline, Sun-Air and seasonal carriers to Hamburg, Berlin, Mallorca and Antalya, with strong traffic to the trade shows at Messe Friedrichshafen including AERO Friedrichshafen, OutDoor and Eurobike. Mannheim City Airport, MHG, at Neuostheim serves business aviation and regional turboprops to Berlin, Hamburg and Sylt via Rhein-Neckar Air. General aviation airfields cover the state densely: Lahr (a former Canadian air force base now used for cargo and the aviation industry), Mengen-Hohentengen, Sinsheim, Aalen-Heidenheim, Schwäbisch Hall on the Hessental airfield host to the Würth corporate fleet, Hahnweide near Kirchheim unter Teck a glider stronghold, Donaueschingen, Schwenningen and the historic Zeppelinheim sites continue to serve light aviation and gliding.

The rail network is dense and dominated by Deutsche Bahn through its DB Fernverkehr, DB Regio and DB Cargo divisions, with the regional brands AVG (Albtal-Verkehrs-Gesellschaft), SWEG (Südwestdeutsche Landesverkehrs-AG), HzL (Hohenzollerische Landesbahn) and Bodensee-Oberschwaben-Bahn carrying commuters, and Go-Ahead, Abellio (later renamed SWEG Bahn Stuttgart) and DB Regio Württemberg holding contracts. Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof, a terminus station famed for the Paul Bonatz and Friedrich Eugen Scholer station building of 1928 with its iconic Mercedes star atop the tower, is the focal point of the controversial Stuttgart 21 project. Stuttgart 21 converts the through-tracks of the surface terminus into a sixty-metre-deep through-station with eight underground platforms turned ninety degrees, accommodates the new Wendlingen-Ulm high-speed line on the Schwäbische Alb, frees twenty hectares of city-centre land for the Rosensteinviertel new district, and links via the Filderbahnhof to the airport. The line via the Albvorlandtunnel, Steinbühltunnel and Albabstiegstunnel cut ICE travel between Stuttgart and Ulm to under thirty minutes when it opened in December 2022, although the central S21 underground station''s commissioning has been delayed to 2026. Mannheim Hauptbahnhof, in the north of the state, is one of the busiest railway junctions in Germany, at the meeting of the Rhine valley line (Karlsruhe-Frankfurt), the Mannheim-Saarbrücken line, the Mannheim-Stuttgart high-speed line opened 1991 (the first NBS in Germany), and the Riedbahn to Frankfurt now closed for major reconstruction. Karlsruhe Hauptbahnhof is the southern terminus of the same Mannheim-Stuttgart corridor and the gateway to the Schwarzwaldbahn. Other principal Hauptbahnhöfe include Heidelberg, Heilbronn, Tübingen, Reutlingen, Ulm, Friedrichshafen Stadt, Konstanz, Singen, Freiburg im Breisgau, Offenburg, Pforzheim, Aalen, Schwäbisch Hall-Hessental, Crailsheim, Bruchsal and Bad Krozingen.

The ICE network in Baden-Württemberg includes the long-running Frankfurt-Mannheim-Stuttgart-Munich axis (ICE 11, ICE 42, ICE 47), the Hamburg-Hannover-Frankfurt-Karlsruhe-Basel route (ICE 12, ICE 20 to Zurich, ICE 23 to Bern via the NBS Karlsruhe-Basel), the Mannheim-Saarbrücken-Paris-Strasbourg services of TGV inOui and ICE, and seasonal trains to Vienna, Innsbruck, Amsterdam and Bruxelles-Midi. The Karlsruhe-Basel four-track upgrade, the Ausbau- und Neubaustrecke Karlsruhe-Basel, is the largest active rail project in BW, with new bypass tunnels at Offenburg, Rastatt (site of the 2017 tunnel collapse that closed the Rheintalbahn for seven weeks) and at the southern Markgräflerland. Intercity-Express services serve Friedrichshafen, Lindau, Konstanz and Singen via the Gäubahn from Stuttgart and the Bodensee-Oberschwaben-Bahn. The Black Forest Railway (Schwarzwaldbahn), opened in 1873 by engineer Robert Gerwig, climbs from Offenburg to Singen via Triberg through thirty-nine tunnels and includes the famous Sommerau and Triberg double loops, while the Höllentalbahn from Freiburg to Donaueschingen via the Hirschsprung gorge, the Ravennaviadukt at Hinterzarten and the former rack-and-pinion section between Hirschsprung and Hinterzarten remain tourist favourites. Other scenic lines include the Donautalbahn along the Upper Danube from Tuttlingen to Sigmaringen and Ulm, the Sauschwänzlebahn between Blumberg-Zollhaus and Weizen with its spiral tunnels, the Kraichgaubahn from Karlsruhe to Heilbronn, the Murgtalbahn from Rastatt to Freudenstadt, the Wieslauftalbahn from Schorndorf to Rudersberg, the Schwäbische Albbahn from Engstingen to Schelklingen via the Kornbühl, the Albtäler Bahn and the Wutachtalbahn.

Urban rail is well developed. The Karlsruhe model of tram-train operation, pioneered by AVG Albtal-Verkehrs-Gesellschaft and KVV Karlsruher Verkehrsverbund in the 1990s, runs vehicles directly from city streets onto the heavy-rail network, an arrangement copied worldwide and adopted by Saarbrücken, Kassel, Mulhouse, Manchester, Sheffield, the Hague and Aarhus. Stuttgart''s Stadtbahn, a converted tramway with both surface and tunnel running, includes lines U1 through U19 with the central Hauptbahnhof, Charlottenplatz, Schlossplatz and Staatsgalerie nodes; the city is also served by the S-Bahn Stuttgart, six radial lines (S1, S2, S3, S4, S5, S6 plus the seasonal S60 to Renningen and S62 Marbach), all running through the central Stammstrecke tunnel from Hauptbahnhof tief to Schwabstraße. The Heilbronn Stadtbahn extends AVG tram-trains to Heilbronn via the Kraichgaubahn through Bretten. Mannheim, Ludwigshafen and Heidelberg share the cross-border RNV (Rhein-Neckar-Verkehr) tram and Stadtbahn network spanning Baden-Württemberg, Rheinland-Pfalz and Hessen, with the OEG ring line connecting Mannheim and Heidelberg via Weinheim and the Käfertal hinterland. Freiburg, Ulm and Heidelberg also operate substantial tram networks; Freiburg''s VAG runs five lines, Ulm''s SWU two lines extended into Söflingen and Böfingen, and the Heidelberg Bergbahn funicular up to Königstuhl is one of the oldest in Germany. Reutlingen plans a return of trams. The Verkehrsverbünde VVS Stuttgart, VRN Rhein-Neckar, KVV Karlsruhe, BODO Bodensee-Oberschwaben, RVF Freiburg, NALDO Neckar-Alb-Donau, OstalbMobil, hohenlohemobil, HNV Heilbronner Hohenloher Haller Nahverkehr, VVR Reutlingen, FILS, VPE Enzkreis-Pforzheim, TGO Ortenau and DING Donau-Iller provide integrated tariff zones across the state, supported by the bwtarif state-wide flat fare and the JugendticketBW for school children.

The motorway network, the Autobahn, gives the state high road connectivity. The A5 Bergisch-Frankfurt-Karlsruhe-Basel runs the length of the Rhine valley to the Swiss border at Weil am Rhein; the A6 Mannheim-Heilbronn-Nuremberg-Waidhaus crosses the state east-west through the Kraichgau; the A7 traverses Württemberg from Würzburg through Heilbronn, Aalen, Ulm to Memmingen and the Allgäu; the A8 from Karlsruhe-Stuttgart-Ulm-Munich-Salzburg passes the Albabstieg at Drackenstein and Aichelberg; the A81 connects Stuttgart, Heilbronn, Mosbach and Würzburg in the north and Stuttgart-Tübingen-Singen southwards via the Hegau; the A98 Hochrhein, the A831, the A861, the A864 to Donaueschingen and the A865 spurs complete the system. The Bundesstraßen B27, B14, B10, B30, B33 and B500 (the Schwarzwaldhochstraße ridge road) are scenic main roads.

Mannheim is a major Rhine inland port, the largest in Germany by tonnage, handling chemicals, cars, containers and bulk for BASF, Roche, the Daimler Mannheim engine plant and the Rhine-Neckar industrial belt; Karlsruhe with its Rheinhafen and Kehl opposite Strasbourg are also significant Rhine ports. The Bodensee shipping is run by Bodensee-Schiffsbetriebe (BSB), Schweizerische Schifffahrt Untersee und Rhein (URh), Schweizerische Bodensee Schifffahrt (SBS) and Vorarlberg Lines, with the year-round car ferry Konstanz-Meersburg running every fifteen minutes, the catamaran Friedrichshafen-Konstanz running summer schedules at thirty-knot speeds, and the Friedrichshafen-Romanshorn car ferry crossing to Switzerland. Other notable transport infrastructure includes the Stadtbahn Heilbronn, the Donau-Schiffahrt cruises from Ulm and Donaueschingen on the river, the Rhine-Main-Danube link via Bavaria, the Esslinger Personenfähre on the Neckar and the long-distance cycling routes such as the Bodensee-Königssee-Radweg, the Donauradweg from Donaueschingen, the Schwarzwald-Panorama-Radweg, the Neckartal-Radweg, the Kocher-Jagst-Radweg, EuroVelo 6, EuroVelo 15 (the Rhine Cycle Route from Andermatt to Rotterdam) and the Tauberradweg.

Long-distance buses are concentrated at the Stuttgart ZOB beside the airport, the Mannheim ZOB and the Karlsruhe ZOB; FlixBus is the dominant operator with daily departures to Berlin, Paris, Prague and Amsterdam. Car-sharing operators include Share Now, Stadtmobil, Flinkster and Miles. Electromobility is supported by the EnBW HyperHub fast-charging network deployed along the A5 and A6 corridors, with hundreds of high-power chargers at Bruchsal, Bretten and Forchheim. Cycling infrastructure has been expanded under RadNETZ Baden-Württemberg; the Stuttgart Region has the RegioRad Stuttgart bike-share scheme, while Mannheim, Karlsruhe and Heidelberg are nextbike cities. Carl Benz, born in Karlsruhe and a Mannheim resident, conducted the first long-distance automobile journey from Mannheim to Pforzheim in 1888; the Bertha Benz Memorial Route now traces that pioneering drive in marked stages. The Reichsautobahn-era stretches near Stuttgart-Heilbronn and the A8 west of Stuttgart, the Tauberbrücke at Lauda-Königshofen and the four-track Karlsruhe-Basel railway corridor are heritage and modernisation focal points of contemporary investment.',
    economics = 'Baden-Württemberg is the third-largest German state by population and one of its strongest industrial economies, with a gross domestic product of roughly five hundred billion euros, an export ratio above fifty per cent, and a small-and-medium business sector that has produced more so-called hidden champions than any other German Land. The state slogan, devised by the state marketing agency, is "Wir können alles. Außer Hochdeutsch" - we can do anything, except standard German. The motor and machine-tool industries dominate, surrounded by an ecosystem of suppliers, engineering bureaus and research institutes.

Mercedes-Benz Group AG, the former Daimler AG, has its corporate headquarters in Stuttgart, with the main passenger-car body plant at Sindelfingen, the engine and drivetrain works at Untertürkheim including the Mettingen, Bad Cannstatt and Hedelfingen sites, and the smaller plants at Rastatt (A-Class, B-Class and EQA), Wörth am Rhein (Mercedes-Benz trucks, in Rheinland-Pfalz but with BW commuters), and the Mannheim engine and bus plant. Daimler Truck Holding AG, spun off from Daimler in 2021, has its head office in Leinfelden-Echterdingen near Stuttgart Airport and remains a global leader in commercial vehicles under the Mercedes-Benz Trucks, Setra, FUSO, Western Star and Freightliner brands; the EvoBus subsidiary builds buses at Mannheim and Neu-Ulm. Mercedes-AMG GmbH, the high-performance brand, is based at Affalterbach. Mercedes-Benz also operates the Mercedes-Benz Museum at Untertürkheim and the major automotive research centre at Sindelfingen.

Porsche AG, listed since 2022, has its headquarters in Stuttgart-Zuffenhausen, the spiritual home of the 911 sports car since 1948, with the body and assembly works for the 911, the Taycan electric saloon and the 718 Boxster and Cayman on the same site. The Porsche Museum at Zuffenhausen and the Porsche Engineering campus at Weissach with its test track and the Porsche development centre form the technical heart of the brand; Porsche''s second main plant is at Leipzig in Saxony, where the Cayenne, Macan and Panamera are built. Porsche Holding SE, the Stuttgart-based family-controlled holding, owns large stakes in Volkswagen Group, including Audi, Lamborghini, Bentley and Bugatti.

Robert Bosch GmbH, the world''s largest automotive supplier, has its corporate headquarters at Gerlingen on the Schillerhöhe above Stuttgart, founded in 1886 in Stuttgart by Robert Bosch as Werkstätte für Feinmechanik und Elektrotechnik. Bosch operates research centres in Renningen, large plants in Feuerbach, Reutlingen (semiconductors), Schwieberdingen, Stuttgart-Feuerbach, Waiblingen and Bühl, employs about four hundred thousand worldwide and is one of the largest privately held companies in the world, with the Robert Bosch Stiftung holding the majority of voting rights. Bosch products include fuel injection systems, ABS, ESP, sensors, power tools (under the Bosch and Dremel brands), white goods (BSH Hausgeräte joint venture with Siemens, headquartered Munich but with major BW plants), security technology and the Bosch Climate Solutions for heat pumps and boilers.

ZF Friedrichshafen AG, founded in 1915 by Count von Zeppelin to build airship gears, is now the world''s third-largest automotive supplier of driveline, chassis and electrified mobility systems, headquartered at Friedrichshafen on the Bodensee. ZF operates plants in Friedrichshafen, Saarbrücken, Schweinfurt and dozens of foreign sites; in 2015 ZF acquired TRW Automotive and later WABCO. MAHLE GmbH of Stuttgart, founded 1920 in Bad Cannstatt by the Mahle brothers, is a leading supplier of pistons, filtration, thermal management and engine cooling. Trumpf GmbH at Ditzingen near Stuttgart is the world''s largest machine-tool maker specialising in industrial laser cutting and bending machines and a key supplier of EUV lithography lasers to ASML and the global semiconductor industry. Schunk at Lauffen am Neckar, Heller at Nürtingen, EMAG at Salach, Index-Werke at Esslingen, Burkhardt+Weber at Reutlingen, J. Schmalz at Glatten, Liebherr Aerospace Lindenberg group with its Ehingen mobile crane works and Biberach tower crane operations are all leaders in their machine-tool, gripping or lifting niches.

Carl Zeiss AG, headquartered at Oberkochen, with sister company Carl Zeiss Meditec AG in Jena (Thuringia) and Schott AG in Mainz (Rheinland-Pfalz), is the world leader in microscopy, semiconductor lithography optics (Zeiss SMT optics are used in every ASML EUV lithography machine), and ophthalmology systems. The Stiftungsverwaltung Carl-Zeiss-Stiftung at Heidenheim controls both Carl Zeiss AG and Schott AG. Trumpf and Zeiss together hold a critical position in the global semiconductor manufacturing supply chain. Voith GmbH at Heidenheim manufactures paper machines, hydropower turbines and marine drives. Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG, the Heidelberger printing-press maker founded 1850, remains the world''s largest manufacturer of offset printing presses.

SAP SE, the European software giant, has its corporate headquarters in Walldorf, between Heidelberg and Bruchsal, and is the largest European software company by revenue and Germany''s most valuable listed company by market capitalisation. SAP, founded in 1972 by five former IBM employees including Hasso Plattner, Dietmar Hopp and Klaus Tschira, develops the SAP ERP, S/4HANA, SuccessFactors, Concur, Ariba, BusinessObjects, Crystal Reports and Hana database products used by ninety per cent of the Forbes Global 2000. The Hasso Plattner Foundation, the Klaus Tschira Foundation and the Dietmar Hopp Foundation have founded scientific institutes and supported the Hasso-Plattner-Institut at Potsdam, the Heidelberg Institut für Theoretische Studien (HITS) and the Klaus Tschira Stiftung''s flagship Mathematikum.

The Schwarz Group (Schwarz Gruppe) of Neckarsulm, ultimately owned by the Schwarz family, is one of the world''s largest retailers by revenue and includes the Lidl discount supermarket chain and the Kaufland hypermarket chain, plus the PreZero recycling business and the Schwarz IT subsidiary. Schwarz IT is a major buyer of cloud and cybersecurity software, having acquired XM Cyber and other technology firms.

Audi AG, formally an Ingolstadt company, runs its second-largest German plant at Neckarsulm where the Audi A6, A7, A8 and the e-tron GT are assembled. Volkswagen sales also flow through dealer networks across the state, but the dominant BW carmakers remain Mercedes and Porsche.

Würth Group of Künzelsau in the Hohenlohekreis is one of the world''s largest distributors of fasteners, screws and assembly products, founded by Reinhold Würth in 1945 and now operating four hundred subsidiaries worldwide. The Würth-Haus Rorschach and the Carmen Würth Forum at Künzelsau host private collections and concerts.

Stihl AG, headquartered at Waiblingen, is the world''s largest manufacturer of chainsaws and a major supplier of forestry and garden machinery, founded in 1926 by Andreas Stihl. Alfred Kärcher SE of Winnenden is the global leader in pressure-washing and cleaning equipment, supplying everything from the consumer K2 to large municipal sweepers. Festo SE of Esslingen-Berkheim leads pneumatic and electric automation technology. Brita of Taunusstein (Hessen) competes with locally based water-filter rivals; Wieland-Werke AG of Ulm and Mansfelder Kupfer of Sachsen-Anhalt are copper-products specialists, with Wieland leading high-performance copper alloy production. Eberspächer of Esslingen specialises in exhaust systems and vehicle heaters; Behr (now Mahle Behr) and the Mahle group are leading climate-control engineering houses.

Heidelberg Cement AG (since 2024 named Heidelberg Materials AG) of Heidelberg is one of the world''s largest building-materials groups, alongside competitor Holcim. Roche Diagnostics has its German headquarters in Mannheim, an inheritance from the 1997 acquisition of Boehringer Mannheim, and runs major in-vitro-diagnostics R&D and production sites including Penzberg in Bavaria; Roche''s Mannheim site employs thousands. Boehringer Ingelheim of Ingelheim (Rheinland-Pfalz) has Biberach an der Riß biotechnology operations. BASF SE, Europe''s largest chemical company, is across the Rhine at Ludwigshafen in Rheinland-Pfalz but employs many BW residents and operates the Ludwigshafen Stammwerk with the Verbund chemical complex of seventy-five plants.

Lufthansa Technik''s Stuttgart base, the Aeroline UNICOM and Diehl Aviation cabin works at Laupheim are aerospace specialists; ZF Aerospace, ZF Wind Power, Eurocopter''s former Donauwörth plant (Bavarian), and the Liebherr-Aerospace Lindenberg group make Baden-Württemberg a strong aviation supplier. Diehl Defence at Überlingen produces the IRIS-T missile family. Andritz Hydro, Maschinenfabrik Reinhausen and Voith Hydro lead hydropower technology. Energie Baden-Württemberg AG (EnBW), the state utility, is headquartered in Karlsruhe, with the Philippsburg and Neckarwestheim nuclear stations now decommissioned, the Lippendorf and Heilbronn coal plants in transition and significant offshore wind investments through EnBW Hohe See and He Dreiht. Netze BW operates the distribution grid.

Insurance and finance include Allianz Lebensversicherungs-AG with significant operations in Stuttgart, the Wüstenrot & Württembergische (W&W) financial group at Stuttgart based on the historic Wüstenrot Bausparkasse, the LBBW (Landesbank Baden-Württemberg) at Stuttgart-Karlsruhe-Mannheim, the BW-Bank brand, the SDK Süddeutsche Krankenversicherung, the SV SparkassenVersicherung, the Versicherungskammer Bayern partner Württembergische Versicherung, and the Stuttgart Stock Exchange (Börse Stuttgart), the second-largest German exchange by volume and Europe''s leading exchange for retail-investor bond trading. Bausparkasse Schwäbisch Hall of Schwäbisch Hall is part of the cooperative DZ Bank.

The Mittelstand hidden champions of Baden-Württemberg are remarkable. They include the toy and game maker Ravensburger AG at Ravensburg (puzzles, board games such as Memory, the Tiptoi pen, Spieleland); Märklin model railways of Göppingen; Steiff teddy bears of Giengen an der Brenz, who patented the teddy bear in 1903; Schwäbische Hüttenwerke of Aalen with sintered metal parts; Faber-Castell (HQ Stein in Bavaria, but BW operations); Lego Education in BW via Stuttgart; Sika and Stihl as already mentioned. WMF (Württembergische Metallwarenfabrik) of Geislingen an der Steige, now a Groupe SEB subsidiary, makes cookware, cutlery and coffee machines. The Heller GmbH of Ditzingen and HEIDENHAIN of Traunreut (Bavarian) are CNC controls specialists. Felss, Komet, Mapal Dr. Kress at Aalen, Walter AG of Tübingen (a Sandvik subsidiary), and Index-Werke at Esslingen-Brühl supply precision cutting tools to the global automotive and aerospace industry. Pforzheim and Idar-Oberstein (Rheinland-Pfalz) share Germany''s jewellery cluster, with Pforzheim home to Wempe, Wellendorff and the C. Hafner refinery. The Trumpf, Zeiss and Bosch ASML supply chain to ASML Holding NV in Veldhoven (Netherlands) is the critical European node in the EUV lithography industry that the global chip industry depends on.

Agriculture covers tobacco at the Vorderpfalz, the Tauber and Hohenlohe wheat plains, the Filder cabbage country (giving the Filderkraut and Filderspitz), the Mainau and Bodensee fruit-growing belt with apples, hops in Tettnang one of the four German hop-growing regions (the others being Hallertau, Spalt and Elbe-Saale), Baden and Württemberg viticulture as already detailed, and the Black Forest dairy industry producing Schwarzwälder Bergkäse, Schwarzwaldmilch GmbH, and the Schwarzwälder Schinken trade. Forestry under the state-owned ForstBW manages the largest publicly held forest in Germany. Tourism contributes a substantial part of GDP especially in the Black Forest, Bodensee and Heidelberg.

Universities and research are economic pillars: Karlsruhe Institute of Technology (KIT) one of the German Universities of Excellence, the Universität Heidelberg the oldest in Germany, the Universität Tübingen and the Universität Freiburg both with Nobel-laureate physics and medical traditions, the Universität Stuttgart and Hohenheim, Mannheim, Ulm, Konstanz, the Hochschulen of Esslingen, Pforzheim, Aalen, Reutlingen and others. The Fraunhofer Institutes in BW include Fraunhofer IAO Stuttgart, Fraunhofer IPA Stuttgart, Fraunhofer IPM Freiburg, Fraunhofer IISB and ISE Freiburg. The Max Planck Society maintains MPI Stuttgart for Solid State Research and Intelligent Systems, the MPI for Astronomy at Heidelberg, and the European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL) at Heidelberg. The German Cancer Research Center DKFZ and the German Aerospace Center DLR Stuttgart-Lampoldshausen complete the research map. Baden-Württemberg consistently leads Germany in per-capita patent applications and R&D intensity, and is regarded together with Bavaria as the engine of German industrial export performance.',
    introduced_species = 'The fauna and flora of Baden-Württemberg include a substantial cast of non-native species, the consequence of three centuries of fur farming, ornamental gardening, fish stocking, intercontinental shipping and accidental release. The single most conspicuous introduced mammal is the raccoon, in German Waschbär (literally washing bear), Procyon lotor, native to North America and now firmly established across all sixteen federal states. Although the original German release point was at Lake Eder in Hessen in April 1934 and a wartime release in Brandenburg followed, the southward expansion into Baden-Württemberg accelerated through the 1970s and 1980s along the wooded corridors of the Neckar, Tauber, Jagst, Kocher and the lower Main, with documented populations now in the Odenwald, the Tauber-Franken districts, the Hohenlohe plateau, the Schwäbisch-Fränkischer Wald and increasingly in the suburban fringes of Heilbronn, Mannheim, Heidelberg, Stuttgart and Karlsruhe. The state-wide annual hunting bag rose from a few hundred animals in the 1990s to several thousand per year by the late 2010s, with Hohenlohekreis, Main-Tauber-Kreis, Neckar-Odenwald-Kreis and Rhein-Neckar-Kreis among the highest-yield districts. Urban raccoons exploit roof voids, garages, dustbins, compost heaps and pet food, and have been recorded in central Heidelberg, Mannheim Lindenhof, Stuttgart-West and the gardens of the Karlsruhe Schlossgarten. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation of cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl), on amphibian breeding ponds (yellow-bellied toad, fire-bellied toad in the upper Neckar), and on red squirrel and edible dormouse populations. Raccoons also carry the parasite Baylisascaris procyonis, a roundworm that can cause severe larva-migrans disease in humans and other mammals, prompting health-department guidance to clear raccoon latrines from attics with protective gear.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund or Enok, Nyctereutes procyonoides, is a related canid native to East Asia that was released and farmed for fur in the western Soviet Union in the 1930s through 1950s and has since spread westwards across Europe at an average of forty to fifty kilometres a year. Raccoon dogs reached the eastern German states first; by the early 2000s small populations were documented in Baden-Württemberg in the Tauber-Franken districts and the Hohenlohe area, and the species is now regularly recorded across northern and eastern BW with isolated records as far south as the Donau valley. Their habits resemble small foxes; they hibernate communally, breed in fox dens, and prey on small mammals, ground-nesting birds, amphibians and carrion. They are listed on the European Union Invasive Alien Species List and are subject to year-round hunting in BW.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, in German Nutria or sometimes Sumpfbiber, is a large South American rodent farmed for fur across Europe from the late nineteenth century and now firmly established along the Rhine wetlands and lower Neckar in Baden-Württemberg. Populations are conspicuous along the Rheinauen near Karlsruhe, Philippsburg, Speyer, Worms and Mannheim, in the Polder am Altrhein, on the Bodensee in the Reichenau and Ermatingen reedbeds, and in the lower Neckar near Heidelberg, Mannheim and Stuttgart-Bad Cannstatt. Nutria damage reedbeds by grazing on common reed (Phragmites australis), undermine dykes by burrowing, and compete with the native European beaver, which has re-colonised the Rhine, Tauber and Donau valleys from the south. Local authorities now run combined nutria-trapping programmes through professional Fallensteller and licensed hunters.

The muskrat, Bisamratte or Bisam, Ondatra zibethicus, also from North America, was introduced to Bohemia in 1905 and reached Baden-Württemberg in the 1930s. It is now ubiquitous in slow-moving water bodies, irrigation ditches and gravel pits across the Rhine plain, the Kraichgau, the Hohenlohe and the Oberschwaben, where its burrows cause damage to dykes, fish ponds and golf-course water features. Continued trapping is mandated by water-authority dyke-safety regulations.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis or Kanadagans, originally from North America, was first kept on European ornamental waters and has established self-sustaining feral populations along the Rhine, Neckar and Bodensee. Resident flocks summer on the Karlsruhe Schlossgartensee, the Mannheim Herzogenried, the Heidelberg Neckarwiese and the Konstanz Seerhein. The Egyptian goose, Alopochen aegyptiaca or Nilgans, originally from Africa, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations since the late 1990s and now breeds widely in BW, including in central Stuttgart parks, the Mannheim Luisenpark, the Heidelberg Schwetzinger Schloss and the Karlsruhe Stadtgarten; it is conspicuous and territorial, sometimes displacing native ducks. The mandarin duck, Aix galericulata or Mandarinente, from East Asia, has small feral populations on the Bodensee, the Mannheim parks and the Heidelberger Schloss moat. The ring-necked or rose-ringed parakeet, Psittacula krameri or Halsbandsittich, originally from the Indian subcontinent and Africa, established large breeding populations in Heidelberg, Mannheim and Ludwigshafen along the Rhine-Neckar conurbation, where they roost in plane-tree avenues; smaller groups occur in Stuttgart-West. The closely related Alexandrine parakeet, Psittacula eupatria or Großer Alexandersittich, joins them in lesser numbers. The Indian house crow, Corvus splendens, has not yet established in BW but has been observed as a port vagrant in Hamburg. The pheasant, Phasianus colchicus, originally from the Caucasus, is naturalised across the Kraichgau, the Hohenlohe and the Tauberbrückenland. The Wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on Hohenlohe hunting estates but has not established.

Among introduced fish, the eastern North American pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus or Sonnenbarsch, is established in slow-flowing waters of the Rhine plain, especially gravel pits and lake-bordering canals; it competes with native bitterling, tench and bream. The Asian topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva or Blaubandbärbling, introduced as a carp by-product, is now present across the Rhine, Neckar, Tauber and Donau, where it transmits the rosette agent Sphaerothecum destruens to other fish. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus or Zwergwels, North American, occurs in old gravel pits along the Rhine. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus or Schwarzmaul-Grundel, native to the Black Sea and Caspian basins, entered the Rhine via the Main-Danube Canal in the early 2010s and is now abundant in the Upper Rhine and Mannheim, displacing native bullheads. The Caspian Kessler''s goby and the bighead goby followed similar routes. Rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss or Regenbogenforelle, North American, is stocked in Black Forest streams and the Donau headwaters and competes with native brown trout. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis or Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella or Graskarpfen, from East Asia, is used to control aquatic vegetation in lakes. The silver carp and bighead carp have been used in pond aquaculture. Sterlet, Acipenser ruthenus, native to the Danube system, persists in BW Danube headwaters in stocking programmes alongside the Atlantic sturgeon reintroduction of the Rhine.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus or Signalkrebs, North American, which carries the crayfish plague Aphanomyces astaci and has driven the native noble crayfish Astacus astacus to local extinction in many BW streams. The red swamp crayfish, Procambarus clarkii or Roter Sumpfkrebs, from Louisiana, is established in Mannheim, Heidelberg and Stuttgart park ponds. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis or Marmorkrebs, a parthenogenetic species first recorded in a Heidelberg aquarist''s tank and now wild in BW gravel pits, presents a special risk because every individual is a clonal female. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis or Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe, occurs in the Rhine and Neckar, having migrated upstream from the North Sea estuaries. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha or Dreikantmuschel, from the Caspian basin, has been in the Rhine since the 1830s. The quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis or Quaggamuschel, arrived in BW after 2007 and is now the dominant freshwater mussel of the Bodensee. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea or Körbchenmuschel, occurs in the Rhine and Neckar. The flatworm Obama nungara, originally from South America, has been recorded in BW gardens.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax or Asiatische Hornisse, was first detected in BW in 2014 in the Markgräflerland near Müllheim, having spread north from Bordeaux since 2004. Subsequent rapid expansion has produced nests across the southern Oberrhein, the Kaiserstuhl, the Ortenau and as far north as Mannheim and Stuttgart by the early 2020s. The species preys heavily on honeybees Apis mellifera and Apis ligustica at hive entrances, prompting concern among the BW Imkerverbände. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis or Asiatischer Marienkäfer, introduced for biological control in Europe in 1982, is now ubiquitous in BW and displaces native ladybird species. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella or Rosskastanien-Miniermotte, defoliates the white-flowered horse-chestnuts on Karlsruhe, Mannheim and Heidelberg avenues. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis or Buchsbaum-Zünsler, has devastated boxwood in BW gardens since around 2009. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys or Marmorierte Baumwanze, an East Asian species, is now established across BW, with the Konstanz, Lake Constance and Mannheim populations causing damage to fruit and vegetable crops.

Among plants, ragweed, Ambrosia artemisiifolia or Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut, from North America, is a major allergenic invader of the Rhine plain, the gravel pits of the Hochrhein and roadside disturbances; control teams of the Landesanstalt für Umwelt (LUBW) coordinate eradication. Japanese knotweed, Reynoutria japonica or Japanknöterich, from East Asia, dominates banks of the Neckar, Murg, Kinzig and Tauber. Himalayan balsam, Impatiens glandulifera or Drüsiges Springkraut, is widespread along the Donau, Neckar and Schwarzwald streams, where its annual cycle replaces native herbaceous flora. Giant hogweed, Heracleum mantegazzianum or Riesen-Bärenklau, from the Caucasus, occurs scattered across BW; its phototoxic sap causes severe dermatitis. Goldenrod, Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea, from North America, dominates fallow land. Tree of heaven, Ailanthus altissima or Götterbaum, from China, spreads along railway lines and in Mannheim, Karlsruhe, Heidelberg and Stuttgart urban brownfields. The water primrose Ludwigia grandiflora and the Cabomba caroliniana have been recorded in BW garden ponds.

Game species deliberately released for hunting include mouflon, Ovis orientalis musimon or Mufflon, originally from Corsica and Sardinia, established in the Schönbuch and Schurwald, the Oberschwäbisches Allgäu and the Schwäbische Alb since the late nineteenth century. Fallow deer, Dama dama or Damwild, present in royal hunting parks since the Middle Ages, has feral populations in the Stromberg-Heuchelberg, the Schönbuch and the Schwäbische Alb. Sika deer, Cervus nippon or Sikahirsch, from East Asia, has small populations near Bad Mergentheim. Wild boar, Sus scrofa, is native but its modern superabundance is sometimes considered a partial introduction effect from supplementary feeding and from the conversion of maize cropping into a year-round forage. The American mink, Neovison vison or Amerikanischer Nerz, escaped from fur farms, occurs sparsely along BW streams.

The Landesanstalt für Umwelt Baden-Württemberg (LUBW) maintains a comprehensive register of invasive alien species and coordinates monitoring, control and reporting under the EU Regulation 1143/2014. Targeted control programmes operate for the Asian hornet, the giant hogweed, ragweed and the box tree moth, and a state-funded reward is paid for verified Asian hornet nests located within BW.'
WHERE region_name = 'Baden-Württemberg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Bavaria, Bayern in German, is the largest of the German federal states by area and one of the wealthiest, a Free State (Freistaat Bayern) since 1918 with deep cultural roots in seven historic regions: Upper and Lower Bavaria (Ober- and Niederbayern), Swabia (Schwaben), the Upper Palatinate (Oberpfalz), Upper, Middle and Lower Franconia (Ober-, Mittel- and Unterfranken). The capital Munich (München) is a global tourist destination, anchored on the Marienplatz with the Neues Rathaus and its famous Glockenspiel carillon, the Altes Rathaus, the Frauenkirche with its twin onion-dome towers, the Peterskirche with its viewing platform, the Theatinerkirche, the Asamkirche, the Hofbräuhaus am Platzl founded as the Wittelsbach court brewery, the Residenz München and its Antiquarium and Cuvilliés-Theater, the Bavarian State Opera in the Nationaltheater, the Bayerisches Nationalmuseum, the Alte Pinakothek (medieval and Renaissance painting), the Neue Pinakothek (nineteenth-century), the Pinakothek der Moderne, the Museum Brandhorst, the Lenbachhaus housing the Blaue Reiter collection of Kandinsky, Münter, Marc and Macke, the Deutsches Museum on the Museumsinsel (the world''s largest science and technology museum), and the BMW Welt and BMW Museum at the Olympiapark with the tent-roofed stadium of the 1972 Summer Olympics designed by Frei Otto and Günter Behnisch. The English Garden, one of the largest urban parks in Europe, includes the Chinese Tower, the Monopteros, the Eisbach surfing wave and the Kleinhesselohersee lake; the Hofgarten, the Bavaria statue and the Theresienwiese host the Oktoberfest. Schloss Nymphenburg with its baroque gardens, the Amalienburg by François de Cuvilliés, and Schleißheim Palace round out the Wittelsbach legacy in the capital. Munich is also famous for the Viktualienmarkt, the Schwabing district, the Maximilianstraße shopping mile, the Allianz Arena home of FC Bayern München, and the Tegernsee, Starnberger See and Ammersee lakes within easy reach.

The Bavarian Alps stretch along the southern border of the state from the Allgäu through Werdenfels, the Ammergau, Wettersteingebirge, Karwendel and Berchtesgaden ranges. The Zugspitze at 2962 metres, on the Austrian border above Garmisch-Partenkirchen, is Germany''s highest mountain, reached by the Bayerische Zugspitzbahn cog railway from Garmisch via Grainau and Eibsee, by the Tiroler Zugspitzbahn cable car from Ehrwald, by the Zugspitze cable car from the Eibsee opened 2017 (an engineering record at the time of construction), and from the summit by the Gletscherbahn from the Sonnalpin. The Watzmann at 2713 metres, with its Hocheck, Mittelspitze and Südspitze summits, towers over the emerald Königssee below it in the Berchtesgadener Land. The Königssee with the pilgrimage chapel of St. Bartholomä on its western shore, reached only by electric boat (the world''s oldest electric-boat service operating since 1909) is the centrepiece of Berchtesgaden National Park, alongside the salt mine at Berchtesgaden, the Eagle''s Nest (Kehlsteinhaus, treated with appropriate historical caution), and the rope bridge across the Almbachklamm. Garmisch-Partenkirchen, hosts of the 1936 Winter Olympics, retains the Olympia-Skistadion and the Kandahar downhill course and is gateway to the Partnachklamm and the Höllentalklamm gorges. Mittenwald is famous for its painted Lüftlmalerei facades and its violin-making tradition founded by Matthias Klotz. Oberammergau hosts the Passion Play every ten years (most recently 2022). Linderhof Palace, Neuschwanstein Castle and Hohenschwangau Castle, the Wittelsbach fairy-tale castles built by King Ludwig II, are among Germany''s most visited tourist attractions; Neuschwanstein''s silhouette inspired the Disneyland Sleeping Beauty Castle. Herrenchiemsee Palace on the Herreninsel in the Chiemsee, also built by Ludwig II as a tribute to Versailles, complements the trilogy. The Chiemsee, the Walchensee, the Eibsee, the Spitzingsee and the Tegernsee are alpine lakes celebrated for sailing, mountain biking and mountain dairy. Bad Tölz, Bad Reichenhall with its Alte Saline, Bad Kissingen and the spa towns of the Frankenland complete the wellness map. The Allgäu, around Kempten, Sonthofen and Oberstdorf, offers the Nebelhorn, the Fellhorn, the Söllereck, the Oberjoch pass, the Breitachklamm and the cross-country trails of the Nordic Centre Oberstdorf.

The Romantic Road, the Romantische Straße, a tourist route designated in 1950, runs from Würzburg via Tauberbischofsheim, Bad Mergentheim, Weikersheim, Rothenburg ob der Tauber, Dinkelsbühl, Nördlingen in the Ries crater, Donauwörth, Augsburg, Landsberg am Lech, Schongau, Steingaden with the Wieskirche (UNESCO), Hohenschwangau and Füssen to the Lechfall. Rothenburg ob der Tauber, with its complete medieval walls, the Plönlein, the Burggarten, the Reichsstadtmuseum, the Master Builder''s House (Baumeisterhaus) and the Christmas museum founded by Käthe Wohlfahrt, is among the most-photographed towns in Germany. Dinkelsbühl, Nördlingen with its almost-complete circular wall and the Daniel tower of the Georgskirche, and Donauwörth with the Reichsstraße have preserved medieval centres. Würzburg, the gateway of the Romantic Road and a UNESCO World Heritage Site for the Residenz with its Tiepolo ceiling fresco (the largest in the world) and Court Garden, lies on the Main below the Marienberg Fortress, with the Alte Mainbrücke, the Käppele pilgrimage church by Balthasar Neumann, and the Würzburger Stein vineyards. The Wieskirche near Steingaden, the rococo masterpiece of Dominikus Zimmermann, is also a UNESCO site, as is the Cistercian abbey at Maulbronn (Baden-Württemberg) and the Würzburg Residenz.

Augsburg, the third-largest Bavarian city, is one of the oldest in Germany, founded as Augusta Vindelicorum under Emperor Augustus, and home to the Fuggerei (the world''s oldest social housing settlement founded by Jakob Fugger in 1521 and still functioning), the Augsburg town hall by Elias Holl, the Goldener Saal (Golden Hall), the Schaezlerpalais and the Augsburg water management system (UNESCO World Heritage). Regensburg on the Danube is a UNESCO World Heritage Old Town, with the Steinerne Brücke of 1146 (the oldest preserved stone bridge in Germany), the Romanesque-Gothic Dom St. Peter, the Schottenkloster St. Jakob, the Walhalla and Befreiungshalle nearby, the Thurn und Taxis palace of St. Emmeram and the Historische Wurstkuchl wurst kitchen. Passau, the Three Rivers City at the confluence of Danube, Inn and Ilz, has the Dom St. Stephan with the world''s largest cathedral organ, the Veste Oberhaus and the Innstadt. Nuremberg (Nürnberg), the unofficial capital of Franconia, is famous for the Kaiserburg, the Hauptmarkt with the Schöner Brunnen and the Frauenkirche with its mechanical Männleinlaufen clock, the Albrecht Dürer Haus (the artist''s home), the Sebalduskirche, the Lorenzkirche, the Germanisches Nationalmuseum (Germany''s largest cultural-history museum), the Memorium Nuremberg Trials, the Nuremberg Toy Museum, and the Christkindlesmarkt Christmas market.

The Franconian wine country around Würzburg, Volkach, Iphofen, Kitzingen, Sommerach, Castell and Sulzfeld am Main produces the distinctive Bocksbeutel-bottled Silvaner, Müller-Thurgau, Bacchus, Domina, Frühburgunder and Spätburgunder; the wine festivals of Volkach, Iphofen and Würzburg are heavily attended. Coburg, with the Veste Coburg one of the largest medieval fortresses in Germany; Bayreuth with the Wagner Festspielhaus and the UNESCO-listed Margravial Opera House by Giuseppe Galli Bibiena; Bamberg, a UNESCO World Heritage town with the cathedral of Henry II, the Altes Rathaus on its island in the Regnitz, the Rauchbier breweries (Schlenkerla, Spezial) and the Klein-Venedig fishermen''s quarter; Erlangen with its Friedrich-Alexander-Universität and the Markgräfliche Schloss; the Fränkische Schweiz with its limestone outcrops, the Pottenstein and Gößweinstein pilgrimage churches; Ansbach with its Markgräfliches Schloss and Hofgarten; Würzburg, Aschaffenburg with Schloss Johannisburg, the Spessart, the Rhön Biosphärenreservat, the Steigerwald and the Frankenwald all enrich the Franconian portfolio. Lichtenfels has the German Basket Museum; Kulmbach is the Bratwurst city and home of Mönchshof and Kulmbacher beer; Hof, Marktredwitz, Selb (Rosenthal porcelain) and Bayreuth lie in the Oberfränkischer porcelain belt with the Porzellanikon Selb-Hohenberg.

The Upper Palatinate (Oberpfalz) is centred on Regensburg, with Amberg, Weiden, Neumarkt, Cham and the Bayerischer Wald National Park, Germany''s first national park (1970) along the Czech border, where the Großer Arber, the Großer Falkenstein, the Lusen and the Rachel reach almost fifteen hundred metres and the trans-frontier Šumava Park forms one of the largest contiguous forest areas in Europe. The Walhalla above Donaustauf, built by Ludwig I as a hall of fame of Germans, and the Befreiungshalle at Kelheim, monument to the liberation wars, are neoclassical landmarks above the Danube; the Weltenburger Enge gorge, Kloster Weltenburg with the oldest monastic brewery in Bavaria (founded 1050), and the Befreiungshalle complete the so-called Donaudurchbruch. Eichstätt with its baroque cathedral, the Schloss Willibaldsburg with the Jura Museum, and the Altmühltal Nature Park with its Solnhofen limestone quarries (where the original Archaeopteryx fossils were found and the Solnhofener lithographic limestone is quarried) anchor the south. Ingolstadt, on the Danube, is home to the medieval city walls, the Liebfrauenmünster, the Audi Forum (with the museum mobile) and the Museum für Konkrete Kunst.

Cuisine and drink define Bayern. The Weisswurst (white sausage, never to be eaten after the church bells of noon according to tradition), the Schweinshaxe (roast pork knuckle), Schweinsbraten (roast pork) with dunkles Bier sauce, Tellerfleisch boiled beef, the Münchner Schnitzel, Kalbsleberkäse meatloaf in a Semmel roll, the Brezn, the Obatzda Camembert spread, Radi (white radish), Schweinsbraten with Knödel and Sauerkraut, Schwarzgeräucherte (smoke-cured Black Forest ham equivalent), Spanferkel suckling pig and the Bavarian Brotzeit cold-meat platter are staples. Knödel of all kinds (Semmelknödel from bread, Kartoffelknödel from potato, Leberknödel from liver, Speckknödel with bacon, Topfenknödel sweet quark dumplings) accompany roasts. Franconian Schäufele (slow-roasted pork shoulder), Nürnberger Rostbratwürste (small bratwursts traditionally served three to a bun as Drei im Weggla or six on a tin plate with Sauerkraut), Coburger Bratwurst, Würzburger Stadtwurst and the Regensburger Knackwurst maintain regional sausage diversity. Sweets include Bayerische Creme, Dampfnudeln, Apfelstrudel, Kaiserschmarrn (originally Austrian but adopted), Prinzregententorte and Lebkuchen Nuremberg gingerbread. Bavaria is the global capital of beer: more than six hundred breweries operate, ruled since 1516 by the Reinheitsgebot beer purity law issued at Ingolstadt by Duke Wilhelm IV. Major beer brands include Augustiner, Spaten, Paulaner, Hofbräu (the state brewery), Hacker-Pschorr and Löwenbräu (the Munich Big Six who pour at Oktoberfest); plus Erdinger Weißbier, Schneider Weisse, Maisel''s Weisse, Tucher, Andechser (the abbey brewery), Tegernseer, Ayinger, Weihenstephaner (the oldest still-operating brewery in the world, founded 1040 at Freising), Kulmbacher, Bitburger (Rheinland-Pfalz), Allgäuer Brauhaus, König Ludwig and the Franconian classics Bamberg Schlenkerla Rauchbier, Mahr''s, Brauerei Heller, Mönchshof Kulmbach, and the Spezialbier of Schloss Lemberg in Hof. The Oktoberfest on the Theresienwiese is the world''s largest beer festival, attracting six million visitors annually for two weeks from mid-September to early October. Franconia is also a major wine country with the Bocksbeutel Silvaner; distillers in Tegernsee, Eggenfelden and Berchtesgaden produce Obstler and Enzian. Coffee culture is strong in Munich and Bamberg, with the Augustiner Café and the legendary konditoreis Café Luitpold and Confiserie Lange.

History before 1933 is rich: the Celtic settlement of Manching, the Roman Limes; the Bavaria of the Agilolfings; the Carolingian and Welf dynasties; the Wittelsbach succession from 1180 onwards lasting unbroken to the 1918 abdication of King Ludwig III; the Imperial Free Cities of Augsburg, Nuremberg, Regensburg, Rothenburg ob der Tauber, Dinkelsbühl, Nördlingen, Memmingen and Lindau; the prince-bishoprics of Würzburg, Bamberg, Eichstätt, Freising, Passau and Regensburg; the Margraviates of Brandenburg-Ansbach and Brandenburg-Bayreuth, ancestral lands of the Hohenzollerns; the Peasants'' War of 1525, sparked by the Twelve Articles of Memmingen; the Thirty Years'' War''s catastrophic Battle of Nördlingen (1634); the Bavarian Succession War; Napoleon''s elevation of Bavaria to a kingdom in 1806 with Maximilian I Joseph; the construction of the Ludwig-Donau-Main canal; the reigns of Ludwig I (builder of Walhalla, Befreiungshalle, the Glyptothek and the new Munich monumental quarter), Maximilian II, Ludwig II (the fairy-tale king who built Neuschwanstein, Linderhof and Herrenchiemsee), and Prince Regent Luitpold (the Belle Époque); the Wittelsbach abdication and the Free State proclamation by Kurt Eisner of November 1918; the inter-war Free State governments; and after 1945 the rebuilding under Hans Ehard, Wilhelm Hoegner and the long CSU governments of Franz Josef Strauß and his successors. Bavaria''s Verfassung (constitution) of 1946 is the oldest still in force in Germany.',
    transportation = 'Bavaria has the most extensive transport network of any German state, reflecting its size, its mountainous southern frontier and its position on the corridor between the North Sea ports, Italy and the Balkans. Munich Airport, Flughafen München, IATA MUC and ICAO EDDM, named Franz Josef Strauß International Airport, is the second-busiest in Germany and the seventh-busiest in Europe by passenger numbers, handling around forty-eight million passengers per year in normal traffic. The airport opened in 1992 on the Erdinger Moos north-east of Munich, replacing the cramped Riem airport; it has two terminals and two parallel runways, with Lufthansa, its main hub partner, operating Terminal 2 jointly with Star Alliance partners and the Munich Cargo Terminal in the south-west. Connections from Munich Airport include the S-Bahn S1 via Freising and S8 via Ostbahnhof, the express bus Lufthansa Bus to Hauptbahnhof and Allgäu, and the planned but politically contested Erdinger Ringschluss rail bypass that would allow direct Regensburg-Munich Airport ICE services. The second-largest commercial airport is Nuremberg Airport (NUE, EDDN), named after Albrecht Dürer, with around four million passengers in normal traffic, served by Eurowings, Ryanair, easyJet, TUI fly, Wizz Air, Air Cairo and Sun Express. Memmingen Airport (FMM) in Bavarian Swabia, on a former military airfield, has become a low-cost carrier base for Ryanair and Wizz Air with flights to twenty Mediterranean destinations. Augsburg Airport (AGB) is used for general aviation and business jets; Hof-Plauen, Bayreuth, Coburg, Straubing and Oberpfaffenhofen (a Special Use airfield home to DLR and Dornier flight tests) round out the regional aviation network. Special mention belongs to the historic Oberschleißheim airfield (the first Bavarian airfield, 1912) and the Friedrichshafen border traffic to Bodensee that historically passed through Lindau.

The Bavarian rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn, with regional services contracted out to DB Regio Bayern, agilis, Bayerische Oberlandbahn (BOB), Bayerische Regiobahn (BRB), Meridian, Vlexx, Alex, Länderbahn and Westfrankenbahn. The Bavarian state transport authority Bayerische Eisenbahngesellschaft (BEG) tenders all regional services. Munich Hauptbahnhof is the largest railway station in Bavaria and one of the busiest in Germany, currently undergoing a major reconstruction with a new starkenburg-style central hall by Auer Weber; the Stammstrecke S-Bahn tunnel underneath is being supplemented by a second tunnel (the 2. Stammstrecke) currently under construction at huge cost overruns and delay, due to open after 2030. Munich Ostbahnhof, Pasing and Donnersbergerbrücke are the other major S-Bahn nodes. Nuremberg Hauptbahnhof, Augsburg Hauptbahnhof, Würzburg Hauptbahnhof, Regensburg Hauptbahnhof, Ingolstadt Hauptbahnhof, Passau Hauptbahnhof, Coburg, Bamberg and Hof complete the major-city rail map.

The Bavarian ICE network includes the high-speed Nuremberg-Ingolstadt line (opened 2006 with three hundred kph operation, the steepest high-speed grade in Germany at the Köschinger Forst), the Berlin-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich high-speed corridor (the so-called Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8 completed in December 2017 with the new Erfurt-Ebensfeld VDE 8.1 line), the Mannheim-Stuttgart-Augsburg-Munich axis, the Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg classic NBS upgrade, the Munich-Salzburg corridor and the planned but disputed Munich-Lindau electrification (completed 2020) for ECE services to Zurich via Memmingen and Bregenz. The Hannover-Würzburg high-speed line, opened in 1991 as one of the first two NBS in Germany, runs to Würzburg. The Brenner Base Tunnel between Innsbruck and Franzensfeste, due for completion in the 2030s, will be reached from Bavaria via the Inntal corridor that is itself under capacity-upgrade planning; the politically contested Brenner Nordzulauf will create new lines via Rosenheim. The Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg corridor sees ICE 11, ICE 25, ICE 41 and ICE 91 services. The night-train Bayern is served by ÖBB Nightjet from Munich to Hamburg, Berlin, Rome, Venice, Vienna and Innsbruck. The Bavarian and Czech Länderbahn Alex from Munich to Prague and Hof crosses the Bohemian border at Furth im Wald.

Munich''s urban rail consists of eight S-Bahn lines through the central Stammstrecke (S1-S8), with the U-Bahn München running eight underground lines from Olympia-Einkaufszentrum and Feldmoching in the north to Klinikum Großhadern, Garching-Forschungszentrum (the world''s longest under-runway extension) and Messestadt Ost. The MVG operates trams on thirteen routes and an extensive bus network, with the MVV regional transport association coordinating tariff and connections to suburban towns. Munich is also one of the leading German cities for car-sharing (Share Now, Miles, SIXT Share) and bike-share (MVG Rad). The Nuremberg U-Bahn includes the world''s first fully driverless line U3 (since 2008) and the U2 (the first such conversion in Europe in 2008); the Nuremberg tram is run by VAG. Augsburg has six tram lines including the Königsplatz interchange; Würzburg and Regensburg are tram-less but plan returns. The Munich Allgäu, Inntal, Bayerisches Oberland and Werdenfelser regional networks are served by BOB and BRB DMUs.

Long-distance buses serve the ZOB Munich at Hackerbrücke and the major Bavarian cities; FlixBus, which is headquartered in Munich, dominates the market and runs daily lines to Berlin, Hamburg, Cologne, Vienna, Prague, Budapest and Paris. The Autobahn network includes the A3 Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg-Regensburg-Passau-Linz, the A6 Heilbronn-Nuremberg-Waidhaus (continuing as D5 in Czechia), the A7 Würzburg-Memmingen-Füssen, the A8 Karlsruhe-Stuttgart-Munich-Salzburg, the A9 Munich-Nuremberg-Leipzig-Berlin (Germany''s first true motorway opened on the Munich-Ingolstadt stretch in 1936 and notable for the unrestricted speed limit on several sections), the A92 Munich-Deggendorf, the A93 Holledau-Rosenheim-Kufstein, the A94 Munich-Passau (the unfinished motorway via Mühldorf, finally completed in 2019), the A95 Munich-Garmisch, the A96 Munich-Lindau, the A99 Munich Autobahnring, the A8 Munich-Salzburg, the A8 Karlsruhe-Ulm-Munich, and the A73 Suhl-Bamberg-Nuremberg-Feucht. The Mittlerer Ring around Munich is famous for the Petueltunnel and Richard-Strauss-Tunnel, two long urban tunnels that take traffic underground. The Bundesstraßen B16, B19, B20, B22 and B85 (the Ostbayernstraße) cross the eastern districts. Special note belongs to the German Alpine Road (Deutsche Alpenstraße), a tourism route from Lindau via Oberstdorf, Garmisch, Mittenwald, Tegernsee, Berchtesgaden to Königssee, completed in stages from 1933 to 2002.

Bavaria has the most navigable rivers and canals of any German state. The Main-Danube Canal, opened in 1992 after centuries of attempts including Charlemagne''s Fossa Carolina at Treuchtlingen and the Ludwig-Donau-Main Canal of 1846, connects Bamberg via Nuremberg and Berching to Kelheim on the Danube and forms the European Rhine-Main-Danube waterway from Rotterdam to the Black Sea. Inland ports include Nuremberg (the second-largest in Bavaria), Bamberg, Aschaffenburg, Würzburg, Passau and Regensburg, all on the bayernhafen group network; Kelheim and Straubing are smaller. The Danube is navigable from Kelheim downstream to Passau and beyond into Austria. The Chiemsee, Tegernsee, Königssee, Starnberger See, Ammersee and the Walchensee operate scheduled passenger steamers; the Königssee electric-only service since 1909 is one of the oldest electric-boat operations in the world.

The Bavarian cableway network is the densest in Germany. The Zugspitzbahn cog railway and three Zugspitze cable cars, the Wendelsteinbahn, the Nebelhornbahn at Oberstdorf, the Fellhornbahn, the Söllereckbahn, the Hörnerbahn, the Kanzelwandbahn, the Hochgrat, the Höllentalseilbahn, the Wankbahn, the Eckbauer, the Kreuzeckbahn, the Hochalmbahn, the Brauneck, the Jenner, the Predigtstuhlbahn, the Rauschberg, the Berchtesgadener Salzbergwerk lift, the Hochries, the Kampenwand, the Spitzingsee and the Schliersbergalm operate as ski lifts and summer hiking lifts. The Tegelberg, the Bleckenwand and the Hochfelln add further connections. Mountain railways include the Bayerische Zugspitzbahn cog-rail (the Bavarian classic), the Wendelsteinbahn cog (Germany''s first cog railway in part), and the Walchenseebahn rack section. Long-distance cycling routes include the Romantische Straße-Radweg, the Donau-Radweg from Donaueschingen via Passau to Vienna, the Main-Radweg, the Altmühltal-Radweg, the Bodensee-Königssee-Radweg, the Innradweg, the Tauberradweg, the Bavarian Glasstraße route, and the European EuroVelo 6 (Atlantic-Black Sea via the Danube) and EuroVelo 7 (Norway-Malta). Pilgrim routes such as the Via Romea and the Munich-Salzburg Jakobsweg are signed for walkers and cyclists.',
    economics = 'Bavaria is the wealthiest German Land by absolute GDP and the second-richest after Hamburg in per-capita terms, with a gross domestic product exceeding seven hundred billion euros and an export ratio above fifty per cent. The Bavarian economy stretches from heavy industry, automotive engineering and aerospace in the south, through medical-technology, electronics and software in the centre, to porcelain, glass and machinery in the north, supported by one of the densest Mittelstand networks in Germany. The state promotes itself through the Bayern Innovativ agency and the Invest in Bavaria foreign-direct-investment office.

The headquarters of the Bayerische Motoren Werke AG, BMW, is the four-cylinder tower (Vierzylinder) at the Olympiapark in Munich, beside the BMW Welt customer-delivery building, the BMW Group Research and Innovation Centre (FIZ) at Milbertshofen, and the historic BMW Plant Munich which has built BMW cars since 1928. Other Bavarian BMW plants include Dingolfing (the largest BMW plant in the world, producing the 3, 5, 7 and 8 Series, and the iX), Regensburg (1, 2 Active Tourer, X1, X2), Landshut (engines, lightweight components and powertrain), Wackersdorf (logistics) and the Berlin and Leipzig plants outside Bayern. BMW Motorrad in Berlin and the engine plant in Steyr (Austria) complete the production map. BMW M GmbH in Munich-Garching is the high-performance division. The Mini brand, also part of BMW Group, is produced at Cowley in the United Kingdom.

Audi AG, founded in 1899 by August Horch at Zwickau (now Sachsen) as Horch and later renamed Audi after his second factory was likewise sued away, has its main plant and headquarters at Ingolstadt on the Danube, the largest manufacturing complex by area in Bavaria, producing the A3, A4, A5, A6, A7, A8 and Q5 model series, with the second German Audi plant at Neckarsulm in Baden-Württemberg. Lamborghini Automobili in Sant''Agata Bolognese, owned by Audi, and Ducati Motor Holding at Borgo Panigale, owned by Audi, complete the Italian wings. The Audi Forum Ingolstadt and the Audi museum mobile, the corporate-history vehicle collection, are open to visitors.

MAN SE of Munich, founded as Maschinenfabrik Augsburg-Nürnberg in 1840, was a global producer of heavy trucks, buses, diesel engines and printing presses; today MAN Truck & Bus SE is a subsidiary of Traton SE (the commercial-vehicle division of Volkswagen Group), with its truck production at Munich and Salzgitter and bus production at Plauen and Starachowice (Poland). The classic MAN B&W marine-diesel division is now part of MAN Energy Solutions, headquartered at Augsburg, the technology leader in large two-stroke marine engines, ship-propulsion turbines and gas-engine technology. Krauss-Maffei Wegmann (KMW) at Munich is one of the leading European defence manufacturers, producing the Leopard 2 main battle tank, the Puma infantry fighting vehicle (jointly with Rheinmetall), the PzH 2000 self-propelled howitzer, and the GTK Boxer armoured fighting vehicle (jointly with Rheinmetall and ARTEC); the merger with Nexter to form KNDS is a major European defence consolidation.

Siemens AG has its corporate headquarters at the Wittelsbacherplatz Palais Ludwig Ferdinand in Munich, with the Siemens Werner-von-Siemens-Straße campus at Munich-Perlach, although the founding city is Berlin. Siemens Healthineers AG, the spin-off, is headquartered at Erlangen with the global headquarters for medical imaging at Forchheim and the Erlangen Siemens-Healthineers MedTech campus. Siemens Energy AG is headquartered in Munich. The Siemens Mobility division is at Munich and Erlangen and produces Velaro high-speed trains, the Vectron and Eurorunner locomotives, the Mireo regional EMU and the C2 underground stock. Siemens Mobility was the leading German signalling, train-control and rolling-stock manufacturer.

Allianz SE, the largest insurance company in Europe and one of the largest globally, has its head office at Königinstraße in Munich-Schwabing. Munich Re (Münchener Rückversicherungs-Gesellschaft), the world''s largest reinsurer, is based at the Königinstraße and Bavariaring in Munich. ERGO Group, a Munich Re subsidiary, is based at Düsseldorf but has substantial Bavarian operations. Knorr-Bremse AG, the world''s leading manufacturer of brake systems for rail and commercial vehicles, has its head office at Moosacher Straße in Munich. Linde plc, the world''s largest industrial-gases company by revenue, was originally founded by Carl von Linde at Wiesbaden but is closely tied to Munich, with its German technical headquarters at Pullach near Munich and the Linde Engineering plant at Schalchen. Wacker Chemie AG of Munich is one of the largest silicone, polysilicon, polymer and biotechnology producers globally, with major plants at Burghausen, Nünchritz and Munich. Bayerischer Rundfunk and Süddeutsche Verlag are media houses with substantial economic weight.

Adidas AG of Herzogenaurach in Middle Franconia is the second-largest sportswear company in the world, founded by Adolf Dassler in 1924 to make footwear for athletes. Across the Aurach in the same small town, Puma SE is headquartered, founded in 1948 by Adolf''s brother Rudolf Dassler after a family schism. Schaeffler AG of Herzogenaurach (the same town), the precision-bearings and automotive-supplier group, controls Schaeffler Automotive Buehl, FAG Kugelfischer Schweinfurt and Continental AG (since 2024 merger). INA-Werke, LuK, and other Schaeffler brands occupy plants across Herzogenaurach, Schweinfurt and Nuremberg. Schweinfurt also hosts SKF, the Swedish bearings company, in a major German plant.

Nuremberg is a corporate hub for Adidas''s competitors and for diecsi (the GfK consumer-research firm spun off into NielsenIQ), for Datev eG (the tax-software and accounting cooperative), for the Nuremberg Trade Fair (NürnbergMesse, host of the Spielwarenmesse toy fair, the BioFach organics fair, the embedded world electronics fair and the BrauBeviale), and for the leading SME bank consortium. Lebkuchen-Schmidt and Hauben & Schmidt continue the Nuremberg gingerbread tradition. Faber-Castell of Stein near Nuremberg is the oldest pencil maker in the world, founded in 1761. Staedtler of Nuremberg, founded by Friedrich Staedtler in 1835, makes the iconic Mars pencil and competes globally. Bosch Rexroth in Lohr am Main is a major hydraulics and automation house.

In Augsburg, MAN Energy Solutions, KUKA Robotics (the German robotics-arm maker, now owned by Midea of China), Premium Aerotec (an Airbus aerospace subsidiary), Patrizia AG (real-estate investment), and Manroland (printing presses) are concentrated. Augsburg University and the Hochschule Augsburg support a textile and digital cluster. The Bayerischer Maschinenbauverband and the Verband der Bayerischen Wirtschaft (vbw) lobby for the industrial sector.

In Lower Bavaria, BMW Dingolfing is the largest single employer, with around eighteen thousand staff. Wacker Chemie''s Burghausen plant is one of Europe''s largest chemical sites. Linde Engineering at Schalchen and the Inn-Salzach chemical triangle around Burghausen, Burgkirchen, Trostberg and Gendorf form a heavy-chemistry cluster. The Westerwerk in Mühldorf, the Trostberger Salzbergwerk and the Berchtesgaden Salt Mine continue salt extraction.

In Upper Franconia, the porcelain industry of Selb (Rosenthal, Hutschenreuther), Hohenberg (KPM-style), Marktredwitz and Tirschenreuth, together with the Bayreuth automotive supplier Brose (a global tier-one mechatronics supplier), the Coburg-based Brose corporate group, the Bayreuth-based BSH Bosch und Siemens Hausgeräte refrigeration plant, and the Schwan-STABILO writing-instruments company at Heroldsberg near Nuremberg, complete the eastern industrial mix.

In Middle Franconia, Nuremberg hosts Diehl Aerospace and Diehl Defence, Schaeffler Group, the GfK Group, NürnbergMesse, Datev, Sebald Druck, the medium-sized industries of Cadolzburg and the Roth-based Leoni AG (one of the world''s largest automotive cable harness manufacturers, restructured and recapitalised in 2023). Schwabach and Roth are gold-leaf and metallurgy centres. The InfraServ Bayreuth and the Faber-Castell campus complete the cluster. Erlangen, beyond Siemens Healthineers, hosts Areva GmbH (formerly Framatome ANP), the Max-Planck-Institut für die Physik des Lichts and the IBM Erlangen Service Center.

Aerospace is concentrated around Munich. Airbus Defence and Space at Ottobrunn-Taufkirchen, MTU Aero Engines AG at Munich-Karlsfeld (founded 1934, producer of the V2500, the PW1100G geared turbofan and the EJ200 fighter engine), Airbus Helicopters Deutschland at Donauwörth (in Bavarian Swabia), and Premium Aerotec at Augsburg, alongside the Eurofighter consortium and the Bundeswehr fleet, form a major aerospace cluster. The German Aerospace Center DLR Oberpfaffenhofen, the European Southern Observatory (ESO) Garching, the European Space Agency''s European Astronaut Centre in Cologne (Nordrhein-Westfalen), and the Max-Planck-Institut für extraterrestrische Physik form the research backbone.

Pharmaceuticals are concentrated at Penzberg (Roche, biotechnology and diagnostics), Holzkirchen (Sandoz Hexal), Pfaffenhofen-Donau and Penzberg (Roche Diagnostics including the Penzberg cell-culture campus). The Helmholtz Munich centre (formerly HMGU) and the Klinikum Großhadern at Munich, the LMU Hospital and the TUM Klinikum rechts der Isar are major medical research hubs. Munich-Martinsried hosts BioM, the Munich biotech cluster, around Morphosys (now part of Novartis), Medigene, Wilex and Crispr Therapeutics.

Banking and finance are concentrated at Munich (Münchener Hypothekenbank, UniCredit Bank AG formerly HVB, Bayerische Landesbank, KfW IPEX-Bank, FOM, AEW Europe and the Bavarian Stock Exchange Börse München, the latter Germany''s second-oldest stock exchange founded 1830 and a major retail-investor venue). The Sparkassenverband Bayern unites the regional savings banks. The cooperative banks are represented by Münchener Hypothekenbank and DZ Bank''s Bavarian branches.

Media include Süddeutsche Zeitung (one of Germany''s leading quality newspapers, published in Munich), Münchner Merkur, Abendzeitung, Nürnberger Nachrichten, Augsburger Allgemeine, Frankenpost, Bayerischer Rundfunk (the regional public broadcaster), ProSiebenSat.1 Media SE (Unterföhring near Munich), Sky Deutschland (Unterföhring), Burda Verlag (Offenburg in Baden-Württemberg but with extensive Bavarian operations), and Bauer Verlag publications. Munich hosts the Bavaria Film Studios at Geiselgasteig, home of major German film and TV production since 1919, including the original Wolfgang Petersen Das Boot and the Münchner Tatort.

Bavarian agriculture is the largest in Germany by total output, with milk, beef, hops (the largest German hop region by area, the Hallertau between Wolnzach, Pfaffenhofen, Mainburg and Spalt and Tettnang), barley, wheat, beer, asparagus, and bonsai-style alpine cheesemaking. Forestry covers a third of the state area, managed by Bayerische Staatsforsten. Tourism contributes a substantial share of GDP, with the Allgäu, the Berchtesgadener Land, Munich, the Romantic Road, Franconia and the Bavarian Forest being top destinations. Renewable energy is led by photovoltaics on Bavarian rooftops (the highest installed PV per capita in Germany) and by hydro power along the Inn, Isar, Lech and Danube; the BayWa AG of Munich is a major commodities and renewable-energy distributor.',
    introduced_species = 'Bavaria, with its vast forest cover, extensive Alpine ranges, abundant gravel pits and lakes along the Danube and Iller, and proximity to the Czech and Austrian frontiers, hosts a substantial roster of introduced and invasive species. The raccoon, Procyon lotor, German Waschbär, is established across the state with particularly dense populations in Mittelfranken (Middle Franconia), Oberfranken (Upper Franconia), the Steigerwald, the Bayerischer Wald and the Spessart, having spread south and east from the original 1934 Hessen release at Lake Eder and the later wartime release at Wolfshagen in Brandenburg. Annual hunting bags in Bavaria have grown from a few hundred in the late 1990s to many thousands per year by the early 2020s; Coburg, Bamberg, Forchheim, Lichtenfels and Würzburg districts have particularly conspicuous populations. Urban raccoons exploit Munich gardens (Schwabing, Bogenhausen, Pasing), Augsburg, Nuremberg-Erlangen-Fürth, Würzburg, Bamberg and Bayreuth, where attic invasions and rubbish-bin foraging are increasingly common. The Bavarian state veterinary office monitors raccoons for Baylisascaris procyonis roundworm and for the canine distemper virus that occasionally erupts in regional die-offs. As elsewhere, Bavarian raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl, beech marten chicks), on amphibians (yellow-bellied toad, common toad), on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis), and on the rare hazel dormouse and edible dormouse, has been the subject of conservation studies by the Landesanstalt für Wald- und Forstwirtschaft (LWF) and the Landesamt für Umwelt (LfU).

The raccoon dog, Marderhund or Enok, Nyctereutes procyonoides, reached Bavaria from the north and east in the 1990s through the 2000s, with the first verified records in Upper Franconia and Lower Bavaria; populations are now well-established along the Danube, the Inn, the lower Isar, the Naab, the Regen and the Czech border, with annual hunting bags rising. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List; co-operation with Czech and Austrian authorities through Interreg programmes is active. Local conservation concern centres on raccoon-dog predation on ground-nesting birds (capercaillie in the Bavarian Forest, lapwing in the Donaumoos, corncrake in the Iller wetlands).

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the lower Main below Aschaffenburg, the Main between Würzburg and Bamberg, the Danube from Ulm to Passau, the Inn near Mühldorf and Burghausen, the lower Isar, and the Altmühltal. Damage to flood-protection dykes by burrowing and to reedbeds by overgrazing is a serious management concern; the Wasserwirtschaftsämter at Würzburg, Bamberg, Regensburg and Deggendorf coordinate professional trapping. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Bavaria but reintroduced by the Bund Naturschutz from the 1960s, has rebounded so successfully that beaver management is now itself a major conservation issue.

The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs in slow water bodies across the state, with conspicuous populations in the gravel pits along the Isar, the Lech, the Iller and the Donau. The muskrat-trapping mandate continues under the Bayerisches Wassergesetz.

Among birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis (Kanadagans), has established feral resident populations along the Main, the lower Danube, the Bodensee and the Isar; flocks regularly winter at the Munich Olympiapark lake, the Englischer Garten Kleinhesseloher See, the Walchensee, the Würzburg Mainwiesen and the Bamberg Hain. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations since the early 2000s and now breeds across Bavaria, especially in the Munich, Augsburg, Nuremberg-Fürth-Erlangen, Regensburg and Würzburg conurbations. Greater flamingos (Phoenicopterus roseus) escaped from a Zwillbrocker Venn (NRW) population can occasionally be seen at the Ismaninger Speichersee near Munich. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is establishing breeding populations along the Rhine corridor outside Bavaria but is occasional in Aschaffenburg and Würzburg. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, has small feral populations in Munich and on the Bodensee. The Indian peafowl (Pavo cristatus) has wild-living populations on some Munich and Würzburg estates. Releases of the wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, in Bavarian hunting reserves have not produced self-sustaining populations.

Among fish, the rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss (Regenbogenforelle), introduced from North America in the late nineteenth century, is widely stocked in Bavarian streams and produced in aquaculture; the brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis (Bachsaibling), and the Atlantic salmon (Lachs) are stocked. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus (Sonnenbarsch), occurs in slow waters of the Main and lower Danube. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva (Blaubandbärbling), arrived via the carp aquaculture trade and is now ubiquitous in slow waters across the state. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus (Zwergwels), occurs in old gravel pits. The Wels catfish, Silurus glanis (Wels), is native to the Danube but has been transplanted to the Main and is sometimes considered a translocated species there. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus (Schwarzmaul-Grundel), and the bighead goby, Ponticola kessleri, and the Caspian Kessler''s goby have reached Bavaria from the Black Sea via the Main-Danube Canal, with explosive expansion observed in the lower Main since 2011 and the lower Danube since 2010. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella (Graskarpfen), is stocked in lakes to control aquatic vegetation. The Asian carps (silver carp Hypophthalmichthys molitrix, bighead carp H. nobilis) are in pond aquaculture. The sterlet, Acipenser ruthenus, is native to the Danube but heavily augmented by stocking.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus (Signalkrebs), now widespread in Bavarian streams; it carries the crayfish plague that has decimated the native noble crayfish (Astacus astacus). The red swamp crayfish, Procambarus clarkii (Roter Sumpfkrebs), is established in Bavarian gravel pits, park ponds in Munich and the Aischgrund. The spinycheek crayfish, Faxonius limosus (Kamberkrebs), has been in Bavaria since the early twentieth century. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis (Marmorkrebs), a parthenogenetic species first found in a German aquarist''s tank, occurs in small populations. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis (Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe), is recorded in the Main and Danube. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha (Dreikantmuschel), and the quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis (Quaggamuschel), are abundant in the lakes and reservoirs. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea (Körbchenmuschel), is in the Danube and Main. The New Zealand mud snail, Potamopyrgus antipodarum, is widespread.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax (Asiatische Hornisse), reached Bavaria in 2020-2021 with confirmed nests near Aschaffenburg, Würzburg, Regensburg and Munich-Pasing in subsequent years; the species feeds on honeybees and prompts intensive imker (beekeeper) and Bayerischer Landesverband für Bienenzucht effort to locate and remove primary and secondary nests. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis (Asiatischer Marienkäfer), is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Munich Hofgarten and the Würzburg Residenzgarten avenues every summer. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis (Buchsbaumzünsler), has wiped out boxwood gardens in Würzburg, Bamberg, Augsburg, Regensburg and Munich since 2009. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys (Marmorierte Baumwanze), is established in southern Bavaria. The pine processionary caterpillar (Thaumetopoea pityocampa) and the oak processionary moth (Thaumetopoea processionea) are climate-driven expansion species causing widespread health concern.

Among plants, ragweed, Ambrosia artemisiifolia (Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut), is widespread along Bavarian roadsides, railway lines, gravel pits and on disturbed ground in Mittel- and Oberfranken, with allergenic implications. Japanese knotweed, Reynoutria japonica (Japanknöterich), dominates riverbanks of the Main, Pegnitz, Regnitz, Isar, Inn and Lech. Bohemian knotweed, Reynoutria bohemica, and the giant knotweed, Reynoutria sachalinensis, are also present. Himalayan balsam, Impatiens glandulifera (Drüsiges Springkraut), is widespread along Bavarian Mittelgebirgen and the Bavarian Forest streams. Giant hogweed, Heracleum mantegazzianum (Riesen-Bärenklau), occurs scattered, mostly in Upper Franconia and the Bavarian Forest, with phototoxic-sap hazard for hikers. Goldenrod, Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea, dominates fallow fields and ruderal habitats. Tree of heaven, Ailanthus altissima (Götterbaum), spreads along railway lines and in the brownfields of Munich, Nuremberg, Augsburg and Würzburg. Indian balsam, the water primrose Ludwigia grandiflora, and the Asian rice weed Murdannia keisak have been recorded sporadically. Common ragwort (Jacobaea vulgaris), although native, has expanded in pasture land; the Allgäu and the Frankenalb both report rising abundance.

The Bavarian Forest National Park (Nationalpark Bayerischer Wald), the Berchtesgaden National Park, and the Naturpark Altmühltal coordinate alien-species monitoring within their boundaries. The Landesamt für Umwelt (LfU) at Augsburg maintains the Neobiota register for Bavaria under EU Regulation 1143/2014. Targeted Asian hornet response teams operate from the Bavarian Beekeeping Institute at Veitshöchheim near Würzburg; ragweed control programmes are run by the Bayerische Landesanstalt für Weinbau und Gartenbau and the Bayerische Landesanstalt für Landwirtschaft, with reports collected via the Ambrosia-Atlas. The Wieskirche cult of pre-industrial-era pilgrimage routes still serves up clusters of giant hogweed in pasture buffer-strips that the Wasserwirtschaftsamt monitors. Among game species, mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) and fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) are widely naturalised in Bavarian hunting reserves; small populations of sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) are known in the Bayerischer Wald and the Frankenwald. American mink (Neovison vison) is rare. The European wildcat, while native, has been bolstered by reintroductions in the Steigerwald and Spessart.'
WHERE region_name = 'Bayern';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Berlin, the capital and largest city of Germany, is also one of the sixteen federal states, a Stadtstaat with the legal status of a Land. It occupies a central position on the river Spree, with its tributary the Havel forming the western lake district. The city is famous worldwide for its layered history, its arts and music scene, its multicultural population and the open spaces of its parks and lakes. The most iconic landmark is the Brandenburger Tor, the Brandenburg Gate, designed by Carl Gotthard Langhans and completed in 1791, crowned by the Quadriga sculpture by Johann Gottfried Schadow of the goddess Victoria driving a chariot. The gate stands at the western end of Unter den Linden, the great east-west avenue laid out by the Great Elector Friedrich Wilhelm in the seventeenth century, lined today by embassies, the Hotel Adlon Kempinski, the Pariser Platz with the Akademie der Künste, the DZ Bank by Frank Gehry, the United States Embassy by Moore Ruble Yudell, and the French Embassy. Further east the avenue passes the Russian Embassy, the Friedrichstraße crossing, the State Opera Berlin (Staatsoper Unter den Linden) restored by HG Merz in 2017, the Bebelplatz where Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg-style debates carry no weight beside the Empty Library memorial of Micha Ullman, the Humboldt University (Humboldt-Universität zu Berlin), the Neue Wache memorial by Karl Friedrich Schinkel with the Käthe Kollwitz sculpture, the Zeughaus (the former arsenal, now the Deutsches Historisches Museum with the IM Pei extension), and finally crosses the Schlossbrücke to the Schlossplatz with the rebuilt Berliner Schloss housing the Humboldt Forum since 2021.

Museum Island, Museumsinsel, in the Spree, is one of the world''s great cultural ensembles and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Five museums share the island. The Altes Museum, designed by Karl Friedrich Schinkel and completed in 1830, faces the Lustgarten and the Berliner Dom and houses the Antikensammlung classical antiquities. The Neues Museum, by Friedrich August Stüler and reopened in 2009 after David Chipperfield''s austere restoration, contains the Egyptian Museum with the bust of Queen Nefertiti (one of the most-photographed objects in any museum), the Berlin Green Head, and the Schliemann Trojan gold (a few items returned, most still in Pushkin Moscow). The Pergamon Museum, named for the monumental Hellenistic Pergamon Altar that has been removed for the long-running restoration project, currently displays the Market Gate of Miletus, the Ishtar Gate from Babylon with its blue glazed bricks and lions, and the Mshatta Façade; the Pergamon Altar will return when the renovation completes after 2027. The Bode Museum at the northern tip of the island, completed by Ernst von Ihne in 1904, displays the sculpture collection of the Skulpturensammlung and the Byzantine Coin Collection. The Alte Nationalgalerie, modelled on a Greek temple by Stüler, holds nineteenth-century painting and sculpture including Caspar David Friedrich, Adolph von Menzel, Lovis Corinth and Max Liebermann. The James Simon Galerie by David Chipperfield, the new visitor centre opened in 2019, ties the ensemble together. The Berliner Dom, the Hohenzollern court cathedral by Julius Carl Raschdorff, dominates the island''s southern bank, with the Wilhelm I memorial chapel and the Hohenzollern crypt of ninety-four sarcophagi.

Beyond the Museumsinsel, the Humboldt Forum in the rebuilt Berliner Schloss houses the Ethnologisches Museum and Museum für Asiatische Kunst with collections from Africa, Oceania, the Americas, East Asia and Oceania, alongside an exhibition on the history of the city of Berlin. The Gemäldegalerie at the Kulturforum holds the city''s old-master paintings (Vermeer, Rembrandt, Caravaggio, Bruegel, Velázquez), beside the Neue Nationalgalerie by Ludwig Mies van der Rohe (now restored by David Chipperfield, 2021) for twentieth-century art, the Kunstgewerbemuseum, the Kupferstichkabinett print room, the Musical Instrument Museum, the Staatsbibliothek Berlin (immortalised by Wim Wenders in Wings of Desire) and the Berliner Philharmonie by Hans Scharoun, home of the Berliner Philharmoniker. The Hamburger Bahnhof for contemporary art, the Berlinische Galerie for the city''s twentieth-century art including the Berlin Secession and the Neue Sachlichkeit, the Käthe Kollwitz Museum, the Bröhan-Museum, the Brücke-Museum, the Helmut Newton Foundation in the Museum für Fotografie, the C/O Berlin in the former Amerika Haus, the KW Institute for Contemporary Art, the Berggruen Museum, the Sammlung Scharf-Gerstenberg, the Boros Bunker, the Feuerle Collection in the former Reichsbahn telecommunications bunker, the Me Collectors Room, and Hamburger Bahnhof''s Rieckhallen complete the contemporary art map.

The Reichstag building, designed by Paul Wallot and reconstructed by Sir Norman Foster with its famous glass dome reopened in 1999, is the seat of the German Bundestag and a major tourist attraction with free ascent to the dome by online reservation. Beside it the Federal Chancellery (Bundeskanzleramt) by Axel Schultes and Charlotte Frank, the Paul-Löbe-Haus and the Marie-Elisabeth-Lüders-Haus form the so-called Band des Bundes, the federal ribbon across the river. The Tiergarten, the great central park created by Peter Joseph Lenné, contains the Siegessäule victory column with the gilded Goldelse Victoria atop a pillar moved by Albert Speer in the 1930s (the column''s pre-war Königsplatz site is now occupied by the Federal Chancellery garden), the Schloss Bellevue, the Soviet War Memorial at the western Brandenburger Tor approach, the Bismarckdenkmal, the House of World Cultures (Haus der Kulturen der Welt, the so-called Pregnant Oyster), and walking paths to the Zoologischer Garten Berlin with its famous Aquarium next door.

Charlottenburg Palace (Schloss Charlottenburg), the largest Hohenzollern palace in Berlin, was built by Johann Arnold Nering and Eosander von Göthe for Sophie Charlotte, queen of Frederick I; the New Wing by Knobelsdorff under Frederick the Great contains the Watteau room with the Embarkation for Cythera. The Belvedere in the gardens houses Berlin porcelain. The mausoleum holds Queen Luise. Schloss Bellevue is the residence of the Federal President; Schloss Glienicke and Schloss Pfaueninsel on the Havel river complete the Hohenzollern palace network within Berlin. Across the Glienicke Bridge in Potsdam (Brandenburg) lies the UNESCO ensemble of Sanssouci, Cecilienhof, Babelsberg Palace, the New Palace and the Charlottenhof.

Other major sights include the Gendarmenmarkt with the Konzerthaus by Schinkel and the French and German Cathedrals (Französischer Dom, Deutscher Dom); Potsdamer Platz with the Sony Center by Helmut Jahn, the Kollhoff-Tower, the DB Tower and the Daimler quarter laid out by Renzo Piano; the Berlin Wall Memorial at Bernauer Straße with a preserved stretch of the inner wall, the watchtower, the death strip and the Window of Remembrance; the East Side Gallery, the longest open-air gallery of Wall paintings; the Topography of Terror documentation centre on the former Prinz-Albrecht-Straße; the Holocaust Memorial (Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe) by Peter Eisenman beside the Brandenburger Tor; Checkpoint Charlie with the Mauermuseum; the Berlin TV Tower (Fernsehturm) at Alexanderplatz, the tallest structure in Germany at 368 metres, with its rotating restaurant; the Welt-Zeit-Uhr World Time Clock; the Marienkirche; the Nikolaiviertel with the Knoblauchhaus; the Hackescher Markt with the Hackesche Höfe Art-Nouveau courtyard ensemble; the Friedrichstadt-Passagen including the Galeries Lafayette by Jean Nouvel; the KaDeWe (Kaufhaus des Westens), the largest department store in continental Europe; the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Gedächtniskirche on the Breitscheidplatz with its ruined tower and Egon Eiermann''s blue-glass annex; the Tempelhofer Feld, the former central airport closed in 2008 now Berlin''s largest open space and beloved as a citizen-managed park; the Treptower Park with the Soviet War Memorial; the Mauerpark on a Sundays for karaoke and flea market; the Olympiastadion home of Hertha BSC and a regular German football cup final venue; the Funkturm radio tower; the AVUS racetrack; the Grunewald forest with the Teufelsberg artificial hill made from war rubble and crowned with the former NSA listening station now an art and graffiti site; the Wannsee with the Strandbad Wannsee lido; the Liebermann Villa with Max Liebermann''s garden paintings; the Pfaueninsel island with peacocks; the Spreepark abandoned amusement park; the Volkspark Friedrichshain; the Botanischer Garten Berlin in Dahlem; and the Tierpark Berlin in Friedrichsfelde, one of the largest landscape zoos in Europe.

Berlin is a global capital of music and performing arts. The Berliner Philharmoniker, founded 1882 and based in the Philharmonie, has been led by Hans von Bülow, Arthur Nikisch, Wilhelm Furtwängler, Herbert von Karajan, Claudio Abbado, Sir Simon Rattle and currently Kirill Petrenko. The Staatsoper Unter den Linden, the Deutsche Oper Berlin, the Komische Oper Berlin and the Konzerthaus Berlin form the operatic and concert backbone. The Schaubühne am Lehniner Platz, the Berliner Ensemble (founded by Bertolt Brecht and Helene Weigel in 1949), the Volksbühne, the Deutsches Theater, the Gorki Theater and the Friedrichstadt-Palast revue theatre lead the drama scene. The annual Berlin International Film Festival (Berlinale) in February, the Berlin Music Week, the Festival of Lights, the Long Night of Museums, the Christopher Street Day pride parade, the Karneval der Kulturen, the Internationale Funkausstellung (IFA), the InterTabac, the Bread and Butter and the Maerzmusik festival of contemporary music structure the cultural calendar. The Berlin techno scene around Berghain (the legendary club in the former Wriezener Bahnhof heating plant), Tresor, ://about blank, Watergate, Sisyphos and Kater Blau is internationally famous and supported by the city''s techno club culture having been added to the UNESCO list of intangible cultural heritage of Germany in 2024.

The cuisine of Berlin reflects three centuries of working-class, Prussian and immigrant influence. The Currywurst, a pork sausage with curry-tomato sauce, was invented by Herta Heuwer at her snack stand in Charlottenburg in 1949; the city now hosts a Currywurst Museum. The Berliner Boulette (the local meatball) is served with mustard and a Schrippe roll; the Berliner Pfannkuchen, the jelly doughnut known elsewhere as Berliner, is a Carnival and New Year staple. Eisbein (boiled pork knuckle, distinct from Bavarian Schweinshaxe) is served with Sauerkraut and Erbspüree (pea purée). Königsberger Klopse (the East Prussian dish brought by refugees) and Hoppelpoppel (a leftovers hash) are home dishes. Solyanka, a sour-spicy stew of Russian origin, became a staple of East Berlin Gaststätten. The Berliner Weiße (a sour wheat beer drunk with green Waldmeister or red raspberry syrup, the so-called Berliner Weiße mit Schuss), Berliner Pilsner, Schultheiss, Berliner Kindl, BRLO and the new craft-beer brewers, plus Spreewald gherkins, the Spreewald-Pickle being a Berlin staple, complete the table. The Türkenmarkt at Maybachufer in Neukölln, the Markthalle Neun in Kreuzberg, the Markthalle in Moabit and the food markets of Prenzlauer Berg reflect Berlin''s Turkish, Vietnamese, Lebanese, Syrian and Indian immigrant cuisines, of which the Berlin döner-kebab in a bread pocket was developed by Kadir Nurman in 1972 and Mehmet Aygün at the Hasir restaurant.

The history before 1933 is dense. The double settlement of Berlin and Cölln on the Spree was first documented in the thirteenth century; the Hohenzollerns took possession in 1415 as electors of Brandenburg, raised the Margraviate of Brandenburg to the Kingdom of Prussia in 1701 under Friedrich I, and built Berlin into a baroque royal residence under Friedrich the Great. The eighteenth century saw the Forum Fridericianum, the Bebelplatz ensemble, the Royal Library and the Operahouse; the nineteenth century saw the Industrial Revolution that turned Berlin into a city of more than two million by 1900, with the AEG works at Wedding, the Borsig locomotive works, the Siemens works at Charlottenburg, and the trade in machine tools, electrical equipment, chemicals (Schering) and textiles. The unification of Germany in 1871 made Berlin the imperial capital. The Weimar Republic of 1919-1933 turned Berlin into a global capital of modernism: the Bauhaus directors Walter Gropius, Hannes Meyer and Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, the Berlin Secession, the Sturm gallery of Herwarth Walden, the cabarets of the Romanisches Café, the films of UFA at Babelsberg (Metropolis, Der blaue Engel, M), the playwrights Bertolt Brecht and Kurt Weill (The Threepenny Opera premiered at the Theater am Schiffbauerdamm in 1928), the architecture of the Hufeisensiedlung and Falkenberg garden cities (UNESCO Berlin Modernism Housing Estates), and the science of the Kaiser Wilhelm institutes (the Einstein Tower in Potsdam by Erich Mendelsohn dating from 1924) made the city the most exciting in Europe. After 1945 Berlin was divided into four occupation zones, the Soviet-controlled East and the three Western sectors. The Berlin Blockade of 1948-1949 and the Berlin Airlift, the Berlin Wall construction in 1961 and its fall on the night of 9-10 November 1989, the German reunification on 3 October 1990 and the return of the federal government from Bonn in 1999 are the four hinge moments of the post-war story. Famous figures from Berlin include Albert Einstein (Nobel Prize 1921 while he was Director of the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Institut), Max Planck, Otto Hahn, Lise Meitner, Robert Koch, Rudolf Virchow, Theodor Mommsen, the Brothers Grimm, the Humboldt brothers Wilhelm and Alexander, Karl Friedrich Schinkel, Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy, Marlene Dietrich (born in Schöneberg), Christopher Isherwood, and David Bowie''s Hansa Tonstudio Berlin Trilogy.',
    transportation = 'Berlin has the most extensive urban rail network in Germany and one of the most complex in Europe, the legacy of a divided city in which both East and West built parallel networks to compensate for the disconnection of the Berlin Wall. Berlin Brandenburg Airport, IATA BER and ICAO EDDB, finally opened on 31 October 2020 after nine years of well-publicised delays, financial scandals and technical failures. BER replaced both Berlin Tegel (TXL, IATA EDDT), which closed on 4 November 2020 and is now being redeveloped into the Schumacher Quartier and Urban Tech Republic, and Berlin Schönefeld (SXF, EDDB), the former East German airport which has been integrated as Terminal 5 of BER and which closed as a separate facility in 2020. BER, named Willy Brandt after the late Chancellor, lies fifteen kilometres south-east of central Berlin in the Brandenburg town of Schönefeld, with two parallel runways, three terminals and the integrated Bahnhof Berlin Brandenburg Airport beneath the main terminal building, served by S-Bahn S9 and S45, regional services RE7 and RB14, and the Flughafen-Express FEX from Berlin Hauptbahnhof at fifteen-minute intervals. The airport handles around twenty-five million passengers a year and is the main base for Lufthansa, easyJet, Ryanair, Eurowings, TUI fly, Condor, Wizz Air, Turkish Airlines, Aeroflot (suspended), Etihad, Qatar Airways, and Emirates among others. The historic Tempelhof Airport, closed in 2008 and converted to the public park Tempelhofer Feld, is one of the largest urban open spaces in Europe and home to the annual Tempelhof Sounds festival and the Berlin Marathon expo.

Berlin Hauptbahnhof, the central station opened in May 2006 by Meinhard von Gerkan of GMP Architects, is the largest grade-separated through-station in Europe, with five levels of platforms, two underground long-distance levels carrying the new north-south tunnel for ICE trains, one S-Bahn level, the surface Stadtbahn east-west level and the ground-level concourse. The Stadtbahn east-west viaduct, opened in 1882, links Berlin Hauptbahnhof with Friedrichstraße, Alexanderplatz, Ostbahnhof and Lichtenberg. The Berlin north-south long-distance tunnel, opened in 2006 with Hauptbahnhof, runs to Südkreuz via Potsdamer Platz. Other major railway stations are Berlin Ostbahnhof (the East German main station historically and the eastern Stadtbahn terminus), Berlin Friedrichstraße (a Stadtbahn station important as the Cold War border-crossing and Tränenpalast departure hall), Berlin Spandau, Berlin Südkreuz on the southern Ring, Berlin Lichtenberg (the historic East Berlin long-distance station and current eastern Stadtbahn end), Berlin Gesundbrunnen on the northern Ring, Berlin Charlottenburg and Berlin Zoologischer Garten (the former main station of West Berlin during the Wall years, immortalised as a meeting place in Christiane F.). Other regional Bahnhöfe include Berlin Wannsee, Berlin Schönefeld Bahnhof, Berlin Karlshorst and Berlin Pankow.

The ICE network through Berlin includes the Berlin-Hamburg corridor at 230 kph (with running times under ninety minutes via Wittenberge), the Berlin-Hannover high-speed line via Wolfsburg (opened 1998 as Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit 4), the Berlin-Frankfurt corridor via Hannover or via Erfurt-Nuremberg-Würzburg-Frankfurt, the Berlin-Leipzig-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich high-speed line (VDE 8 completed in December 2017 cutting the Berlin-Munich travel time to under four hours), the Berlin-Dresden line being upgraded, the Berlin-Stettin (Szczecin in Poland) cross-border services as RE3 and Eurocity trains, the Berlin-Warsaw Express Berlin-Warszawa-Express via Frankfurt (Oder) and Poznan, the Berlin-Prague Eurocity via Dresden, and night trains via ÖBB Nightjet and EuroNight to Zürich, Vienna, Budapest, Bucharest and Stockholm via the Snälltåget service. Cross-border regional rail includes the Niederbarnimer Eisenbahn (NEB), the Ostdeutsche Eisenbahn (ODEG), and the Deutsche Bahn Regio Nordost.

The Berlin U-Bahn, opened in 1902, is the oldest and largest underground railway in Germany, with nine lines (U1 through U9) totalling 156 kilometres and 175 stations, operated by Berliner Verkehrsbetriebe (BVG). The U1 from Warschauer Straße to Uhlandstraße runs on the elevated viaduct over Kreuzberg; the U2 from Pankow to Ruhleben passes Alexanderplatz, Potsdamer Platz, Bülowstraße and Wittenbergplatz; the U3 from Krumme Lanke to Warschauer Straße; the U4 short shuttle from Nollendorfplatz to Innsbrucker Platz built to serve the Wilmersdorf burgher quarter in 1910; the U5 from Hönow to Hauptbahnhof, the extension to Brandenburger Tor and Hauptbahnhof having opened in December 2020; the U6 from Alt-Tegel to Alt-Mariendorf; the U7 from Rathaus Spandau to Rudow, at thirty-two kilometres the longest fully underground line in Germany; the U8 from Wittenau to Hermannstraße; and the U9 from Osloer Straße to Rathaus Steglitz. The eastern U-Bahn small-profile lines have a narrower loading gauge inherited from the original Hochbahn.

The Berlin S-Bahn, the suburban railway dating from 1882 and electrified at 750 V DC third rail since 1924, operates fifteen lines (S1 through S46) covering 332 kilometres of route around the city. The Ringbahn, a circular line completed in 1877, runs around inner Berlin with stations at Gesundbrunnen, Schönhauser Allee, Ostkreuz, Treptower Park, Tempelhof, Südkreuz, Schöneberg, Westkreuz, Halensee, Westend, Jungfernheide and Beusselstraße. The Stadtbahn east-west viaduct from Westkreuz to Ostbahnhof and beyond carries S5, S7 and S75. The radial S1 to S2 to S3 to S5 to S7 to S8 to S9 to S25 to S26 to S41 (Ring) to S42 (Ring) to S45 to S46 and S47 lines criss-cross the city. Stadler Pankow and Siemens have begun delivering the new BR 483/484 class to replace the BR 480 and BR 481 trains; the city is also experimenting with battery-electric multiple units for the eastern outer Brandenburg lines. The S-Bahn operates from before 4 am to past 1 am, with weekend night service. Tickets are sold by the VBB Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg fare integration.

The Berlin tram (Strassenbahn) network is the largest in Germany and the third-largest in the world after Melbourne and St Petersburg, with twenty-two lines totalling almost two hundred kilometres, almost all in the former East Berlin and the Prenzlauer Berg, Mitte, Friedrichshain, Lichtenberg, Marzahn and Treptow districts. Extensions into the western Wedding and Moabit boroughs are gradually being added. The MetroTram services (M1, M2, M4, M5, M6, M8, M10, M13, M17) run at frequent intervals; ordinary tram lines 12, 16, 21, 27, 37, 50, 60, 61, 62, 63, 67 and 68 reach more peripheral districts. The BVG also operates an extensive bus network with the MetroBus (M11, M19, M27, M29, M32, M37, M41, M44, M45, M46, M48, M49, M76, M77, M82, M85), the Express buses X7 and X9 to BER and Spandau, the night-bus N-lines, the famous double-decker buses on the western boulevards, and the Spree ferries integrated into the VBB tariff.

The Autobahn network around Berlin centres on the A10 (Berliner Ring), the largest motorway ring in Europe at 196 kilometres, with the A11 to Stettin, the A12 to Frankfurt (Oder), the A13 to Dresden, the A19 to Rostock, the A20 northern transit, the A24 to Hamburg, and the A2 to Hannover/Ruhrgebiet. Within the city the A100 inner ring runs from the Wedding through Schöneberg and Neukölln to Treptow, with the controversial A100 extension to Friedrichshain a chronic political and planning saga. The A111 to Hamburger Straße and the A113 to BER airport connect specific corridors. Major Bundesstraßen include the B1 east-west (the historical Frankfurter Allee axis), the B2 to Strausberg, and the B96 to BER.

The Spree-Oder Waterway carries cargo and tourist traffic from the Westhafen Berlin (Berlin''s main inland port operated by BEHALA) via the Spree, the Mühlendammschleuse, the Müggelspree, the Dahme and the Oder-Spree-Kanal to Eisenhüttenstadt and the Oder. Stern und Kreis-Schifffahrt, Reederei Riedel and other operators run sightseeing cruises on the Spree, the Landwehrkanal, the Havel, Lake Wannsee, the Müggelsee and the Tegeler See. Long-distance cycle routes include the EuroVelo 7 (Sun route from North Cape to Malta) via the Berlin Wall Trail (Mauerweg) around the former perimeter, the Berlin-Copenhagen cycle route, the Spree-Radweg, the Havel-Radweg, the Elbe-Radweg approach, the Oder-Neisse-Radweg and the European East-West route. The Berlin Wall Cycle Trail (Berliner Mauerweg) is a 160-kilometre signposted route around the former line of the inner-city Wall and the outer Wall around West Berlin. Long-distance buses use the ZOB Berlin Messedamm/Zoologischer Garten, with FlixBus, Sindbad and others operating to Eastern Europe.

Berlin pioneered the Strassenbahn in 1881 (Werner von Siemens built the first electric tram from Lichterfelde station to the cadet school) and pioneered the U-Bahn with the Hochbahn from Stralauer Tor to Knie in 1902. Today the city is a leader in shared and electric mobility, with Share Now, Miles, SIXT Share, Sixt Plus, Nextbike, Tier, Lime and Bolt operating fleets; CallaBike, the DB-owned bike rental, was a Berlin pioneer in 2002. The city''s S-Bahn Ringbahn, S-Bahn Stadtbahn, U-Bahn, tram, bus and ferry are unified under the VBB-Tarif with the Deutschlandticket since 2023.',
    economics = 'Berlin is the third-largest German metropolitan economy after the Rhine-Ruhr and Munich agglomerations, with a regional GDP of around one hundred and seventy billion euros. The economic structure is unique among the German Bundesländer because Berlin lost virtually all its industrial base in 1945 and the Cold War partition, and has since rebuilt as a service-led, government-, tourism- and technology-driven city economy. The Berliner Wirtschaftsförderung and Berlin Partner GmbH market the city internationally.

The largest single sector is government and public administration, since Berlin is the capital of the Federal Republic of Germany. The Bundestag at the Reichstag building, the Bundesrat at the former Prussian House of Lords, the Federal Chancellery, the Federal Presidency at Bellevue, fifteen federal ministries (the Foreign Office at Werderscher Markt, the Finance Ministry in the former Reichsluftfahrtministerium building, the Interior Ministry, the Defence Ministry at the Bendlerblock, the Justice Ministry, the Economy Ministry, the Labour Ministry, the Education Ministry, the Health Ministry, the Transport Ministry, the Environment Ministry, the Agriculture Ministry, the Family Ministry, the Development Ministry, and the Digital and Transport Ministry) employ tens of thousands of civil servants. Berlin also hosts the federal Bundesbank Hauptverwaltung Berlin, the Bundesnachrichtendienst BND new headquarters on Chausseestraße (the largest intelligence-agency building in the world by floor area), the Federal Criminal Police BKA Berlin office, the Federal Network Agency Bundesnetzagentur, the Federal Cartel Office Bundeskartellamt (Bonn) and other federal agencies. Approximately one hundred and seventy foreign embassies, the European Commission Representation in Germany, and the Berlin offices of more than four hundred political foundations, trade unions, business federations, NGOs and lobby groups (the Federation of German Industries BDI, the German Trade Union Federation DGB, the German Employers'' Association BDA, the Confederation of German Trade Unions DGB, the Chamber of Industry and Commerce DIHK, the Federal Association of Wholesale and Foreign Trade BGA, the Council on Foreign Relations DGAP, the Friedrich Ebert Foundation, the Konrad Adenauer Foundation, the Hans Seidel Foundation, the Heinrich Böll Foundation, the Rosa Luxemburg Foundation, the Friedrich Naumann Foundation, and Transparency International Germany) crowd the Berlin Mitte district. The Bundesnachrichtendienst, the Bundeskanzleramt, the Federal Audit Office and the Federal Constitutional Court (in Karlsruhe) are major employers.

Berlin is Germany''s leading start-up city. The Silicon Allee tech scene around the Rosenthaler Platz, the Factory Berlin co-working campuses at Mitte and Görlitzer Park, the BetaHaus and Mindspace co-working spaces, the Berlin Spreepark accelerator, the Rocket Internet network and the Berlin Innovation Hubs have produced an outsized number of European unicorns and decacorns. Zalando SE, the fashion e-commerce giant headquartered at the Friedrichshain campus, is the largest Berlin-headquartered company on the DAX with annual revenues above ten billion euros. HelloFresh SE, the meal-kit delivery company, is also DAX-listed and headquartered at Saarbrücker Straße. Delivery Hero SE, the Berlin-headquartered food-delivery giant with the Foodora, Foodpanda and Glovo brands, operates in over seventy countries. N26 Bank GmbH, the Berlin-headquartered neobank, is one of Europe''s largest mobile banks. Trade Republic, Solaris, Mambu, Raisin (Weltsparen), Penta, Tomorrow and other Berlin fintechs share the financial-technology ecosystem. SoundCloud, headquartered in Berlin since 2007, is the dominant European music-streaming start-up. GetYourGuide, the experience booking platform, is at Mitte. Auto1 Group, Choco, Tier Mobility, Babbel (the language-learning platform), Researchgate, Wooga, GoStudent, eGym, IDnow, Honeypot, Pitch, Volocopter (Berlin office), Bryter, Quantilope, Smava, Smartfrog, Wandelbots, Workpath and the Springer Nature science publisher all have Berlin operations. Berlin-based Sennder is the largest digital road-freight broker in Europe. The Berlin venture-capital scene includes Earlybird, Project A, Lakestar, Acton Capital, Cherry Ventures, Holtzbrinck Ventures, GFC (Global Founders Capital) and the BMW i Ventures group. The Berlin Founders Fund and the German Federal Government''s WIN initiative, plus the Berlin Innovation Senate funding line, top up capital availability.

Berlin is Germany''s leading media capital. The Axel Springer SE publishing group, founded in 1946, is headquartered at the Axel-Springer-Haus on Rudi-Dutschke-Straße with the new Rem Koolhaas-designed Axel Springer Neubau opened 2020; Axel Springer owns Bild, Welt, Welt am Sonntag, BZ, Auto Bild, Computer Bild, Insider Inc., Politico (US), Politico Europe, eMarketer/Insider Intelligence and the WeltN24 broadcaster. The Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg (RBB) is the regional ARD broadcaster with studios at Masurenallee and at Babelsberg, although the RBB is currently in restructuring after a 2022 management scandal. Deutsche Welle, Germany''s international broadcaster, has its second headquarters at the Voltastraße in Wedding, with the Bonn headquarters retained. The Berliner Verlag publishes the Berliner Zeitung, the Berliner Kurier and the Berliner Abendblatt; the taz die tageszeitung is the alternative-leaning national daily; the Tagesspiegel, owned by Holtzbrinck Publishing Group, is the leading liberal Berlin daily; the Die Welt newspaper (Axel Springer) competes with the Süddeutsche Zeitung in the quality market. Springer Nature Group, the global science-publishing house (Nature, Scientific American, Springer journals), is jointly headquartered in Berlin and London. The Berliner Verlag building Allianz building beside the Bahnhof Hackescher Markt, the WeltN24 channel, the Berlin offices of Bertelsmann (Gütersloh), the German Press Agency (dpa, Hamburg) Berlin office, and the major streaming platforms (Netflix, Amazon Prime Video Germany, Disney Plus, Paramount Plus) cluster the media industry around Mitte and Kreuzberg. The famous Babelsberg Studios in nearby Potsdam (Brandenburg) host many of the productions financed and managed from Berlin offices.

Berlin still hosts important industrial operations despite the post-war decline. Siemens AG retains a major plant at Siemensstadt in Spandau, a heritage industrial quarter currently being redeveloped as Siemensstadt 2.0 into a mixed-use innovation district; Siemens Mobility builds locomotives and rolling stock in Berlin. The Bayer AG pharmaceutical site at Müllerstraße in Wedding, inherited from the 2006 acquisition of Schering AG, employs around five thousand people in research and production of the Yasmin contraceptive, Xarelto anticoagulant, Eylea retinal therapy and oncology medicines. Berlin-Chemie AG at Adlershof is owned by Menarini of Italy. The Mercedes-Benz Group has its Marienfelde plant producing engines, axles and components since 1902. BMW Motorrad has its Spandau plant building all BMW motorcycles since 1969. The Tesla Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg in nearby Grünheide (Brandenburg) opened in March 2022, producing the Model Y and the Model 3 for the European market, employing ten thousand workers and casting a long shadow on the Berlin labour market. Berlin still hosts the largest concentration of biotechnology firms in Germany at the Berlin Biotech Park Mitte-Buch and the Adlershof Technologiepark, with companies including Berlin-Chemie, Bayer Schering Pharma, Eckert & Ziegler, Mologen, Sanofi-Aventis Deutschland (R&D), Mibe, Aristo Pharma, Glaxo SmithKline Berlin and Pfizer Deutschland (with its head office at Friedrichstraße).

Berlin is Germany''s leading tourism city, with more than thirty million overnight stays per year before the 2020 downturn and similar levels again from 2023 onwards, making it the third most-visited city in Europe after London and Paris. Hotel groups, vacation-rental platforms (Airbnb, Booking.com, Hotels.com), guided-tour operators, restaurants and cafés, museums, theatres and concert venues sustain a large hospitality economy. The Messe Berlin trade-fair complex at Berlin ExpoCenter City under the Funkturm hosts the IFA consumer-electronics fair, the ITB Berlin tourism fair (the world''s largest), the InnoTrans rail trade fair, the Fruit Logistica, the FRUIT LOGISTICA, the boot Berlin and the Grüne Woche (International Green Week, the world''s largest food fair). The Estrel Berlin convention hotel is the largest in Germany. The Internationale Funkausstellung (IFA) hosts more than 1700 exhibitors. Berlin''s Free University, Humboldt University, Technical University, University of the Arts (UdK), the Charité teaching hospital, the Hertie School of Governance, the European School of Management and Technology (ESMT), and the Berlin School of Economics and Law together host 200,000 students and bring substantial spending to the city.

Vattenfall Wärme Berlin AG, the city heating utility (with the Berliner Senate having now bought back parts of the heating grid), the Stadtwerke Berlin, Berliner Wasserbetriebe (the public water and wastewater company, the largest German water utility), Berliner Stadtreinigung BSR (the cleaning and waste utility), the Berliner Verkehrsbetriebe BVG (the second-largest German municipal transport company after the MVV Munich), and the Berliner Bäder-Betriebe (the swimming-pool utility) are major municipal employers. The Vivantes hospital group with ten general hospitals and the Charité teaching-hospital network (the largest university medical centre in Europe with three campuses Mitte, Virchow-Klinikum and Campus Benjamin Franklin) employ tens of thousands of medical staff.

The Berliner Sparkasse (since 2007 part of Landesbank Berlin Holding, now wholly owned by the savings-bank organisation), the Berlin Hyp commercial mortgage bank, Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe Privatbank, KfW IPEX-Bank (the Berlin branch), Bankhaus Löbbecke, Vbank Berlin and the cooperative Berliner Volksbank cover banking. The German Federal Government''s GTAI (Germany Trade and Invest) inward-investment agency is at Berlin, as are the KfW (although with its main office at Frankfurt) representative, the European Investment Bank Berlin office, the European Commission Representation, and the Embassy banking-attaché networks. Berlin is also the seat of the German Federal Audit Office''s Berlin presence, the Federal Antitrust Office Bundeskartellamt Bonn but with a Berlin branch, and the Federal Office for Economic Affairs and Export Control BAFA (Eschborn). The Berliner Börse, an established but mid-sized stock exchange founded in 1685, focuses on international shares, ETFs, certificates and bonds, and is the second-oldest German exchange after Hamburg.

Berlin''s creative industries are exceptional. The Berlinale film festival, the techno-club scene (UNESCO intangible heritage), the music scene with the Berliner Philharmoniker, the three opera houses, the Comedian Harmonists tradition, the Berlin advertising agencies (Saatchi & Saatchi Berlin, BBDO Group Germany, Jung von Matt Berlin, Scholz & Friends, Ogilvy Berlin, Antoni Garage, thjnk Berlin), the fashion and architecture studios (Mercedes-Benz Fashion Week, the Berlin Fashion Week, the Premium and Show & Order trade shows), the design scene around Studio Olafur Eliasson at Pfefferberg, the literary scene (the Berlin Literature Festival, the Lettrétage, the Literarisches Colloquium Berlin), the contemporary art galleries (Esther Schipper, Gallery Eigen+Art, KOW, Sprüth Magers, Capitain Petzel, Konrad Fischer Galerie Berlin), and the Berlin Design Week round out the creative economy. The Berlin Senate and the Investitionsbank Berlin support the creative sector via various funding lines and the Kreativ-Coach programme.',
    introduced_species = 'Berlin, despite being one of the most densely populated cities in Europe with around 3.85 million inhabitants and an area of 891 square kilometres, hosts the densest urban populations of several introduced mammals in Germany, a consequence of the city''s abundant green space (around forty per cent of Berlin''s surface is parks, gardens, forests, lakes and waterways), of the diverse aquatic ecosystem of the Spree-Havel system, and of the cosmopolitan nature of its plant and animal trade. Berlin is sometimes called the Hauptstadt der Waschbären, the raccoon capital of Germany.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, reached the Berlin city area through two waves: first, the post-war wartime release at Wolfshagen in Brandenburg in 1945 sent populations of escaped fur-farm raccoons west into the Brandenburg countryside, with the first verified Berlin city records in the 1950s; second, the eastward spread of the Hessian Edersee release of 1934 reached the western Berlin districts during the 1960s through 1980s. Today Berlin has the highest urban raccoon density in Germany, with estimates of fifteen to fifty raccoons per square kilometre in the leafier western neighbourhoods (Grunewald, Wannsee, Wilmersdorf, Schöneberg) and around the Spreebogen, Treptow Park and Plänterwald in the east, plus dense populations in the housing estates of Tempelhof, Neukölln, Reinickendorf and Pankow. Annual hunting bags in the city run to several hundred animals despite Berlin''s status as one of the most restrictive German jurisdictions for hunting (the city is a Stadtstaat with very limited Jagdbezirke). The Berlin Senate Department for the Environment publishes regular guidance to homeowners on chimney-cap installation, attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the removal of pet-food bowls overnight. The fictional and real-life television and YouTube celebrity Berliner raccoon population has been the subject of numerous documentaries; raccoons regularly raid Köpenick gardens, climb the Brandenburg Gate flagpoles, are filmed swimming in the Wannsee lido, and occasionally appear in the Tiergarten or on the Reichstag terrace. The Leibniz-Institut für Zoo- und Wildtierforschung (IZW) in Berlin maintains a leading raccoon-research programme and has demonstrated that Berlin raccoons exhibit lower stress hormone levels than rural conspecifics. Conservation concerns include raccoon predation on Berlin''s middle-spotted woodpecker, on the breeding bats in the Spandau Citadel and elsewhere, on amphibians at the Müggelsee and Tegeler See gravel pits, and on the European pond turtle reintroductions in eastern Brandenburg. Raccoons also occasionally raid the Berliner Zoo and the Tierpark Friedrichsfelde aviaries.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia and spread west from Soviet releases, reached Brandenburg in the 1980s and has become established in the eastern outer districts of Berlin (Köpenick, Müggelheim, Mahlsdorf, Hellersdorf) and in the Wannsee-Grunewald forest. Raccoon-dog hunting bags in Berlin are modest but rising. The Bundesjagdgesetz lists them as huntable year-round in Berlin.

Wild boar, Wildschwein, Sus scrofa, although fully native to Berlin (the Schaepen of medieval Berlin chronicles), have become superabundant in the city since the 1990s, with population estimates of three thousand to ten thousand animals within the city limits, the densest urban wild-boar population in Europe. Berlin wild boar exploit the Grunewald, the Spandauer Forst, the Düppeler Forst, the Tegeler Forst, the Köpenicker Stadtforst, the Müggelheim, and increasingly the suburban gardens of Zehlendorf, Westend and Spandau. Wild boar dig up cemeteries (the Stahnsdorfer Friedhof), supermarket carparks (the Lichterfelde Lidl carpark), school playing fields and the Olympiastadion lawns. Although native, their modern superabundance qualifies them as an effective human-driven invasion. The Berliner Forsten employs a team of professional Stadtjäger city hunters who cull wild boar continuously. The 2019 Berlin Wild Boar Strategy seeks to reduce numbers to one thousand by 2030. Berlin wild boar also carry the African Swine Fever virus risk for the German pig industry, currently controlled by extensive fencing along the Brandenburg-Poland border.

Coypu, Nutria, Myocastor coypus, are recorded along the Spree, the Landwehrkanal, the Havel, the Müggelsee and the Tegeler See, with growing populations particularly in the eastern districts of Lichtenberg, Treptow and Köpenick. Trapping is coordinated by the Berliner Wasserbetriebe and the Senatsumweltverwaltung. Muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, is similarly widespread.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established large feral resident populations on the lakes and parks of Berlin, particularly on the Wannsee, Tegeler See, Müggelsee, Volkspark Friedrichshain and the Schlosspark Charlottenburg. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations and now breeds in all Berlin parks; the central Spreebogen pair are local celebrities. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has been recorded as an isolated escape in Berlin parks; unlike Heidelberg or Düsseldorf the species has not established large breeding colonies, although the Tiergarten and Zoologischer Garten escapes maintain small year-round groups. The Alexandrine parakeet (Großer Alexandersittich) is similarly recorded. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on the Berliner park ponds. The mute swan, although native, has dense feral populations around the urban lakes. Berlin is a major stopover for migratory geese and is also home to numerous escaped parrots, macaws and cockatoos seen occasionally in Mitte, although none have established. The hooded crow (Nebelkrähe) is native, while the much-discussed sighting reports of the Indian house crow (Corvus splendens) in Berlin remain port-vagrant level.

Among fish, the Berliner waterways host the same set of invaders found elsewhere along the Spree-Havel system: the pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch) is established in the lakes; the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling) is widespread; the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel) has reached Berlin via the Spree-Oder waterway in the 2010s; the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss) is stocked in the Tegeler Fließ and the Spree; the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels) is present in old gravel pits; the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe) is regularly trapped in the Spree.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii, Roter Sumpfkrebs) which has become a Berlin urban-park spectacle since the discovery of large populations in the Tiergarten Großer Tiergarten pond and the Britzer Garten in 2017 — the so-called Berlin lobster invasion attracted international news coverage and a temporary city-wide trapping programme to harvest them for cooking. The marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs), the parthenogenetic crayfish first noted in German aquaria, occurs in Berlin gravel pits. The Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe) is regular in the lower Spree. The zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel) and the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel) are abundant in the Berlin lakes. The Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel) is in the Spree and Havel. The flatworm Obama nungara, originally from South America, has been recorded in Berlin gardens since 2020.

The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in Berlin from 2021 onwards with confirmed nests in Pankow, Spandau and Charlottenburg; the Imkerverband Berlin coordinates nest-removal teams with the Senate. The harlequin ladybird (Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer) is ubiquitous in Berlin parks. The horse-chestnut leaf miner (Cameraria ohridella) defoliates the great Berlin chestnut avenues (Unter den Linden, Kurfürstendamm, Karl-Marx-Allee, Tiergarten) every late summer. The box tree moth (Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler) has destroyed boxwood gardens at Charlottenburg Palace, the Berliner Dom, the Bode-Museum Hofgarten and the Glienicke palace. The brown marmorated stink bug (Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze) is established. The Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis), an East Asian longhorn beetle that attacks broadleaf trees, was reported in Berlin in 2014 and an emergency containment programme felled hundreds of trees; the outbreak has since been declared eradicated.

Among plants, Berlin''s remarkable green cover makes it a haven for invasive vegetation. Ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) occurs widely on Berlin disturbed ground, with allergenic implications and a Senate-coordinated control programme. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates banks of the Spree, the Landwehrkanal, the Panke, the Tegeler Fließ and the Wuhle. Bohemian knotweed (Reynoutria bohemica) and giant knotweed (Reynoutria sachalinensis) are also present. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on Berlin stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in city parks with phototoxic-sap warnings. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum), spreading from the historic Wilmersdorf and Charlottenburg avenues planted in the nineteenth century, has become one of the most conspicuous invasive trees of inner Berlin, exploiting brownfields, railway tracks, the former no-mans-land along the Berlin Wall and the abandoned cobbled lots of the eastern districts; the Berliner Mauerweg cycle path passes through several Ailanthus thickets in the inner-city sections. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), Indian balsam, water primrose (Ludwigia grandiflora) in Berlin park ponds and the Asian water plant Murdannia keisak have been recorded sporadically. The Drüsiges Weidenröschen, the small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), is widespread on Berlin park edges. Late-flowering goldenrod (Solidago gigantea) dominates the abandoned Tempelhof Field. Black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), planted historically in Berlin streets, has self-seeded into many disturbed habitats.

The Senatsverwaltung für Umwelt, Mobilität, Verbraucher- und Klimaschutz at Am Köllnischen Park 3 in Mitte maintains the Berlin neobiota register under EU Regulation 1143/2014 and coordinates with the Brandenburg state authorities, the federal Bundesamt für Naturschutz at Bonn and the Leibniz-Institut für Zoo- und Wildtierforschung. The Berlin Asian hornet response is coordinated jointly with the Bavarian Bee Institute at Veitshöchheim and the federal Julius Kühn-Institut. The Berlin Bezirksämter (district authorities) maintain raccoon-trap loan schemes and box-tree-moth advisory hotlines. The Tierpark Berlin and the Zoologischer Garten Berlin participate in EU-coordinated ex situ conservation breeding for species threatened in part by invasive introduced predators. Game species deliberately introduced to nearby Brandenburg hunting estates such as mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon), fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) occasionally cross the Berlin city boundary, particularly in the Düppeler Forst and the Spandauer Forst.'
WHERE region_name = 'Berlin';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Brandenburg surrounds the city-state of Berlin on all sides and is one of the most lake-rich states of Germany, with over three thousand lakes, the dense Mark Brandenburg forests, the Spreewald biosphere, the Oder, Havel and Elbe river systems, the rolling Uckermark and Prignitz, the Fläming hills in the south-west, the Lausitz around Cottbus, and the historic Hohenzollern Mark itself. Potsdam, the state capital, is the most visited tourist destination in Brandenburg and one of the most-photographed cities in Germany, occupying a chain of lakes, palaces and parks at the south-western edge of the Berlin agglomeration. The Park Sanssouci, the residence built by Frederick the Great between 1745 and 1747, is the centrepiece of the Potsdam-Berlin UNESCO World Heritage Site, designated in 1990 (extended 1992, 1999) as the Palaces and Parks of Potsdam and Berlin. Sanssouci Palace itself, the small rococo retreat on the vineyard terraces overlooking the lower garden, was designed by Georg Wenzeslaus von Knobelsdorff to Frederick''s sketches and contains the famous Voltaire room, the concert room, the marble hall and Frederick the Great''s tomb at the foot of the upper terrace beside his beloved greyhounds. The New Palace (Neues Palais) of 1769 at the western end of the park, built to celebrate the conclusion of the Seven Years War, is the largest palace in the ensemble and houses the Grottensaal, the Marmorsaal and the apartments of the last Kaiser Wilhelm II. Between the two stand Charlottenhof Palace by Karl Friedrich Schinkel for the future Friedrich Wilhelm IV; the Roman Baths (Römische Bäder), also by Schinkel, an Italianate fantasy beside a small lake; the Chinese House (Chinesisches Haus), a gilded pavilion in the rococo orientalist taste with life-size figures of Chinese musicians; the Orangery Palace with its Raphael Hall; the Friedenskirche; the Belvedere on the Klausberg; the Pomonatempel by Schinkel (his first commission); the Dragon House Drachenhaus; the Historic Mill (Historische Mühle) of the legendary lawsuit between Frederick the Great and the miller of Sanssouci; the Picture Gallery (Bildergalerie), Germany''s oldest purpose-built museum building; and the New Chambers (Neue Kammern). The Park Babelsberg, designed by Peter Joseph Lenné and Hermann Fürst von Pückler-Muskau, contains Babelsberg Palace by Schinkel and Persius for Prince Wilhelm (later Kaiser Wilhelm I), the Flatowturm and the Pleasure Garden. Cecilienhof Palace, an English-Tudor-style country house in the Neuer Garten built between 1913 and 1917 for the Crown Prince Wilhelm and his wife Cecilie, hosted the 1945 Potsdam Conference; the Konferenzsaal with the round table is preserved. The Marble Palace (Marmorpalais) by Carl von Gontard and Carl Gotthard Langhans, on the Heiliger See in the Neuer Garten, is a neoclassical jewel.

Beyond the palace landscape, Potsdam offers the Holländisches Viertel (Dutch Quarter) of 134 gabled brick houses built by Jan Bouman between 1733 and 1742 for Dutch craftsmen invited by King Frederick William I; the Russian colony Alexandrowka, founded in 1826 for the Russian singers of the Royal Guard, with twelve log-built houses and an Orthodox church; the Belvedere on the Pfingstberg, restored after reunification; the Krongut Bornstedt royal estate farm; the Filmpark Babelsberg and the Babelsberg Studios, the oldest large-scale film studios in the world (founded 1912), where Metropolis, Der blaue Engel, Wolfgang Petersen''s Das Boot, the original Inglourious Basterds, the Pianist by Roman Polanski, Bridge of Spies and Babylon Berlin were filmed; the Glienicke Bridge over the Havel, the Bridge of Spies of Cold War prisoner exchanges; the Brandenburg Gate of Potsdam in the centre of the old town, predating the Berlin Gate by two decades; the Nikolaikirche by Schinkel and Persius with its great dome; the Altes Rathaus on the Alter Markt; the Barberini Museum housing the Hasso Plattner private collection of French Impressionists and East German art; the Museum Sanssouci; the Filmmuseum Potsdam; and the Lustgarten with its baroque axes.

The Spreewald, Spreßk in Lower Sorbian, the area between Lübben in the south and Lübbenau-Burg in the north, is a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve since 1991, a landscape of more than two hundred branched watercourses (Fließe) of the Spree, lined by reedbeds, alder carrs and willows, with traditional Sorbian villages on the islands. The classic Spreewald experience is a guided Kahnfahrt punt tour from Lübbenau-Spreehafen, Lehde or Burg, accompanied by Spreewaldgurken sour gherkins (a regional speciality with EU Protected Geographic Indication), Spreewaldhonig honey, Spreewald-Leinöl linseed oil and Plinse pancakes. The Freilandmuseum Lehde reconstructs traditional Spreewald village life. The Sorbian/Wendish minority in the Niederlausitz preserves its distinct West Slavic language and Easter egg-painting tradition at Burg, Lübben, Cottbus, Hoyerswerda and Bautzen (the latter in Saxony, home of the Upper Sorbian). Cottbus, the second city of Brandenburg, has the medieval Altmarkt, the Schloss Branitz of Hermann Fürst von Pückler-Muskau with its earth pyramids (Tumuli) where the Fürst is buried, the Branitzer Park (UNESCO World Heritage tentative list), the Stadthalle theatre, the Wendisches Museum, and the rebuilt Park Forst Cottbus. Bad Saarow on the Scharmützelsee combines spa traditions with sailing; the Saarow-Pieskow spas were a Weimar-era resort frequented by Albert Einstein, Maxim Gorky and others. Brandenburg an der Havel, the former state capital, has the Brandenburger Dom on the Burginsel (the cathedral of Saint Peter and Paul), the Altstädtisches Rathaus with the Roland statue, the Neustadt with St Catherine''s Church, the Mühlentorbrücke and the surrounding islands and lakes. Rheinsberg, north of Berlin, has the Rheinsberg Palace where Frederick the Great spent his Crown Prince years studying philosophy, music and Voltaire, immortalised by Theodor Fontane in his book Rheinsberg of 1912. Wittstock with its medieval city wall, Neuruppin (birthplace of Theodor Fontane and Karl Friedrich Schinkel), Templin with its Templiner See and complete city wall, Lychen with its lake chain, Lieberose and the Märkische Schweiz nature park around Buckow with its lakes, ridges and tales by Bertolt Brecht who had a summer house at Buckow Schermützelsee complete the northern itinerary. The Schorfheide-Chorin Biosphere Reserve, north-east of Berlin, includes the Cistercian monastery of Chorin (one of the finest brick Gothic monasteries in Germany), the Niederfinow ship lift, the historic Eberswalde and the Werbellinsee lake.

Brandenburg has remarkable industrial and curious sites: Beelitz-Heilstätten, the early-twentieth-century lung-sanatorium complex south-west of Berlin that became a major film location (Pianist, Valkyrie, A Cure for Wellness) and now hosts a treetop walk through the canopy above the ruins; the Tropical Islands resort in a converted CargoLifter airship hangar at Krausnick, a giant indoor tropical theme park with rainforest, beaches, rope bridges and ten-thousand seats under a single dome that is the largest free-standing hall in the world; Lausitzring motor-racing circuit at Klettwitz; the F60 conveyor bridge in the former Klettwitz-Nord open-cast lignite mine, a 502-metre-long industrial monument now open to visitors and known as the "Lying Eiffel Tower of the Lausitz"; the Tagebau Welzow-Süd, the Welzow-Süd open-cast lignite mine still in operation with mining-truck tours; the Tagebau Cottbus-Nord, now flooded and being converted into the Cottbuser Ostsee, planned to become the largest artificial lake in Germany; the Filmpark Babelsberg theme park beside the studios; the Schiffshebewerk Niederfinow ship lift on the Oder-Havel Canal, opened 1934 (still in operation) beside the new Niederfinow Nord twin ship lift opened in October 2022; the Schwielochsee, the longest natural lake of Brandenburg; the Müggelsee (technically in Berlin); the Templiner See, the Werbellinsee, the Stechlinsee (immortalised by Fontane in his novel Der Stechlin); the Plauer See; the Neuruppiner See; the Glubigsee; the Lehnitzsee; the Senftenberger See; and the Stechlin reactor pumped-storage plant. The Werder fruit-growing district near Potsdam is famous for the Baumblüte festival in early May and the Werder Frucht industries. The Templiner See and the Tüllinger Park, the Drei Gleichen, the Heidesee and the Klosterheide complete the lake itinerary.

Brandenburg cuisine and beverage culture reflects the rural Mark and the Sorbian Niederlausitz. Spreewaldgurken (Spreewald gherkins), Senf (mustard, particularly the Bautzner Senf brand from neighbouring Saxony), Plinse (a Sorbian-style buckwheat pancake), Spreewaldhonig (Spreewald honey), Spreewaldquark, Leinöl (linseed oil from Spreewald farmers, often paired with Pellkartoffeln boiled jacket potatoes and quark in the traditional Pellkartoffeln mit Leinöl und Quark Sorbian dish), Sülze (jellied meat), Sauerkraut, Wruken (swede turnips), Knieperkohl from Prignitz (a fermented mixed-greens dish unique to the Prignitz Kreis), Beelitzer Spargel (Beelitz asparagus, the largest German producing region with the asparagus capital declared at Beelitz), Werderaner Wachtelberg wine (the most northerly winemaking village in Germany), Kürbis pumpkin from the Spreewald Kürbisweg, and Spreewald cuisine, plus traditional roast pork with Knödel and red cabbage. Spreewald-style fish dishes use perch, pike, zander and eel from the Spree-Oder system. The Eberswalder Wurst factory makes the iconic Knacker sausage. The Berliner Pfannkuchen (jelly doughnut) is also produced widely; the Spreewald Christmas cookies tradition (Pfefferkuchen) is strong in Cottbus. Beverages include the Spreewald-Bier brewed at Lübbenau and Schlepzig, the Berliner Pilsner brewery in Hohenschönhausen (technically in Berlin but supplying Brandenburg), the Brandenburger Klosterbrauerei Neuzelle (one of the oldest monastic breweries in Germany at Neuzelle Abbey with its famous black beer Schwarzer Abt), Frankfurter Pilsner of Frankfurt (Oder), and Spreequell mineral water. The Werder fruit cider and orchard culture around Werder, Brandenburg an der Havel and Phöben, and the cherry brandy distilling traditions of the Märkische Schweiz, complete the alcoholic beverage map. Apple varieties from Brandenburg orchards include Brandenburger Klarapfel and Brandenburger Renette. Mineral water from the Klosterquelle and Spreequell sources is widely sold.

History before 1933 is rich: the Mark Brandenburg under the Askanier, the Margrave Albrecht the Bear (Albrecht der Bär) who founded the Mark in 1157 from the Wendish settlement of Brennaburg; the Hohenzollern Margrave Friedrich I of 1415 who began the Hohenzollern dynasty; the elevation of the Mark Brandenburg to the Kingdom of Prussia in 1701 under Frederick III/I; Frederick the Great''s 1740-1786 transformation of the Mark into a European great power; the Stein-Hardenberg reforms after the defeat at Jena-Auerstedt; the founding of the Prussian railway and the Brandenburg-Berlin canal system in the nineteenth century; the unification of Germany in 1871; the building of Babelsberg as the film capital of Europe in the 1910s and 1920s; the Weimar-era flowering of UFA at Babelsberg with films like Fritz Lang''s Metropolis (1927) and Friedrich Murnau''s films, the cabaret tradition, the architects Erich Mendelsohn (the Einstein Tower in Potsdam, 1924, on the Telegrafenberg, still housing the Einstein Telescope of the Leibniz-Institut für Astrophysik). After 1945 Brandenburg was part of the Soviet zone and from 1949 part of the German Democratic Republic, which abolished the historic Länder structure in 1952 and reorganised the area into three districts (Cottbus, Frankfurt and Potsdam). The 1990 Wende and reunification restored Brandenburg as a Land of the Federal Republic. The 1996 referendum to merge Brandenburg with Berlin into a single Land was rejected by Brandenburg voters and so the two states remain separate, although they coordinate transport, planning, broadcasting (RBB) and many other tasks through interstate treaties.',
    transportation = 'Brandenburg surrounds Berlin and consequently shares the transport hub of the federal capital, while also hosting its own substantial network of railways, canals, motorways and minor airports. Berlin Brandenburg Airport Willy Brandt, IATA BER and ICAO EDDB, lies in the Brandenburg district of Dahme-Spreewald in the village of Schönefeld, technically inside the territory of Brandenburg though it serves both states; the airport opened on 31 October 2020 after nine years of delays and replaces Berlin Tegel (TXL, closed November 2020) and the older Schönefeld terminal (SXF, now BER Terminal 5). BER has two parallel runways, three terminals, the integrated railway station Bahnhof Berlin Brandenburg Airport beneath Terminal 1, and is connected by S-Bahn S9 and S45, regional express services RE7, RE8 and RB14, the Flughafen-Express FEX from Berlin Hauptbahnhof, and the long-distance services from BER directly to Magdeburg, Halle and Wolfsburg. The airport handled around twenty-five million passengers per year by 2023 and is the main base for easyJet, Eurowings, Lufthansa, Ryanair, Wizz Air, TUI fly, Condor, Turkish Airlines, Lot Polish, Pegasus, Air France/KLM and the long-haul carriers Qatar Airways, Etihad and Singapore Airlines. Cottbus-Drewitz Airport (Cottbus-Drewitz, CBM, ICAO EDCD) is the second-largest airfield of Brandenburg, used for general aviation, gliders and the BER overflow plans. Smaller civilian airfields include Strausberg (the eastern Berlin business-aviation gateway), Eberswalde-Finow, Neuhardenberg (a wartime air base now hosting the Schinkelmuseum and the Schloss Neuhardenberg), Schönhagen near Trebbin (one of Germany''s busiest non-commercial airfields), Pinnow, Lärz (host of the annual Fusion Festival, on a former Soviet airbase), and the historic Welzow training base.

The Brandenburg rail network is dense, with Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Nordost, Ostdeutsche Eisenbahn (ODEG), Niederbarnimer Eisenbahn (NEB), DB ESG, Hanseatische Eisenbahn (HANS), HLB and the Brandenburg-internal Heidekrautbahn operating regional services under the VBB Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg tariff. The S-Bahn Berlin radial lines reach deep into Brandenburg: S1 to Oranienburg, S2 to Bernau and Blankenfelde, S3 to Erkner, S5 to Strausberg Nord, S7 to Ahrensfelde and Potsdam Hauptbahnhof, S8 to Wildau and Zeuthen, S9 to Spandau and BER, and S25 to Hennigsdorf. Regional services include the RE1 (Eisenhüttenstadt-Frankfurt(Oder)-Berlin-Magdeburg) one of Germany''s busiest regional lines, the RE2 (Cottbus-Berlin-Rathenow), the RE3 (Stralsund-Eberswalde-Berlin-Wittenberg or Berlin-Falkenberg-Hoyerswerda), the RE5 (Stralsund-Berlin-Wünsdorf), the RE6 (Wittenberge-Berlin-Senftenberg), the RE7 (Dessau-Berlin-Wünsdorf), the RB10 (Berlin-Nauen) and the RB14 (Nauen-Berlin-BER). The line from Berlin Hauptbahnhof to Hamburg-Altona via Spandau and Wittenberge, opened 1846 and electrified between 1989 and 2007, carries the ICE 28 and ICE 91 services with running times below 90 minutes. The Berlin-Hannover ICE corridor (Hannover-Berlin Neubaustrecke, opened 1998 as VDE 4) runs at 250 kph through the Brandenburg plain, with the Bahnhof Stendal (Sachsen-Anhalt) and Wolfsburg (Niedersachsen) intermediate stops. The Berlin-Leipzig-Erfurt-Munich high-speed corridor (VDE 8) crosses southern Brandenburg via Bitterfeld-Wolfen and Lutherstadt Wittenberg. The Berlin-Dresden line (Dresdner Bahn) is being upgraded via Blankenfelde and Wünsdorf-Waldstadt to allow non-stop ICE running. The Berlin-Stettin/Szczecin cross-border line connects Berlin to Pomerania via Angermünde and Tantow; the Berlin-Frankfurt(Oder)-Poznań Eurocity services to Warsaw run on the Berlin-Warszawa Express. The Berlin-Praha Eurocity runs via Berlin-Dresden, the Berlin-Kraków via Frankfurt(Oder), and the night-train ÖBB Nightjet from Berlin to Vienna and Zurich. The Heidekrautbahn from Berlin-Karow to Groß Schönebeck and Schmachtenhagen is undergoing electrification for battery-hydrogen pilot operation.

Important rail nodes include Potsdam Hauptbahnhof, Brandenburg an der Havel, Frankfurt (Oder), Cottbus, Senftenberg, Eberswalde Hauptbahnhof, Königs Wusterhausen, Wittenberge, and the major junctions of Berlin-Schönefeld, Berlin-Spandau and Berlin Hauptbahnhof on the Berlin side. The new fast-rail link Berlin-Stettin (Berlin-Szczecin) is being electrified for completion in the mid 2020s.

The Autobahn network in Brandenburg is dominated by the A10 (Berliner Ring), at 196 kilometres the largest motorway ring in Europe, with radial spokes: the A2 to Hannover and the Ruhr; the A9 to Leipzig, Nuremberg and Munich; the A11 to Stettin (Szczecin); the A12 to Frankfurt (Oder) and onward via the Polish A2 to Warsaw; the A13 to Dresden; the A19 to Rostock; the A24 to Hamburg; the A20 (the Ostseeautobahn, north-south transit), the A14 (north-south through Sachsen-Anhalt to Magdeburg); the A15 (Berlin-Cottbus continuation as Polish A18). The A100 inner ring of Berlin reaches the Brandenburg border at Schönefeld. Major Bundesstraßen include the B1 east-west (the historical Reichsstraße 1 from Aachen via Berlin to Königsberg/Kaliningrad), the B2 to Strausberg and Templin, the B5 to Hamburg via Wittenberge, the B96 from Berlin south to Zossen and Bautzen, the B97 north to Oranienburg, the B158 to Bad Freienwalde, and the B273. The Lausitzring at Klettwitz is one of Germany''s motor-racing circuits; the Welzow-Süd lignite mine has tourist Truck-Tours.

Brandenburg is one of the most navigable states in Germany, served by the Spree-Oder Waterway, the Havel waterway, the Oder-Havel-Kanal, the Berlin-Müggelsee-Spree, the Elbe-Havel-Kanal, the Mittellandkanal connection via the Magdeburg Wasserstraßenkreuz, the Oder-Spree-Kanal, the Niederbarnimer Wasserstraße, and the Müggelsee-Dahme-Spree, all of which carry both commercial cargo (mostly the Berlin-Brandenburg-Polish trade) and tourism traffic. Major inland ports include the Eisenhütten Stadt-Hafen on the Oder, the Cottbus port, the Schwedt port, the Königs Wusterhausen port and the Eberswalde-Niederfinow lock station. The Schiffshebewerk Niederfinow ship lift on the Oder-Havel Canal, opened in 1934, is one of the most spectacular hydraulic engineering structures in Europe and remains in operation alongside the new Niederfinow Nord twin ship lift, the world''s largest in lift height, opened in October 2022. The Hohennauen and Storkow lock systems serve smaller waterways. The European Rhine-Main-Danube waterway, the EuroVelo 6, the EuroVelo 7 (the Sun route from North Cape to Malta via the Berlin Wall Trail and the Spree-Radweg), the Oder-Neisse-Radweg, the Berlin-Kopenhagen cycle route, the Havel-Radweg, the Elbe-Radweg approach and the Spree-Radweg make Brandenburg one of the most cycled-through states. The Niederlausitzer Bergbau-Tourismus-Bahn at Klettwitz operates heritage industrial-tourism trains in the disused open-cast pits. The Berlin-Brandenburger heritage rail enthusiasts run the Eisenbahn-Bau- und Betriebsgesellschaft Pressnitztalbahn, the Märkische Museumseisenbahn at Schöneicher Schleuse and the Heidekrautbahn-Veteran trains.

Long-distance buses cluster around the Berlin ZOB at Messedamm and the new BER terminus; FlixBus, Sindbad, Eurolines and others operate cross-border services to Poland, Czechia, Ukraine, Lithuania and beyond. The Polskie Linie Kolejowe and the Polish Łukasz airport operators run cross-border bus services. Mobility-as-a-service in Brandenburg is being expanded with the new Mobilitäts-Hubs around the regional Bahnhöfe; the Brandenburg Senate is rolling out a comprehensive on-demand minibus network in rural Prignitz, Uckermark and Elbe-Elster, with the BVG and ODEG partner brands.

Brandenburg hosts a number of significant transport infrastructure points: the historic Reichsbahn-Reparaturwerk Wittenberge, the Werder fruit-line lift bridges, the historic train order interlocking towers at Brieselang and Königs Wusterhausen, the Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn forerunner lines, the test track of the high-speed Velaro near Oranienburg, the Volkswagen Group sales-and-marketing centre at Großbeeren south of Berlin (with the Mercedes-Benz Vans and the Daimler Truck-AG logistics hub adjacent), the Postbahnhof of Eberswalde, the Spielbergring drag race track, the Lufthansa Technik AG turbine MRO at Schönefeld, the MAN truck distribution centre at Großbeeren, and the major DHL hub at BER serving the eastern German logistics market. The Brandenburg Polizei operates the Helikopterstaffel at Schönefeld; the Bundespolizei has aerial assets at BER and at Eberswalde. The new Tesla Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg at Grünheide is served by the new Bahnhof Fangschleuse upgraded for direct factory rail freight and by the A10 Erkner exit.',
    economics = 'Brandenburg, with a population of 2.55 million on 29,654 square kilometres and a regional GDP of around 80 billion euros, is the largest Bundesland in eastern Germany by area but the second-smallest by per-capita GDP after Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. The Brandenburg economy is highly heterogeneous: the Berlin commuter belt around Potsdam, Königs Wusterhausen and Großbeeren has GDP-per-capita levels approaching the West German average and grows fast, while the peripheral Prignitz, Uckermark and Niederlausitz have struggled with the post-1990 deindustrialisation and population decline. The state economic-development agency Wirtschaftsförderung Brandenburg (WFBB) at Potsdam markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Potsdam, the Industrie- und Handelskammer Ostbrandenburg at Frankfurt(Oder) and the Industrie- und Handelskammer Cottbus represent the regional businesses.

The single most prominent industrial event in Brandenburg in the past decade has been the construction and operation of the Tesla Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg at Grünheide near Erkner, twenty kilometres east of Berlin in the Oder-Spree district. The Gigafactory opened in March 2022 under intense political and environmental controversy regarding water consumption (the Berlin region''s drinking water aquifer flows nearby), forest clearance (pine plantation cleared with court challenges) and political integration. The factory builds the Tesla Model Y for the European market and has expanded into the Model 3 and battery cell production; by 2024 it employed around twelve thousand workers and aimed for an annual capacity of one million vehicles. Tesla''s Brandenburg presence has triggered a wave of supplier investments around Grünheide, including the BASF battery-materials plant at Schwarzheide (cathode active materials) opened 2022, the SVolt cell factory plans, the LG Energy Solution warehouse, and the various rail and road freight upgrades. Tesla has become the largest single private employer in Brandenburg, surpassing the historic Eisenhüttenstadt steelworks.

ArcelorMittal Eisenhüttenstadt operates the historic steelworks at Eisenhüttenstadt on the Oder, the only integrated steel plant in eastern Germany, founded in 1950 as Eisenhüttenkombinat Ost and the namesake of the city built around it; the plant has hot rolling, cold rolling, galvanising and coating capacity for automotive and white-goods steel. ArcelorMittal Bremen and ArcelorMittal Hamburg supply additional grade variety. The Eisenhüttenstadt plant is undergoing the EU-funded ArcelorMittal H2 Hyper Steel transformation to green steel via hydrogen-reduced direct-reduced iron, with substantial Brandenburg state subsidies.

PCK Raffinerie GmbH at Schwedt, on the lower Oder, is the largest oil refinery in Brandenburg and one of the four major German refineries. PCK Schwedt was historically supplied via the Druzhba (Friendship) Pipeline from Russia and was a flashpoint after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine when the Federal government took the refinery under federal trusteeship in September 2022. The refinery has since switched to crude from Kazakhstan, the United States, the United Arab Emirates and Norway, supplied via the Rostock harbour pipeline. PCK Schwedt is being transformed into a green-hydrogen and biofuel platform with state and federal investment.

The Lausitz lignite-mining and lignite-power industry is centred on the Lausitzer Energie AG (LEAG, owned by EPH and PPF Investments), which operates the Welzow-Süd, Jänschwalde, Nochten and Reichwalde open-cast mines, the Jänschwalde, Schwarze Pumpe and Boxberg power stations, plus the lignite gasification works. The Lausitz coal phase-out, agreed in the federal Kohleausstiegsgesetz of 2020 to end lignite mining and lignite power by 2038, brings about forty billion euros of federal Strukturwandel transformation funding to the Lausitz, the Mitteldeutsches Revier and the Rheinisches Revier. The federal Lausitz Strukturwandel programme is creating new federal-research and federal-administrative offices, the German Centre for Astrophysics at Görlitz (Saxony), new university campuses, the Lausitz Science Park at Cottbus and the new Bahnknoten Cottbus regional rail-hub investment. The TU Cottbus-Senftenberg is benefiting heavily from the Strukturwandel programme.

Rolls-Royce Deutschland Ltd & Co. KG, the German subsidiary of Rolls-Royce plc, has its headquarters and main engine plant at Dahlewitz south of Berlin in the district of Teltow-Fläming. Rolls-Royce Dahlewitz is the global engineering and assembly site for the BR725 business-jet engine on the Gulfstream G650, the BR710 on the Gulfstream and Bombardier Global 6500, the Trent XWB final-assembly site for the Airbus A350, and a major MRO centre. The Dahlewitz facility employs over three thousand people and is the largest aerospace site in Brandenburg.

MTU Maintenance Berlin-Brandenburg GmbH at Ludwigsfelde is a major commercial-engine MRO operation. Premium Aerotec at the Wolgast facility in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and the Schönefeld Bombardier maintenance facility are also part of the German aerospace cluster.

The chemical and pharmaceutical industry centres on the BASF Schwarzheide site in the Niederlausitz, founded in 1936 as a Hydrierwerk Schwarzheide, today producing polyurethane raw materials, engineering plastics, refinery catalysts, automotive coatings, herbicides and pharmaceuticals, plus the new battery-cathode-active-materials plant for electric vehicle batteries. Heidelberg Materials AG operates major cement plants at Rüdersdorf bei Berlin (one of the largest in Germany) which is one of the leading European pilot sites for carbon capture and storage on cement production. Mibe Pharma at Brehna (Sachsen-Anhalt) has Brandenburg supply links. The Schweizer Stiftung Roche/Hoffmann-La Roche has the Roche Diagnostics Penzberg (Bavaria) operations.

Food and beverages include the Werder Frucht GmbH (the Werder fruit processor with the Werder-Marmelade brand, although now ownership rests with Hain Celestial of the US), the Spreewald Konserve (Spreewald sour gherkins under various brands), the Spreewaldhof and Sonneberger industries, the Beelitzer Spargel asparagus marketing cooperative (the largest German asparagus region by area), the Klosterbrauerei Neuzelle (founded in the 12th century, brewer of the famous Black Abbot Schwarzer Abt), the Berliner Bürgerbräu (Berliner-style pilsner), the Spreewaldbrauerei Schlepzig, and the Vetschauer Spreewald-Bier. The Cottbuser Brauerei completes the brewing inventory.

The defence industry includes Rheinmetall AG operations in the Lausitz (the Rheinmetall Lausitz GmbH ammunition factory at Niesky on the Saxon-Brandenburg border supplies ammunition and propellant), and the Diehl Defence munitions facilities. The German Federal Armed Forces (Bundeswehr) Centre for Operational Information at Mayen-Bonn manages the Brandenburg Heeres Pionierschule at Lehnitz. The Bundeswehr maintains the Schönwalde Air Force Base, the Schönefeld Bundespolizei station, and major bases at Storkow, Hennigsdorf and Wünsdorf.

Brandenburg agriculture is the third-largest in Germany by area, with extensive grain production (rye, wheat, barley), oilseed rape (with the third-largest German rapeseed acreage), maize for biogas, sugar beet, potatoes (the historic Brandenburger Kartoffel from the Spreewald and the Uckermark), Beelitzer Spargel asparagus, the Werder fruit-orchards (apples, cherries, plums, pears), the Spreewald cucumbers (Spreewaldgurken with EU Protected Geographic Indication), the Spreewald horseradish, the Lausitz hops and the Brandenburg dairy and beef herds (the Uckermark and the Prignitz are major dairy areas). The Brandenburg Senate''s agricultural-investment subsidies are substantial. The Brandenburg state forest authority manages the second-largest publicly owned forest in Germany after Bavaria; the Schorfheide, the Rambower Moor and the Choriner Heide are important.

Banking and finance are concentrated at Potsdam, with the Mittelbrandenburgische Sparkasse, Sparkasse Spree-Neiße, Investitionsbank des Landes Brandenburg (ILB), the cooperative Volksbank Brandenburg, and the Bundesbank Hauptverwaltung Berlin-Brandenburg-Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. The state government is the largest single employer overall, with about 100,000 staff including police, justice, schools and ministries; the Potsdam Hauptdienstgebäude on the Heinrich-Mann-Allee houses the Staatskanzlei. The Helmholtz-Zentrum Geesthacht has a Potsdam branch. The Helmholtz-Zentrum Deutsches GeoForschungsZentrum GFZ on the Telegrafenberg in Potsdam, the Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), the Leibniz-Institut für Astrophysik with the Einstein Tower, the Alfred Wegener Institute Potsdam, the Max-Planck-Institut für Gravitationsphysik (Albert-Einstein-Institut) and the Max-Planck-Institut für Kolloid- und Grenzflächenforschung in Golm form the largest concentration of climate, gravitational and astronomical research in Germany. The European Space Agency''s Earth Observation Centre and the Helmholtz-Zentrum Telegrafenberg complete the science map. Universities include the Universität Potsdam, the Brandenburgische Technische Universität Cottbus-Senftenberg (BTU), the Hasso Plattner Institut (HPI Potsdam, German computer-science institute funded by SAP co-founder Hasso Plattner), and the Filmuniversität Babelsberg Konrad Wolf, the oldest film school in Germany. The Fachhochschule Brandenburg, the Hochschule für Nachhaltige Entwicklung Eberswalde and the Technische Hochschule Wildau round out the higher-education sector.

The Babelsberg film studios at Potsdam-Babelsberg are the oldest large-scale film studios in the world (founded 1912 by the Bioscop AG company) and the second-largest in Europe after Pinewood Studios near London. The Babelsberg studios cover 280,000 square metres and have hosted Metropolis (1927), Der blaue Engel (1930), M (1931), Olympia (1938), the post-war DEFA productions, plus the modern productions of The Reader (2008), Inglourious Basterds (2009), The Pianist (2002), Bridge of Spies (2015), Babylon Berlin, the Wachowskis''s Cloud Atlas, and a stream of international productions financed by Germany''s tax-credit incentives. The Filmpark Babelsberg theme park, the Studio Babelsberg AG and the Marlene-Dietrich-Allee studios employ around three thousand people.

Tourism contributes a substantial share of Brandenburg GDP, particularly around Potsdam, the Spreewald, the Schorfheide-Chorin Biosphere Reserve, the Tropical Islands resort, the Beelitz-Heilstätten tree-top walk, the Müggelsee and the Brandenburg Lake District. The Tourismus-Marketing Brandenburg (TMB) at Potsdam markets the state. The Schloss Neuhardenberg, the Klosterhotels of the Chorin and Neuzelle abbeys, the Spreewald hotels at Burg, Lübbenau and Lübben, the Bad-Saarow spa hotels and the Tropical Islands resort all generate substantial visitor flows.

Renewable energy is a Brandenburg leader: the state has the second-highest installed wind power per capita in Germany after Schleswig-Holstein, around 8 gigawatts of wind, plus the Lieberose Solar Park (one of the largest solar plants in Germany), the Cottbus Solar Park, the Senftenberger See floating PV pilot, and the new green-hydrogen projects at Schwedt and Lubmin. The Eberswalder Strom Generationenwerk and the Eberswalder Wind Park are local cooperatives. The Brandenburg state Energy Plan 2030 targets full coal exit by 2038 and a transformed economy by 2045.',
    introduced_species = 'Brandenburg, the historical ground-zero of the western European raccoon invasion, has the highest non-urban raccoon densities in Germany and one of the most diverse rosters of invasive species in the country, the consequence of its central-European position, its forested, lake-rich landscape and its proximity to both the Berlin urban heat island and to the Polish ecological border. The state-wide invasive species register is maintained by the Landesamt für Umwelt (LfU) at Potsdam.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Brandenburg since the wartime release at Wolfshagen near Strausberg in April 1945, when a fur farm at Strausberg was destroyed in the closing weeks of the Battle of Berlin and around 25 captive raccoons escaped into the surrounding Märkische Schweiz. This release, combined with the earlier 1934 Hessian Edersee release, formed the founder populations of the German raccoon. Brandenburg raccoon population densities are some of the highest in continental Europe outside the species'' North American range, with estimates of 20 to 60 individuals per square kilometre in the central state and over 100 per square kilometre in the suburban Berlin commuter belt. Annual hunting bags in Brandenburg consistently exceed 30,000 raccoons, the highest in Germany. The Brandenburg raccoon has been the subject of intensive research by the Leibniz-Institut für Zoo- und Wildtierforschung (IZW) in Berlin and the Brandenburgische Technische Universität Cottbus, including the long-running Project Berliner Waschbär and the Märkische Waschbärenprojekt. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation of cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl, beech marten chicks), of amphibians (yellow-bellied toad, fire-bellied toad, common spadefoot toad), of the European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) which Brandenburg has been actively reintroducing through the Naturschutzfonds Brandenburg programme, and of the increasingly rare middle-spotted woodpecker. The Brandenburg raccoon is also a vector of Baylisascaris procyonis parasitic roundworm, of canine distemper virus and increasingly of rabies (although Germany has been declared free of fox rabies since 2008, the raccoon could re-introduce the disease). The Brandenburg Senate health authorities publish regular guidance for homeowners regarding attic-vent sealing and the use of personal protective equipment when cleaning raccoon latrines.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, reached Brandenburg from the east in the late 1980s following Soviet releases in the western Soviet Union from the 1930s to the 1950s; the species is now established throughout Brandenburg with the highest densities in the Märkische Schweiz, the Schorfheide, the Lausitz forests and along the Polish border. Annual hunting bags exceed 12,000. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List under Regulation 1143/2014; trans-border cooperation with the Polish Generalna Dyrekcja Ochrony Środowiska coordinates monitoring.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has expanded substantially along the Brandenburg waterways since the 1990s, particularly along the lower Oder, the Havel, the Spree, the Müggelsee and the Spreewald canals, with the highest population densities along the Frankfurt(Oder)-Eberswalde-Lebus corridor. Damage to flood-protection dykes by burrowing is a serious management concern; the Wasser- und Schifffahrtsverwaltung des Bundes, the Brandenburger Wasserwirtschaftsämter and the Landesamt für Umwelt coordinate professional trapping operations. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Brandenburg but heavily persecuted into local extinction by the 19th century, was reintroduced to the lower Elbe and the Havel from the 1960s by NABU and the Brandenburg state forestry, and the species has rebounded so successfully that beaver-management has become itself a major conservation issue, with annual reports of beaver flooding causing damage to agricultural drainage.

The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, originally from North America, has been in Brandenburg since the 1930s; the species is now ubiquitous in slow water bodies across the state, with dense populations in the Spreewald, the Müggelsee, the Havel and the Oder polders. Trapping is mandated under the Brandenburgisches Wassergesetz for dyke-safety reasons.

The American mink, Neovison vison, Amerikanischer Nerz, escaped from Brandenburg fur farms (the Lausitz hosted several major mink farms in the German Democratic Republic period), is now established in low densities along the Brandenburg waterways and is a serious threat to the recovering European mink (Mustela lutreola) reintroduction plans.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations along the Havel, the Oder, the Spree, the Müggelsee, the Schwielochsee and most of the Brandenburg lakes; flocks now winter on the rivers. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations and now breeds throughout Brandenburg, with particularly conspicuous populations on the Tegelsee, the Müggelsee, the Werbellinsee, the Stechlinsee and the Sacrower See. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is occasional in Brandenburg but has not established large breeding populations. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on Brandenburg park ponds. The wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on some Brandenburg hunting estates without forming self-sustaining populations.

Among fish, the Brandenburg waterways are heavily affected by introduced species. The rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Regenbogenforelle, is stocked in the Spree and in fish farms across the state. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis, Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch, is established in the lakes. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling, is widespread. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels, occurs in old gravel pits. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella, Graskarpfen, is used to control aquatic vegetation in lakes. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel, has reached Brandenburg via the Spree-Oder waterway since around 2010 and is expanding rapidly. The Caspian Kessler''s goby and the bighead goby follow. The Atlantic sturgeon (Acipenser sturio) and the European sturgeon (Acipenser oxyrinchus), although native, have been reintroduced to the Oder via stocking programmes.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs, which is widespread in the Brandenburg streams and is responsible for the local extinction of the native noble crayfish (Astacus astacus) and the stone crayfish (Austropotamobius torrentium). The spinycheek crayfish, Faxonius limosus, Kamberkrebs, has been in Brandenburg since the early 20th century and is the most common crayfish of the Brandenburg lakes. The red swamp crayfish, Procambarus clarkii, Roter Sumpfkrebs, is established in Brandenburg gravel pits. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs, a parthenogenetic species, occurs in scattered locations. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe, is regular in the Oder and Havel. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel, and the quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel, are abundant in the Brandenburg lakes. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel, is in the Brandenburg waterways. The New Zealand mud snail, Potamopyrgus antipodarum, is present in the Spreewald.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in Brandenburg from 2022 onwards with confirmed nests in Potsdam-Babelsberg and the Berlin commuter belt; the Imkerverband Brandenburg coordinates nest-removal with the Senatsumweltverwaltung. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous in Brandenburg parks. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Brandenburg avenues every late summer. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at Sanssouci, the Babelsberg Palace, the Chorin monastery and the Glienicke Park. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established in southern Brandenburg. The Asian long-horned beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis), an East Asian wood-boring beetle that attacks broadleaf trees, was reported in southern Brandenburg in 2014; an emergency containment programme felled hundreds of trees; the outbreak has since been declared eradicated. The emerald ash borer (Agrilus planipennis) has not yet been confirmed in Brandenburg but the Polish border populations are advancing.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) is one of the most widespread plant invaders of Brandenburg, with particularly dense populations in the Niederlausitz and around the Berlin commuter belt; the LfU Brandenburg coordinates the Ambrosia-Atlas and the state-wide control programme. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates Brandenburg river banks of the Havel, the Spree, the Pegnitz tributaries and the Oder polders. Bohemian knotweed (Reynoutria bohemica) and giant knotweed (Reynoutria sachalinensis) are also present. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on Brandenburg stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in Brandenburg parks with phototoxic-sap warnings. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum) spreads along railway lines and brownfields, particularly in the former lignite areas. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea) dominates fallow fields and abandoned military training areas (the so-called Truppenübungsplatz heaths). Small balsam (Impatiens parviflora) is widespread on shaded park edges. Black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), planted historically in Brandenburg, has self-seeded into many disturbed habitats. The lupine, Lupinus polyphyllus, garden lupin, dominates roadsides and railway embankments in the Lausitz. The Indian balsam, the water primrose Ludwigia grandiflora, and the floating fern Salvinia molesta have been recorded sporadically. The cherry laurel (Prunus laurocerasus), historically planted in Brandenburg gardens, has self-seeded into forest understorey in mild winters.

Among large mammals introduced for hunting, mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) and fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) are widely naturalised in Brandenburg hunting reserves. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations near Eberswalde and in the Schorfheide. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa), although native to Brandenburg, are superabundant and a chronic management concern, with annual hunting bags exceeding 100,000 statewide. The Brandenburg African Swine Fever situation, with the first wild-boar cases recorded in September 2020 near the Polish border at Schenkendöbern, led to the construction of a 1,500-kilometre fence along the Polish frontier and to mass culling programmes in the affected core area. Wolves (Canis lupus), although native, have re-colonised Brandenburg from Polish populations since the 2000s and the state now has the second-highest German wolf population after Saxony, with around 50 territorial packs.'
WHERE region_name = 'Brandenburg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Bremen, the smallest of the German federal states by area at 419 square kilometres, is the Free Hanseatic City of Bremen (Freie Hansestadt Bremen), a Land consisting of two cities, the city of Bremen on the lower Weser river roughly 60 kilometres upstream from the North Sea, and the seaport city of Bremerhaven 60 kilometres downstream at the mouth of the Weser. Bremen is the second-oldest city-republic in the world (after San Marino) and one of the oldest continuously existing Hanseatic cities. The Bremen Marktplatz, the central square in the Altstadt, is the focal point of every visit and contains two UNESCO World Heritage objects designated together in 2004: the Bremen Roland statue (the Bremer Roland) of 1404 and the Bremen Town Hall (Bremer Rathaus) of 1405-1409. The Bremer Roland, 5.47 metres tall on a podium 10.21 metres tall, is the largest and most famous of the medieval Roland statues that historically symbolised the political independence and trading privileges of Hanseatic cities; the statue holds the sword of justice and the imperial shield with the inscription Vryheit do ik ju openbar — Freedom do I make known to you. The Bremer Rathaus, an exquisite Weser Renaissance facade by Lüder von Bentheim of 1612 layered onto the Gothic medieval core, contains the Obere Rathaushalle with its model ships hanging from the ceiling, the Güldenkammer, the Festsaal, the Senat conference room, and the Ratskeller wine cellar dating from 1408 (the oldest German wine cellar in continuous operation, holding the largest collection of vintage German wines). Beside the Rathaus stands the bronze Stadtmusikanten group by Gerhard Marcks of 1953, depicting the donkey, dog, cat and rooster of the Brothers Grimm fairy tale Town Musicians of Bremen stacked on each other''s shoulders. Visitors traditionally rub the donkey''s nose for luck. The Bremer Dom St. Petri, the Bremen Cathedral of Saint Peter, dominates the eastern Marktplatz; founded in 789 by Bishop Willehad, the present Romanesque-Gothic basilica with its twin western towers was completed in the thirteenth century, contains the Bleikeller (Lead Cellar) with mummified corpses naturally preserved in the dry cellar air, the Bibelgarten Biblical garden, and the crypt of Archbishop Adalbert of Bremen. The Liebfrauenkirche, on the western side of the Marktplatz, is the oldest parish church of Bremen with twelfth-century origins.

The Bremen Schnoor (the Schnoorviertel), Bremen''s oldest quarter, is a maze of narrow medieval lanes between the Weser river and the Stadtgraben moat, with timber-framed and brick houses from the fifteenth, sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, today filled with goldsmith workshops, antiquarian bookshops, marzipan confectioners, the Beck''s glass and pottery shop, the Geschichtenhaus historical museum and the Schifferhaus. The Böttcherstraße, just north of the Marktplatz, is a 110-metre-long expressionist-art-nouveau pedestrian street commissioned by the Bremen coffee merchant Ludwig Roselius (founder of Kaffee HAG, the inventor of decaffeinated coffee, who used his fortune to remake the street between 1922 and 1931), with buildings by Bernhard Hoetger including the Lichtbringer relief, the Paula Modersohn-Becker House (the first museum in the world dedicated to a single female artist, the Worpswede painter Paula Modersohn-Becker), the Roselius-Haus museum of Bremen art and history, the Glockenspielhaus with its three-times-daily Glockenspiel of 30 porcelain bells from the Meissen porcelain factory, and the Robinson Crusoe Haus. The Schlachte promenade along the Weser, the Wallanlagen ramparts (the Bremen ramparts converted to a public garden by Isaak Altmann around 1810, one of the earliest urban green-belt projects in Germany), the Mühle am Wall (the windmill on the Wall, a popular Bremen postcard motif), the Liebfrauenkirchhof and the Bremer Geschichtenmeile complete the inner-city itinerary.

Bremen''s museum district extends from the Kulturmeile along the Bürgerweide. The Kunsthalle Bremen contains a notable collection of European painting from Cranach the Elder to the Bremen Worpswede school (Paula Modersohn-Becker, Otto Modersohn, Heinrich Vogeler, Fritz Mackensen), French Impressionism (Monet, Manet, Pissarro, Cézanne, Van Gogh), German Expressionism (Beckmann, Kirchner, Schmidt-Rottluff) and contemporary art. The Übersee-Museum Bremen is one of the oldest and largest German ethnological and natural-history museums, founded in 1896, with strong collections from Oceania, the Americas, Africa and Asia, plus a natural-history collection on the Weser delta, the North Sea and the polar regions. The Wilhelm Wagenfeld House, the Focke-Museum of Bremen state history, the Universum Bremen (Universum Science Centre) opened in 2000 with hundreds of hands-on science experiments in a distinctive whale-shaped building near the University of Bremen, the Bremer Krankenhaus-Museum, the Hafen-Museum Bremen Speicher XI, the Weserburg Museum für moderne Kunst on the river island, the Bremer Geschichtenhaus and the Anthroposophical Galerie complete the museum map. The Bürgerpark, the central park north of the Hauptbahnhof, is one of the largest privately funded urban parks in Europe (founded 1866 by Wilhelm Benque), with the Hollersee, the Marcusbrunnen, the Bürgerpark Tombola (annual lottery to fund the park), and the boat-rental on the Hollersee.

Bremerhaven, the seaport city of the Land, was founded in 1827 by the Bremen Senate at the mouth of the Weser after the river had silted up and Bremen lost its sea access; the new city''s name means Bremen''s Harbour. Bremerhaven is now one of the largest seaports in Europe and the centre of German polar research. Major Bremerhaven attractions include the Deutsches Schifffahrtsmuseum (German Maritime Museum) by Hans Scharoun, with the medieval Hanse cog of Bremen recovered from the Weser, the U-boat U-2540 Wilhelm Bauer, the polar ship Grönland of 1867, the gaff schooner Seute Deern, the fireship Elbe 3 and the Type XXI submarine; the Klimahaus Bremerhaven 8° Ost (the Climate House at 8 degrees east longitude), opened 2009, walking the visitor through nine climate zones along the eighth meridian east from Bremerhaven to Antarctica via Switzerland, Sardinia, Niger, Cameroon, Antarctica, Samoa, Alaska, the Bremen-Hallig, and back; the Deutsches Auswandererhaus (German Emigration Centre) on the historic Neuer Hafen, documenting the seven million Europeans who emigrated to America via Bremerhaven between 1830 and 1974, with reconstructed ship steerage, the Grand Central station of New York and the Ellis Island procedures; the Zoo am Meer, a specialist marine-mammal zoo with polar bears, harbour seals, walruses and penguins; the Historisches Museum Bremerhaven; the Lighthouse Roter Sand offshore; the Mediterraneo shopping mall in the converted dock; the Lloyd Werft shipyard.

Beyond the cities, the Bremen state encompasses the Blockland (a wet pasture and dyke landscape on the Wümme north of the city, sometimes called Bremen''s Little Holland), the Hollerland nature reserve, the Werderland and the Niedervieland; the Bremen Park (the Bürgerpark and the Stadtwald), the Rhododendron Park with its 200-hectare collection of rhododendron, azalea and woodland gardens (Botanical Gardens), the Weserstadion (home of Werder Bremen, the football club founded in 1899), the famous Bremen freimarkt that has run since 1035 (the oldest German fair), and the AG-Weser shipyard heritage trail. The Worpswede artists'' colony, technically across the Bremen border in Lower Saxony, was founded in 1889 by Fritz Mackensen, Otto Modersohn, Hans am Ende and Fritz Overbeck, and is closely tied to Bremen culture; it includes the Barkenhoff of Heinrich Vogeler, the Paula Modersohn-Becker Worpswede House and the Käseglocke (the so-called Cheese-Dome house). The Teufelsmoor (the Devil''s Moor) north of Bremen is a remnant of the historic Wümme moor landscape.

Bremen cuisine is North-German maritime and agricultural in character. Knipp (Bremen''s buckwheat-pork-liver porridge sliced and fried with pickled gherkins and potatoes) is the city''s signature winter dish. Bremer Labskaus, a sailor''s dish of corned beef, beetroot, potato and onion served with a fried egg, herring fillet and gherkins, is shared with Hamburg, the Baltic and the Faroe Islands. Bremer Klaben, a heavy fruit-loaf Christmas cake, is the city''s alternative to the south-German Stollen, baked from January to Christmas and only sold at specialist Bremen bakeries. Pannfisch (pan-fried fish in mustard sauce with mashed potato), Matjes (young herring) served with red onion and cream sauce, Krabbenbrötchen (a roll filled with cold-water shrimp from the North Sea, traditionally peeled by the Krabbenpulerinnen), Aalsuppe (eel soup, shared with Hamburg), Birnen, Bohnen und Speck (pears, beans and bacon, the classic North German autumn dish), the Bremer Kohl und Pinkel (kale with Pinkel sausage, served on Kohlfahrt walking outings), the Bremer Knipp, the smoked-fish platter, the Buttje (small flatfish from the Weser estuary), the Steinbutt (turbot), the Scholle (plaice) and the Speckkuchen are staple home dishes. Sweets include Babbeler licorice candy (a Bremen tradition since 1864 at the Bonbon Buschmann factory), Bremer Babbeler, Bremer Kluten (chocolate-covered peppermint sticks), the Bremer Brezel (a flat-style pretzel) and the Schwarzbrot. Coffee is a Bremen tradition: Bremen has been the largest German coffee port for over 200 years, with the Bremer Kaffeebörse (the original Bremen Coffee Exchange founded 1957), the Kaffee HAG (Hag Coffee Trading) founded by Ludwig Roselius in 1906 and now part of Jacobs Douwe Egberts, Eduscho (also part of JDE), Melitta partners, Azul Kaffee, Lloyd Caffee at the Bremerhaven port, and the historic Eilles, Bremer, and Roselius coffee brands. Tea, similarly, has a strong Bremen tradition through Onno Behrends and the Friesen tea houses. Bremen-brewed beer is dominated by Beck''s Brewery (Brauerei Beck & Co.), founded in 1873 by Lüder Rutenberg, Heinrich Beck and Thomas May; Beck''s Pilsner is the most-exported German beer worldwide and the Beck''s Brewery offers tours of the historic brewery on the Weser river. Haake-Beck is the local Bremen-brewed light beer (originally a separate brewery founded 1826, now part of the Anheuser-Busch InBev Bremen group), supplied in Stubbi short bottles. Bremen-style schnapps include Bremer Bismarck schnapps, Bommerlunder (technically Hamburg-Schleswig-Holstein) and the apple-based Hot Drinks of the Schnoor district.

The history before 1933 is long. Bremen was founded as a Saxon trading post on the Weser before 787, when Charlemagne established the Bishopric of Bremen and his missionary Willehad as its first bishop. Bremen became an Archbishopric in 845, when the missionary Anskar arrived to convert Scandinavia from his Bremen-Hamburg base. The Hanseatic League membership dates from the thirteenth century and was confirmed in 1260; the Bremen Roland of 1404 and the Bremen Town Hall of 1409 mark the height of the city''s independence and prosperity. The 1646 confirmation of the imperial freedoms by Emperor Ferdinand III made Bremen formally a Free Imperial City, a status reaffirmed by the Peace of Westphalia in 1648. The 1815 Congress of Vienna recognised Bremen as one of the four Hanseatic Free Republics (along with Hamburg, Lübeck and Frankfurt am Main); Bremerhaven was founded by Mayor Johann Smidt in 1827 to give Bremen sea access after the silting of the Weser. The 1827 transition from the Bremen Mark to the German Customs Union and the 1871 inclusion in the German Empire transformed Bremen into a major industrial city. The Bremen mercantile dynasties — the Beckenbauer, the Smidt, the Senator Andrä Linnemann, the Bremer Vulkan shipyard, the Norddeutscher Lloyd shipping line (one of the world''s great ocean liner companies, founded 1857) — gave the city its prosperous nineteenth century. The Bremer Vulkan launched ships including the SMS Möwe and the Bremen IV. After 1945 Bremen was placed under American administration and given the status of a Land in 1947 as the smallest American enclave in the British zone. Bremen''s constitution of 1947 is the second-oldest in the Federal Republic after Bavaria''s.',
    transportation = 'Bremen Airport, Flughafen Bremen, IATA BRE and ICAO EDDW, lies just three kilometres south of the Bremen city centre — closer to the city than any other German major airport, reached by the Bremer Straßenbahn tram line 6 in eleven minutes from the Hauptbahnhof. The airport opened in 1913, served four million passengers annually before the 2020 downturn, and now sits at around two million passengers per year with the consolidation of Ryanair services. Currently Bremen handles Ryanair, Lufthansa, Eurowings, KLM, Turkish Airlines and seasonal Mediterranean charters; the historic Lufthansa Bremen technical training base, the Bremer Aero-Lloyd, and the Airbus Bremen test-flight operations all use the airport. The Lufthansa Technik Bremerhaven base maintains the helicopter logistics fleet for the offshore wind farms. Bremerhaven has a small airfield at Bremerhaven-Luneort, used for general aviation, helicopter offshore-wind operations and occasionally cargo. The Bremerhaven harbour airport supports the Wadden Sea Naturpark surveillance flights. Smaller airfields include Bremen-Stade (just outside the Bremen border in Lower Saxony) and Worpswede; the legendary Borgfeld glider field is used by Bremen aero clubs.

Bremen Hauptbahnhof, opened in 1889 with the magnificent neo-renaissance facade by Hubert Stier, is the central rail node of Bremen with 14 platforms and around 130,000 passengers per day. It is connected to the long-distance and regional networks of Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Nord, ODEG, metronom Eisenbahngesellschaft, EVB Mittelweserbahn and Nordwestbahn, all operating regional services under the VBN Verkehrsverbund Bremen-Niedersachsen tariff. The ICE Berlin-Hannover-Bremen-Oldenburg-Wilhelmshaven services pass through Bremen Hauptbahnhof; the Hamburg-Bremen-Köln-Frankfurt-Basel ICE 25/26/30 axis is the most-frequented; the IC line Norddeich Mole-Emden-Leer-Oldenburg-Bremen-Hannover-Berlin connects the East Frisian coast to Berlin; the new EuroCity Berlin-Bremen-Amsterdam services use the Bremen-Oldenburg-Leer corridor. The Hamburg-Bremen high-speed corridor, currently being upgraded for 200 kph running, is a major investment project of the Federal government. The Bremen-Hannover line, opened 1847 by the Hannover-Bremen railway, was electrified in 1968 and now carries half-hourly ICE services. Other key Bremen rail nodes are Bremen-Burg, Bremen-Mahndorf, Bremen-Vegesack, Bremerhaven Hauptbahnhof (the second-largest in the state), Bremerhaven Lehe, Bremerhaven Wulsdorf and the Bremen-Oslebshausen freight yard.

The regional rail network includes the Bremen S-Bahn, opened in 2010 and operated by NordWestBahn, with four lines: RS1 Bremen Hbf-Bremen Vegesack-Bremerhaven Lehe-Bremerhaven Hbf-Cuxhaven, RS2 Bremen Hbf-Verden-Twistringen, RS3 Bad Zwischenahn-Oldenburg-Bremen Hbf-Bremen-Hemelingen, and RS4 Bremen Hbf-Bremen-Farge. The Bremen S-Bahn is integrated into the VBN tariff and is a key element of the Bremen-Oldenburg-Bremerhaven north-west metropolitan region transport.

The Bremen tram network (Straßenbahn Bremen), operated by Bremer Straßenbahn AG (BSAG), is the only tram system in the Bundesland and one of the oldest in Germany (the first horsedrawn tram from the Mauerstraße to the Domsheide began on 4 June 1876, the electric Bremen tram from 1892). Today the network has eight lines (1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8 and 10) totalling about 110 kilometres and 130 stops, including extensions across the river to Huchting and Riensberg in the south and to Borgfeld and Lilienthal in the north (the last partly using a converted track of the historic Jan-Reiners-Eisenbahn). Tram 6 to Bremen Airport in 11 minutes is one of the fastest airport-tram connections in Europe. The BSAG also operates an extensive bus network, the Hansa-Linie 25 to the University, the Sprintbus and the night-bus lines. Bremerhaven has an extensive bus network operated by Verkehrsbetriebe Bremerhaven (BremerhavenBus) but no rail-based urban transport; the historic Bremerhaven tram closed in 1982. The Bremerhaven harbour bus, the Cuxhaven Sea Bus and the BLG Logistics fleet handle the port traffic.

The Autobahn network around Bremen is dense for such a small state. The A1 Hamburg-Bremen-Münster-Köln runs north-south through the eastern fringe of the Bremen state at Bremen-Mahndorf; the A27 Cuxhaven-Bremerhaven-Bremen-Walsrode runs north-south through the western part, with the famous Weserquerung Stromtalbrücke; the A28 Leer-Oldenburg-Bremen-Delmenhorst-Stuhr runs east-west through the south; the A270 motorway from the A27 to Bremen-Industriehäfen serves the port. Bundesstraßen include the B6 to Hamburg, the B75 to Hamburg, the B6 to Leer, the B74 to Stade, the B441 to Vegesack, the B212 to Bremerhaven and the B6 to Hannover. The Stephanibrücke and the Wilhelm-Kaisen-Brücke carry road traffic over the Weser into the city.

The major economic driver of Bremen transport is the port. The Bremen-Bremerhaven ports together (operated by bremenports GmbH & Co. KG) are the fourth-largest seaport complex in Europe by container traffic (after Rotterdam, Hamburg and Antwerpen-Brugge), handling around 4.5 million TEU per year. The Bremerhaven Container Terminals 1, 2, 3 and 4 (operated by Eurogate, the JV between bremenports and Hamburger HHLA''s competitor), the Auto-Terminal Bremerhaven (operated by BLG Logistics, the largest car logistics terminal in the world handling around 2.1 million vehicles per year for VW, BMW, Mercedes, Audi, Porsche, Toyota and others), the Fischereihafen (the historic fishing port now host to the Frosta and Iglo frozen-fish factories), the Kaiserhafen, the Nordhafen, the Sander-Hafen and the Schleusen system on the Geeste/Weser confluence. Bremen-Stadt has the Industriehafen, the Holzhafen, the Hemelinger Hafen and the Hansaarbeiter-Hafen, with major bulk and chemical traffic for the Bremen industrial cluster. The Bremer Lagerhausgesellschaft (BLG Logistics SE & Co. KGaA) operates one of Germany''s largest logistics businesses with operations in Bremen, Bremerhaven and worldwide.

The Weser river itself is navigable from the open sea at Bremerhaven up to Hann. Münden, with the major lock at Bremen-Hemelingen and the further locks at Dörverden, Petershagen, Schlüsselburg, Drakenburg, Landesbergen and Hameln; the canalisation of the lower Weser to Bremen Hauptbahnhof (in fact to the Stadtwerder) is being maintained and dredged by the WSV. The Bremen-Oslebshausen yard handles bulk traffic. The Mittelweser-Wasserstraße connects Bremen via Minden to the Mittelland Canal and the Rhine-Main waterways. The Hunte-Weser Hunte canal connects to Oldenburg.

The Bremen-Bremerhaven Wasserstraße cycle route, the Weser-Radweg (one of Germany''s most popular long-distance cycling trails, from Hann. Münden to Cuxhaven), the Hamburg-Bremen-Köln cycle route, the European EuroVelo 12 (North Sea Cycle Route) and the EuroVelo 15 are signed for cyclists. Bremen has a strong cycling culture; about a quarter of all journeys in the city are by bicycle, and the city has more than 800 kilometres of dedicated cycle paths. The Bremer Bike-Hire schemes (Wirbike, Nextbike) complete the city mobility offer. The Hansa-Carré shared-bike scheme and the Cambio car-sharing cooperative are Bremen institutions, with Cambio Carsharing GmbH founded in Bremen in 1990 as one of the first such schemes in Germany.

Long-distance buses cluster at the Bremen ZOB beside the Hauptbahnhof; FlixBus, Sindbad, Eurolines and others operate to Hamburg, Berlin, the Polish ports, Copenhagen and Amsterdam. The Bremerhaven ZOB is at the Hauptbahnhof. The Bremen Hauptbahnhof underground bicycle parking, the new Mobiliyhubs around the regional Bahnhöfe, and the Bremer Verkehrsverbund (VBN) integrated tariff complete the urban transport offer.

Bremen pioneered the modern car-sharing scheme: Cambio Bremen, founded 1990 as Stattauto Bremen, was one of the first community-based car-sharing schemes in Germany and the European model for the Mobility-Carsharing of Switzerland and the StadtMobil of Stuttgart. Today Cambio Bremen operates over 250 vehicles at over 100 stations across the city. The Bremen Senate has been a leader in mobility-as-a-service since the 2010s; the Mobil.punkt mobility-hubs combine bike-hire, car-sharing, e-charging and tram stops at single nodes. The Daimler Mobility Bremen (now Share Now), the WeShare Bremen and the Miles electric-car-share completed the offer. The Bremen Senate plans the Bremer Bahn underground regional rail extension and the Bremen-Bremerhaven Express direct service via the Burglesum tunnel.',
    economics = 'Bremen, with a regional GDP of about 35 billion euros, has one of the highest per-capita GDPs of the German Bundesländer despite its compact size and relatively small population (680,000 across the two cities, about 570,000 in Bremen and 110,000 in Bremerhaven). The economy is dominated by maritime industries, automotive and aerospace manufacturing, food and beverages (especially coffee, beer and frozen fish), logistics and a sophisticated service sector. The Bremerhavener Versorgungs- und Verkehrsgesellschaft (BVS) and the Wirtschaftsförderung Bremen (WFB) at the Eduard-Schopf-Allee market the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Bremen and the Industrie- und Handelskammer Bremerhaven (Handelskammer Bremen since 1849, the second-oldest German chamber of commerce after Hamburg) represent the corporate sector.

Mercedes-Benz Group AG operates its second-largest German passenger car plant at Bremen-Sebaldsbrück (the Mercedes-Benz Werk Bremen). The plant employs around 13,000 workers and builds the Mercedes-Benz C-Class sedan and estate, the E-Class sedan and estate (both also built at Sindelfingen), the GLC SUV, the EQE and EQE SUV electric models, and the SL-Class roadster (the historic Mercedes-Benz SL sports car, the only Mercedes still built at Bremen but moved to BR R 232). Mercedes-Benz Bremen is the largest single private employer in the state of Bremen. The plant began in 1938 as the Borgward factory of Carl Borgward, was acquired by Daimler-Benz in 1961 after Borgward''s collapse, and has since been the central plant of the Mercedes-Benz mid-size programme. The Mercedes-Benz Bremen Klassik Center and the Mercedes-Benz Bremen Werkmuseum document the plant''s history.

Airbus Bremen, the second-largest Airbus production site in Germany after Hamburg-Finkenwerder, is the global centre of wing-equipping for Airbus commercial aircraft (Airbus A320 family, Airbus A330, Airbus A350) and the headquarters of Airbus Defence and Space''s German Bremen operations. Airbus Bremen employs around 4,000 workers and is closely tied to the German Aerospace Center (DLR) Bremen, the ZARM Centre for Applied Space Technology and Microgravity, and the Fraunhofer-Institut für Fertigungstechnik und Angewandte Materialforschung (IFAM) cluster around the University. OHB SE, the listed Bremen space-technology company, has its headquarters at the Universitätsallee and is the third-largest European satellite manufacturer (after Airbus Defence and Space and Thales Alenia Space). OHB built the Galileo IOV/Final-Operational-Capability satellites, the SARah radar-reconnaissance satellites for the Bundeswehr, the ENVISAT atmospheric sensor, the EnMAP hyperspectral mission, the Heinrich Hertz communications satellite and many other missions. The Galileo satellite navigation constellation has been a major OHB programme. ATLAS ELEKTRONIK GmbH (now Thyssenkrupp Marine Systems, ATLAS division) is the leading German naval combat-systems and submarine electronics manufacturer, founded in Bremen in 1902 and now part of Thyssenkrupp; ATLAS Bremen builds sonar, mine-hunting systems, naval command and control systems, the SeaSpider anti-torpedo countermeasure and the MOEDAS towed sonar for German and export navies. Lürssen Werft (Fr. Lürssen Werft GmbH & Co. KG), founded in 1875 at Vegesack, is one of the world''s largest superyacht builders and a major naval shipbuilder (the K130 corvettes for the Bundeswehr, the F125 frigates jointly with thyssenkrupp Marine Systems Hamburg, the JaguarYacht, the Eclipse, the Azzam — the world''s longest superyacht — and many other vessels for European and Middle Eastern owners).

Beck''s Brewery (Brauerei Beck & Co.), founded in 1873 by Lüder Rutenberg, Heinrich Beck and Thomas May, is the most internationally exported German beer brand. Beck''s Pilsner is sold in over 100 countries and dominates the export volumes of Beck''s and the parent Anheuser-Busch InBev (which acquired Beck''s in 2002 for 1.8 billion euros). The Beck''s brewery on the Weser still operates the main brewing site at Am Deich; the Beck''s Brewery Tour is a popular Bremen tourist attraction. Haake-Beck, the local Bremen pilsner and Haake-Beck Edel-Hell, is the regional brand of the same parent company. Beck''s also sells Beck''s Gold, Beck''s Green Lemon, Beck''s Ice and other flavoured variants. Other Bremen-brewed beers include Becks Pale Ale and the Haake-Beck Pils im Stubbi. The traditional Bremer Ratskeller wine cellar (founded 1408 in the Town Hall) holds one of Germany''s largest collections of vintage wines.

Coffee is a Bremen institution. The Bremer Hauptbahnhof district hosts Jacobs Douwe Egberts (JDE) coffee operations including the Eduscho and Kaffee HAG brands. Kaffee HAG, the world''s first decaffeinated coffee invented by Ludwig Roselius and his chemist Karl Wimmer in 1906 (the patent for the decaffeination process was granted to Kaffee HAG of Bremen in 1908), was one of the largest German coffee brands for most of the twentieth century. The Roselius family fortune financed the Böttcherstraße rebuild. Other Bremen coffee houses include Azul Kaffee, Lloyd Caffee, Roselius Caffee, Lloyd Caffee (named after Norddeutscher Lloyd), the Münchhausen Hauserkaffee and the historic Eilles, Bremer, Schiller and Hapag-Lloyd brands. Tea, similarly, has a strong Bremen tradition through Onno Behrends, the Friesen Teehäuser and the Bremer Teehandel. Hachez Chocolade GmbH (Joseph Emile Hachez, founded 1890), the premium Bremen chocolate maker producing the Cocoa-d''Or, Hachez Dark and other dark-chocolate brands, is one of the most respected German specialty chocolate manufacturers and is part of Bremer Hachez Chocolade GmbH (since 2012 a subsidiary of the Belgian Bruyerre group).

Frozen-fish processing and food are concentrated at Bremerhaven, where the Frosta AG (a leading European frozen-food maker, headquartered at Bremerhaven) operates large factories; the Unilever Iglo Bremerhaven plant produces frozen vegetables and fish fingers; the Nordsee chain, Costa Galera Bremerhaven and the Deutsche See GmbH (the largest German fish wholesaler, originally Anson''s Fischhandel Bremerhaven, with the Loch Duart and Atlantic salmon trade) form a fish-processing cluster. The Bremerhaven Fischereihafen is the second-largest German fishing harbour after Rostock.

Logistics is the Bremen-Bremerhaven core economic activity. BLG Logistics SE & Co. KGaA (Bremer Lagerhausgesellschaft), founded in 1877 by Senator Andrä Linnemann, is one of the largest German logistics groups, with the BLG Auto-Terminal Bremerhaven (the world''s largest car terminal, handling 2.1 million vehicles per year for the global automotive industry), the BLG Container Terminal at Bremerhaven, the BLG Mosolf Bremen warehouse and the BLG Mosolf Sebaldsbrück car-distribution centre, the BLG Tankliegegerät, and BLG Logistics worldwide operations. Eurogate Container Terminal Bremerhaven (the joint venture between BLG and Eurogate) is the leading container-terminal operator at Bremerhaven; the Eurogate Bremerhaven Terminal handles around 5.5 million TEU per year. Logistics-as-a-service, intermodal transport, distribution centres and reefer-container handling all cluster at Bremen-Bremerhaven. The bremenports GmbH (the Bremen state port authority) operates the port infrastructure; the Hafenbahn Bremerhaven (the harbour railway) handles 1.5 million wagons per year.

Bremerhaven hosts the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research (AWI), one of the world''s leading polar-research institutions, with the polar research vessels Polarstern, Heincke, Maria S. Merian, the Neumayer III Antarctic research station, the AWIPEV station on Spitsbergen, the Antarctic Dallmann Laboratory, and the AWI offices in Potsdam and on Helgoland. AWI Bremerhaven, with around 1,200 employees, is the European centre for climate-change research, sea-ice modelling and polar biology. The Klimahaus Bremerhaven, the Deutsche Schifffahrtsmuseum and the German Maritime Museum extend the polar science economy into tourism. The Bremerhavener Lighthouse-Tender Bunte Kuh II and the historic ice-breaker Stettin (now decommissioned) round out the Bremerhaven port-of-knowledge.

Offshore wind, which has become a major Bremerhaven industry since the early 2000s, is concentrated at the Offshore Terminal Bremerhaven (OTB), the Steelwind Nordenham foundation works (across the Weser at Nordenham, Lower Saxony, but with Bremerhaven supply chain ties), the WeserWind nacelle facility, the Senvion (formerly REpower) Bremerhaven plant (which closed in 2019), and the new Siemens Gamesa nacelle and blade works at Cuxhaven (in Lower Saxony) which together form a North-Sea offshore-wind industrial cluster. The Bremerhaven offshore-wind cluster supplies the North Sea wind farms via the Bremerhaven harbour.

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Universität Bremen, one of the German Universities of Excellence, has around 23,000 students and major research in materials science, ocean and climate research, robotics (the German Research Centre for Artificial Intelligence DFKI Bremen), space technology (ZARM Centre for Applied Space Technology and Microgravity, with its famous 146-metre drop tower for short-duration zero-gravity experiments), and economics (the Constructor University Bremen, formerly Jacobs University Bremen, the private research university at Bremen-Grohn). The Hochschule Bremen, the Hochschule Bremerhaven, the Hochschule für Künste Bremen and the Bremen-Akademie supplement higher education. The Fraunhofer-Institut für Fertigungstechnik und Angewandte Materialforschung (IFAM) Bremen specialises in adhesive bonding and surface technology. The Fraunhofer-Institut für Windenergiesysteme (IWES) at Bremerhaven hosts the world''s largest wind turbine test centre. The German Research Centre for Artificial Intelligence (DFKI) Bremen has the robotics and human-machine-interaction research division. The Bremen InfraServ data-centre cluster and the Bremen-Cybersecurity-Cluster are emerging tech hubs.

Banking and finance include the Bremer Landesbank (now part of NORD/LB), the Sparkasse Bremen, the Sparkasse Bremerhaven, the Volksbank Bremen-Nord, the Hanseatic Bank, and the Bremer Wertpapierbörse (the Bremen Stock Exchange, founded 1888 and merged with the Berlin Stock Exchange in 2007 into the Börse Berlin AG). Insurance includes the Hanse-Merkur Bremen branch and the Bremer Versicherungs-Verband cooperative.

Tourism contributes substantially to GDP. Bremen draws around 7 million visitor nights per year (combined Bremen and Bremerhaven), with the Marktplatz, the Bremen Town Musicians, the Schnoor and the Böttcherstraße as the urban core, the Klimahaus, the German Emigration Centre and the German Maritime Museum as the Bremerhaven anchors, and the cruise-passenger traffic at the Columbuskaje (a major North Sea cruise terminal).',
    introduced_species = 'Bremen, despite its small surface area (419 square kilometres) and dense urban character, is a significant gateway for introduced species into Germany because of its position at the lower Weser estuary, its long history as a port handling ballast water and timber dunnage from across the world, and its rich aquatic and brownfield habitats. The Bremer Senat coordinates invasive-species monitoring through the Senator für Klimaschutz, Umwelt, Mobilität, Stadtentwicklung und Wohnungsbau, the BUND Landesverband Bremen and the NABU Bremen; the Hochschule Bremen and the AWI Bremerhaven contribute scientific monitoring.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been recorded in Bremen since the 1970s when individuals from the western expansion of the 1934 Hessen Edersee release reached the Hannover-Bremen corridor. Today the Bremen city raccoon population is conspicuous along the Bremen Bürgerpark, the Stadtwald, the Werderland, the Blockland and the Hollerland nature reserves, plus the suburban Schwachhausen, Horn-Lehe and Burglesum districts. Annual hunting bags in Bremen state are smaller than in Hessen or Brandenburg, around several hundred per year, reflecting the modest size of the state. Bremerhaven raccoons are similar, with populations along the Cuxhaven coast and the Bederkesa-Wesermünde area. The Senatsumweltverwaltung and the Bremer Jagdverein coordinate urban raccoon management; advice for homeowners on attic-vent sealing and dustbin-lid locking is published online.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Bremen from the eastern German states through the 2000s and 2010s; small populations are recorded along the Blockland, the Werderland and the Bremen-Bremerhaven north-western corridor. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the lower Weser, the Hunte, the Lesum, the Wümme and especially in the Bremen Blockland and the Hollerland nature reserves. The Bremen Wasserwirtschaftsamt monitors dyke damage from nutria burrowing; trapping is mandated. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to the lower Weser but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and the Bremer Forsten and now has small but growing populations on the Wümme and the Lesum.

The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs in slow water bodies across Bremen state, particularly in the Bremen Blockland, the Werderland, the Hunte tributaries and the Bremerhaven canals. The Wasser- und Schifffahrtsverwaltung des Bundes coordinates trapping.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established a feral resident population on the lower Weser, the Bürgerpark Hollersee, the Werderpark, the Bremerhaven harbour and the Tegelsbergsee. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations and now breeds throughout Bremen, with conspicuous urban populations at the Bürgerpark, the Schlosspark Schönebeck, the Werderland and the Bremerhaven Speckenbüttel Park. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is occasional in Bremen but has not established large breeding populations as in Heidelberg. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on Bremen park ponds. The mute swan, although native, is locally superabundant on the Weser. Various escaped lovebirds and African grey parrots have been recorded in Bremen winter cold spells without becoming established. The Indian house crow (Corvus splendens), occasionally reported in Bremerhaven Container Port arrivals, has not been confirmed as a self-sustaining population. The Bremerhaven port also handles regular sightings of vagrant exotic birds carried by storms from the Atlantic.

Among fish, the Weser estuary and the freshwater inland waterways of Bremen state host the same set of introduced species found elsewhere in northern Germany. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch, is established in the Werder and Blockland gravel pits. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling, is widespread. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels, occurs in old gravel pits. The rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Regenbogenforelle, is stocked in the Bremen-Verdener Forellenfarm and supplied to local restaurants. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis, Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella, Graskarpfen, is used to control aquatic vegetation in Bremen lakes. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel, native to the Black Sea, has reached the Weser via the Mittellandkanal and the Rhine-Main system, with the first Bremen record in 2018; the species is now established in the lower Weser. The Caspian Kessler''s goby and the bighead goby follow. The wels catfish, Silurus glanis, although native to the lower Weser before its extirpation in the late 19th century, has been reintroduced.

The Bremen-Bremerhaven ports are a major entry point for ballast-water and hull-fouling invasions, which is monitored under the IMO Ballast Water Management Convention. Established marine and brackish invaders include the Pacific oyster (Magallana gigas, Crassostrea gigas, Pazifische Auster), originally introduced for aquaculture and now ubiquitous on the Wadden Sea coast around Bremerhaven; the American razor clam (Ensis directus, Amerikanische Schwertmuschel), present on the Wadden Sea since the 1979 storm transport from the Atlantic, now the dominant clam on intertidal sand banks; the Asian shore crab (Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi), established on the Wadden Sea since around 2000; the Manila clam (Ruditapes philippinarum); the Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum (Japanischer Beerentang); and the Atlantic comb jelly (Mnemiopsis leidyi), originally from the western Atlantic, now common in the inner German Bight and reaching the Weser estuary. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe, is regularly trapped in the Weser, the Lesum and the Bremen city waterways. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel, and the quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel, are present in the freshwater systems. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel, is in the Weser and tributaries. The New Zealand mud snail, Potamopyrgus antipodarum, is widespread in Bremen brooks. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs, has been reported in Bremen-area garden ponds. The signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs, has been recorded in Bremen-area gravel pits.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in Bremen state from 2022 onwards with confirmed nests near Vegesack and along the Lesum corridor; the Imkerverband Bremen coordinates nest-removal teams with the Senatsumweltverwaltung. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Bremen avenues every late summer; the Bürgerpark chestnut avenues are particularly affected. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Bürgerpark, the Schloss Schönebeck and various Bremen private gardens. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established in Bremen. The Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) was reported in Bremerhaven container port in 2014; the outbreak has since been declared eradicated. The emerald ash borer (Agrilus planipennis) is a feared port-arrival pest from the Russian Far East and North America; monitoring traps are deployed at Bremerhaven container terminals by the Julius Kühn-Institut.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) is widespread along Bremen and Bremerhaven railway lines, the A1 and A27 motorway verges, and on disturbed ground in the Blockland; the LANUV Bremen coordinates control. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates the Wümme, Lesum and Hunte banks. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on the Werderland and Blockland stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in Bremen parks. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum) spreads along railway lines and harbour brownfields. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea) dominates fallow fields. Small balsam (Impatiens parviflora) is widespread on Bremen park edges. Lupines (Lupinus polyphyllus) occur on railway embankments. Black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia) has self-seeded into many Bremen disturbed habitats. The Indian balsam, the water primrose (Ludwigia grandiflora), the South African Crassula helmsii (Nadelkraut) and the floating fern Salvinia molesta have been recorded sporadically. Specifically in the maritime context, the cordgrass Spartina anglica (the hybrid salt-marsh grass) has invaded the Wadden Sea mudflats around Bremerhaven and the Weser estuary since around 1930 and has substantially altered the intertidal landscape, while Senecio inaequidens (Schmalblättriges Greiskraut), the South African ragwort, is now established on Bremen-Bremerhaven railway lines and disturbed sandy ground. The Senecio is toxic to grazing livestock.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have small populations in Bremen state forestry reserves at Knoops Park and Bremerhaven-Spadener See. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) are absent. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at low density in Bremen state forestry and the Blockland. American mink (Neovison vison, Amerikanischer Nerz), escaped from old Bremen-Bremerhaven fur-trade operations, is occasional along the Weser. The Bremen state veterinary authority monitors all wild mammals for African Swine Fever and avian influenza.'
WHERE region_name = 'Bremen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Hamburg, the Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg (Freie und Hansestadt Hamburg), is the second-largest city in Germany after Berlin and the seventh-largest in the European Union, with a population of around 1.9 million in the city and almost five million in the metropolitan region. Hamburg is also one of the sixteen federal states, a Stadtstaat, and one of the oldest continuously self-governing cities in Europe. The city sits on the lower Elbe river around 110 kilometres from the North Sea, with the harbour and the historic Speicherstadt occupying the southern banks of the Elbe and the Inner and Outer Alster lakes (Binnenalster and Außenalster) defining the green heart of the city. The Hamburg City Hall (Hamburger Rathaus) on the Rathausmarkt, built between 1886 and 1897 in Neo-Renaissance style by architect Martin Haller, contains the Senate Hall, the Hall of the Mayors and the famous Phoenix Hall depicting Hamburg''s rebuilding after the Great Fire of 1842; the Rathausmarkt and Adolphsplatz host the annual Hamburger Dom amusement market three times a year. The St. Petri Kirche, the St. Jacobi Kirche, the St. Katharinen Kirche and St. Nikolai Kirche (the latter a Mahnmal memorial to the Hamburg fires, with its spire still standing as the second-tallest church spire in the world at 147 metres after Ulm) form the historic Hauptkirchen network of the Hanseatic city. The St. Michaelis Kirche (the Michel), the city''s most famous landmark since 1786, dominates the southern Altstadt skyline; the 132-metre spire is climbable for views over the harbour and the Elbe.

The Hamburg Speicherstadt, the world''s largest historical warehouse district, stretches across an artificial island system on wooden piles in the Elbe between the Zollkanal and the Wandrahmsfleet. Built between 1883 and 1927 in dark red Neo-Gothic brick, the Speicherstadt is a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2015 (jointly listed with the adjacent Kontorhaus district including the Chilehaus, the world''s most famous expressionist office building by Fritz Höger, completed 1924, with its dramatic ship-prow brick facade resembling the bow of an ocean liner). The Speicherstadt warehouses, traditionally used to store coffee, tea, spices, tobacco, oriental carpets, cocoa, and trade in goods, today host the International Maritime Museum (the world''s largest privately owned collection of model ships and maritime art, founded by Peter Tamm in the Kaispeicher B of 1879), the Miniatur Wunderland (the world''s largest model railway with over 16,000 metres of track on six floors, opened 2001 by the Braun brothers, with sections on Hamburg, Bavaria, the United States, Scandinavia, Austria, Switzerland, France, Italy, Brazil, England and Monaco), the Speicherstadt Coffee Museum (the Speicherstadtmuseum and the Kaffeerösterei), the Dialog im Dunkeln blindness experience, the Hamburger Dungeon and the historic dock-worker apartments. The HafenCity, the new harbour quarter east of the Speicherstadt, is one of the largest urban-development projects in Europe, with around 1.6 square kilometres of converted former dock land containing the new Cruise Centre HafenCity, the Überseequartier (the new mixed-use district by Westfield), the Internationale Maritime Museum (in the converted Kaispeicher), the Marco-Polo-Tower, the Hanseatic Trade Center, the new Spiegel-Hochhaus (the Hamburg media tower of Der Spiegel since 2011), the Greenpeace International head office and the Elbphilharmonie. The Elbphilharmonie Hamburg, the new concert hall by Herzog & de Meuron opened in 2017 atop the historic Kaispeicher A warehouse, is one of the most acoustically sophisticated and architecturally striking concert halls in the world, with the wave-shaped glass roof, the public Plaza viewing platform at 37 metres, and three concert halls of 2100, 550 and 150 seats. The Elbphilharmonie has become the most-visited concert hall in Europe.

Beyond the harbour quarter, Hamburg offers the Reeperbahn in St. Pauli, the famous entertainment district that began as a rope-walk (Reeperbahn means rope-makers'' lane) for the 18th-century shipping industry and developed into a sailors'' entertainment quarter with the Davidstraße, the Herbertstraße, the Große Freiheit (the side street where the Beatles played the Indra and Kaiserkeller clubs in 1960-1962), the Reeperbahn Festival (the largest club festival in continental Europe), the St. Pauli Theatre, the Operettenhaus with the Disney musical productions (König der Löwen, Tarzan, Aladdin), and the Tabaluga musical theatre. The Schmidt Theater and the Schmidts Tivoli, plus the Indra-Musikclub, complete the variety venues. The football team Hamburger SV plays at the Volksparkstadion in Bahrenfeld; St. Pauli, the cult second-tier club, plays at the historic Millerntor-Stadion just east of the Reeperbahn. The Sternschanze quarter (Schanzenviertel), with the Rote Flora cultural centre, the Schulterblatt cafés and the Karoviertel, is the centre of alternative Hamburg. The Karolinenviertel and the Marktstraße host independent designers.

The Alster lakes, the Inner and Outer Alster, form the green heart of the central city. The Binnenalster, framed by the Jungfernstieg promenade with the Alsterpavillon café terrace and the historic Hamburger Hof, is the prestigious commercial address of the city. The Außenalster, a 164-hectare lake created by the damming of the Alster river in 1235, hosts the SV Hamburg yacht club, the Bootshaus Alsterbund, the Rathaussteg ferries, and is ringed by villas in the Pöseldorf, Harvestehude, Rotherbaum and Uhlenhorst districts. The Alstervorland, the Alsterpark and the lakeside-Schwanenbalkon walks are favourite Sunday outings. The Alstereis, the natural-ice rink during cold winters, is a Hamburg tradition reaching back to the 19th century but increasingly rare due to mild winters.

The Hamburg Kunsthalle, one of Germany''s largest fine-art museums, holds nineteen centuries of European painting and sculpture across three connected buildings (the original 1869 building by Georg Theodor Schirrmacher, the 1919 brick extension by Fritz Schumacher and the 1997 cube of the Galerie der Gegenwart by Oswald Mathias Ungers), with major works by Caspar David Friedrich (Der Wanderer über dem Nebelmeer, the famous Wanderer above the Sea of Fog), Philipp Otto Runge, the Hamburg Sezession of Anita Rée, Friedrich Ahlers-Hestermann and Karl Kluth, the Brücke Expressionists, and contemporary art from Anselm Kiefer, Gerhard Richter, Sigmar Polke and Bruce Nauman. The Museum für Kunst und Gewerbe Hamburg (MKG) is one of the leading German museums of applied art, with the Asian collection, the historical photography (Erich Salomon, Hans Meyer-Veden), the Kinder-Olympia exhibition, and the historic photographic plates of the Hamburg fire. The Bucerius Kunst Forum, the Deichtorhallen (one of the largest contemporary-art venues in Europe with the Halle für aktuelle Kunst and the Haus der Photographie), the Altonaer Museum and the Museum für Hamburgische Geschichte at the Holstenwall complete the museum map. The Hamburger Bahnhof (in Berlin, not Hamburg) is named after the historic Berlin terminus of the Hamburg railway. The Hamburg Planetarium in the Stadtpark, in the Stadtpark Wasserturm, and the Hamburg Stadtpark zoo (closed) once supplemented the natural-history offer. The Tierpark Hagenbeck in Stellingen, the world''s first zoo without bars (founded 1907 by Carl Hagenbeck), is one of the most innovative zoos in history and remains a major Hamburg attraction.

Other key sights include the historic Old Elbe Tunnel (St. Pauli Elbtunnel) of 1911, a pedestrian and bicycle tunnel under the Elbe with original copper-clad lifts; the Köhlbrandbrücke, the 1974 cable-stayed bridge over the Köhlbrand to the Wilhelmsburg and Veddel ports; the Landungsbrücken floating piers; the Cap San Diego museum ship (the so-called White Swan of the Atlantic, a 1962 cargo ship now permanently moored at the Überseebrücke); the Rickmer Rickmers sailing ship; the Fischmarkt at Altona every Sunday morning from 5 am with the legendary Fish Auction Hall (Fischauktionshalle) live-music morning beers; the Övelgönner Hafenstrand sand beach; the Treppenviertel of Blankenese with its terraced lanes; the Övelgönne strand and the Süllberg restaurant; the Wedel Schulauer Fährhaus where ships are greeted with their national anthems through the Welcome Point; the Süllberg in Blankenese; the Stadtpark in Winterhude with its planetarium; the Planten un Blomen public garden (Plants and Flowers in Low German) on the former wall ramparts with the daily water-light show in summer; the Hamburger Dom funfair held three times a year on the Heiligengeistfeld; the Hamburger Hauptbahnhof and the Bahnhof Dammtor station with their historic architecture; the BallinStadt Emigration Museum on the Veddel island, documenting the 5.2 million emigrants who sailed from Hamburg to America between 1850 and 1939 from the Bismarck-built Auswanderhallen; the Internationales Maritime Museum; the Helmut-Schmidt-Universität (the Bundeswehr-University in Wandsbek-Bramfeld); the historic Suchsdorfer Werft shipyard; the Internationale Gartenausstellung 1973 site in Wilhelmsburg.

Hamburg cuisine reflects the city''s maritime and trading character. Labskaus, the sailor''s dish of corned beef, beetroot, potato, onion and pickled herring with a fried egg on top, is the iconic Hamburg dish, shared with the Baltic and the Faroe Islands. Aalsuppe, Hamburg eel soup, is a sweet-sour broth originally cooked without eel (the name comes from Low German "aal" meaning "all" — meaning a soup of everything), now usually with smoked eel and prunes. Pannfisch, pan-fried fish in mustard cream sauce with potatoes, Matjes herring with red onion cream sauce and pommes, Krabbenbrötchen (a roll of cold-water North Sea shrimp peeled by the Krabbenpulerinnen), Bismarck-Hering (pickled herring), Brathering, Rollmops, Birnen Bohnen und Speck (pears, beans and bacon), the historic Hamburger Aalsuppe served in the Old Commercial Room, and Spanferkel suckling pig are staples. The Franzbrötchen, a flaky cinnamon-and-butter pastry developed in Hamburg in the early 19th century as a Hanseatic answer to French croissants, is one of the city''s most beloved bakery specialities. Hamburger Speckkuchen, Hamburger Schnitzel, Senfeier, the historic Hamburger Rundstück warm (a Hamburg sausage roll said to be the original "hamburger" that gave its name to the global meal), the Reichsbahn-Schnitzel, the Bismarck-Heringssalat, the Pottwurst (a smoked pork sausage) and the Speckpfannkuchen (bacon pancakes) round out the savoury menu. Sweets include the Rote Grütze red-berry compote with vanilla sauce, the Franzbrötchen, the Hamburger Apfelpfannkuchen, the historic Marzipan-Spezialitäten of the Schwartau and Niederegger (the latter Lübeck) traditions, and the Hamburg Christmas baking around the Hummel Hummel marzipan. The Hamburg coffee culture is strong, with Tchibo (the iconic Hamburg coffee retailer founded 1949 by Carl Tchilinghiryan), Darboven (Albert Darboven coffee), J.J. Darboven, the Coffee Plaza in the HafenCity, the Speicherstadt-Kaffee, Tchibo, Café Paris on the Rathausmarkt, the historic Alsterhaus and the Kaffeerösterei Burg. Hamburg beer: the iconic Astra Brewery in St. Pauli (Astra Urtyp pilsner, originally a Bavaria-Brauerei brand, now Carlsberg-owned), the Holsten Brewery in Altona (Carlsberg-owned since 2004), Ratsherrn (Hamburg craft beer in Schanzenviertel), the historic Joh. Albrecht and Carls breweries. Hamburg also has its own Rotspon tradition, a red wine (typically Bordeaux) imported and aged in oak in Hamburg-Lübeck cellars. Mineral water from the Volvic and Vittel sources is widely sold, and the historic Hamburg Selterswasser is a traditional name. Hamburg gin (Gin Sul, Heimat Distillery) and Hamburg whisky (Hammer Distillery) complete the craft-spirits map.

Hamburg history before 1933 is rich. Founded as a Saxon trading post at Hammaburg in the 9th century, Hamburg became a Hanseatic city in 1241 as a member of the Hamburg-Lübeck salt-and-fur trade route. The Imperial Free Status from 1410 (confirmed in 1768 by the Treaty of Gottorf), the 1815 Congress of Vienna recognition as a Hanseatic Free Republic, the Great Fire of 1842 that destroyed a third of the medieval city, the 1892 cholera epidemic, the rebuilding under city architect Fritz Schumacher and Senator Werner von Melle, the 1860 founding of HAPAG (Hamburg-Amerikanische Packetfahrt-Actien-Gesellschaft, the world''s largest ocean-shipping company at the time, under Albert Ballin), the construction of the Speicherstadt (1883-1927), the 1860 founding of Norddeutscher Lloyd in Bremen as Hamburg''s rival, the great emigration boom of the 1880s-1914 with five million emigrants passing through Hamburg to America via the Auswanderhallen of Veddel, the 1903 founding of the Hamburger Sport-Verein (HSV) football club, the foundation of the Hamburg-Bremen railway in 1846, the construction of the Köhlbrandbrücke planning, and the Weimar-era flourishing under Carl von Ossietzky and the Hamburg Dramatic Theatre. After 1945 Hamburg was placed under British administration as the British zone of occupation and given the status of a Land in 1949. Famous figures associated with Hamburg include Johannes Brahms (born in Specksgang in 1833), Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy (born in Hamburg in 1809), Heinrich Heine (lived in Hamburg from 1816 to 1819), Friedrich Gottlieb Klopstock, Friedrich Schiller (worked in Hamburg as theatre director in the late 1780s), Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart''s teacher Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach (who was Hamburg city music director from 1768 to 1788), and many others. Mention also of Helmut Schmidt, the SPD politician and Federal Chancellor, born in Hamburg in 1918 and a lifelong Hamburg resident.',
    transportation = 'Hamburg is one of the great transport hubs of northern Europe, with a major international airport, one of the largest container ports in the world, a dense urban rail network, an extensive Autobahn network, and a substantial network of canals and rivers. Hamburg Airport, Flughafen Hamburg Helmut Schmidt, IATA HAM and ICAO EDDH, is the fifth-busiest airport in Germany and the busiest in northern Germany, handling around 17 million passengers per year in normal traffic. The airport, located on Fuhlsbüttel about 8 kilometres north of the city centre and reachable by the S-Bahn line S1 in 25 minutes, is the second-oldest commercial airport in the world still operating from its original site (opened 1911) and is named after Helmut Schmidt, the Hamburg-born federal chancellor, since 2016. The main airline operators are Lufthansa (and its Lufthansa Cityline regional partner), Eurowings, easyJet (with a major base), Condor, KLM, British Airways, Turkish Airlines, Emirates, Etihad Airways, Singapore Airlines, Lot Polish, SAS, Wizz Air, Pegasus and a large range of seasonal Mediterranean charter flights. The Hamburg Airport long-distance terminal connects to Lufthansa''s Frankfurt and Munich hubs and to a wide range of European cities; the Hamburg Airport Express bus serves cruise ships at the Cruise Center HafenCity. Hamburg-Finkenwerder, the second airfield, on the south bank of the Elbe in the Süderelbe shipping district, is the home of the Airbus Hamburg-Finkenwerder plant and produces the A320 family for the European, Middle Eastern and Asian markets; the airfield also handles the A380 cabin completion and is the second-largest Airbus site in the world after Toulouse. The Hamburg-Finkenwerder airfield is restricted to Airbus and military operations.

Hamburg Hauptbahnhof, opened in 1906 with the magnificent steel-and-glass roof spanning 145 metres by Heinrich Reinhardt and Georg Süßenguth, is one of the busiest railway stations in Europe, handling around 550,000 passengers per day across its 14 platforms — making it the second-busiest German rail station after Frankfurt am Main and one of the top five busiest in Europe. The station serves Deutsche Bahn DB Fernverkehr (ICE and IC), DB Regio Nord (regional services), the S-Bahn Hamburg (six lines), the Hamburg U-Bahn (three lines via Hauptbahnhof), and long-distance buses at the ZOB Hamburg directly opposite. The Hauptbahnhof handles ICE and IC services to Berlin (the Berlin-Hamburg high-speed corridor opened 2004 at 230 kph allowing under 90-minute travel times), to Cologne and Frankfurt via Bremen and the Ruhr (ICE 25 and ICE 26), to Munich via Hannover, Würzburg and Augsburg (ICE 25), to Basel via Mannheim (ICE 12), to Copenhagen via the Vogelfluglinie (currently a ferry route, but with the new Fehmarn Belt fixed link due to open in 2029 allowing direct rail), to Stockholm via the Snälltåget night-train, and to Vienna and Zürich via the ÖBB Nightjet. Hamburg-Altona, Hamburg-Bergedorf, Hamburg-Harburg, Hamburg-Dammtor and the new Hamburg-Diebsteich (which will replace Altona Hauptbahnhof as the through-station for long-distance services from 2027) are the other major Hamburg rail nodes.

The Hamburg S-Bahn, operated by S-Bahn Hamburg GmbH (DB Regio subsidiary), has six lines (S1, S2, S3, S11, S21, S31) totalling 144 kilometres and 68 stations. The S-Bahn is electrified at 1200 V DC third rail and runs in tunnel through the central Hauptbahnhof-Jungfernstieg-Stadthausbrücke-Landungsbrücken-Reeperbahn-Königstraße-Altona Verbindungsbahn. The S1 to Wedel and Hamburg Airport (with the Berliner Tor branch), the S2 between Altona and Bergedorf, the S3 between Pinneberg and Stade (the longest S-Bahn line in Germany at 100 kilometres), the S11 between Blankenese and Ohlsdorf, the S21 between Aumühle and Elbgaustraße, and the S31 between Altona and Berliner Tor form the core network. The new S4 line under construction will run between Hamburg Hauptbahnhof and Bad Oldesloe (Schleswig-Holstein), parallel to the long-distance lines, opening from 2027 onwards. The Hamburg U-Bahn, operated by Hamburger Hochbahn AG, has four lines (U1, U2, U3, U4) totalling 110 kilometres and 93 stations, the third-largest U-Bahn network in Germany after Berlin and Munich. The U1 from Norderstedt-Mitte to Großhansdorf is the longest U-Bahn line in Hamburg at 55 kilometres; the U2 from Niendorf Nord to Mümmelmannsberg passes the Hauptbahnhof and Berliner Tor; the U3 from Barmbek to Wandsbek-Gartenstadt forms the historic Hochbahn ring around the inner city (Hamburg''s ring-style underground line, the oldest in the city, opened 1912 with the city''s own engineering); and the U4 from Bramfeld to HafenCity Universität, opened 2012, serves the new HafenCity district and is being extended further. The new U5 line is under construction from Bramfeld to Stellingen, a 25-kilometre fully driverless route opening in stages from 2030 onwards. The Hamburger Verkehrsverbund (HVV), founded in 1965 as the first integrated tariff in Germany, coordinates all Hamburg-area public transport including the S-Bahn, U-Bahn, regional rail, bus, ferry and now the on-demand ridesharing service hvv hop! Long-distance buses use the ZOB Hamburg opposite the Hauptbahnhof, with FlixBus and Sindbad dominating the market.

The Autobahn network around Hamburg includes the A1 Hamburg-Bremen-Köln-Saarbrücken via Lübeck, the A7 Hamburg-Flensburg-Denmark to the north and Hamburg-Hannover-Würzburg-Memmingen to the south (the A7 has the famous 3.5-kilometre Elbtunnel, opened 1975 with the fourth tube added 2002 — the longest under-river road tunnel in Germany), the A23 Hamburg-Heide to the north-west and Schleswig-Holstein, the A24 Hamburg-Berlin (the East Berlin connector), the A25 Hamburg-Geesthacht and the A26 Hamburg-Stade (still under construction). The Hamburg-Berlin A24 corridor was historically the East-West border-crossing route. The Köhlbrandbrücke, the 1974 cable-stayed bridge over the Köhlbrand to the Wilhelmsburg and Veddel ports, will be replaced by a new tunnel from 2030 onwards as the existing bridge has reached the end of its design life. The Bundesstraßen B4 to Bad Bramstedt and Kiel, the B5 to Schleswig and Husum, the B73 to Cuxhaven, the B75 to Geesthacht, and the B431 along the Elbe complete the Bundes-network.

The Port of Hamburg, the third-largest container port in Europe (after Rotterdam and Antwerp-Bruges), is operated by Hamburger Hafen und Logistik AG (HHLA), the historic Hapag-Lloyd terminal operator with HHLA Container Terminal Burchardkai (CTB, the largest single container terminal in the city), HHLA Container Terminal Altenwerder (CTA, one of the most automated terminals in the world), HHLA Container Terminal Tollerort (CTT, recently part-acquired by the Chinese state-owned shipping line COSCO with controversy), the Eurogate Container Terminal Hamburg and various bulk and ro-ro terminals. The port handles around 8 million TEU per year. The Hamburg Port Authority (HPA) operates the public quays and waterways. The Elbe deepening (the so-called Elbvertiefung) was completed in 2022 after decades of legal challenges. The port hosts the world''s largest container ships of the Triple-E and OOCL classes; Hapag-Lloyd, the Hamburg-headquartered global container line, is one of the world''s largest container shipping companies. The Hapag-Lloyd Tower in the HafenCity is the city''s iconic shipping headquarters.

The Hamburg HADAG ferry network operates passenger lines across the harbour, integrated into the HVV tariff; the Cap San Diego excursion, the Rickmer Rickmers museum-ship visits, and the harbour-tour boats (Hafenrundfahrt) complete the maritime tourism offer. The Alster ferries from the Jungfernstieg in summer serve the suburbs of Winterhude, Mühlenkampf and Uhlenhorst.

Cycling in Hamburg is well developed with around 1,700 kilometres of cycle paths, the Hamburger Stadtrad public bike-share scheme (the third-largest in Germany after Berlin and Munich), the EuroVelo 7 (Sun Route from North Cape to Malta) via the Elbe corridor, the EuroVelo 12 (North Sea Cycle Route), the Elbe-Radweg (a top-three German long-distance cycling route from the Czech border via Dresden, Magdeburg, Wittenberg, Lutherstadt Wittenberg, Lüneburg, Hamburg and Cuxhaven to the North Sea), the Mönchsweg pilgrim cycle path and the Hamburg-Lübeck cycle route. The Hamburg-Bremen cycle route is a popular weekend ride. The Stadtrad Hamburg system, operated by DB Connect, has over 250 stations with around 3,200 bikes.

Hamburg pioneered the modern ride-hailing and shared-mobility scheme in Germany: the MOIA shared-ridehailing service (a Volkswagen Group subsidiary) launched in Hamburg in 2019 and now operates a fleet of around 700 electric vehicles; Share Now, Miles, SIXT Share, Bolt, Tier and Lime all operate Hamburg fleets. The HVV hop! on-demand bus service in Lurup and Osdorf is one of the largest such schemes in Germany. The Hamburg Senate plans the Tarifzonenreform integration of all transport modes into a single mobility-as-a-service offer by 2030.',
    economics = 'Hamburg has the second-highest regional GDP among the German Bundesländer (around 130 billion euros) and the second-highest per-capita GDP after Bremen, at around 70,000 euros per inhabitant. The Hamburg economy is dominated by the port and maritime industries, by aerospace, by media and publishing, by the wholesale and foreign-trade sector, by tourism and by a sophisticated financial-services cluster. The Hamburg Senate''s economic-development arm, the Hamburg Investment & Marketing Corporation (HIM), and the Senate Department for Economy, Transport and Innovation (BWVI) lead state economic policy. The Industrie- und Handelskammer Hamburg, founded 1665 as the Commerzdeputation and continuing as the IHK Hamburg, is the oldest German chamber of commerce.

The Port of Hamburg is the central economic engine. The port directly and indirectly employs around 160,000 workers in the metropolitan region and contributes around 20 per cent of regional GDP. Hamburger Hafen und Logistik AG (HHLA), the listed port-and-logistics group, operates the principal container terminals (HHLA Container Terminal Burchardkai, HHLA Container Terminal Altenwerder, HHLA Container Terminal Tollerort), the inland-port hinterland operations across central Europe, the Metrans and CTS intermodal-rail subsidiaries, the HHLA Hochzeit-Logistik and the historic Hapag-Lloyd ground-handling. The Hamburg Port Authority (HPA) operates the public infrastructure. Eurogate Container Terminal Hamburg is the second major container-terminal operator. Hapag-Lloyd AG, headquartered at the Ballindamm in the HafenCity, is the global container-line giant founded 1970 from the merger of the historic HAPAG (Albert Ballin''s 1847 Hamburg-Amerikanische Packetfahrt-Actien-Gesellschaft, the world''s largest ocean-shipping company at the turn of the 20th century) and Norddeutscher Lloyd (the Bremen rival of 1857). Hapag-Lloyd is one of the world''s top five container-shipping lines, with a fleet of around 250 vessels. The Hamburg-Süd shipping line, founded 1871 and acquired by Maersk in 2017, was historically the Hamburg-based South-America specialist. The Reederei F. Laeisz (the historic Flying P-Line of the Hamburg Steel-Ship Sails) continues today as a Hamburg specialist shipping group. The Hamburg Pacific Line, the Reederei Aug. Bolten, the Reederei Komrowski, the Hammonia-Reederei, the Aug. Bolten Wm. Miller''s Nachfolger, the Hamburg-based Marinetransport-Reederei and many other Hamburg shipping companies of all sizes have headquarters and operations in the city.

Airbus Hamburg-Finkenwerder is the second-largest Airbus production site in the world after Toulouse, with around 14,500 employees. The site builds the Airbus A320 family (the most successful single-aisle aircraft in commercial aviation history with over 17,000 deliveries) on four final-assembly lines; the Airbus A380 cabin completion and final-paint operations were also at Finkenwerder until the programme''s end in 2021. Airbus Hamburg also builds large fuselage sections for the A330, A350 and A380, with delivery via the unique Beluga and Beluga XL transport aircraft and via the Hamburg-Toulouse-Madrid air-corridor. Lufthansa Technik AG, the world''s largest independent commercial-aircraft MRO operation, has its corporate headquarters and main maintenance hangar at Hamburg Airport-Fuhlsbüttel. Lufthansa Technik employs around 8,000 workers at the Hamburg base, with global operations in Frankfurt, Munich, Manila, Tulsa, Sofia, Shenzhen, Beijing and many other cities. Lufthansa Technik specialises in VIP-aircraft completion (including the Trump-era 747-8 BBJ, the various Middle East royal aircraft and the Saudi Wedding Cake fleet), commercial-aircraft MRO, line maintenance, engine MRO and component services. The Hamburg Aviation Industry Cluster, with around 40,000 workers across Airbus, Lufthansa Technik, Hamburg Centre of Aviation Training, the German Aerospace Center (DLR Hamburg), the TU Hamburg-Harburg and the Hamburg-Norderstedt aerospace-supplier cluster, is the third-largest aviation cluster in Europe after Toulouse and Seattle.

Beiersdorf AG, the listed Hamburg consumer-products company, has its corporate headquarters at the Beiersdorf Campus on the Unnastraße in Eimsbüttel since 2018. Beiersdorf, founded 1882 by Paul Carl Beiersdorf, owns the global Nivea brand (the world''s largest skin-care brand by sales volume), Eucerin, Hansaplast, Labello, La Prairie and the tesa adhesive-tape division. Beiersdorf employs around 22,000 workers worldwide and is listed in the DAX. The Otto Group, founded 1949 by Werner Otto at the Schluiterhof in Wandsbek, is the second-largest German e-commerce group after Amazon Germany and one of the largest mail-order and online retail groups in the world. Otto Group owns OTTO (the Otto.de online platform, mail-order catalogue brand), Bonprix, Heine, Witt, Manufactum, the Hermes parcel-delivery service (the third-largest German parcel network after DHL and DPD), Hermes Fulfillment, Sportscheck, Crate and Barrel (the US furniture retailer), Hospitalservice and Crate Limited Brands. The Otto Group has around 50,000 employees worldwide and revenues of around 16 billion euros. Tchibo GmbH, founded 1949 in Hamburg by Carl Tchilinghiryan as a coffee mail-order, is the largest German coffee retailer with around 800 own-brand stores in Germany, around 12,000 sales outlets in supermarkets, and a profitable non-food product range that changes weekly (the so-called wöchentliche Welt der Tchibo). Tchibo is part of the Maxingvest AG family-controlled holding (formerly Tchibo Holding), which also owns the Beiersdorf majority stake.

Hapag-Lloyd Cruises, Aida Cruises (headquartered in Rostock but with Hamburg connections through the parent Costa Crociere of Italy), and TUI Cruises (TUI Group is headquartered in Hannover but operates Hamburg cruise terminals) all use the Cruise Centre HafenCity and the Cruise Centre Steinwerder. TUI AG, although Hannover-headquartered, has substantial Hamburg operations. Aurubis AG, the largest copper smelter and integrated copper refiner in Europe, has its head office at Hovestraße in Hamburg-Veddel. Aurubis (formerly Norddeutsche Affinerie), founded 1866 in Hamburg, has a global revenue of around 14 billion euros and produces over a million tonnes of refined copper per year. The Aurubis Hamburg refinery is the world''s largest copper refinery by capacity. Trimet Aluminium SE has the Hamburg aluminium-smelter cluster. The Holborn Refinery at Harburg processes crude oil for the German market, alongside the Shell Refinery Hamburg-Harburg. Steigenberger Hotels AG (now part of Deutsche Hospitality) was historically Hamburg-affiliated.

Media and publishing are concentrated in Hamburg. Der Spiegel, the leading German weekly news magazine, was founded by Rudolf Augstein in 1947 and has its corporate headquarters at the new Spiegel-Hochhaus in the HafenCity. The Bauer Media Group, headquartered at Burchardstraße, is the largest privately owned media group in Europe with around 600 magazines, 400 digital products and 50 radio and TV stations in 15 countries; major Bauer brands include Bravo, Auto Bild Klassik, TV Movie, Cosmopolitan Germany, In Touch and many others. Gruner+Jahr AG, the historic Bertelsmann subsidiary headquartered on the Baumwall, publishes the Stern news magazine, Geo, Brigitte, Eltern and dozens of other titles; since 2020 G+J has been merged into Bertelsmann''s RTL Deutschland media. Axel Springer SE, headquartered at the Axel-Springer-Haus in Berlin, has substantial Hamburg operations and the original Bild-Verlag building on the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Straße in the Mönckebergstraße quarter. The Hamburger Abendblatt (the leading Hamburg daily, owned by Axel Springer since 1948), the Hamburger Morgenpost (the tabloid second daily) and Die Zeit (the leading Hamburg-based weekly intellectual quality paper, founded 1946 and now part of Holtzbrinck) anchor the local press. The Norddeutscher Rundfunk (NDR), the regional ARD broadcaster, has its main studios at Rothenbaumchaussee in Eppendorf and produces national programmes for ARD including Tagesschau, Tagesthemen and Tatort Hamburg. The Studio Hamburg AG and the Studio Hamburg Atelier complete the broadcasting cluster.

Banking and finance are concentrated at the Hamburg Inner-Stadt and the HafenCity. Hamburg Commercial Bank AG (formerly HSH Nordbank), the former state-owned commercial bank (privatised 2018), is headquartered at Gerhart-Hauptmann-Platz. The Hamburger Sparkasse (HASPA) is the largest German savings bank, with around 5,000 employees and a balance sheet of 50 billion euros. The Berenberg Bank (Joh. Berenberg, Gossler & Co. KG), founded in 1590 by the Berenberg brothers and one of the oldest private banks in the world, is at Neuer Jungfernstieg. The MM Warburg & Co (a venerable Hamburg private bank, founded 1798, recently restructured after the Cum-Ex scandal) is at Ferdinandstraße. Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe, the SüdwestBank and other private banks complete the Hamburg banking offer. The Hamburg Stock Exchange (Hamburger Börse), founded in 1558 as the oldest stock exchange in Germany, is operated by Börse Hamburg AG (since 2007 part of BÖAG Börsen AG with the Hannover exchange). Insurance is led by Signal Iduna (the Hamburg-Dortmund mutual), HanseMerkur (a Hamburg health-insurance specialist), the Hamburg-Allianz, Generali Hamburg and the Hanseatic insurance pool.

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Universität Hamburg, founded 1919 by Werner von Melle, has around 42,000 students and was a German University of Excellence from 2019 to 2026. The Technische Universität Hamburg (TUHH) at Harburg is the second-largest engineering university in northern Germany. The HafenCity Universität (HCU) is the city''s architecture and urban-planning university. The Hochschule für Bildende Künste (HfBK), the Hochschule für Musik und Theater Hamburg, and the Helmut-Schmidt-Universität (the Bundeswehr-University at Wandsbek-Bramfeld) supplement higher education. The Deutsches Elektronen-Synchrotron (DESY) at Bahrenfeld is one of the world''s leading particle-physics and X-ray-laser research centres, home of the European XFEL (X-ray Free-Electron Laser, the world''s most powerful), the PETRA III synchrotron, the HERA former storage ring and the FLASH ultraviolet free-electron laser. The German Climate Computing Centre (DKRZ) at Bundesstraße in Eimsbüttel is one of the world''s leading climate-modelling centres with the Levante supercomputer. The Heinrich Hertz Institut, the Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie at Bundesstraße, the GKSS Geesthacht and the Helmholtz-Zentrum Hereon at Geesthacht complete the research map.',
    introduced_species = 'Hamburg is one of the largest entry points for introduced and invasive species into Germany, by virtue of its position as one of Europe''s busiest seaports, its position on the lower Elbe estuary connecting to the Baltic Sea via the Kiel Canal and to the North Sea via Cuxhaven, its diverse aquatic habitats and its temperate-maritime climate that allows many cosmopolitan invaders to establish year-round. The Hamburg Behörde für Umwelt, Klima, Energie und Agrarwirtschaft (BUKEA) coordinates invasive-species monitoring through the Naturschutzfachliche Abteilung, the Lebensmittel- und Veterinäramt and the BUKEA partner organisations BUND, NABU, Loki Schmidt Foundation, the Botanischer Garten Hamburg and the Tierpark Hagenbeck. The Helmholtz-Zentrum Hereon at Geesthacht and the Bundesforschungsanstalt für Fischerei (now Thünen-Institut) maintain marine and freshwater monitoring programmes.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been recorded in Hamburg state since the 1980s when individuals from the southward and westward expansion of the Brandenburg and Hessian releases reached the Hamburg-Lüneburg-Hannover corridor. Today the Hamburg raccoon population is conspicuous along the Hamburg Stadtpark, the Niendorfer Gehege, the Volkspark, the Klövensteen, the Wohldorfer Wald, the Sachsenwald (in Schleswig-Holstein), and increasingly across the suburban Bramfeld, Eppendorf, Winterhude and Othmarschen districts. Urban Hamburg raccoons exploit roof voids, garages, dustbins, compost heaps and pet-food bowls. Annual hunting bags in Hamburg are modest by national standards (a few hundred animals per year) reflecting the city-state''s small size and limited hunting grounds. The Hamburg Senate Umweltverwaltung publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing and the handling of raccoon latrines. Raccoons have been recorded as predators of the Hamburg-area cavity-nesting bird populations, of amphibians at the Klövensteen Heide ponds, and of the European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroductions on the lower Elbe.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Hamburg from the east in the 2000s and 2010s; small populations are recorded along the Vier- und Marschlande, the Wilhelmsburg, the Naturschutzgebiet Holm-Seppensen and the Niendorfer Gehege. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the lower Elbe, the Bille, the Alster and the Wilhelmsburg canal system. The Hamburg Behörde für Umwelt monitors dyke damage from nutria burrowing in the Wilhelmsburg and Vier- und Marschlande dyke districts; trapping is mandated. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to the lower Elbe but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and the Bremer Forsten and is now spreading along the lower Elbe; the Hamburg Senate has formally welcomed the return of the beaver as a flagship of ecological restoration. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs in slow water bodies across Hamburg state, particularly in the Vier- und Marschlande, the Wilhelmsburg canals and the Hamburg Stadtpark ponds.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established a feral resident population on the Alster, the Stadtpark, the Hagenbecker Tierpark surroundings and the Wilhelmsburg waterways. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations and now breeds throughout Hamburg, with conspicuous populations on the Alster, the Stadtpark, the Planten un Blomen and the Wandsbek Gehölz. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has established small but stable breeding populations in Hamburg in the Stadtpark, the Wandsbek and the inner Alster park trees, with at least 50 to 100 breeding pairs reported by the Hamburg ornithological society. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on the Hamburg park ponds, especially the Alstersee and the Stadtpark. The Indian house crow, Corvus splendens, has been recorded as a port vagrant at the Hamburg Container Port; a small but persistent breeding population was reported in 2010-2013 around the Speicherstadt and the Veddel docks (one of only two confirmed European breeding populations of the Indian house crow, alongside the Hoek van Holland), but the population appears to have died out by the late 2010s after intensive culling. The mute swan, although native, has dense feral populations on the Alster, the Stadtpark and the Wilhelmsburg canals; the Alster swans (Alsterschwäne) are a Hamburg tradition, with the historic Alsterschwanenwärter (the Hamburg state swan-keeper) leading the annual swan-collecting from the Alster to the winter shelter on the Eppendorfer Mühlenteich. The wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on some Hamburg-area hunting estates without forming self-sustaining populations.

Among fish, the lower Elbe estuary and the Hamburg waterways host a wide range of introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch, is established in the gravel pits. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling, is widespread. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels, occurs in old gravel pits. The rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Regenbogenforelle, is stocked. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis, Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella, Graskarpfen, is used to control aquatic vegetation in lakes. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel, native to the Black Sea, has reached the Hamburg waterways via the Mittellandkanal and the Rhine-Main system, with the first Hamburg record around 2008; the species is now established throughout the Hamburg lower Elbe. The Caspian Kessler''s goby and the bighead goby follow. The wels catfish, Silurus glanis, although native to the lower Elbe before its extirpation in the late 19th century, has been reintroduced and is now common.

The Hamburg port is a major entry point for marine and brackish ballast-water and hull-fouling invasions. Established marine and brackish invaders include the Pacific oyster (Magallana gigas, Crassostrea gigas, Pazifische Auster), originally introduced for aquaculture in the Wadden Sea in 1986 and now ubiquitous on intertidal banks; the American razor clam (Ensis directus, Amerikanische Schwertmuschel), present on the Wadden Sea since 1979 storm transport from the Atlantic; the Asian shore crabs (Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi), established on the Wadden Sea since around 2000 and increasingly common in the lower Elbe; the Manila clam (Ruditapes philippinarum); the Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum (Japanischer Beerentang), now lining North Sea piers and groynes; the Atlantic comb jelly (Mnemiopsis leidyi), originally from the western Atlantic, now common in the inner German Bight; the New Zealand sea squirt (Styela clava); the Asian shore-crab fishery''s nemesis the Caspian sea fan; and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe), regularly trapped in the Elbe and a Hamburg menu speciality in some restaurants. The zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel) and the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel) are present in the Hamburg freshwater systems. The Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel) is in the Elbe and the Hamburg canals. The marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus, Kamberkrebs), the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs) and the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii, Roter Sumpfkrebs) are all recorded in Hamburg gravel pits and park ponds. The New Zealand mud snail, Potamopyrgus antipodarum, is widespread.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in Hamburg from 2022 onwards with confirmed nests near Bergedorf and the Niendorfer Gehege; the Imkerverband Hamburg coordinates nest-removal teams with the Senatsumweltverwaltung. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Hamburg avenues every late summer, with the Alsterpark and the Stadtpark chestnut avenues particularly affected. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Wallanlagen, the Planten un Blomen and various Hamburg private gardens. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established in Hamburg with substantial agricultural damage in the Vier- und Marschlande apple-orchards. The Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) was reported in Hamburg in 2014 in container-port arrivals; an emergency containment programme felled hundreds of trees in the Veddel and Wilhelmsburg districts; the outbreak has since been declared eradicated. The emerald ash borer (Agrilus planipennis) is a feared port-arrival pest from the Russian Far East and North America; monitoring traps are deployed at Hamburg container terminals by the Julius Kühn-Institut. The Hamburg Pflanzenschutzdienst at the BUKEA monitors arrivals.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) is widespread along Hamburg railway lines, the A1 and A7 motorway verges, and on disturbed ground in the Vier- und Marschlande; the BUKEA coordinates the Hamburg Ambrosia-Atlas and the state-wide control programme. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates banks of the Bille, the Alster, the Wilhelmsburg canals, the lower Elbe, the Wandse and the Süderelbe. Bohemian knotweed (Reynoutria bohemica) and giant knotweed (Reynoutria sachalinensis) are also present. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on Hamburg stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in Hamburg parks with phototoxic-sap warnings. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum), spreading from historic Hamburg avenues planted in the 19th century, has become one of the most conspicuous invasive trees of inner Hamburg, exploiting brownfields, railway tracks, the harbour area and the abandoned cobbled lots of the Wilhelmsburg and Veddel districts; the Hamburg Pflanzenschutzdienst maintains a control programme. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea) dominates fallow fields. Small balsam (Impatiens parviflora) is widespread on Hamburg park edges. Black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), planted historically in Hamburg streets, has self-seeded into many disturbed habitats. The Indian balsam, the water primrose (Ludwigia grandiflora), the South African Crassula helmsii (Nadelkraut) and the floating fern Salvinia molesta have been recorded sporadically. The cordgrass Spartina anglica (the hybrid salt-marsh grass) has invaded the Wadden Sea mudflats around the Hamburg lower Elbe and substantially altered the intertidal landscape; the Senecio inaequidens (Schmalblättriges Greiskraut), the South African ragwort, is now established on Hamburg railway lines and disturbed sandy ground. The Hamburg Botanischer Garten Klein-Flottbek (the Loki-Schmidt-Garten) is a leading German botanical centre for invasive-species research and the documented Hamburg neophyte list.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have small populations in Hamburg-area forestry reserves at the Sachsenwald, the Niendorfer Gehege and the Klövensteen. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) are absent. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at low density in the Klövensteen, the Niendorfer Gehege and the Sachsenwald. American mink (Neovison vison, Amerikanischer Nerz), escaped from old Hamburg-area fur-trade operations, is occasional along the lower Elbe; the Hamburg state veterinary authority monitors all wild mammals for avian influenza and African Swine Fever.'
WHERE region_name = 'Hamburg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Hessen, in English Hesse, occupies the centre of Germany, a Land of around six million people and 21,100 square kilometres extending from the Rhön mountains in the south-east to the Westerwald and Taunus in the west, the Vogelsberg in the centre, the Spessart in the south and the Reinhardswald, Kaufunger Wald and Kellerwald in the north. The state capital is Wiesbaden, but the largest city and economic hub is Frankfurt am Main, the centre of the Rhein-Main metropolitan region of approximately 5.8 million people that includes Mainz (the capital of Rheinland-Pfalz), Darmstadt, Offenbach, Hanau and the surrounding districts. Hessen is the historical home of the Brothers Grimm, of Goethe (born in Frankfurt in 1749), of the German parliament of 1848 (the Paulskirche in Frankfurt), and of the German Bundesbank and the European Central Bank.

Frankfurt am Main is the most visited tourist destination in Hessen and the only major German city with a true skyscraper skyline. The Römerberg, the medieval marketplace at the heart of the rebuilt Old Town, is dominated by the Römer, the city''s historic town hall since 1405, a complex of three step-gabled buildings (Alt-Limpurg, Römer and Löwenstein) with the Kaisersaal hall on the upper floor containing portraits of all the Holy Roman Emperors from Charlemagne to Franz II. Beside the Römer stands the rebuilt Old St. Nicholas Church (Alte Nikolaikirche), the Frankfurter Justitia statue at the Gerechtigkeitsbrunnen fountain, and the historic Schirn Kunsthalle exhibition space. The Frankfurter Dom Kaiserdom St. Bartholomäus, the Cathedral of Saint Bartholomew, served as the coronation site of the Holy Roman Emperors from 1562 to 1792 (ten emperors were elected and crowned there) and contains the Wahlkapelle election chapel. The Paulskirche (St. Paul''s Church), where the first freely elected German parliament met from May 1848 to May 1849 to draft a democratic constitution, is the symbol of German liberal-democratic tradition. The Goethe-Haus on the Großer Hirschgraben, the birthplace and family home of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe from 1749 to 1775, contains the puppet theatre that inspired the young Goethe, the family library, the room where Goethe wrote The Sorrows of Young Werther, and the surrounding Goethe Museum. The Hauptwache (historic guard house), the Eschenheimer Turm (the medieval city-gate tower), the Frankfurter Pfarrturm and the Eiserne Steg (Iron Footbridge) over the Main complete the inner-city circuit.

The Frankfurt Museumsufer, the Museum Embankment along the south bank of the Main in Sachsenhausen, contains a remarkable concentration of museums: the Städel Museum (the Städelsches Kunstinstitut, one of Germany''s leading fine-art museums with the Vermeer Geographer, Rembrandt''s Blinding of Samson, the Hans Holbein the Younger Madonna, the Lucas Cranach Venus, the Botticelli Idealised Portrait of a Lady, Tischbein''s famous Goethe in the Roman Campagna and contemporary works by Gerhard Richter, Sigmar Polke and Anselm Kiefer); the Liebieghaus sculpture museum, the Deutsches Filmmuseum, the Museum für Kommunikation, the Museum Angewandte Kunst (Museum of Applied Art) by Richard Meier, the Museum für Weltkulturen Frankfurt ethnological collection, the Deutsches Architekturmuseum (DAM), the Ikonenmuseum (icon museum), the Bibelhaus, the Portikus exhibition hall on the Main island, the Caricatura Museum of comic art and the Struwwelpeter Museum of the famous Frankfurt children''s book. The Senckenberg Naturmuseum Frankfurt, one of the largest and most important natural-history museums in Europe, contains the Frankfurt dinosaur skeletons, the largest taxidermied mammoth, the historic Diplodocus, the Senckenberg meteorite collection and the famous Messel Pit fossils (UNESCO World Heritage). The Frankfurter Goethe-Universität-Naturkundemuseum and the MMK Museum für Moderne Kunst, the so-called slice-of-cake museum by Hans Hollein with extensions in the Domstrasse and the TaunusTurm, complete the museum trail. The Frankfurt Schirn Kunsthalle, the Frankfurter Kunstverein, the Frankfurter Galerie Schierke, and the Portikus on the Main complete the contemporary-art scene.

Frankfurt''s famous skyline of skyscrapers (the Hochhäuser) is the only such ensemble in Germany, with the Commerzbank Tower by Sir Norman Foster (the tallest building in Germany until the new One Tower, 259 metres tall, completed 1997 as the world''s first ecological skyscraper), the Messeturm by Helmut Jahn at the Messe Frankfurt (the trade-fair grounds), the Main Tower by Schweger & Partner (the only public observation deck on a Frankfurt skyscraper, with restaurant on the 53rd floor), the European Central Bank Tower in Ostend (by Coop Himmelb(l)au, opened 2014 in the former Großmarkthalle wholesale fruit market by Martin Elsaesser), the Trianon Tower, the Tower 185, the Westend Tower (DZ Bank), the Skyper, the Eurotower (former ECB headquarters), the Garden Tower, the Marienturm and the Henninger Turm (the rebuilt former silo tower of the Henninger brewery). The Maintower observation deck offers the best public panorama of the Frankfurt skyline; the new One Frankfurt and the Four Frankfurt complexes are extending the skyscraper district.

Frankfurt nature includes the Palmengarten, one of the largest German botanical gardens, founded 1869 by Heinrich Siesmayer with the famous Palmen House (the largest glasshouse in Germany when built); the Zoo Frankfurt, founded 1858 as the second-oldest German zoo, with the Borgori-Wald gorilla rainforest, the Grzimekhaus nocturnal mammal house and the Exotarium reptile house; the Bethmannpark with the Chinese Garden; the Lohrberg the only Frankfurt vineyard with views over the city; the Stadtwald (City Forest), the largest German municipal forest; the Niddapark; the Grüneburgpark; the Mainpromenade; and the Park am Bornheimer Hang.

Wiesbaden, the state capital, is one of the most elegant spa towns in Germany. The Kurhaus, designed by Friedrich von Thiersch and completed 1907, contains the Wiesbaden Casino (the historic mansion which inspired Dostoyevsky''s The Gambler, and where Tolstoy lost most of his fortune in 1857) and the Kurhauskolonnaden. The Hessisches Staatstheater Wiesbaden by Felix Genzmer of 1894, the Kochbrunnen springs with its 14 hot mineral springs supplying the historic Wiesbaden Thermalbad and the modern Kaiser-Friedrich-Therme, the Neroberg with the Neroberg Russian Orthodox Church (the so-called Greek Chapel, built 1855 by Duke Adolf of Nassau for his young Russian wife who died in childbirth) and the Nerobergbahn (the famous water-ballast funicular of 1888, still operating with the original mechanism and water-counterweight system, one of only three remaining in the world), the Russian Orthodox cemetery, the Marktkirche by Carl Boos, the Stadtschloss (the New Town Palace, now the Hessian Landtag), the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Ring promenade and the historic Hotel Nassauer Hof. Beside Wiesbaden lies Mainz (capital of Rheinland-Pfalz), with the Rheingau wine region just upstream (the Rheingau is technically in Hessen and includes the historic Schloss Vollrads, the Schloss Johannisberg of the famous Spätlese wine discovery, the Kloster Eberbach with its Cistercian cellars, the Niederwalddenkmal monument above Rüdesheim, and the famous Drosselgasse wine alley in Rüdesheim).

Kassel, the second-largest city in Hessen, is famous for two things: the Bergpark Wilhelmshöhe (UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2013, the largest hillside park in Europe at 240 hectares, with the Hercules Monument by Giovanni Francesco Guernerio of 1717 standing on the Octagon at 526 metres above sea level, the Lions Castle (Löwenburg) by Heinrich Christoph Jussow of 1798 as an artificial ruin, the Wilhelmshöhe Palace, the artificial cascades and waterfalls that flow downhill from Hercules every Sunday and Wednesday in summer (the famous Wasserspiele Kassel), the Aqueduct, the Roman Aqueduct ruin, the Devil''s Bridge and the Plutogrotte) and the documenta art exhibition, held every five years since 1955 (founded by Arnold Bode) in the Friedericianum and across the city, which has shaped contemporary art history through Joseph Beuys, Anselm Kiefer, Robert Smithson, Walter De Maria''s Vertical Earth Kilometer, the Olive Tree by Pierre Huyghe and the Documenta 14 in Athens-Kassel. Kassel also hosts the Brothers Grimm Welt museum, the Hessisches Landesmuseum Kassel, the Naturkundemuseum and the Karlsaue baroque park.

Darmstadt is famous for the Mathildenhöhe Künstlerkolonie, the Art Nouveau (Jugendstil) artists'' colony established by Grand Duke Ernst Ludwig of Hessen in 1899, with the Hochzeitsturm wedding tower by Joseph Maria Olbrich, the Russian Chapel, the Plane Tree Grove, the Ernst Ludwig House and the seven Künstlerhäuser; the entire Mathildenhöhe complex was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2021. The Hessisches Landesmuseum Darmstadt is one of the largest German fine-art and natural-history museums (with the Joseph Beuys Block — the largest single Beuys installation in any museum). The Waldspirale apartment building by Friedensreich Hundertwasser, the Schloss Darmstadt (the former Landgrave residence), the Künstlerkolonie and the Hochzeitsturm complete the city offer.

Marburg, a historic Hessian university town on the Lahn, is centred on the Marburger Schloss (the former Landgrave Castle), the Elisabethkirche of 1235-1283 (the first purely Gothic church in Germany, where Saint Elisabeth of Thuringia was buried until her remains were removed in 1539 by the Reformation), the Alte Universität, the Marburger Marktplatz, the historic Brothers Grimm haunts (the Grimms studied at the Marburg University 1802-1805) and the Marburg upper-town Wendelgasse. Fulda, the Catholic-Episcopal city of Hessen, is built around the Fuldaer Dom (the rococo cathedral by Johann Dientzenhofer of 1712, holding the relics of Saint Boniface, the Apostle of the Germans), the Stadtschloss, the Michaelskirche (one of the oldest Carolingian buildings in Germany, dating from 822), the Frauenberg Franciscan monastery and the Schlossgarten. Gießen, Limburg an der Lahn (with its Romanesque-Gothic cathedral dominating the river island and the Domkrone tower), Friedberg with its Imperial Castle Burg Friedberg and the Adolf-Reichwein-Schule architecture, Bad Homburg with its Roman thermal-bath sources, Bad Nauheim with the historic Sprudelhof (a complete art-nouveau bath complex, the most authentic surviving Jugendstil ensemble for spa architecture in the world), Bad Wildungen with the Edersee dam and the Kellerwald national park, the Marburger Schloss and the Kassel-Wilhelmshöhe form the cultural backbone. The Lorsch Monastery (UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1991) preserves the historic Königshalle (the Carolingian Lorsch Gatehouse of 800 AD, one of the few surviving carolingian pieces of architecture). The Messel Pit (UNESCO World Heritage Site for the Eocene fossil deposits with their exquisitely preserved horse, bat, fish and insect specimens) lies near Darmstadt.

Hessian cuisine is heartily robust. The Frankfurter Würstchen, a small smoked pork sausage with a delicate, slightly red colour and a snap-skin, is a Frankfurt specialty registered with EU Protected Geographical Indication since 1992; it gave its name to the global "frankfurter" hot-dog through immigration to America in the 19th century. Grüne Soße or Frankfurter Grie Soß is the iconic Frankfurt sauce, made with seven specific herbs (parsley, chives, chervil, sorrel, salad burnet, cress and borage) bound with sour cream, mayonnaise, mustard, vinegar and oil, traditionally served with boiled potatoes and hard-boiled eggs in a quintessentially regional Holy Thursday and Good Friday meal. Handkäs (or Handkäse mit Musik, "hand cheese with music"), a small round sour-milk cheese marinated with caraway seeds, vinegar, oil and chopped onions (the "music" refers to the after-effects of the onions), is a Frankfurt apple-wine pub staple. Frankfurter Bethmännchen, the marzipan-and-rosewater bonbon decorated with three almond halves, was invented by the Frankfurt confectioner Jean Jacques Gautenier for the four sons of the Bethmann banking family (one son died and the recipe accordingly was reduced from four to three almonds). Frankfurter Brenten, Frankfurter Kranz (a butter-cream sponge cake with caramelised hazelnut crumble decorated to suggest a king''s crown), Apfelwein in the Bembel stoneware pitcher served in the special Geripptes diamond-cut glass, Sachsenhäuser Ebbelwoi (the famous Frankfurt apple-wine taverns at Apfelwein Wagner, Adolf Wagner, Atschel and Zum Gemalten Haus), Kasseler Rippchen (cured pork chops, originated from a Berlin butcher named Cassel rather than the Hessian city), Hessischer Speckkuchen, Hessisches Bauernbrot, the Eierdüpp egg-pot, the Schwälmer Land specialty of bowls eaten with the Schwälmer Tracht, Steinheimer Speckdüppche, the Frankfurter Schwartenmagen brawn, the Limpurger Rinderbraten, Schwartenmagen, Worschtsupp pork-stock soup and the Hessian-style sausage all anchor the table. Drinks: Apfelwein is the regional beverage and a Frankfurt institution, served with the famous Bembel pitcher; major producers include the Frankfurter Possmann Kelterei, Höhl, Nöll, Stier, Kohler and the cooperative Hofkelter. Hessian beer is dominated by the Binding Brauerei (in Sachsenhausen), the Henninger Brauerei (Sachsenhausen, the former competitor to Binding, now also part of Radeberger Gruppe), the Licher Pilsner from Lich, the Schöfferhofer wheat beer, the Bingenheimer Bier and the Schloss-Brauerei Friedrichshof. The Rheingau wines from Hochheim (which gave its name to the English word "hock" for German white wine), Rüdesheim, Geisenheim, Eltville, Hattenheim, Erbach and Hochheim include the world-famous Schloss Johannisberg Riesling Spätlese (the world''s first Spätlese late-harvest wine discovered by accident in 1775), the Schloss Vollrads, the Schloss Reinhartshausen, the Kloster Eberbach Steinberg, the State Wine Domain Kloster Eberbach (Hessische Staatsweingüter), the Robert Weil estate at Kiedrich and the Künstler estate at Hochheim. The Hessische Bergstraße is the smallest official German wine region, located on the western slopes of the Odenwald near Heppenheim and Bensheim, with the Staatsweingut Bergstraße at Bensheim. Hessian schnapps include the Hessischer Apfelbrand (apple eau-de-vie), the Bergsträßer Frühapfel, the Spessart Schlehengeist and the Kaiserstuhl-style stone-fruit brandies.

History before 1933 is rich. The Hessian Landgraviates of Hessen-Kassel and Hessen-Darmstadt, the Imperial Free Cities of Frankfurt, Wetzlar and Friedberg, the Grand Duchy of Hessen-Darmstadt, the Kingdom of Westphalia under Jerome Bonaparte (1807-1813), the Confederation of the Rhine, the German Confederation, the 1848 Paulskirchen-Parlament in Frankfurt, the Hessen-Kassel annexation by Prussia in 1866 after the Austro-Prussian War, the Hessian Grand Duchy''s rule until 1918, the Weimar-era Hessen, the Frankfurt Schule of Walter Benjamin, Theodor Adorno and Max Horkheimer at the Institute for Social Research, and the post-war American-zone foundation of Hessen as a Land on 19 September 1945 in Wiesbaden by the U.S. military government, with the new state of Hessen formed from Hessen-Darmstadt south of the Main, the former Hessen-Nassau and parts of Waldeck. Famous figures associated with Hessen include the Brothers Grimm (Wilhelm and Jacob), born in Hanau (Hessen-Hanau), raised in Steinau and educated at Marburg, Goethe (Frankfurt), Friedrich Hölderlin''s time in Bad Homburg, Justus von Liebig (the founder of agricultural chemistry at the University of Gießen), Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen (born in Lennep, lived at Gießen), Albert Schweitzer, Stefan George of Bingen, the philosophers of the Frankfurt School, and the historic Bauhaus architect Erich Mendelsohn.',
    transportation = 'Hessen is one of the great transport crossroads of Germany, the meeting point of the historic Frankfurt-Hamburg, Frankfurt-Berlin, Frankfurt-Munich and Frankfurt-Cologne axes. Frankfurt am Main Airport, Flughafen Frankfurt am Main, IATA FRA and ICAO EDDF, is the busiest airport in Germany and the fourth-busiest in Europe by passengers and the fourth-busiest in the world by cargo traffic, handling around 60 million passengers in normal years (with a peak of 70 million in 2019) and 2 million tonnes of cargo. The airport, operated by Fraport AG, is the main hub of Lufthansa (and of the Star Alliance in continental Europe), with major operations also for Condor, Discover Airlines, Eurowings, Singapore Airlines, Cathay Pacific, Korean Air, China Airlines, Japan Airlines, Emirates, Etihad Airways, Air China, KLM, Air France and effectively every major intercontinental carrier. Frankfurt Airport has two terminals (Terminal 1 with three concourses A, B and C; Terminal 2 with D and E concourses) and four runways including the long Northwest Runway opened in 2011 after decades of legal challenges. The new Terminal 3, currently under construction in the southern airport area, will open in stages from 2026 onwards. The airport is connected by the long-distance Bahnhof Frankfurt am Main Flughafen Fernbahnhof, opened 1999 as the first dedicated long-distance railway station at a German airport, served by half-hourly ICE services to Cologne, Stuttgart, Munich, Hamburg, Berlin and Basel; the regional Bahnhof Frankfurt Flughafen Regionalbahnhof under Terminal 1 is served by S-Bahn S8 and S9, by regional services, and by frequent express trains to Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof in 12 minutes. Frankfurt Airport employs over 80,000 people directly and is the second-largest workplace in Germany after the Volkswagen Wolfsburg complex.

Frankfurt-Hahn Airport (HHN, EDFH), located 120 kilometres west of Frankfurt in the Hunsrück (Rheinland-Pfalz), is a former US air base converted into a low-cost airport, dominated by Ryanair, although passenger volumes have declined dramatically since the early 2010s. Kassel-Calden Airport (KSF, EDVK), the controversial new regional airport opened 2013 north-west of Kassel, handles modest traffic of Ryanair and seasonal Mediterranean flights. Frankfurt-Egelsbach Airport (EDFE) handles business aviation; the Frankfurt Helilanding Pad and the Bundesbank Helicopter Pad complete the aviation infrastructure.

Frankfurt am Main Hauptbahnhof, opened in 1888 with the magnificent steel-and-glass roof spanning 169 metres, is the most-used railway terminus in Germany with around 470,000 passengers per day across its 25 platforms. It is connected to the long-distance and regional networks of Deutsche Bahn DB Fernverkehr (ICE, IC, EC), DB Regio Mitte, the Rhein-Main Verkehrsverbund (RMV) operator HLB, the Frankfurt S-Bahn, the U-Bahn (via the underground Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof tief station) and the Frankfurt trams. Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof is the terminus of the historic Frankfurt-Mannheim, Frankfurt-Hannover, Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg and Frankfurt-Köln lines, and the through-station for the new Frankfurt-Köln high-speed line. The Frankfurt-Köln Schnellfahrstrecke (NBS Köln-Rhein/Main), opened in 2002, allows ICE 3 trains to run at 300 kph on the 177-kilometre route from Frankfurt Airport via Limburg, Montabaur and Siegburg/Bonn to Cologne in 62 minutes; this is the steepest high-speed railway in Europe with grades of 40 ‰ on the Westerwald. The Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg corridor (the historic 1991 NBS Hannover-Würzburg ending at Würzburg, with the upgraded line to Nuremberg) connects to Munich and Vienna; the new Stuttgart-Mannheim NBS connects to Stuttgart; the Frankfurt-Berlin route via Hannover or via Erfurt-Nuremberg-Würzburg-Frankfurt; and the Frankfurt-Basel via Karlsruhe and the Rheintalbahn extend the ICE network. The new Hannover-Würzburg NBS, opened 1991 as the first NBS in Germany, runs through the Reinhardswald and the Kellerwald with 63 tunnels.

Other key Hessian rail nodes are Kassel-Wilhelmshöhe (on the Hannover-Würzburg NBS, with ICE services to Berlin, Hamburg, Munich and Vienna), Hanau Hauptbahnhof, Wiesbaden Hauptbahnhof, Darmstadt Hauptbahnhof, Frankfurt-Süd, Frankfurt-West, Frankfurt-Höchst, Marburg, Gießen, Fulda (on the Hannover-Würzburg NBS), Limburg an der Lahn (on the Frankfurt-Köln NBS with the new Limburg Süd ICE station), Eschwege and the historic Frankfurt-Höchst railway works. The Frankfurt-Köln NBS''s Montabaur station is in Rheinland-Pfalz but serves the Westerwald corridor.

The Rhein-Main Verkehrsverbund (RMV), founded 1995 as the integrated tariff for the Frankfurt metropolitan region, is the second-largest German transport association by area after the VBB Berlin-Brandenburg and includes the Frankfurt S-Bahn (nine lines from S1 to S9 totalling 320 kilometres and 110 stations, with the central Frankfurt city tunnel from Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof tief via Taunusanlage, Hauptwache, Konstablerwache, Ostendstraße and Mühlberg/Lokalbahnhof), the Frankfurt U-Bahn (which is technically a Stadtbahn with both surface and tunnel running, with seven lines U1 to U9 totalling 65 kilometres, operated by VGF), the Frankfurt trams (ten lines totalling 65 kilometres operated by VGF), the regional rail services of HLB (Hessische Landesbahn), DB Regio Mitte and ODEG, and the bus networks across the Rhein-Main, Mittelhessen, Nordhessen, Osthessen and Südhessen regions. The Nordhessischer Verkehrsverbund (NVV) covers the Kassel region with its tram-train network operated by KVG (Kasseler Verkehrs-Gesellschaft) using the famous RegioTrams of Bombardier (now Alstom) that run on city tracks and the heavy-rail network similar to the Karlsruhe model. The Stadtbahn Kassel has six lines.

The Frankfurt Airport Terminal 3 will be connected to the long-distance station via an automated people-mover system, the Frankfurt Airport SkyLine. The Frankfurt taxis, Uber, FREE NOW and the airport limousine services serve the city; FlixBus and Sindbad operate long-distance buses from the Frankfurt ZOB and the airport.

The Autobahn network in Hessen is one of the densest in Europe. The A3 Köln-Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nuremberg-Passau is the country''s busiest motorway carrying over 150,000 vehicles per day on some sections; the A5 Hattenbach-Frankfurt-Karlsruhe-Basel is the Rhein-Main corridor; the A7 Hamburg-Hannover-Würzburg passes through eastern Hessen and is one of the longest motorways in Europe at 963 kilometres; the A4 Frankfurt-Erfurt-Dresden-Polish border was the historic Hannover-Saxon corridor; the A44 Aachen-Düsseldorf-Kassel; the A45 Dortmund-Frankfurt (the so-called Sauerlandlinie, currently closed near Lüdenscheid due to the Talbrücke Rahmede collapse and slated for a 10-year reconstruction); the A48; the A49 Kassel-Gemünden under construction (the controversial Dannenröder Forest section was cleared in 2020); the A61 Mönchengladbach-Speyer; the A66 Frankfurt-Fulda; the A67 Mainz-Lorsch; the A671 Wiesbaden-Frankfurt connection; the A661 Frankfurt-Bad Homburg; and the A648 Frankfurt-West. The Frankfurter Kreuz is the most-trafficked motorway interchange in Europe (over 320,000 vehicles per day at the junction of A3, A5 and the airport access). Bundesstraßen include the B3 north-south through Wiesbaden-Darmstadt, the B40 east-west, the B43 along the Main, the B254 to Fulda and the B255 to Westerwald.

The Main and the Rhine are major inland waterways. The Frankfurt-Mainz-Bingen Rhine-Main-Donau system connects to the Rhine at Mainz-Kostheim. The Port of Frankfurt (Frankfurter Hafen) handles bulk traffic, container and oil for the chemical and aerospace industries; the Offenbacher Hafen and the Hanauer Hafen are similar. The Mainvorland in Sachsenhausen is the historic Frankfurt riverside. Cycling routes include the Main-Radweg (a top German long-distance trail from Creußen to Mainz via Bayreuth, Bamberg, Würzburg and Frankfurt), the Hessischer Radfernweg, the Lahntalradweg, the Fulda-Radweg, the Werra-Radweg, the EuroVelo 6 (Atlantic-Black Sea) and the EuroVelo 15 (Rhine Cycle Route from Andermatt to Rotterdam).',
    economics = 'Hessen has the second-highest regional GDP-per-capita among the German Bundesländer (after Hamburg) at around 50,000 euros and a total GDP of around 320 billion euros, dominated by financial services, the Frankfurt Airport hub, chemical and pharmaceutical industries, automotive parts, machine tools, and a sophisticated trade-fair, conference and media economy. The Hessen Trade and Invest GmbH (HTAI) at Wiesbaden markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Frankfurt, the IHK Wiesbaden, the IHK Darmstadt, the IHK Kassel and the IHK Gießen represent the regional businesses.

The Frankfurt banking and financial sector is the largest in continental Europe. The European Central Bank (ECB, Europäische Zentralbank, EZB), the central bank of the eurozone, has its headquarters at the new ECB Tower in Ostend in the former Großmarkthalle wholesale fruit market (the 185-metre twin-tower by Coop Himmelb(l)au opened 2014), housing around 4,000 staff. The Deutsche Bundesbank, the German central bank with its global gold-reserve vault, has its head office at the Wilhelm-Epstein-Straße in Westend. The Bank for International Settlements (BIS) Frankfurt office is at the Mainzer Landstraße. Deutsche Bank AG, the largest German private bank, has its corporate headquarters at the Deutsche-Bank-Twin-Towers at Taunusanlage 12. Commerzbank AG, the second-largest German private bank, has its corporate headquarters at the Commerzbank Tower at Kaiserplatz. DZ Bank AG, the central institution of the German cooperative banking sector, has its head office at the Westend Tower at Platz der Republik. The KfW Bankengruppe, the federal-government development bank and the largest German promotional bank, has its head office at the Palmengartenstraße. Frankfurter Sparkasse, the city''s savings bank, has its head office at the Neue Mainzer Straße. Helaba (Landesbank Hessen-Thüringen), the state bank, has its head office at the MAIN Tower. Other major Frankfurt banks include BNP Paribas Germany, Citi Germany, Goldman Sachs Frankfurt (which has expanded dramatically since Brexit), JPMorgan Frankfurt (also expanded post-Brexit), Morgan Stanley Frankfurt, UBS Frankfurt, Credit Suisse Frankfurt (now part of UBS), Banco Santander, ING-DiBa AG (the German subsidiary of ING Group, headquartered at Theodor-Heuss-Allee), Société Générale and many others. Deutsche Börse AG, the operator of the Frankfurt Stock Exchange (Börse Frankfurt) and the international derivatives exchange Eurex, the bond electronic trading platform Tradegate, and the Xetra Trade Platform, has its corporate headquarters at the Mergenthalerallee in Eschborn (the so-called "City West"). Clearstream Banking, the central securities depository, is part of Deutsche Börse. The Frankfurt Stock Exchange, founded 1585 and the second-largest German exchange after Hamburg in size of cash-equity trade, lists the DAX 40 leading German companies. EZA, the Eurex, EUREX Clearing AG and the Frankfurt Stock Exchange together form the world''s second-largest exchange operator. The Frankfurt Insurance and reinsurance cluster includes the German subsidiaries of Allianz Global Corporate & Specialty, Generali, Zurich Insurance Group, AXA, Talanx, Hannover Re Frankfurt office, Munich Re Frankfurt office, AIG, Liberty Mutual, Allianz Trade, the cooperative Versicherungskammer Bayern, and the actuarial-services firm Towers Watson. The Frankfurter Versicherungskammer AG, the R+V Versicherung, the Provinzial Hessen and the Continentale all have Frankfurt operations. The Frankfurt fintech and crypto cluster has grown substantially since 2015 with companies like 360T (the EBS-Brokertec brokerage), Boursarama and the Frankfurt Cyber Defence Cluster.

Industry remains substantial. Opel Automobile GmbH, founded 1862 by Adam Opel at Rüsselsheim, today owned by Stellantis after the 2017 sale by General Motors to PSA Peugeot Citroën, has its main passenger-car plant and corporate headquarters at Rüsselsheim am Main. The plant produces the Opel Astra, Opel Grandland, Opel Crossland and the related Stellantis derivatives DS 7 Crossback and Citroën C5 Aircross; Opel''s sister plants are at Eisenach (Thuringia) and Kaiserslautern (Rheinland-Pfalz). Opel Engineering at Rüsselsheim is one of the largest automotive engineering centres in Europe. Volkswagen Kassel-Baunatal, the largest VW component plant in the world, builds gearboxes, axles and electric-drive units for the VW global production network, employing around 17,000 workers. Continental AG, the listed tyre, automotive electronics and rubber-products group (DAX 40 since 1996), has its Frankfurt locations including ContiTech and the Frankfurt-Niederrad headquarters of the powertrain spin-off Vitesco Technologies. Bombardier Transportation Kassel (now Alstom Kassel since the 2021 Alstom-Bombardier merger) builds the modern Velaro D ICE, the Talent regional EMUs, the Coradia Stream EMUs, the Coradia iLint hydrogen trains, and the Mireo regional EMUs; Alstom Kassel is one of the largest German rail-vehicle plants. The Edag Engineering Group at Wiesbaden is a major automotive engineering-services group. The Heraeus Holding GmbH at Hanau is a global precious-metals, dental, sensor-technology and biomaterials company founded 1851; Heraeus has annual revenues of around 22 billion euros. The Carl Stahl Group is an industrial machinery and crane manufacturer. The B. Braun Melsungen AG (Family-owned medical-technology company founded 1839 at Melsungen, the global infusion-therapy specialist with annual revenues of 8 billion euros) is the largest German family-owned medical-technology company. Fresenius SE & Co. KGaA, the listed Bad Homburg-based global healthcare group, owns Fresenius Medical Care (the world''s largest dialysis service), Fresenius Kabi (infusion therapy), Fresenius Helios (the largest German private hospital operator), and Fresenius Vamed; total annual revenues 40 billion euros. The Schenker Logistik (DB Schenker), the global logistics arm of Deutsche Bahn, has its Frankfurt operations.

Merck KGaA, the listed Darmstadt-based pharmaceutical, chemical, life-sciences and electronics group, was founded in 1668 at Darmstadt by Friedrich Jacob Merck as the Engel-Apotheke pharmacy and is the oldest pharmaceutical and chemical company in the world. Merck KGaA has annual revenues of around 22 billion euros and produces pharmaceuticals (the cancer-immunotherapy drug Bavencio, the oral fertility drug Gonal-f, the cancer-cell-line drug Erbitux, the multiple-sclerosis drug Rebif and the diabetes drug Glucophage), life-sciences instruments (the SAFC business of laboratory chemicals, the MilliporeSigma laboratory-water systems acquired from Sigma-Aldrich and Merck Millipore), and electronics chemicals (the liquid-crystal materials for LCD displays, the OLED stack materials and the semiconductor specialty chemicals, including the EUV resists for ASML lithography). Merck KGaA is unrelated to Merck & Co. of the United States since the 1917 separation; the German Merck is the original company. Sanofi-Aventis Deutschland GmbH (the German subsidiary of Sanofi, the French pharmaceutical giant) has its main R&D and production site at Frankfurt-Höchst on the former Hoechst AG industrial complex; Sanofi at Frankfurt-Höchst is one of the largest pharmaceutical R&D sites in Europe. The Industriepark Höchst, the former Hoechst AG headquarters complex, is one of the largest single chemical-industrial complexes in Europe (4.5 square kilometres) and hosts Sanofi-Aventis, Bayer CropScience (subsidiary of Bayer AG), Celanese, Clariant, Almatis, Allessa, Cinco, Cytec, Lyondell Basell and many other tenants. The Lyondell Basell Industries Holding, the German subsidiary of LyondellBasell, has its Frankfurt-Höchst polyolefin plant. The Hoechst AG was historically the world''s largest chemical company at the turn of the 20th century, founded 1863 at Höchst by August Wilhelm von Hofmann and Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Meister as the Theerfarbenfabrik Meister, Lucius & Brüning; the 1997 break-up of Hoechst AG into Sanofi-Aventis and Celanese was one of the largest pharmaceutical mergers in European history.

The Hessen trade-fair sector is anchored by Messe Frankfurt, the world''s third-largest trade-fair operator after the Hannover Messe and the Las Vegas Convention Center; Messe Frankfurt operates around 130 trade fairs per year on the 578,000 square-metre fairground including the Frankfurt Buchmesse (the world''s largest book fair, established 1454 with the rediscovery in 1949 as a modern trade fair), the Frankfurt Musikmesse and Prolight + Sound, the Frankfurt Automechanika, the Frankfurt IAA Mobility (since 2021 in Munich), the Achema chemical-engineering fair, the Ambiente consumer-goods fair, the Light + Building, the ISH Sanitärindustrie, the Heimtextil, the Paperworld and the Christmasworld. The Wiesbadener Spielbank and Casino, the Henkell Sektkellerei champagne house at Wiesbaden (founded 1832, the largest sparkling wine producer in Germany and now part of Henkell-Freixenet), and the Eichbaum Brauerei at Mannheim (slightly across the Hessian border) complete the consumer-products cluster.

Hessen is also a major media and IT centre. The ZDF (Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen), the second largest German public broadcaster, has its main studios and headquarters at Mainz-Lerchenberg (technically in Rheinland-Pfalz, but the Frankfurt newsroom and the Wiesbaden offices are substantial). The Hessischer Rundfunk (HR), the regional ARD broadcaster, has its main studios at the Bertramstraße in Frankfurt-Dornbusch. The Deutsche Welle Frankfurt office, the international broadcaster Deutsche Welle (DW) Bonn-Berlin, has its Frankfurt office at the Voltastraße. The major IT companies in Hessen include T-Systems International (the systems-integration subsidiary of Deutsche Telekom, headquartered at Frankfurt), Atos Information Technology, IBM Germany Frankfurt operations, Microsoft Germany at Bad Homburg and Munich, Oracle Germany at Eschborn, SAP Customer Experience Frankfurt office, Capgemini Frankfurt and the German Software AG headquartered at Darmstadt. The Frankfurt-Eschborn axis is one of the largest German IT corridors. The DE-CIX (Deutscher Commercial Internet Exchange) Internet Exchange Point at Frankfurt is the world''s largest by aggregated traffic (peaking at over 17 Tbit/s), operated by DE-CIX Management GmbH. Frankfurt has the highest concentration of data centres in continental Europe, with around 60 carrier-neutral colocation facilities operated by Digital Realty, NTT, Equinix and others; the Frankfurter Datacenter cluster is the gateway for European-Asian and European-Indian internet traffic.

Universities and research are significant. The Johann Wolfgang Goethe-Universität Frankfurt am Main, founded 1914 as a private university, has around 47,000 students and the Klinikum der Goethe-Universität (one of Germany''s largest university hospitals); the Frankfurt Institute for Advanced Studies (FIAS), the Max-Planck-Institut für Biophysik, the Max-Planck-Institut für Hirnforschung at Frankfurt, the Max-Planck-Institut für Empirische Ästhetik at Frankfurt, the Senckenberg Naturforschung Institut, and the Frankfurt Institute for Theoretical Physics complete the city research map. The Philipps-Universität Marburg, the second-oldest Protestant university in Germany (founded 1527 by Philipp the Magnanimous, Landgrave of Hessen) has around 22,000 students. The Technische Universität Darmstadt, the Justus-Liebig-Universität Gießen (named after Justus von Liebig the founder of agricultural chemistry), the Universität Kassel and the Universität Fulda complete higher education. The GSI Helmholtzzentrum für Schwerionenforschung at Darmstadt is the home of the FAIR Facility for Antiproton and Ion Research, one of the world''s largest particle-physics facilities. The Fraunhofer-Institut für Sichere Informationstechnologie SIT and the Fraunhofer-Institut für Solare Energiesysteme have Hessian operations.',
    introduced_species = 'Hessen is the historic ground-zero of the western European raccoon invasion: the original German raccoon release occurred at the Edersee in northern Hessen on 12 April 1934, when the Prussian forest officer Wilhelm Sittich-Freiherr von Berlepsch released two breeding pairs of raccoons (Procyon lotor) at the Wildpark Edersee near Bad Wildungen, under the authorisation of the Prussian Reichsforstmeister, with the explicit intention of enriching the local game fauna. From that founding population of four animals, the species expanded steadily across central Germany over the following decades, with the second major release from the wartime fur-farm at Wolfshagen in Brandenburg in 1945 forming a second nucleus. The Hessian Edersee raccoons reached the Vogelsberg, the Kellerwald, the Reinhardswald and the Frankfurt-Wiesbaden lower Main valley by the 1960s, the Rhein-Main metropolitan area by the 1970s, and saturated all Hessian habitats by the 2000s. Today Hessen has one of the densest raccoon populations in Europe, with estimates of 50 to 80 raccoons per square kilometre in the Kellerwald, the Reinhardswald, the Rhön and the suburban Rhein-Main region, plus very dense urban populations in Frankfurt, Wiesbaden, Darmstadt, Kassel, Marburg and the smaller cities. Annual hunting bags in Hessen exceed 25,000 raccoons, making the state one of the top three German states for raccoon hunting. The Hessisches Landesamt für Naturschutz, Umwelt und Geologie (HLNUG) at Wiesbaden maintains the Hessen Neozoa register and coordinates with the federal Bundesamt für Naturschutz (BfN) under EU Regulation 1143/2014. Frankfurt and Kassel both publish citizen guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the handling of raccoon latrines (which are a source of the parasitic roundworm Baylisascaris procyonis). The Frankfurter Zoo and the Tierpark Wiesbaden participate in EU-coordinated invasive-species awareness programmes. The Senckenberg Forschungsinstitut at Frankfurt has been a leading researcher of the German raccoon expansion, with telemetry studies of the Hessian and Brandenburg populations under the direction of the long-running Project Waschbärenforschung. The Edersee, the historic Hessian release site, is today a popular Wildpark with a small commemorative raccoon enclosure.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Hessen from the east in the 2000s; the species is now established throughout Hessen with the highest densities in the Vogelsberg, the Rhön, the Kellerwald and the Reinhardswald. Annual hunting bags exceed 8,000. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Hessian Rhine plain (the Hessisches Ried), the lower Main, the Lahn, the Eder, the Fulda and the Werra. Damage to flood-protection dykes by burrowing and to reedbeds by overgrazing is a serious management concern; the Hessisches Wasserwirtschaftsverwaltung and the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt coordinate professional trapping. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Hessen but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and HLNUG since the 1980s and has now recolonised the Eder, Fulda, Lahn and Werra; the Hessian beaver population is one of the largest in central Germany. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Hessen.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations along the Main, the Rhine, the Lahn, the Werra and the Edersee. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded dramatically; Hessen has some of the densest Egyptian goose populations in Germany, with the Frankfurt Mainufer, the Wiesbaden Kurpark, the Darmstadt Herrngarten and the Kassel Karlsaue all hosting large breeding populations. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has established the largest German breeding population in Wiesbaden, Mainz and the Frankfurt-Darmstadt Rhein-Main area, with around 2,000 breeding pairs in the Wiesbaden Biebrich Schlosspark, the Frankfurt Westend, the Frankfurt-Süd cemetery, the Darmstadt Herrngarten and the Mainz Hauptbahnhof district. The Wiesbaden Halsbandsittiche are one of the most studied feral populations of the species in Europe. The Alexandrine parakeet, Großer Alexandersittich, Psittacula eupatria, joins them in smaller numbers. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on Hessian park ponds. The wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on Hessian hunting estates without becoming self-sustaining.

Among fish, the Rhine, the Main, the Lahn, the Fulda, the Eder and the Werra all host introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch, is established in the Hessian gravel pits. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling, is widespread. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels, occurs in old gravel pits. The rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Regenbogenforelle, is stocked in the Hessian trout farms and the Eder, Fulda and Lahn streams. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis, Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella, Graskarpfen, is used to control aquatic vegetation in Hessian lakes. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel, native to the Black Sea, has reached Hessen via the Rhine and the Main from the Main-Donau-Kanal in the early 2010s, with the first Frankfurt record around 2010; the species is now established throughout the Hessian Main and lower Rhine, with substantial impact on native bullheads. The Caspian Kessler''s goby and the bighead goby follow. The wels catfish, Silurus glanis, although historically native to the Rhine, has been augmented by stocking.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs, widespread in the Hessian streams and responsible for local extinctions of the native noble crayfish (Astacus astacus) and the stone crayfish (Austropotamobius torrentium). The red swamp crayfish, Procambarus clarkii, Roter Sumpfkrebs, is established in the Frankfurter Stadtwald and the Wiesbaden-Biebrich Schlosspark ponds. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs, the parthenogenetic species first noted in a German aquarist''s tank, occurs in Hessen. The spinycheek crayfish, Faxonius limosus, Kamberkrebs, is widespread. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe, is regular in the Main and Rhine. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel, and the quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel, are abundant in the Hessian lakes and the Rhine. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel, is in the Rhine and Main.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in Hessen from 2020 onwards, with the first Hessian nest discovered near Wiesbaden in 2020 and rapid expansion since; the Imkerverband Hessen coordinates nest-removal teams with the HLNUG. By 2024 hundreds of Asian hornet nests had been removed in southern Hessen. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Hessian chestnut avenues every late summer; the Wiesbaden Kurpark and the Frankfurt Bockenheimer Anlage are particularly affected. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Wiesbaden Kurpark, the Frankfurt Palmengarten, the Schwetzingen Palace and various Hessen private gardens. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established in the Rhein-Main and Wiesbaden Rheingau, with substantial agricultural damage in the Hessian fruit orchards.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) is widespread in Hessen, with particularly dense populations in the Rhein-Main metropolitan area, the Wetterau and the southern Hessian Ried; the HLNUG coordinates the Hessen Ambrosia-Atlas and the state-wide control programme. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates banks of the Main, the Lahn, the Eder and the Fulda. Bohemian knotweed (Reynoutria bohemica) and giant knotweed (Reynoutria sachalinensis) are also present. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on Hessian stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in Hessen parks with phototoxic-sap warnings. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum) spreads along Hessian railway lines and in the Frankfurt-Wiesbaden brownfields; the Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof Bahnhofsviertel district is famous for its Ailanthus thickets growing through cracked pavements. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, planted historically in Hessen streets and now self-seeding into many disturbed habitats), the Indian balsam, the water primrose (Ludwigia grandiflora), the South African Crassula helmsii (Nadelkraut) and the floating fern Salvinia molesta have been recorded sporadically. The Senecio inaequidens (Schmalblättriges Greiskraut), the South African ragwort, is now established on Hessian railway lines and disturbed sandy ground.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in Hessen-area forestry reserves and hunting estates, particularly in the Kellerwald, the Reinhardswald, the Rhön, the Vogelsberg and the Spessart. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Reinhardswald and the Rhön. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at high density in all Hessian forests and the Frankfurt Stadtwald, with annual hunting bags exceeding 40,000 statewide. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Kellerwald and the Rhön. Wolves (Canis lupus), although native, have returned to Hessen from Polish and eastern German populations from around 2015, with the first confirmed Hessian pack established in the Reinhardswald around 2020.'
WHERE region_name = 'Hessen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, often abbreviated as MV or Meck-Pomm, is the north-eastern most German federal state, bordering the Baltic Sea (Ostsee) to the north and Poland to the east, covering 23,180 square kilometres and home to around 1.6 million people, the lowest population density of any German state at about 70 persons per square kilometre. The state combines the historic territories of the duchies of Mecklenburg-Schwerin and Mecklenburg-Strelitz, the western parts of historic Pomerania (Vorpommern) including the islands of Rügen and Usedom, and parts of the former Swedish Pomerania around Stralsund and Greifswald. Schwerin is the state capital, Rostock the largest city, and Stralsund, Greifswald, Wismar, Neubrandenburg and Neustrelitz the other major cultural centres.

Schwerin Palace (Schweriner Schloss), the so-called Neuschwanstein of the North, is the most iconic tourist attraction of the state. Built on an island in the Schweriner See by the Mecklenburg-Schwerin dukes between 1843 and 1857 by Georg Adolf Demmler in romantic Renaissance Revival style, the palace is now the seat of the Mecklenburg-Vorpommern state parliament (Landtag). The 365 chambers, the Throne Room, the Goldener Saal, the chapel, the Schlosspark with the Burggarten, the Tribüne riding-house and the orangery make the complex one of the finest German romantic-historicist palaces. Beside the palace stands the Schweriner Dom (Schwerin Cathedral), a Brick Gothic basilica built between 1280 and 1416, with a 117-metre tower (the highest tower in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern) and the famous Triumphal Cross of 1420. The Staatliches Museum Schwerin holds the Mecklenburg-Schwerin court collection, including the famous Dutch Golden Age paintings of Jan Brueghel, Frans Hals, Carel Fabritius and Pieter Saenredam, plus French eighteenth-century paintings of Jean-Baptiste Oudry. The Schelfstadt Old Town, the Marktplatz with its Neues Palais (the historic government building now housing the Heimatmuseum), and the Pfaffenteich pond, with its tunnel between the Hauptbahnhof and the city, complete the city circuit.

Rostock, the largest city of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, is the great Hanseatic port of the Baltic. The Marienkirche (St. Mary''s Church), a Brick Gothic basilica of 1454, contains the famous astronomical clock of Hans Düringer of 1472 (one of only two surviving 15th-century astronomical clocks in Europe still in working condition, with the calendar dial set to repeat in the year 2017 after 500 years) and the carved oak rood-screen. The Universität Rostock, founded in 1419 by Duke Johann III of Mecklenburg, is the oldest university in northern Europe and the third-oldest German university; the Universitätsplatz at the Hauptgebäude (the magnificent neo-renaissance main building of 1870), the Rostock Bibliothek and the Marienkirche form the academic core. The Rostock Heiligengeisthof, the Petrikirche, the Nikolaikirche, the Steintor and the Kröpeliner Tor (the western city-gate, in fact the symbol of Rostock featured on the Mecklenburg coat-of-arms), the Kröpeliner Straße shopping mile, the Schwaansche Straße with its preserved Hanseatic merchants houses and the Stadthafen with the historic warehouses and the cog (Hansekogge), are the central highlights. The Rostock Zoo at the Barnstorfer Anlagen, with the Eisbär polar-bear and walrus enclosure, the Darwineum evolution-themed pavilion (opened 2012) and the Polarium polar-animal exhibit (opened 2018), is the largest zoo in northern Germany. The Schiffahrtsmuseum Rostock at the IGA-Park, the Forschungsschiff Marine Polarstern (when in port), and the Stadtmarina at the Stadthafen, all reflect the maritime heritage. Warnemünde, on the Baltic five kilometres north of Rostock at the mouth of the Warnow, is one of the most popular German seaside resorts, with the broad Strandpromenade, the historic lighthouse Leuchtturm Warnemünde of 1898 (37 metres tall, climbable), the Teepott exhibition pavilion, the Alter Strom harbour with the fish restaurants, the Mole pier, and the Hanse Sail Rostock — the annual gathering of tall ships from across Europe held every August. Warnemünde is also Rostock''s cruise port, the largest German cruise terminal on the Baltic.

The Wismar UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 2002 jointly with Stralsund) preserves one of the most intact medieval Hanseatic Old Towns in northern Europe. The Marktplatz, one of the largest medieval marketplaces in northern Germany at 100 by 100 metres, is dominated by the Wismar Town Hall (1817-1819, Friedrich Wilhelm Cobergher) and the Wasserkunst Wismar fountain (1602, by Philipp Brandin), with the Alter Schwede (1380), the Westphalia House (1380) and the Reuter House surrounding it. The St. Nikolaikirche, the St. Georgenkirche (restored after wartime devastation), the St. Marienkirche tower (with the partial church remains since the post-war demolition of the bombed body), the Schweinsbrücke pig-bridge over the Mühlenbach, the Wassertor and the Alte Holzhafen with its preserved Hanseatic warehouses are all part of the UNESCO inscription. The Wismarer Stadtgeschichtliches Museum is in the Schabbellhaus, the famous Brick Renaissance burgher mansion of 1571. The Wismar Phantom Ship F.W. Murnau is celebrated by the F.W. Murnau Society (Murnau filmed his Nosferatu, A Symphony of Horror in Wismar in 1922; the Wassertor and the harbour appear in the film).

Stralsund, the second UNESCO Old Town (jointly inscribed with Wismar), is one of the most beautiful Brick Gothic ensembles in the Baltic. The St. Marienkirche (with its 104-metre tower, the tallest church in northern Germany before the 19th-century rebuild reduced it slightly), the St. Nikolaikirche and the St. Jakobikirche form the three Hauptkirchen. The Stralsunder Rathaus (1300-1350), one of the most beautiful Hanseatic town halls in northern Europe, has the famous seven-gabled west facade. The Wulflamhaus, the Wulflam-Haus and the Kütertor complete the marketplace. The Stralsund Ozeaneum, opened 2008 by Behnisch Architekten, is one of the most ambitious oceanographic museums in Europe with the Baltic and North Atlantic aquariums and the suspended whale skeletons. The Deutsches Meeresmuseum, in the former Convent of St. Catherine, is the parent museum of the Ozeaneum and the Nautineum on the island of Dänholm. The Stralsund Strelasund Bridge and the Rügenbrücke connect Stralsund to the island of Rügen.

Rügen, the largest German island (974 square kilometres), is connected to Stralsund by the Rügenbrücke and the Rügendamm. The most famous feature is the Königsstuhl, the 118-metre chalk cliff at the heart of the Jasmund National Park, immortalised by Caspar David Friedrich''s Chalk Cliffs on Rügen (1818). The Jasmund National Park, declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site as part of the Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe in 2011, includes the Hochuferweg cliff-top trail, the Stubbenkammer headland, the Wissower Klinken and the Adlerhorst. The Sellin Pier (Seebrücke Sellin), Rügen''s most-photographed structure, is the historic 394-metre pier at Sellin beach with the romantic restaurant pavilion. Binz, Sellin, Göhren and Baabe are the four classic Rügen seaside resorts in the Bäderarchitektur style. The Kap Arkona at the northern tip of Rügen, with the historic Schinkel lighthouse and the new lighthouse, the Slavic temple ruin of Jaromarsburg and the village of Vitt with its thatched fishermen''s cottages, the Putgarten and the Bug peninsula. The Putbus residence with its Theater Putbus and the Schlosspark, the Hiddensee island (a quiet, car-free island reached by the Vitte ferry, the home of the writer Gerhart Hauptmann), the small towns of Bergen auf Rügen, Sassnitz and Saßnitz Mukran (the ferry port), and the Bug peninsula complete Rügen''s tourist offer. The Rasender Roland (Roaring Roland) narrow-gauge steam railway, with its historic 750 mm tracks running between Putbus and Göhren via Binz and Sellin, has been operating since 1895 and is one of the iconic Rügen experiences.

Usedom, the second-largest German island (445 square kilometres, shared with Poland — about a third of the island is the Polish city of Świnoujście), is famous for its 42-kilometre-long sandy beach (the longest continuous beach on the German Baltic), its bäderarchitektur resorts of Bansin, Heringsdorf and Ahlbeck (the so-called Three Imperial Spas, the Kaiserbäder), the Ahlbeck Pier (the oldest German pier still in operation), and the Wolgast Schloss. The Achterwasser lagoon on the south of the island is a quiet inland sea.

Heiligendamm, near Bad Doberan on the Mecklenburg coast, is the oldest seaside resort in continental Europe, founded in 1793 by Duke Friedrich Franz I of Mecklenburg-Schwerin. The historic Weißer Stadt am Meer (the white town by the sea), a curving line of seven classicist white buildings facing the Baltic, served as the venue for the G8 Summit in 2007. Today Heiligendamm is a luxury resort.

The Mecklenburg Lake District (Mecklenburgische Seenplatte), the largest interconnected lake landscape in central Europe, contains around 2000 lakes spread across the central state. The Müritz, at 117 square kilometres, is the largest lake entirely within Germany (Lake Constance has more area but extends into Switzerland and Austria) and the third-largest lake in Germany. The Müritz National Park, encompassing the western Müritz and the Serrahn beech forest (the second Mecklenburg UNESCO Beech Forest site), the historic town of Waren (Müritz), the Müritzeum (the lake museum at Waren with the largest freshwater aquarium in Germany), the Plauer See, the Krakower See, the Schweriner See, the Tollensesee, the Kummerower See and the Malchiner See, with the Schlossinsel Mirow, Schloss Mirow, Schloss Hohenzieritz (where Queen Luise of Prussia died in 1810), Schloss Schwerin, Schloss Ulrichshusen, Schloss Bothmer at Klütz, the Buchenwald monastery at Rehna and the Cistercian monastery of Doberan (Bad Doberan Münster) — the latter one of the most beautiful Brick Gothic churches in Germany. Bad Doberan also hosts the famous Molli steam railway, the world''s oldest narrow-gauge steam railway in continuous operation since 1886 (running between Bad Doberan, Heiligendamm and Kühlungsborn West).

Greifswald, on the Bay of Greifswald near the mouth of the Ryck, is the third university town of MV with the Universität Greifswald founded in 1456 (the second-oldest in northern Europe after Rostock), the Greifswald Marienkirche, the historic Old Town with its narrow lanes, and the Caspar David Friedrich Centre (the painter was born in Greifswald in 1774). The Greifswald Wieck harbour, the Eldena ruins of the Cistercian monastery, the Saaler Bodden lagoon and the surrounding Vorpommern landscape complete the area. The Anklam Otto Lilienthal Museum honours the Pomeranian-born flight pioneer.

Mecklenburg cuisine includes Mecklenburger Rippenbraten (roast pork ribs), Mecklenburger Vorsuppe (a sweet-sour soup of dried fruit and meat broth), Mecklenburger Sauerfleisch (jellied pork), Hagebuttensuppe (rose-hip soup), Plinsen pancakes, Klöße (potato dumplings), Sanddorn (sea-buckthorn from Rügen — a Mecklenburg specialty fruit rich in vitamin C, used in marmalades, juices and liqueurs), Fischbrötchen (rolls with marinated herring or fried fish), Räucherfisch (the smoked fish from the Baltic and Bodden, particularly Räucheraal smoked eel, Räucherflunder smoked flounder, and Räucherbutt smoked turbot), Fischsuppe, Bratheringen, Mecklenburger Eintopf and Schweinekopf gepökelt. Drinks: Lübzer Pils (the state beer), Rostocker Pilsator, Stralsunder Pilsener, Hanseaten Pilsener, Mecklenburger Mecklenburg-Korn (a fine grain spirit), Stralsunder Klassik. Mecklenburg wines from the small Werder-an-der-Havel district (technically Brandenburg) and the Schloss Proschwitz estate (in Saxony) are sold throughout MV. The Mecklenburg-Vorpommern milk and dairy industry produces the Bad Doberaner butter, the historic Mecklenburger Schinken (smoked ham), the Edamer Käse from the Edamer dairy in Schlieffen and the Tollenser Käse.

History before 1933 is rich. The Mecklenburg lands were settled by Slavic Obotriten and Liutizen tribes from the 7th to 12th centuries, with the medieval Mecklenburg founded by Henry the Lion in 1167. The Hanseatic League era from the 12th to 17th centuries made Wismar, Rostock and Stralsund three of the leading Hanseatic ports. The Mecklenburg Duchy was split in 1701 into Mecklenburg-Schwerin and Mecklenburg-Strelitz, both continuing as separate states until 1934. The Vorpommern lands, ruled by Swedish Pomerania from the Peace of Westphalia in 1648 until 1815 (Wismar was Swedish until 1903 under formal lease), then by Prussian Pomerania until 1945, are home to the Baltic Hanseatic heritage. The 1918 German Revolution dissolved both Mecklenburg duchies; the new Land of Mecklenburg was formed in 1934, then split in 1945 into Soviet zone Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, then renamed Mecklenburg in 1947, then abolished into the GDR Bezirke Rostock, Schwerin and Neubrandenburg in 1952. The reunification of 1990 reformed the new Land Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. Famous figures from the state include Caspar David Friedrich (Greifswald), Otto Lilienthal (Anklam), Marshal von Blücher (Rostock), Heinrich Schliemann (the discoverer of Troy, born in Neubukow), Fritz Reuter (the Low German writer, Stavenhagen), Theodor Fontane (no, Fontane was Neuruppin in Brandenburg, never mind), Ernst Moritz Arndt (Rügen-born poet), Philipp Otto Runge (Wolgast, Romantic painter), and the present Federal Chancellor Angela Merkel (raised in Templin near Brandenburg but with MV university links at Leipzig).',
    transportation = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, the most sparsely populated German Bundesland, has a transport network shaped by the long Baltic Sea coast, the multitude of inland lakes of the Mecklenburg Lake District, and the historic Hanseatic ports. Rostock-Laage Airport, IATA RLG and ICAO ETNL, located on a former Soviet airbase 28 kilometres south-east of Rostock, is the largest commercial airport in the state, handling around 250,000 passengers per year. Carriers operate seasonal Mediterranean and Egyptian charter flights, plus Lufthansa Cityline flights to Munich. Heringsdorf Airport on Usedom (HDF, EDAH) handles around 30,000 passengers per year with seasonal Mediterranean charter flights and some regular Lufthansa Cityline flights to Frankfurt and Munich; this is one of Germany''s smallest commercial airports. Smaller airfields include Neubrandenburg-Trollenhagen (a former Soviet airbase), Anklam, Barth, Schwerin-Parchim (a former NVA airbase used by Russian air-cargo carrier Sky Gates Airlines as a cargo hub), and the historic Peenemünde airfield (which had aerospace heritage but is now used as a museum airfield). The aviation industry in MV is modest by national standards.

The MV rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Nordost, with the regional brands ODEG (Ostdeutsche Eisenbahn), Usedomer Bäderbahn (UBB), Hanseatische Eisenbahn (HANS), Pressnitztalbahn-Veteran, NEB and the historic Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn Molli operating regional and tourist services. The state-wide tariff is administered by the VMV-Verkehrsgesellschaft Mecklenburg-Vorpommern at Schwerin. Rostock Hauptbahnhof, opened 1886, is the largest railway node in the state, with ICE and IC services to Berlin (the Berlin-Rostock route, 3 hours, completed as electrified in 1991), to Hamburg via Schwerin (ICE 2 hour 45), and to Munich and Stuttgart via the long Berlin corridor. Schwerin Hauptbahnhof, Stralsund Hauptbahnhof, Greifswald Hauptbahnhof, Wismar Hauptbahnhof, Neubrandenburg, Pasewalk, Anklam, Demmin, Waren (Müritz) and Bützow are the other major rail nodes. The Berlin-Rostock-Warnemünde corridor carries IC and EC services; the Berlin-Stralsund-Sassnitz/Mukran corridor with the Stralsund-Berlin ICE/IC and the seasonal IC ferry to Trelleborg-Sweden, Klaipėda-Lithuania or Helsinki-Finland (the latter no longer in service since 2020). The Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn Molli, a 900 mm narrow-gauge steam railway from Bad Doberan via Heiligendamm to Kühlungsborn West, has been operating since 1886 and is one of the world''s oldest steam railways in continuous operation. The Rasender Roland, a 750 mm narrow-gauge steam railway on Rügen from Putbus via Binz to Göhren, has been operating since 1895. The Usedomer Bäderbahn (UBB) runs the standard-gauge electric railway from Wolgast across the Peenebrücke to Heringsdorf and Ahlbeck on Usedom, with cross-border service to Świnoujście in Poland.

The Autobahn network in MV is anchored by the A20 (Ostseeautobahn) running from Lübeck via Rostock to Stralsund and Anklam to the Polish border at Pomellen, where it connects to the Polish S6 to Szczecin and the A6 onward. The A19 connects Berlin to Rostock; the A24 Hamburg-Berlin crosses the southern part of the state from Schwerin; the A14 from Magdeburg, currently being extended north to Schwerin, is one of the slowest German Autobahn megaprojects with full completion expected after 2030. The A28 to Bremen and the A29 connect to the lower Weser region. Bundesstraßen include the B96 from Berlin via Neubrandenburg to Stralsund and Sassnitz on Rügen (the so-called Hannover-Stettin axis), the B105 from Lübeck via Rostock to Stralsund, the B104 east-west, the B109 to Stettin via Anklam, the B193 north-south, and the B196 to Sassnitz.

The Rostock Port (Hafen Rostock), operated by Rostock Port GmbH, is one of the largest German Baltic-Sea ports. It handles container traffic, bulk cargo, oil, chemicals and ferry passengers. The Rostock-Trelleborg ferry to Sweden, operated by TT-Line and Stena Line, is one of the busiest ferry routes on the Baltic. The Rostock-Gedser ferry to Denmark, operated by Scandlines, runs every two hours. The Rostock cruise terminal at Warnemünde Pier 8 handles around 200,000 cruise passengers per year and is the largest German cruise port on the Baltic, with Aida Cruises (which has its main shipbuilding at Neptun Werft Rostock), Costa Cruises, MSC Cruises, Norwegian Cruise Line and Royal Caribbean as the major operators. The Sassnitz-Mukran Port on Rügen, originally built for the historic German-Soviet rail-ferry between East Germany and Klaipėda (Lithuania), now handles ferry services to Trelleborg-Sweden, Klaipėda-Lithuania (via DFDS) and the heavy-lift transports. The Wismar Port handles bulk cargo and the Wismar Shipyard (formerly MV Werften Wismar) ship repair. The Stralsund Volkswerft (formerly MV Werften Stralsund) has reorganised through the MV Werften insolvency. The Schwedt port (technically in Brandenburg but linked to MV) and the Anklam port complete the inland-port system on the Peene and the Oder.

The MV waterways include the Müritz-Elde Wasserstraße, the Müritz-Havel-Wasserstraße connecting the Müritz to the Berlin Spree-Havel system, the Peene river from the Tollensesee to the Greifswalder Bodden, and the Warnow from Schwerin to Rostock. The Müritz, the Krakower See, the Plauer See and the Tollensesee operate passenger boat services in summer. Long-distance cycling routes include the Ostseeküsten-Radweg (the Baltic Sea Coast Cycle Route, EuroVelo 10 from Cuxhaven via Lübeck, Wismar, Rostock, Stralsund and Greifswald to the Polish border), the Mecklenburgischer Seenradweg (the Mecklenburg Lakes Cycle Route from Lüneburg via Schwerin, Plau am See, Waren, Mirow and Rheinsberg to Berlin), the Hamburg-Rügen Radweg, the Berlin-Kopenhagen Radweg, the Berlin-Usedom Radweg, the Stettiner Haff Radweg and the EuroVelo 7 (Norway-Malta). The Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn Molli line is integrated into the cycle network with bike-carriage on every train.

The Hanse Sail Rostock, held every August in Warnemünde, brings around 200 tall ships and traditional vessels from the Baltic and the North Sea to Rostock, making it one of the largest maritime festivals in Europe. The Greifswalder Bodden, the Strelasund and the Achterwasser are sailing waters. The Tollensesee and the Plauer See are favourites for windsurfing. The MVV (Mecklenburg-Vorpommern Verkehrsverbund) coordinates regional bus and rail services; the VVR-Verkehrsbetrieb Vorpommern-Rügen and VVR-Vorpommern-Greifswald operate the regional bus networks. Long-distance buses use the ZOB Rostock and the ZOB Schwerin; FlixBus and Sindbad operate services to Berlin, Hamburg, Copenhagen and Warsaw.

MV pioneered the modern e-bus pilot programmes in the 2010s with the BUS-2-X programme of the Rostock public transport authority RSAG (Rostocker Straßenbahn AG), which operates the Rostock tram network (the only tram system in the state) — six lines totalling 36 kilometres and 79 stations, the second-oldest German electric tram system (operational since 1881, electrified 1904). The Schwerin tram network (Schweriner Verkehrsbetriebe) has three lines. The Mecklenburg-Vorpommern Senate plans the new Fehmarn Belt fixed link, which when it opens in 2029 will connect MV to Denmark via the Vogelfluglinie, dramatically cutting travel times to Copenhagen and Stockholm. The Sassnitz-Mukran Port is being expanded for the offshore-wind cluster.',
    economics = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has the lowest regional GDP per capita of all German Bundesländer, around 30,000 euros, although the state economy has steadily grown since reunification and the structural transformation continues with substantial federal Strukturwandel funds for the historic lignite-mining and shipbuilding regions. The total state GDP is around 50 billion euros. The MV Senate''s economic-development arm, the Wirtschaftsförderung Mecklenburg-Vorpommern (Invest in MV), markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Rostock, the IHK Schwerin and the IHK Neubrandenburg represent the regional businesses.

Tourism is the largest single economic sector. MV hosts around 8 million visitors per year (the third-highest among the German states after Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg), with the Baltic Sea coast, the Mecklenburg Lake District, Rügen, Usedom, Heiligendamm, the Hanseatic Old Towns of Stralsund and Wismar, the Müritz National Park and the historic Schwerin all drawing substantial visitor flows. The Tourismusverband Mecklenburg-Vorpommern at Rostock markets the state. The TUI AG (Hannover-headquartered) has substantial MV operations including the Heiligendamm resort. The Aida Cruises ships are built at Neptun Werft Rostock; the MV Werften (Wismar, Stralsund, Warnow) shipyards built cruise vessels until the insolvency of 2022. The Yachtcharter sector is concentrated at Heiligenhafen, Greifswald, Stralsund and the Mecklenburg Lake District.

Shipbuilding has been historic. The Neptun Werft GmbH at Warnemünde, founded 1850 and now part of Meyer Werft of Papenburg (Niedersachsen), builds the engine-rooms and cabin sections for the Meyer-Werft cruise ships; the Volkswerft Stralsund (formerly the State Shipyard of the GDR, then the largest cruise-ship builder in the world), the MV Werften Wismar and the Aker MTW Wismar are restructuring through state-supported investment. The new Sassnitz-Mukran Port offshore-wind installation hub serves the Baltic wind farms. The MV Werften insolvency in 2022 led to one of the largest restructurings of recent German industrial history.

Wind energy and renewables are major MV growth sectors. The Nordex SE wind-turbine manufacturer has its main rotor-blade plant at Rostock; the Senvion (formerly REpower) onshore-wind plant at Lübz remained until the 2019 insolvency. The Vestas Blades Lauchhammer plant is in Brandenburg but supplies MV. The Baltic 1 offshore wind farm at Zingst, the Baltic 2 wind farm near Rügen, the EnBW Hohe See, the Wikinger and the planned Sassnitz-Mukran installation hub all serve the Baltic offshore-wind industry. Onshore wind covers a substantial part of the state with around 1,800 turbines. Biogas plants are widespread in the agricultural Mecklenburg countryside.

Agriculture and food processing are major employers. MV has the largest German cereal-farming area per capita and is the third-largest agricultural state by area. Wheat, rye, oilseed rape, sugar beet, maize, potatoes, oats and barley dominate; cattle, pigs and poultry farming are significant. The Mecklenburgische Schweizerei dairy, the Greifenfeld dairy, the MecklenburgerKüche food processor, the Rostocker Lager, the Müritzer Lebensmittel and the Sanddorn-Storchennest distillery on Rügen complete the agricultural value chain. The Sanddorn (sea-buckthorn) industry around Rügen and the Darß-Zingst peninsula is a regional specialty supplying juices, marmalades, oils and cosmetics to the German market. The Rügenwalder Mühle, although historically from Rügenwalde in Pomerania (now Darłowo, Poland) but headquartered at Bad Zwischenahn (Niedersachsen), maintains a meaningful presence in MV.

The Rostock Port is the largest single port economic engine, with around 50 million tonnes of cargo per year. Ferry services to Sweden, Denmark and the Baltic States; bulk cargo for the chemical industry; the Aida Cruises homeport; the Hanseatic offshore-wind installation harbour. The Rostock Port also serves as the hinterland gateway for Berlin and the eastern German market.

Defence-industry presence includes the historic Werft Volkswerft Stralsund, the Werft Wismar, the Bundeswehr Marine Hafenkommando Warnemünde, and the German Federal Navy''s base at Rostock-Warnemünde. The Bundeswehr Marine Operations Centre Glücksburg (Schleswig-Holstein) coordinates the Baltic Sea operations. The Federal Police''s Bundespolizei See has its Rostock base at Sassnitz.

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Universität Rostock, founded 1419, with around 14,000 students, is the oldest university in northern Europe; major research in plasma physics (the Leibniz-Institut für Plasmaforschung und Technologie INP Greifswald is a leader in low-temperature plasma applications), in marine biology (the IOW Leibniz-Institut für Ostseeforschung at Warnemünde), in fisheries (the Thünen-Institut Rostock), and in ageing research (the Greifswald University Medical Centre and the SHIP Study of Health in Pomerania, one of the largest German population-cohort studies). The Universität Greifswald, founded 1456, has around 10,000 students and a research focus on plasma physics (the Max-Planck-Institut für Plasmaphysik IPP Greifswald is the home of the Wendelstein 7-X stellarator, the most successful experimental fusion device of the stellarator type, achieving record energy-confinement results since 2015), on infection biology and on marine biology. The Hochschule Stralsund, the Hochschule Wismar, the Hochschule Neubrandenburg and the Hochschule für Musik und Theater Rostock complete the higher-education sector. The Leibniz-Institut für Nutztierbiologie at Dummerstorf, the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut on the island of Riems (the German federal animal-disease research institute, the home of foot-and-mouth, swine-fever and avian-flu research) and the Leibniz-Institut für Atmosphärenphysik at Kühlungsborn complete the research map.

The Rostock-Schwerin-Stralsund-Greifswald axis hosts a small but growing IT and creative-industries sector. The MV-Werft software-engineering team, the Rostock Stadtsoftware-Cluster, the Wismar TechCampus and the Greifswald Wendelstein technology park host emerging start-ups. The Schwerin Hauptpost as a national-level office is no longer significant since Deutsche Post relocated headquarters to Bonn. Banking and finance are concentrated at Rostock and Schwerin with the OstseeSparkasse Rostock, the Sparkasse Mecklenburg-Schwerin, the Sparkasse Vorpommern, the cooperative Pommersche Volksbank and the Volksbank Mecklenburg-Strelitz. The MV-Bank, the state-owned development bank, supports SMEs.

Media in MV include the Norddeutscher Rundfunk (NDR) regional studios at Rostock and Schwerin (the NDR Landesfunkhaus Mecklenburg-Vorpommern at Schwerin), the Ostsee-Zeitung (the leading regional daily newspaper, based in Rostock), the Schweriner Volkszeitung, the Nordkurier (Neubrandenburg) and the Greifswald-Stralsunder Volkszeitung. The MV state government uses the historic Schweriner Schloss for the Landtag and the Schwerin Staatskanzlei for the state-government ministries. The state has experienced steady population decline since the 1990s but is now stabilising with a slight gain since 2020.',
    introduced_species = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, with its long Baltic Sea coast (about 2,000 kilometres including the heavily indented shoreline), its multitude of inland lakes (around 2,000 lakes in the Mecklenburg Lake District), its low human-population density and its position on the eastern fringe of the German raccoon distribution, hosts a distinctive roster of introduced and invasive species, with strong representation of eastern European invaders alongside the standard western European set. The Landesamt für Umwelt, Naturschutz und Geologie Mecklenburg-Vorpommern (LUNG MV) at Güstrow coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern since the 1980s when individuals from the Brandenburg Wolfshagen 1945 release expanded north and east; today the species is established throughout MV with the highest densities in the Mecklenburgische Seenplatte (the Mecklenburg Lake District), the Schaalsee Biosphere Reserve, the Sternberger Seenland, the Müritz National Park, the Schorfheide buffer-zone to the south, and increasingly in the suburban Rostock, Schwerin and Neubrandenburg districts. Annual hunting bags in MV exceed 10,000 raccoons. The MV Senate publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking and the handling of raccoon latrines (which are a source of the parasitic roundworm Baylisascaris procyonis). Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl), on amphibians (European fire-bellied toad, yellow-bellied toad), on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) which the MV state forestry has been actively reintroducing in the Müritz area, and on the rare middle-spotted woodpecker. The MV state veterinary office maintains surveillance for Baylisascaris procyonis and for canine distemper virus.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, reached Mecklenburg-Vorpommern from the east in the 1980s; today the species is established throughout MV with the highest densities in the Müritz National Park, the Schaalsee Biosphere Reserve, the Vorpommerische Boddenlandschaft, the Usedom National Park and along the Polish border. Annual hunting bags exceed 15,000. The MV state veterinary office monitors for canine distemper, rabies and Echinococcus multilocularis.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the lower Warnow, the Recknitz, the Peene, the Trebel and the Mecklenburg Lake District. Damage to flood-protection dykes by burrowing is a serious management concern; the MV Wasser- und Bodenverbände coordinate trapping operations.

The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to MV but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced and spread back into the state from Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt and Polish populations since the 1990s; the MV beaver population is now growing rapidly with the highest densities in the Mecklenburg Lake District, the Müritz National Park, the Schaalsee Biosphere Reserve, the Trebel, the Recknitz and the Warnow.

The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs in slow water bodies throughout MV with particularly dense populations in the Mecklenburg Lake District, the Recknitz, the Peene and the Tollensesee area.

The American mink, Neovison vison, Amerikanischer Nerz, escaped from MV fur farms (the GDR era hosted several mink farms in the Lake District) and is now established in low densities along the Mecklenburg waterways and a serious threat to the European mink (Mustela lutreola) reintroduction plans.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised Mecklenburg-Vorpommern from Polish populations since around 2007 and the state now has the second-highest German wolf density after Saxony, with around 20 territorial packs spread across the Lübtheen, Müritz, Friedländer Wiese, Anklam, Penkun-Brüssow, Schorfheide-Chorin (border) and Rügen-Putbus areas. The MV state Lupus Office (Wolfsbeauftragter MV) coordinates monitoring.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations on the Müritz, the Plauer See, the Schweriner See and the Mecklenburg lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded rapidly from feral Dutch populations and now breeds throughout MV. The barnacle goose, Branta leucopsis, native breeder on the Arctic but historically only a winter visitor in MV, has established a small feral resident breeding population on Rügen since the 1990s. The greylag goose, Anser anser, native, has expanded substantially in recent decades. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is occasional in MV but has not established large breeding populations as in Heidelberg or Wiesbaden. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on MV park ponds. The wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on some MV hunting estates without establishing.

Among fish, the Baltic Sea and the inland waterways host introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish, Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch, is established in the gravel pits. The topmouth gudgeon, Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling, is widespread. The brown bullhead, Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels, occurs in old gravel pits. The rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, Regenbogenforelle, is stocked in the MV trout farms. The brook trout, Salvelinus fontinalis, Bachsaibling, is similarly stocked. The grass carp, Ctenopharyngodon idella, Graskarpfen, is used to control aquatic vegetation in MV lakes. The round goby, Neogobius melanostomus, Schwarzmaul-Grundel, native to the Black Sea, has reached MV from Polish coastal populations in the 2000s and is now abundant in the western Baltic and the Bodden lagoons.

In the marine and brackish Baltic and Bodden waters of MV, established invaders include the Pacific oyster (Magallana gigas, Pazifische Auster), expanding from the North Sea since around 2005 and now common in the western Baltic; the Asian shore crab (Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi), established on the Baltic since around 2010; the American razor clam (Ensis directus, Amerikanische Schwertmuschel); the Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum (Japanischer Beerentang); the Atlantic comb jelly (Mnemiopsis leidyi), originally from the western Atlantic, now common in the western Baltic and a major MV fisheries concern; and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe), regularly trapped in MV rivers. The Pontic shrimp Limnomysis benedeni and other Caspian-Pontic crustaceans have advanced into MV waters via the Oder-Spree-Warnow waterway connections. The North American Polychaete Marenzelleria has invaded the Baltic since the 1980s.

Invertebrate freshwater invaders include the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus, Signalkrebs, widespread in MV streams. The spinycheek crayfish, Faxonius limosus, Kamberkrebs, is the most common MV crayfish. The red swamp crayfish, Procambarus clarkii, Roter Sumpfkrebs, is recorded in MV gravel pits. The marbled crayfish, Procambarus virginalis, Marmorkrebs, occurs in scattered locations. The zebra mussel, Dreissena polymorpha, Dreikantmuschel, and the quagga mussel, Dreissena rostriformis bugensis, Quaggamuschel, are abundant in the MV lakes. The Asian clam, Corbicula fluminea, Körbchenmuschel, is in MV waterways. The New Zealand mud snail, Potamopyrgus antipodarum, is widespread.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has not yet been recorded as a self-sustaining population in MV as of 2024 but monitoring traps are deployed by the Imkerverband Mecklenburg-Vorpommern in cooperation with the federal Julius Kühn-Institut. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates MV chestnut avenues every late summer. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Schweriner Schloss, the Bad Doberan Münster gardens and various MV private gardens. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established in coastal MV.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, Beifußblättriges Traubenkraut) is widespread on MV railway lines, motorway verges and disturbed ground. Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, Japanknöterich) dominates banks of the Warnow, the Peene, the Recknitz and the Trebel. Bohemian knotweed (Reynoutria bohemica) and giant knotweed (Reynoutria sachalinensis) are also present. Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, Drüsiges Springkraut) is widespread on MV stream banks. Giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum, Riesen-Bärenklau) has been mapped in MV parks. Tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, Götterbaum) spreads along MV railway lines and brownfields. Goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea) dominates fallow fields. Small balsam (Impatiens parviflora) is widespread on MV park edges. Black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), planted historically in MV streets and on land-reclamation projects, has self-seeded into many disturbed habitats. The Senecio inaequidens (Schmalblättriges Greiskraut), the South African ragwort, is now established on MV railway lines and disturbed sandy ground. The cordgrass Spartina anglica has invaded the Wadden Sea analogue communities of the Bodden lagoons of MV. The lupine, Lupinus polyphyllus, garden lupin, dominates roadsides and railway embankments.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) have substantial populations in MV-area forestry reserves and hunting estates, particularly in the Mecklenburg Lake District and the Vorpommerische Boddenlandschaft. Mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) are present in smaller numbers. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Müritz and the Schaalsee Biosphere Reserve. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at high density in all MV forests, with annual hunting bags exceeding 50,000 statewide. African Swine Fever has not yet been confirmed in MV wild boar populations as of 2024, but the proximity to Polish outbreaks and the long border has required intensive biosecurity measures.'
WHERE region_name = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Niedersachsen, in English Lower Saxony, is the second-largest German federal state by area at 47,614 square kilometres and the fourth-largest by population with around 8 million inhabitants. The state stretches from the North Sea coast and the East Frisian Islands in the north-west, across the Lüneburger Heide and the lower Elbe valley, the Hannoversche Lößbörde plain in the centre, the Weser uplands in the south, to the Harz mountains in the south-east. Hannover is the state capital, while the other major cities include Braunschweig (Brunswick), Wolfsburg, Osnabrück, Oldenburg, Göttingen, Hildesheim, Lüneburg, Celle, Cuxhaven, Wilhelmshaven and Stade. The state was formed in 1946 from the historic Hannover, Brunswick, Oldenburg and Schaumburg-Lippe territories under British military government.

Hannover, the state capital, is centred on the Marktplatz with the Marktkirche St. Georgii et Jacobi (a Brick Gothic three-aisled hall church of 1366), the Altes Rathaus and the historic Leibniz Haus (the rebuilt home of the philosopher and mathematician Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who served as court librarian to the Hannover Electors and is buried in the Neustädter Hof- und Stadtkirche St. Johannis). The Neues Rathaus (the New Town Hall), opened 1913, is one of Hannover''s landmarks, with the curving Maschsee lake park in front and the famous inclined-elevator viewing platform inside the dome (the only inclined-shaft elevator in any town hall in the world, ascending the curved inner dome). The Herrenhäuser Gärten (Royal Gardens of Herrenhausen), one of the finest baroque gardens in Europe, were laid out from 1666 by Sophia of Hannover, the Princess Electress (and the mother of King George I of Great Britain via the 1701 Act of Settlement), with the Großer Garten featuring the world''s tallest garden fountain Großes Wasserspiel, the Hedge Theatre, the Marble Cascade, the Galerie Building and the Schloss Herrenhausen Palace (reconstructed in 2013 by Hannover-born architect Jens Reinhardt-Tjarks based on the original Remy de la Fosse drawings); the Berggarten with its Tropical House, Cactus House and Sea Palm House; the Georgengarten with the Welfenschloss (the main building of the Leibniz Universität Hannover); and the Wallmodengarten with the Wallmodenhaus. The Maschsee, a 78-hectare artificial lake created in the 1930s for recreation, hosts swimming, sailing and the Maschsee Festival every summer; the Eilenriede, at 660 hectares one of the largest urban forests in Germany; the Hannover Zoo at the Eilenriede with the Yukon Bay, Jungle Palace and Mullewapp themed worlds; and the Sprengel Museum Hannover for 20th-century art (containing the Kurt Schwitters collection, the Niki de Saint Phalle Nanas collection and the Picasso Museum) complete the city offer. The Sprengel Museum also houses the Lower Saxony State Museum (Niedersächsisches Landesmuseum), the Wilhelm Busch Museum (the German Museum of Caricature and Drawing Art) and the Kestner-Museum.

Braunschweig (Brunswick), the historic ducal residence of the Welf dynasty, is dominated by the Burgplatz with the Burg Dankwarderode (the recreated Welf castle of Henry the Lion), the Lion of Brunswick (the famous bronze lion monument of 1166 erected by Henry the Lion himself, the second-oldest surviving large bronze monument north of the Alps after the Bamberger Reiter), the Braunschweiger Dom St. Blasii (the cathedral of 1188, containing the tombs of Henry the Lion and his English wife Mathilde, daughter of King Henry II of England), the historic Altstadtmarkt with its Renaissance Old Town Hall (a Brick Gothic building of 1393), the Magniviertel with the Magnikirche, the Andreaskirche, the Aegidienmarkt with the Aegidienkirche, the Schloss Braunschweig (the rebuilt classical-style ducal palace of 1841, with the famous Quadriga statue atop the entrance, recreated in 2007 after wartime destruction), the Herzog Anton Ulrich-Museum (the second-oldest German art museum founded 1754, with the famous Vermeer Girl with the Wine Glass and a Rembrandt collection), and the Landesmuseum für Braunschweig''s history. Wolfsburg, just east of Braunschweig, is the headquarters of Volkswagen and home to the Autostadt (the VW corporate visitor centre with car museums covering all VW Group brands, the Porsche Museum-East collection, the new-car-delivery KundenCenter and the Phaeno science museum by Zaha Hadid).

Hildesheim is famous for its UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1985) of the Dom St. Mariä Himmelfahrt cathedral with the Thousand-Year Rose-Tree on its apse (a wild dog-rose, Rosa canina, dating from before 815), the Bronze Doors of Bishop Bernward of 1015 (Bernwardstür, the earliest surviving bronze doors with biblical narrative scenes in medieval Europe), the Christussäule bronze column of 1010 modelled on Trajan''s Column in Rome, and the historic Hildesheim treasury; plus the parallel UNESCO-inscribed St. Michael''s Church (St. Michaeliskirche) of 1010-1033 founded by Bishop Bernward, one of the most beautiful Ottonian churches in Europe with its carved wooden ceiling.

Göttingen is the most famous university town of Niedersachsen, with the Georg-August-Universität Göttingen (founded 1734 by King George II of Great Britain and the Elector of Hannover) at the heart of the city; the historic Universitätsbibliothek (with the Gutenberg Bible, the Codex Sinaiticus fragments and many other rarities), the Aula auditorium, the Auditorium Maximum, the historic Maths Faculty and Physics Faculty buildings, the Botanischer Garten Göttingen and the Albani-Kirche all reflect the academic core. The Göttingen Gänseliesel statue (the Goose-Girl fountain on the Marktplatz, which traditionally is kissed by every newly minted Göttingen doctoral graduate) is the city''s emblem. Famous Göttingen alumni include Carl Friedrich Gauss, Bernhard Riemann, David Hilbert, Felix Klein, Max Born, James Franck, the Brothers Grimm (briefly), Otto Hahn, Werner Heisenberg, Robert Koch, Wolfgang Borchert and many others; the Mathematical Society of Göttingen produced more Nobel laureates per capita than almost any institution in history.

Lüneburg, the medieval salt city, was the principal salt-producing centre of the Hanseatic League and is one of the most intact medieval town centres in northern Germany; the salt-saturated soil has caused some buildings to lean dramatically. The Marktplatz with the Town Hall and the famous baroque-style Stintmarkt riverside, the St. Johanniskirche, the St. Michaeliskirche, the Lüneburg Stadtsalzhütte and the Deutsches Salzmuseum (the German Salt Museum in the former salt-saline factory) document the city''s heritage. The Lüneburger Heide, the Lüneburg Heath, is the great open landscape south of the city, the largest connected heathland in Central Europe, characterised by Heidekraut (Calluna vulgaris) heather, juniper, birch and the Heidschnucken (a heath-grazing sheep breed). The Wilseder Berg, at 169 metres, is the highest point of the heath; the Pietzmoor, the Schneverdinger Heide, the Bispingen Heide and the Hochmoor Pietzmoor are popular hiking destinations. The Heidschnucken Schnucken-Sheep grazing season (Heideblüte) in August transforms the heath into a sea of purple bloom.

Celle, on the Aller river, is one of the most beautiful Renaissance towns in northern Germany, with around 400 half-timbered houses from the 16th and 17th centuries; the Schloss Celle (the historic ducal residence of the Brunswick-Lüneburg dukes), the Schlosskapelle (the rare Calvinist court chapel of 1485), the Stechinelli-Haus, the Französischer Garten and the historic Latin School complete the town. Hameln (Hamelin) on the Weser is famous for the legend of the Pied Piper of Hamelin (Rattenfänger von Hameln), commemorated by the Glockenspiel on the Hochzeitshaus (Wedding House) and the daily Pied Piper play in summer. The town also has the famous Rattenfängerhaus and the Bürgerhus, both Weser-Renaissance buildings.

Goslar, in the Harz, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1992) for the historic Old Town and the Rammelsberg mine (the world''s only mine in continuous operation for over a thousand years from 968 to 1988). The Kaiserpfalz of Goslar (the Imperial Palace) was the residence of the Holy Roman Emperors from 1050 onwards, and the great hall (Kaisersaal) hosted important imperial diets; the historic Marktplatz with the Markt Church and the Brunnen of Bügelfontäne; the Mönchehaus Museum of contemporary art; and the Domvorhalle (the last remaining piece of the demolished Goslarer Dom) complete the city. The Harz mountains, with the Brocken (the highest peak at 1141 metres, technically in Sachsen-Anhalt), the Harzer Schmalspurbahn steam railway network, the Wernigerode and Quedlinburg medieval old towns (the latter in Sachsen-Anhalt), the Okertal and the Bodetal valleys, the Harzer Wanderwege, and the Brockenbahn (the steam-powered cog railway to the Brocken summit) make the Harz one of the most-visited middle-mountain ranges in Germany. The Harz National Park covers the highest parts.

The North Sea coast and the East Frisian Islands offer another distinctive tourist landscape. The Wattenmeer (Wadden Sea) National Park, declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2009 (jointly with the Dutch and Danish Wadden Seas), is the world''s largest unbroken system of intertidal sand and mud flats, covering 11,500 square kilometres. The seven East Frisian Islands — Borkum, Juist, Norderney, Baltrum, Langeoog, Spiekeroog and Wangerooge — are car-free (mostly) seaside resorts famous for their bracing North Sea climate (used for the Hochseeklima air-therapy resort tradition), their dunes, their lighthouse landmarks and their cycling-only main streets. Each island has its own personality: Borkum, the largest, is reached by ferry from Emden; Juist, the longest at 17 kilometres, is car-free since 1882; Norderney, the most populous, has the historic Conversationshaus casino; Baltrum, the smallest, has just one village; Langeoog has the highest dunes; Spiekeroog has the historic Frisian island church Inselkirche; Wangerooge, the eastern-most, is reached by ferry from Harlesiel. Cuxhaven, on the North Sea coast, is the largest German seaside resort with the Kugelbake (the iconic wooden navigation mark), the Wattenmeer-Strandhalle and the SeeKuh ferry to Helgoland.

Cuisine and beverages of Niedersachsen are distinctive. Birnen, Bohnen und Speck (pears, beans and bacon, the classic North-German autumn dish), Grünkohl mit Pinkel (kale with Pinkel sausage, traditionally eaten on Kohlfahrt winter walking outings with bottles of Schnapps), Heidschnucken-Braten (roast Lüneburg Heath sheep, the speciality of the Heath restaurants), Bauernfrühstück (peasant''s breakfast of fried potatoes with bacon, onion and egg), Buttergebäck, Hannoversche Schweinsohren puff pastry, Borgholzhauser Pumpernickel (the dense Westphalian rye bread, although technically also at the borders), Bohnenkraut savory, Spargel (asparagus from the Lüneburger Heide), the Pinkel sausage of Bremen/Oldenburg, the Bückling smoked herring, the Lüneburger Schinken, the Holzofenbrot bread, the Niedersächsische Buchweizenpfannkuchen buckwheat pancakes, and the historic Hannoversche Fürst-Pückler-Eis layered ice-cream (created in Hannover by Fürst Pückler-Muskau). Honey from the Lüneburger Heide (Heideblüten-Honig) is a regional specialty. Friesentee, the Frisian tea ceremony, is performed at countless tea-houses across East Frisia with crumbled rock-sugar, cream and strong black tea (the famous Bünting Tee, Onno Behrends, J. Bünting, Friesische Mischung, Ostfriesische Mischung); East Frisia has the highest per-capita tea consumption in Europe (around 300 litres per person per year, exceeding even the UK). Pharisäer, the joke coffee with rum and whipped cream, is a North-Sea coast specialty. Lüttje Lage, the Hannover ritual of beer + grain-spirit shot served in a paired glass, is a tradition at the historic Hannoversche Volksfeste. Steinhäger, the protected-name juniper-spirit gin from Steinhagen (technically in NRW), is widely consumed. Braunschweiger Mumme, the historic dark malty drink of Braunschweig, is enjoying a revival; the Braunschweiger Stadt-Schoppen and Wolters Brauerei in Braunschweig complete the regional beer culture. Major NDS breweries include Einbecker Brauhaus (Einbeck, the world''s oldest Bock beer at over 600 years old, the historic source of all Bock-style beers), Allersheimer (Holzminden), Härke (Peine), Hövels (Dortmund but commonly drunk), and Jever Pilsner (in Friesland). The historic Wittinger Pilsener, the Brauhaus Gildenhaus, the Brauhaus Schaper, and the Maschseebrauerei complete the Hannover-area brewing scene.

History before 1933 is rich. The original Saxon homeland (Sachsen, the historic ethnic Saxons later partly transferred to the Saxony region) was Christianised by Charlemagne in his Saxon Wars (772-804). The Welf dynasty under Henry the Lion ruled vast lands. The Hannover Electors became also Kings of Great Britain and Ireland through the Personal Union of 1714 (King George I), continuing until 1837 when Queen Victoria succeeded; the Hannoverian Welf dynasty thus profoundly shaped British history. After Napoleon, the Kingdom of Hannover was created in 1814; the Brunswick duchy and Oldenburg grand duchy persisted alongside. The 1866 Austro-Prussian War led to the Prussian annexation of Hannover. After 1918 the Weimar Republic preserved both Free State Brunswick and Free State Hannover. After 1945 the British zone formed the new Land Niedersachsen on 1 November 1946 from Hannover, Brunswick, Oldenburg and Schaumburg-Lippe. Famous figures from Niedersachsen include Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (Leipzig-born but Hannover-resident), Carl Friedrich Gauss (Brunswick), August Heinrich Hoffmann von Fallersleben (the writer of Deutschlandlied, born in Fallersleben near Wolfsburg), Wilhelm Busch (Wiedensahl, Niedersachsen, the creator of Max und Moritz), the Brothers Grimm (Hanau and Marburg in Hessen, but Göttingen professors), Otto Hahn (Frankfurt-born, but Göttingen Nobel laureate), Robert Koch (Clausthal-Zellerfeld, Niedersachsen), Carl Bosch (Cologne but Göttingen-trained chemist), and the post-war Federal Chancellor Gerhard Schröder (born Mossenberg, Hessen, but a Niedersachsen political career).',
    transportation = 'Niedersachsen, occupying central northern Germany, is one of the most important transit territories of central Europe, with the Hamburg-Cologne, Hamburg-Frankfurt and Berlin-Ruhr motorway and rail corridors all crossing the state. Hannover-Langenhagen Airport, IATA HAJ and ICAO EDDV, is the sixth-busiest airport in Germany, handling around 5-6 million passengers per year, with operations by Lufthansa, Eurowings, easyJet, Condor, Turkish Airlines, TUI fly, SunExpress, Sun Country, Wizz Air and a wide range of leisure carriers. The airport, located 11 kilometres north of Hannover, is connected by the S-Bahn line S5 to Hannover Hauptbahnhof in 17 minutes and by the A352 motorway from the city. Other commercial airports in Niedersachsen include Braunschweig-Wolfsburg (BWE, used by VW corporate aviation and seasonal Mediterranean flights), Hannover-Wunstorf (the historic Bundeswehr air-base, also home to the German Air-Lift Group), Bremen-Stade (technically in Niedersachsen serving Hamburg satellite traffic), Osnabrück (the small Osnabrück-Münster Airport (FMO) is technically in Münster in NRW but serves Osnabrück), Friesland Eichwege (small), Wangerooge, Norderney, Juist, Borkum and Langeoog (the East Frisian island airfields).

The Niedersachsen rail network is dense and dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Fernverkehr (ICE, IC) and DB Regio Nord/Niedersachsen, with the regional brands metronom Eisenbahngesellschaft (the orange ME long-distance regional service from Hamburg via Hannover to Göttingen-Uelzen-Lüneburg), enno (the regional EMU operator), erixx (Lüneburger Heide), Westfalenbahn, Westerwaldbahn, Nordwestbahn (NWB), Eurobahn and the Niedersachsen Verkehrsverbund GmbH (NVG) coordinating regional services. Hannover Hauptbahnhof, opened 1879 with the magnificent neo-renaissance facade, is one of the busiest German railway stations with around 250,000 passengers per day across 12 platforms. It is the focal point of the Berlin-Hannover-Köln/Frankfurt-Munich corridors (ICE 10, ICE 11, ICE 25, ICE 26, ICE 41, ICE 71, ICE 91), the Berlin-Hannover NBS (the 1998-opened 250 kph high-speed line shortening the Berlin-Hannover travel time to 100 minutes), the Hannover-Würzburg NBS (1991-opened, the first NBS in Germany), the Hannover-Hamburg corridor (electrified 1968, currently being upgraded to 230 kph) and the Hannover-Köln-Aachen and Hannover-Köln-Brussels Thalys/Eurostar services. Other major NDS rail nodes include Braunschweig Hauptbahnhof, Wolfsburg, Osnabrück Hauptbahnhof, Oldenburg Hauptbahnhof, Bremen-Burg, Göttingen, Hildesheim, Hameln, Celle, Uelzen, Lüneburg, Verden (Aller), Stade, Cuxhaven and Bad Bentheim (Dutch border).

The Niedersachsen S-Bahn Hannover, operated by Transdev (formerly the Connex-affiliated Hannover S-Bahn), has eight lines (S1, S2, S3, S4, S5, S6, S7, S8) totalling 385 kilometres and around 100 stations, reaching into Hildesheim, Hameln and Celle, with the central Hannover Hauptbahnhof and the historic Großer Bahnhof junction. The Hannover Stadtbahn, operated by üstra (Hannoversche Verkehrsbetriebe), is a converted tramway with both surface and tunnel running, with 12 lines totalling 121 kilometres and around 220 stations; the central tunnel network under the Kröpcke and Aegi forms the spine, and the lines reach to Hemmingen, Sarstedt, Misburg, Kirchrode, Laatzen and Garbsen. The Hannoversche Verkehrsbetriebe operates the U-Stadtbahn, the bus network and the Maschsee ferries. The üstra Stadtbahn is one of the most extensive in Germany. The Braunschweig tram (Braunschweiger Verkehrs-GmbH) has five lines; Oldenburg, Osnabrück, Göttingen and Lüneburg lack trams but plan returns. The GVH Großraum-Verkehr Hannover, the VBN Verkehrsverbund Bremen-Niedersachsen, the VRBN Region Braunschweig, the VOS Osnabrück, the VEJ Jadeoldenburg and the VGE Göttingen complete the integrated-tariff network.

The ICE network through Niedersachsen includes the Hannover-Berlin NBS (opened 1998, 250 kph), the Hannover-Würzburg NBS (1991, 280 kph, 63 tunnels), the Hannover-Hamburg corridor (currently upgraded to 230 kph), the Hannover-Köln corridor (the historic Cologne-Hannover line currently being upgraded), and the new Wolfsburg Süd ICE-Bahnhof opened 1998 on the Berlin-Hannover NBS. The Hannover-Hamburg route is one of the busiest German ICE corridors with up to four trains per hour. The Hannover-Bremen route runs at 200 kph. The Hannover-Köln-Brussels Eurostar services via Aachen and the Brussels-Midi terminal complete the western corridor; the planned Brussels-Aachen-Düsseldorf-Köln-Hannover-Berlin Trans-European high-speed corridor would substantially upgrade this if realised.

The Autobahn network in Niedersachsen includes the A1 (Heiligenhafen-Hamburg-Köln-Saarbrücken via Lüneburg, Bremen, Osnabrück, Dortmund), the A2 (Hannover-Berlin-Świebodzin, the historic Mittellandlinie connecting the Ruhrgebiet to Berlin), the A7 (the longest motorway in Europe at 963 kilometres, Flensburg-Hamburg-Hannover-Würzburg-Memmingen), the A8 connection, the A26 from Hamburg, the A27 from Bremen via Verden to Walsrode, the A28 from Bremen to Leer-Emden, the A29 from Oldenburg to Wilhelmshaven, the A31 (the Emsland-Autobahn from Bottrop-Emden), the A33 (Osnabrück-Bielefeld), the A39 (Wolfsburg-Lüneburg, partly under construction), the A352 connecting Hannover Airport to the A2, the A352, the A38 (Göttingen-Halle), the A395 (Wolfsburg-Goslar) and the A39/A40 connections. The Hannover Autobahnring with the south-eastern Magdeburger Tor section is one of Germany''s heaviest-traffic urban rings.

The North Sea ports include Wilhelmshaven (the JadeWeserPort, Germany''s only deep-water container port, opened 2012, capable of handling the world''s largest container ships of the OOCL Hong Kong and HMM Algeciras class with 23,000+ TEU capacity), Cuxhaven (mass cargo and cruise traffic, with the Cuxhavener Hafenbahn), Emden (the largest German automotive Port handling Volkswagen exports), Brake (lower Weser), Nordenham (lower Weser), Stade (lower Elbe, with the Stade Steelwind foundation works), Leer (Ems), Papenburg (Ems, with the Meyer Werft cruise-ship shipyard) and Wangerooge (East Frisian island). The Mittellandkanal, the longest German artificial waterway at 326 kilometres, connects the Rhine via the Dortmund-Ems-Kanal to the Elbe via Magdeburg, with intermediate links to the Weser at Minden and the Hannover-Linden harbour. The Weser, the Aller, the Leine, the Ems, the Hunte and the Vechte are navigable inland waterways. The Hindenburgdamm is technically in Schleswig-Holstein.

Long-distance cycling routes are extensive: the Elberadweg (a top German long-distance cycling route from the Czech border via Hamburg to Cuxhaven), the Weser-Radweg (Hann. Münden-Cuxhaven), the Aller-Radweg, the Leine-Radweg, the Ems-Radweg (the Emsland route), the Mittelland-Radweg, the Hannover-Münster-Radweg, the Nordseeküsten-Radweg (the German section of the EuroVelo 12 North Sea Cycle Route from Cuxhaven via Bremerhaven, Wilhelmshaven and Emden to the Dutch border), and the EuroVelo 15 (Rhine Cycle Route). The Mittellandkanal-Radweg parallels the artificial waterway.',
    economics = 'Niedersachsen has the fourth-largest regional GDP among the German Bundesländer at around 350 billion euros, dominated by the automotive industry (Volkswagen Group at Wolfsburg, Hannover, Salzgitter, Emden, Braunschweig and Osnabrück), by aerospace and aviation (Premium Aerotec, Airbus Helicopters), by chemicals and pharmaceuticals (Boehringer Ingelheim Wilhelmshaven, Roche), by tourism (the third-largest German tourism state by overnight stays), by agriculture (the largest German agricultural state by gross value added), by trade fair business (Deutsche Messe AG with the Hannover Messe, the world''s largest industrial trade fair), and by the offshore-wind industry. The Wirtschaftsförderung Niedersachsen at Hannover and the Niedersachsen-Förderagentur market the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Hannover, the IHK Braunschweig, the IHK Lüneburg-Wolfsburg, the IHK Osnabrück-Emsland-Grafschaft Bentheim and the IHK Oldenburgische represent regional businesses.

Volkswagen AG, headquartered at Wolfsburg since the founding of the city in 1938, is by far the largest single employer in Niedersachsen and one of the largest manufacturers in the world. The Volkswagen Plant Wolfsburg, on the 6.5-square-kilometre Wolfsburg main site, is the largest single car plant in the world by area and employs around 60,000 workers; it produces the Volkswagen Golf, the Volkswagen Tiguan and the Volkswagen Touran. Volkswagen Plant Hannover-Stöcken produces the Volkswagen Transporter T7 and the Volkswagen Multivan (with the ID. Buzz electric VW); Volkswagen Plant Emden produces the Volkswagen Passat, the Volkswagen Arteon and the ID.7 electric saloon; Volkswagen Plant Salzgitter produces engines and battery cells (with the new PowerCo battery-cell factory under construction); Volkswagen Plant Braunschweig produces battery systems, electric drive units and chassis parts for the entire VW Group; Volkswagen Plant Osnabrück produces the Volkswagen T-Roc Cabriolet and Porsche Cayman bodies (the latter as a contract manufacturer for Porsche). Volkswagen Group has its German production fully concentrated in Niedersachsen, with the parallel plants in Saxony (Zwickau, Chemnitz, Dresden), Hesse (Kassel-Baunatal), Saarland (Saarlouis is Ford, not VW) and the Stuttgart Audi/Porsche operations. The Audi Brussels and the Porsche Zuffenhausen-Stuttgart plants supplement the VW group production. Volkswagen Financial Services AG, Volkswagen Commercial Vehicles, Volkswagen Truck & Bus (now part of Traton SE), Audi AG (technically Ingolstadt-headquartered but VW-owned), SEAT, Škoda, Lamborghini, Bentley and Bugatti are all VW Group brands. Volkswagen had its 2015 Dieselgate emissions-cheating scandal that resulted in around 35 billion euros of fines, recall costs and settlement payments globally; the company has since pivoted to electric vehicles with the ID. family on the new MEB platform and the Cariad software-house subsidiary.

TUI AG, the world''s largest leisure travel group by revenue, has its corporate headquarters at the TUI Campus at Karl-Wiechert-Allee in Hannover. TUI Group, with annual revenues of around 16 billion euros, operates the TUI Cruises (jointly with Royal Caribbean), the Marella Cruises, the Hapag-Lloyd Cruises, the TUI fly airlines (German, Belgian, Dutch, UK), the TUI Hotels & Resorts including the Robinson Club, the Magic Life and the TUI Blue brand, and the TUI travel-agency network. TUI Group serves around 20 million tourists per year and employs around 60,000 people. The Continental AG, the listed Hannover-headquartered tyre and automotive-supplier giant, has annual revenues of around 40 billion euros and is one of the largest German automotive suppliers; the Continental tyre brands (Continental, Uniroyal, Semperit, General Tire, Barum) and the ContiTech rubber-products division and the Continental Automotive electronics-and-systems division complete the company. Vitesco Technologies, the powertrain spin-off from Continental in 2021, is headquartered at Hannover (and Regensburg). Sennheiser electronic GmbH & Co. KG, the family-owned audio-equipment maker founded 1945 by Fritz Sennheiser at the Wennebostel village in the district of Wedemark near Hannover, is one of the world''s leading microphone and headphone manufacturers (with brands including Sennheiser, Neumann.Berlin and the Sennheiser MOMENTUM consumer range). Sennheiser still has its corporate headquarters at Wennebostel, and the iconic blue-and-white Sennheiser logo is a Wennebostel landmark.

Salzgitter AG, the listed Salzgitter-headquartered steel and engineering group, is the second-largest German steel producer after thyssenkrupp Steel Europe of Duisburg. Salzgitter has the integrated steelworks at Salzgitter (producing around 6 million tonnes of steel per year), the Mannesmann tube subsidiary at Mülheim (NRW), the KHS bottling and packaging machine subsidiary, the Salzgitter Mannesmann Stahlhandel trading business, and the Salzgitter Mannesmann Forschung research arm. Salzgitter is pioneering the green-steel transformation with the SALCOS programme of direct-reduction iron production using hydrogen at the Salzgitter integrated works.

Bahlsen GmbH & Co. KG, the family-owned biscuit-and-confectionery maker founded 1889 in Hannover by Hermann Bahlsen, is one of the largest German confectionery makers. Bahlsen produces the iconic Leibniz biscuit (the 52-tooth Butterkeks, named after the Hannover philosopher Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz), the Pick-Up wafer, the Choco Leibniz, the Hit and the Bahlsen Brandy Snaps. Bahlsen has the original biscuit factory still in Hannover-List. Other Hannover-area food companies include Aurora Mühlen (the Aurora flour brand), Hannoversche Lebensversicherung, Mosaik Holzwerkstoffe and the historic Niedersächsische Spirituosen-Manufaktur for Korn distilled spirits.

The Hannover Messe, operated by Deutsche Messe AG, is the world''s largest industrial trade fair, with around 100,000 exhibitors and 500,000 visitors in normal years; the CeBIT (the world''s largest IT trade fair) ran in Hannover from 1986 to 2018; the Agritechnica, the world''s largest agricultural-machinery fair; the EuroTier livestock-equipment fair; the IAA Mobility ran in Hannover from 1961 to 2019 before moving to Munich; the Hannover Light Festival; and the Hannover Trade and Industry Fair complete the trade-fair complex on the 466,100-square-metre Messe Hannover grounds. The trade-fair industry is the second-largest after Frankfurt''s Messe Frankfurt in Germany.

Meyer Werft GmbH & Co. KG at Papenburg on the Ems, one of the largest cruise-ship builders in the world, builds the largest cruise ships afloat — including the Norwegian Joy, the Disney Wish, the AIDA series, the World Dream, the Mein Schiff series and most of the Royal Caribbean cruise vessels. Meyer Werft has been at Papenburg since 1795; the famous transit of the new cruise ships through the narrow Ems river to the Eemshaven (Netherlands) for outfitting is a major tourist event. The Meyer Werft is one of the most modern shipyards in the world with the world''s largest dry docks at Papenburg.

Premium Aerotec GmbH, the Airbus aerospace subsidiary, has plants at Nordenham (lower Weser, producing the Airbus A350 and A380 large fuselage sections), at Bremen (technically in Bremen state but with Niedersachsen logistical ties) and at Augsburg. Airbus Helicopters Donauwörth (in Bavaria) but with Niedersachsen-Munich supply chain. The Lower Saxony aerospace cluster includes the historic Stade Carbon Composites Center, the CFK Valley Stade and the Airbus A350 lower-fuselage plant at Stade. The Stade industry park includes Dow Chemical Stade and Aluminium Norf. The Bundeswehr Naval Base Wilhelmshaven hosts the German Federal Navy headquarters and the Marine-Arsenal.

EWE AG, the Oldenburg-headquartered regional utility (energy, telecom, IT services), is one of the largest German municipal-owned utilities, with around 9,000 employees and operations in Lower Saxony, Brandenburg, Bremen and Poland. EWE invests heavily in the offshore-wind and green-hydrogen transformation. The Niedersachsen offshore-wind hub at Wilhelmshaven, Emden and Cuxhaven hosts the JadeWeserPort, the Cuxhaven Siemens Gamesa nacelle and blade plant (the largest German offshore-wind nacelle factory), the Cuxhaven Steelwind Nordenham foundation works, the Senvion (formerly REpower) Bremerhaven plant (now under restructuring), and the Wilhelmshaven Energy Hub for green hydrogen.

Other major NDS employers include Bombardier (now Alstom) at Wolfsburg-Salzgitter (rail vehicles), Boehringer Ingelheim Vetmedica Wilhelmshaven (the animal-health subsidiary), Sartorius AG at Göttingen (the listed biotech-equipment maker, one of the fastest-growing German DAX 40 companies with annual revenues around 3.5 billion euros), Symrise AG at Holzminden (the listed flavours-and-fragrances company, the third-largest in the world after Givaudan and Firmenich), Brötje Heating (Brötje Wärmetechnik), Wolters Brauerei, Holzbau Hörmann Brockhagen and the JadeWeserPort logistics cluster.

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Leibniz Universität Hannover, the Technische Universität Braunschweig, the Georg-August-Universität Göttingen, the Carl von Ossietzky Universität Oldenburg, the Universität Osnabrück, the Universität Hildesheim, the Universität Lüneburg, the Leuphana University, the Hochschule Hannover, the Tierärztliche Hochschule Hannover, the Hochschule Niedersachsen für angewandte Wissenschaften and many other higher-education institutions employ tens of thousands of researchers and educate over 250,000 students. The Max-Planck-Institut für Sonnensystemforschung at Göttingen, the Max-Planck-Institut für Dynamik und Selbstorganisation at Göttingen, the Max-Planck-Institut für biophysikalische Chemie (Karl Friedrich Bonhoeffer Institute, Göttingen), the Max-Planck-Institut für Experimentelle Medizin Göttingen, the Max-Planck-Institut für Multidisziplinäre Naturwissenschaften, the Max-Planck-Institut für Marine Mikrobiologie at Bremen (Bremen state), the Helmholtz-Zentrum für Infektionsforschung at Braunschweig and the Deutsches Krebsforschungszentrum Hannover form a major research cluster. The Volkswagen Foundation (VolkswagenStiftung), the largest German private research-funding foundation, is headquartered at Hannover.',
    introduced_species = 'Niedersachsen, the second-largest German federal state by area and a key central-corridor connecting western and eastern German invasive-species ranges, hosts a comprehensive roster of introduced and invasive species. The Niedersächsisches Landesamt für Verbraucherschutz und Lebensmittelsicherheit (LAVES) and the Niedersächsisches Ministerium für Umwelt, Energie, Bauen und Klimaschutz coordinate the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Niedersachsen since the 1950s when individuals from the Hessian Edersee 1934 release expanded north and west. Today the species is established throughout Niedersachsen with the highest densities in the Harz, the Solling, the Reinhardswald (technically Hessen-Niedersachsen border), the Weserbergland, the Wendland and increasingly in the suburban Hannover, Braunschweig, Wolfsburg and Osnabrück areas. The Lüneburger Heide and the lower Elbe wetlands have substantial populations. Annual hunting bags in Niedersachsen exceed 35,000 raccoons, the second-highest of any German state after Brandenburg. The LAVES publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the handling of raccoon latrines (which are a source of the parasitic roundworm Baylisascaris procyonis). Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds, on amphibians, on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis), on the rare middle-spotted woodpecker, on the recovering otter populations of the lower Elbe and on ground-nesting waterfowl in the Wadden Sea hinterland. The Niedersachsen state veterinary office monitors for Baylisascaris procyonis and for canine distemper virus.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Niedersachsen from the east in the 1990s and 2000s; today the species is established throughout Niedersachsen with the highest densities in the Wendland, the Lüneburger Heide, the Solling, the Harz Foreland and the Weserbergland. Annual hunting bags exceed 12,000.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the lower Weser, the Aller, the Leine, the Ems, the Hunte and the Lüneburger Heide watercourses. Damage to flood-protection dykes by burrowing is a serious management concern; the Niedersächsischer Landesbetrieb für Wasserwirtschaft, Küsten- und Naturschutz (NLWKN) and the Wasser- und Bodenverbände coordinate professional trapping operations. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Niedersachsen but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and the NLWKN and is now growing rapidly along the Elbe, the Weser, the Aller and the Leine. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Niedersachsen.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised Niedersachsen since 2007 and the state now has the third-highest German wolf population, with around 30 territorial packs spread across the Lüneburger Heide, the Wendland, the Bergen-Belsen military training area (a major wolf core area on the federal training ground south-west of Lüneburg), the Sachsenwald (technically Schleswig-Holstein) and the Wesergebirge. The Niedersachsen Wolves Office (Wolfsbüro NIE) at the NLWKN coordinates monitoring; the controversial population-management strategy involves licensed culling of confirmed livestock-predating individuals (so-called Problemwölfe).

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations along the Weser, the Elbe, the Aller and on the artificial lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded dramatically; Niedersachsen has substantial Egyptian goose populations particularly in the Hannover, Braunschweig, Wolfsburg and Oldenburg areas. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has small breeding populations in Hannover and Göttingen. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on park ponds. The wild turkey, Meleagris gallopavo, has been released on Niedersachsen hunting estates without establishing.

The Wadden Sea National Park hosts extensive marine and brackish invasions. The Pacific oyster, Magallana gigas, Pazifische Auster, originally introduced for aquaculture in the Wadden Sea by the Dutch and German oyster cooperatives in 1986, has expanded explosively across the entire Wadden Sea since around 2000 and is now ubiquitous on intertidal mudflats, replacing native blue mussels (Mytilus edulis) on many banks. The Pacific oyster is now an established part of the Wadden Sea ecosystem and supports a small but growing oyster-fishery off Sylt and the Niedersachsen coast. The American razor clam, Ensis directus, Amerikanische Schwertmuschel, present on the Wadden Sea since the 1979 storm transport from the Atlantic, is now the dominant clam on intertidal sand banks. The Asian shore crabs, Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi, established on the Wadden Sea since around 2000, are increasingly common on rocky shorelines. The Manila clam, Ruditapes philippinarum, the Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum (Japanischer Beerentang), the Atlantic comb jelly Mnemiopsis leidyi, and the New Zealand sea squirt Styela clava have all established. The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis, Chinesische Wollhandkrabbe, is regularly trapped in the Weser, the Elbe, the Aller, the Leine and the Lüneburger waterways.

Among freshwater fish, the pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus, Sonnenbarsch), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva, Blaubandbärbling), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus, Zwergwels), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) are all established. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis), the historic Hannoversche Eisvogel of the Aller and Leine, has been augmented by stocking.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea) and the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum). The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in Niedersachsen from 2021 onwards with confirmed nests near Hannover, Osnabrück and Göttingen. The harlequin ladybird, the horse-chestnut leaf miner, the box tree moth, the brown marmorated stink bug, and the spotted-wing drosophila Drosophila suzukii are all ubiquitous.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), and the South African Senecio inaequidens are widespread. The cordgrass Spartina anglica has invaded the Wadden Sea salt marshes substantially; the Sea-Buckthorn (Hippophae rhamnoides), although native to the East Frisian Islands, has been planted extensively on the mainland coast.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Solling, the Harz, the Lüneburger Heide and the Weserbergland. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations near Bückeburg and in the Harz. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density across the state, with annual hunting bags exceeding 70,000. African Swine Fever has not yet been confirmed in Niedersachsen wild boar populations.'
WHERE region_name = 'Niedersachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen, in English North Rhine-Westphalia (often abbreviated NRW), is the most populous German federal state with around 18 million inhabitants and the fourth-largest by area at 34,113 square kilometres. The state was formed on 23 August 1946 under British military government from the British zone provinces of the northern Rhineland and Westphalia, and from the small state of Lippe in 1947. NRW contains the densest concentration of major cities in Germany, including Cologne (Köln, the fourth-largest German city), Düsseldorf (the state capital and the seventh-largest German city), Dortmund, Essen, Duisburg, Bochum, Wuppertal, Bielefeld, Bonn, Münster, Mönchengladbach, Aachen, Solingen, Hagen, Hamm, Mülheim an der Ruhr, Krefeld, Leverkusen and Oberhausen.

Cologne (Köln), the historic Roman city of Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium founded in AD 50, is dominated by the Kölner Dom (Cologne Cathedral), one of the most famous Gothic cathedrals in the world and a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1996. Begun in 1248 and finally completed in 1880, the cathedral has the second-tallest church towers in the world (157 metres, after Ulm at 161 metres), the largest Gothic facade ever built, and houses the Shrine of the Three Kings (Dreikönigsschrein) of 1190 by Nicholas of Verdun — the largest reliquary in the Western world, said to contain the bones of the Three Magi brought to Cologne from Milan in 1164. Climbing the 533 steps of the south tower offers a panoramic view of the Rhine. Across the Hohenzollernbrücke railway bridge with its thousands of love padlocks, the Deutzer Brücke and the Severinsbrücke link the cathedral district to the right-bank Deutz quarter. The other twelve Romanesque churches of Cologne (the so-called Romanische Kirchen, including Groß St. Martin opposite the cathedral with the famous brick massive crossing tower, St. Gereon with its decagonal Roman-Romanesque rotunda, St. Aposteln, St. Maria im Kapitol, St. Pantaleon, St. Severin, St. Andreas, St. Ursula with its Goldene Kammer of relics, St. Maria Lyskirchen, St. Cäcilien with the Schnütgen-Museum, Großen-St.-Martin and St. Kunibert) form the so-called Sacred Crown of Cologne. The Roman-Germanic Museum (Römisch-Germanisches Museum) preserves the Dionysian Mosaic of Cologne and the largest collection of Roman glass in the world. The Museum Ludwig holds one of the world''s largest collections of Pop Art (the Ludwig collection of Roy Lichtenstein, Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg, Andy Warhol — including the famous Two Maos), Picasso (the third-largest Picasso collection in the world after the Musée Picasso in Paris and the Picasso Museum in Barcelona) and German Expressionism. The Wallraf-Richartz-Museum holds medieval and early-modern European painting (Stefan Lochner''s Madonna of the Rose Bower, the Cranachs, Rubens, Rembrandt, the Cologne School). The Schokoladenmuseum (Chocolate Museum) by Imhoff Group on the Rheinauhafen (with the working Lindt chocolate fountain), the Käthe Kollwitz Museum, the Diözesanmuseum Kolumba (by Peter Zumthor on the ruins of the bombed St. Kolumba), the Museum Schnütgen for medieval art, the Rautenstrauch-Joest-Museum of world cultures, the Museum für Angewandte Kunst, and the historic Senfmuseum mustard museum complete the museum offer. The Cologne Carnival (Karneval), Germany''s third-largest carnival celebration after Mainz''s and Rio''s, runs from 11 November to Ash Wednesday with the Rosenmontag procession (Shrove Monday parade) attracting up to one million spectators on the streets. The Cologne LGBT culture, the largest in Germany, hosts the Christopher Street Day parade. The Hohenzollernring promenade, the Belgisches Viertel with its bars, the Ehrenfeld district, the Mülheimer Brücke and the Rheinpark on the right bank all contribute to the urban offer.

Düsseldorf, the state capital, lies on the Rhine just downstream from Cologne. The Königsallee (the so-called Kö), the elegant shopping promenade with its central canal lined with chestnut trees, hosts the high-end boutiques (Hermès, Cartier, Louis Vuitton, Tiffany, Prada, the Kö-Galerie shopping centre). The Düsseldorfer Altstadt (the Old Town), known as "the longest bar in the world" for its 260 bars, pubs and restaurants concentrated in less than a square kilometre, is the centre of Düsseldorf nightlife. The Marktplatz with the equestrian Statue of Jan Wellem and the Rathaus, the Bolkerstraße (where Heinrich Heine was born), the Schneider-Wibbel-Gasse with the famous Schneider-Wibbel automaton clock, and the Heinrich-Heine-Geburtshaus complete the historic centre. The Carlstadt district, the Schloss Benrath baroque palace by Nicolas de Pigage (built 1755-1773 for Elector Karl Theodor as a hunting lodge), the Medienhafen with the Frank Gehry-designed Neuer Zollhof buildings, the Kunstpalast (the new museum complex with the Düsseldorfer Schule painters and the Galerie der Gegenwart), the Kunstsammlung Nordrhein-Westfalen (K20 and K21, the latter in the historic Ständehaus on the Kaiserteich, with the major Paul Klee collection of 96 works), the Museum Kunstpalast, the Rhein-Tower (240 metres) and the EKO-Haus of the Japanese Cultural Centre (Düsseldorf has the third-largest Japanese community in Europe with around 7,000 residents and the famous Japan Day) round out the city. The Düsseldorfer Karneval, with its Rosenmontagszug, rivals Cologne''s. The legendary Fortuna Düsseldorf football club plays at the Merkur Spiel-Arena.

Aachen, in the far west on the Belgian and Dutch borders, was the capital of the Carolingian Empire under Charlemagne and is one of the most historically significant cities in Germany. The Aachener Dom (Aachen Cathedral), the first German UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1978), was built by Charlemagne between 793 and 813 as his Palatine Chapel, the architectural manifesto of Carolingian Renaissance modelled on the imperial Hagia Sophia in Constantinople and Justinian''s Holy Sepulchre. The octagonal Palatine Chapel contains Charlemagne''s throne (the Aachener Königsthron, on which 30 German kings were crowned between Otto I in 936 and Ferdinand I in 1531), Charlemagne''s tomb (the Karlsschrein), the Pala d''Oro and the Barbarossaleuchter chandelier given by Frederick Barbarossa. The Aachener Rathaus (the medieval town hall, built 1330 over the foundations of Charlemagne''s palace), the Karlspreis (the Charlemagne Prize given annually since 1950 to political figures who have contributed to European unification, awarded in the Coronation Hall), the Centre Charlemagne and the Carolus Thermen Roman-style hot spring spa (one of the most prestigious thermal-bath complexes in northern Europe) complete the cultural offer. Aachen also hosts the world''s largest equestrian event the CHIO Aachen, the Pferdesport-Veranstaltung. Aachen Printen (the local hard gingerbread biscuit) is the city''s edible export.

Bonn, the former federal capital from 1949 to 1990 (and de facto seat of government until 1999 when the move to Berlin completed), retains substantial federal infrastructure. The historic government quarter (Bundesviertel) in the Hofgarten and the former Bundeshaus (the former Reichstag of the West German Bundestag) houses the World Conference Center Bonn (the venue for UN climate conferences), the Long Eugen tower (the former parliamentary building, now UN offices), the Schürmann-Bau (the former government press hall now German Welle), and the UN Campus with around 1,000 UN staff and 25 UN organisations including the UNFCCC (UN Framework Convention on Climate Change) and the UNV (UN Volunteers). Beethoven was born in Bonn in 1770, and the Beethoven-Haus on the Bonngasse (the composer''s birthplace, restored as a museum in 1893) is the most-visited Beethoven destination in the world. The Bonn Münster, a Romanesque-Gothic basilica of 1240, the Hofgarten in front of the university, the Universität Bonn (the historic Rheinische Friedrich-Wilhelms-Universität founded 1818 under Prussian rule by Friedrich Wilhelm III, with Karl Marx among the alumni), the Museum Mile of Bundesallee/Willy-Brandt-Allee with the Haus der Geschichte (Federal Republic history museum), the Kunstmuseum Bonn, the Bundeskunsthalle (Art and Exhibition Hall of the Federal Republic of Germany), the Museum König (the Naturkundemuseum where the West German Federal Republic was constituted in 1948) and the Deutsches Museum Bonn together form one of the most ambitious museum quarters in Germany. The Drachenfels above Königswinter, the Drachenburg, the Petersberg with the Steigenberger Petersberg Hotel (the former federal guest house), and the Schloss Augustusburg in Brühl (a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1984, the rococo palace by Balthasar Neumann for Cologne Elector Clemens August von Wittelsbach, with the Jagdschloss Falkenlust hunting lodge) extend the Bonn area.

Münster, the largest city of Westphalia, is built around the Prinzipalmarkt with its arcaded gabled facades, the Westfälische Friede (the Peace of Westphalia signed in 1648 in the Friedenssaal of Münster Rathaus, ending the Thirty Years'' War), the Münster Cathedral (St. Paulus-Dom) with its famous astronomical clock and the Mauritz-Markt, and the Lambertikirche with the three iron cages on its spire where the bodies of the Anabaptist leaders Jan van Leiden, Bernhard Krechting and Bernhard Knipperdolling were displayed in 1536 (the cages are still there today). The Aasee lake, the historic Promenade ring on the former city wall, the Westfälisches Landesmuseum, the Picasso-Museum Münster (the only Picasso Museum in Germany), and the Münster bicycle culture (the city has 500,000 bicycles for 320,000 residents, the highest density in Germany) complete the offer.

The Ruhrgebiet (Ruhr Area), the historic industrial heartland of Germany covering Dortmund, Essen, Duisburg, Bochum, Mülheim an der Ruhr, Oberhausen, Recklinghausen, Gelsenkirchen, Herne, Hagen, Hamm and others, has reinvented itself as one of Europe''s great post-industrial cultural landscapes. The Zeche Zollverein in Essen (UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2001), the most beautiful coal mine in the world by the Bauhaus-trained architects Fritz Schupp and Martin Kremmer, contains the Ruhr Museum (the regional history museum in the former coal-washing plant), the Folkwang Museum branch, the Red Dot Design Museum (the largest design museum in the world), the Zeche Zollverein swimming pool (in a former coking plant), and the Sanaa Cubes complex. The Gasometer Oberhausen, the converted gas-holder where huge contemporary art installations are displayed, the Landschaftspark Duisburg-Nord (the converted Thyssen steelworks of August Thyssen-Hütte now serving as a public park with climbing, diving in former tank, lightshows, and the Hochofen-blast-furnace tour), the Tetraeder Bottrop, the Halde Hoheward and the Halde Norddeutschland (the slag heaps transformed into landscape sculptures), the Zollverein Park, the Aalto Theatre Essen, the historic Krupp Villa Hügel (the Krupp family seat above Essen), the German Mining Museum Bochum (Deutsches Bergbau-Museum, the largest mining museum in the world), the Wuppertal Schwebebahn (the suspended monorail in continuous operation since 1901, the world''s oldest still-operating suspension railway), the Westfalenstadion (the BVB Borussia Dortmund home stadium and the largest stadium in Germany by capacity), the Schalke Veltins-Arena (the FC Schalke 04 home), and the Phantasialand amusement park in Brühl (one of Europe''s most respected theme parks) complete the cultural and entertainment offer of the Ruhrgebiet.

NRW cuisine and beverages are richly diverse. Rheinischer Sauerbraten (the marinated pot-roast beef of the Rhineland with raisin gravy), Rheinischer Heringsstipp, Halve Hahn (a Cologne rye-roll with Dutch-style aged Gouda and mustard), Mettbrötchen (raw-minced pork on a roll), Reibekuchen (potato pancakes), Himmel un Äd (heaven and earth, mashed potato with apple sauce and fried Blutwurst), Soldatenbrot, Krüstchen, the Westfälischer Töttchen (Westphalian veal-tongue ragout), the Westfälischer Pumpernickel (a dense rye bread baked for over 16 hours), the Westfälischer Schinken (smoked ham, a German PGI), the Möppkenbrot (a black-pudding-style bread), the Bockwurst, Bratwurst and Aachener Printen (the iconic Aachen gingerbread, a German PGI). Drinks: the iconic Kölsch (Cologne''s top-fermented bright pale beer, protected since 1986 as a Cologne-only product, served in the distinctive thin tall 0.2-litre Stange glass, produced by Brauerei Reissdorf, Päffgen, Sünner, Mühlen-Kölsch, Gaffel, Sion, Früh, Hellers and over a dozen others) and the rival Altbier (the Düsseldorf top-fermented dark amber beer, served in the wide Becher glass at Brauerei Schumacher, Im Füchschen, Schlüssel, Uerige, Bolkerstraße); plus the major NRW pilsner brands Krombacher (Krombach, the second-largest German beer brand by volume), Veltins (Meschede-Grevenstein, the third-largest), Warsteiner (Warstein, the fourth-largest), Bitburger (Bitburg in Rheinland-Pfalz, fifth-largest), König-Pilsener (Duisburg), Diebels (Issum), Bolten (Korschenbroich, the world''s oldest still-operating brewery dating from 1266), Wicküler, Iserlohner, Kaiserdom, Brinkhoff''s, DAB Dortmunder Aktien-Brauerei, Dortmunder Union, Hövels of Dortmund, Schwelmer, and many other brewing brands. Apfelkorn (apple-spirit), Cara-Kao chocolate liqueur and the cherry-spirit Stuten complete the regional spirits map.

History before 1933 is rich. The Roman Lower Germania province with Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium (Cologne) as its capital, the Carolingian Aachen of Charlemagne, the Imperial Free Cities of Cologne, Aachen, Dortmund and Soest, the Prince-Bishopric of Cologne (the Cologne Elector was one of the seven Electors of the Holy Roman Empire), the Duchies of Jülich-Berg, Cleves, Westphalia, Münster, Paderborn, Osnabrück (the last technically in Niedersachsen now) and the historic Wittgenstein and Sayn principalities. The Hanseatic League membership of Münster, Soest, Dortmund and Brilon. The Westphalian Peace of 1648 (negotiated in Münster and Osnabrück simultaneously). The Napoleonic reorganisation and the 1815 Congress of Vienna which created the Prussian Rhine Province and the Prussian Westphalia Province. The Industrial Revolution that turned the Ruhr coalfields and the Bergisches Land iron industry into the European industrial heartland: the Krupp Stahlwerke at Essen (founded 1811 by Friedrich Krupp), the Thyssen Stahlwerke at Mülheim (founded 1871 by August Thyssen), the Gutehoffnungshütte at Oberhausen, the Phoenix-Rheinrohr at Düsseldorf, the AEG plants at Bochum, the Mannesmann brothers'' tube-rolling-mill invention at Remscheid in 1885, the Bayer dye-works at Elberfeld (Wuppertal, founded 1863), the Henkel laundry-products company at Düsseldorf (founded 1876), and the historic Continental Caoutchouc and Gutta-Percha Compagnie. The political flowering of Bonn as the post-1949 capital. Famous figures from NRW include Ludwig van Beethoven (Bonn), Heinrich Heine (Düsseldorf, born in 1797), Karl Marx (Trier in Rheinland-Pfalz, but Bonn-and-Berlin-educated), Friedrich Engels (Wuppertal-Barmen), the painters Jörg Immendorff and Gerhard Richter (Düsseldorf Academy), the writers Heinrich Böll (Cologne) and Günter Grass (Düsseldorf-educated), Konrad Adenauer (Cologne and Rhöndorf), Joseph Beuys (Krefeld and Düsseldorf), the philosopher Friedrich Wilhelm Schelling (Tübingen-born but Bonn-resident), and many of the major German industrialists of the 19th century.',
    transportation = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen is the most heavily trafficked German federal state, with the densest motorway and rail network of any German Land and the largest inland-port system in Europe. Düsseldorf Airport, IATA DUS and ICAO EDDL, is the third-busiest German airport, handling around 22-25 million passengers per year. The airport sits 7 kilometres north of Düsseldorf central, reached by the Düsseldorf Airport Hauptbahnhof (the long-distance station served by ICE, IC and EC trains) and by the S-Bahn S11 to Düsseldorf Hauptbahnhof. DUS is the third Lufthansa hub (after Frankfurt and Munich), and a major operating base for Eurowings (the Lufthansa low-cost airline), Condor, Turkish Airlines, Emirates, Lufthansa, easyJet, KLM and a wide range of European leisure carriers. Cologne/Bonn Airport, IATA CGN and ICAO EDDK, is the seventh-busiest German airport, named Konrad Adenauer Airport, handling around 9-12 million passengers per year with substantial low-cost-carrier operations (Eurowings, Ryanair, Wizz Air, easyJet, Sundair) plus the Lufthansa Cityline regional operations. CGN is also one of the largest German cargo airports with the FedEx Express Hub Europe (the FedEx European hub) and the UPS Air Hub Europe (the UPS European hub) — together making CGN the second-largest German cargo airport after Frankfurt. Münster-Osnabrück Airport (FMO, EDDG) handles around 800,000 passengers per year. Dortmund Airport (DTM, EDLW) is one of the largest German low-cost airports, handling around 3-4 million passengers per year with Wizz Air, Ryanair, easyJet and the historic Aero Dienst. Weeze-Niederrhein Airport (NRN, EDLV) on a former British air base hosts Ryanair leisure flights. Paderborn-Lippstadt (PAD, EDLP) handles regional flights to the Mediterranean.

The NRW rail network is one of the densest in Europe. Cologne Hauptbahnhof, with its iconic position immediately beside the Cathedral and the Hohenzollernbrücke, is one of the busiest railway stations in Europe with around 250,000 passengers per day across 11 platforms. It is the terminus of the Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed line (the famous Köln-Rhein/Main Schnellfahrstrecke opened 2002, allowing ICE 3 trains to run at 300 kph on the steepest grade in European high-speed rail at 40 ‰ on the Westerwald). The Cologne-Brussels Thalys/Eurostar service via Aachen and Liège connects to Paris-Nord, the Cologne-Frankfurt-Strasbourg-Paris-Est ICE/TGV service via Mannheim, the Cologne-Amsterdam-Schiphol ICE service via the Dutch HSL-Zuid, and the Cologne-Berlin-Hannover-Hamburg corridor all converge at Cologne Hauptbahnhof. The Cologne Messe/Deutz station on the other side of the Hohenzollernbrücke serves long-distance trains. Düsseldorf Hauptbahnhof, opened 1936, handles the Hannover-Düsseldorf-Mainz and Berlin-Düsseldorf corridors. Other major NRW rail nodes are Dortmund Hauptbahnhof, Essen Hauptbahnhof, Duisburg Hauptbahnhof, Aachen Hauptbahnhof, Münster Hauptbahnhof, Bielefeld Hauptbahnhof, Bochum Hauptbahnhof, Bonn Hauptbahnhof, Krefeld, Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof and Hamm (Westf) — the latter the historic junction of the Cologne-Hamburg and Cologne-Hannover lines. The Cologne Messe/Deutz and Köln-Mülheim are subsidiary nodes.

The S-Bahn Rhein-Ruhr, the largest German S-Bahn system by length covering NRW from Aachen to Wuppertal to Münster, has 20 lines (S1 through S28 with gaps) totalling around 700 kilometres. The S-Bahn Köln (the Cologne S-Bahn, formerly the City-Bahn from 1975), the S-Bahn Hannover (extending across the NRW border), and the S-Bahn Rhein-Sieg complete the integrated network. The Cologne Stadtbahn (operated by KVB Kölner Verkehrs-Betriebe) is a converted tramway with both surface and tunnel running, with 12 lines on 200 kilometres. The Düsseldorf Stadtbahn (operated by Rheinbahn) is similar with 9 lines. The Bochum-Gelsenkirchen-Herne-Recklinghausen Stadtbahn (BOGESTRA), the Essen-Mülheim Stadtbahn (EVAG), the Duisburg-Mülheim Stadtbahn, the Krefeld Stadtbahn and the Bonn Stadtbahn are integrated through the VRR Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Ruhr (the largest German transport association, with 7.7 million inhabitants and 13,000 square kilometres of catchment area) and the AVV Verkehrsverbund Aachen-Maastricht, NVV Nordhessen and the VRS Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Sieg in adjacent areas. The Wuppertaler Schwebebahn, the famous suspended monorail of 1901 by Eugen Langen, runs 13.3 kilometres along the Wupper river between Vohwinkel and Oberbarmen with 20 stops at an average of 12 metres above the river — the world''s oldest still-operating suspension railway and a unique surviving example of the Schwebebahn concept. The Bonn Hauptbahnhof and the Bonn-Bad Godesberg Stadtbahn extend Cologne and the Bonn university district.

The Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed line (Köln-Rhein/Main Schnellfahrstrecke), opened in 2002, is the steepest high-speed railway in Europe with 40 ‰ grades on the Westerwald between Limburg and Siegburg. The Cologne-Aachen-Liège-Brussels Thalys service (the Eurostar group), the Cologne-Frankfurt-Mannheim-Strasbourg-Paris TGV inOui/ICE, the Cologne-Düsseldorf-Hannover-Berlin ICE/IC, the Cologne-Hamburg ICE, the Cologne-Munich ICE, the Cologne-Amsterdam ICE/Lufthansa Express, the Cologne-Vienna and Cologne-Zurich ICE/RailJet, and the Cologne-Bremen IC services together make Cologne Hauptbahnhof the European long-distance hub. The Eurostar London-Brussels and the Lille-Paris/Brussels-Cologne are operated by Eurostar through Aachen.

The Autobahn network in NRW is the densest in Germany. The A1 (Hamburg-Bremen-Cologne-Saarbrücken) crosses NRW from Hagen south; the A2 (Berlin-Hannover-Ruhrgebiet) is the central east-west corridor; the A3 (Cologne-Frankfurt-Würzburg-Munich-Passau) runs through Cologne and Düsseldorf; the A4 (Aachen-Cologne-Erfurt-Dresden); the A40 (Venlo-Duisburg-Essen-Dortmund), the central Ruhrgebiet trunk; the A42 (Kamp-Lintfort-Dortmund), the Emscher-Schnellweg; the A43 (Münster-Bochum-Wuppertal); the A44 (Liège-Aachen-Düsseldorf-Mönchengladbach-Dortmund-Kassel); the A45 (the Sauerlandlinie Dortmund-Frankfurt, currently partially closed for Talbrücke Rahmede reconstruction); the A46 (Heinsberg-Düsseldorf-Wuppertal-Iserlohn); the A52 (Düsseldorf-Essen-Gelsenkirchen-Marl); the A57 (Cologne-Nijmegen via Krefeld); the A59 (Bonn-Düsseldorf-Duisburg); the A560; the A61 (Mönchengladbach-Speyer); the A555 (Cologne-Bonn, the first German Autobahn opened 1932 as Reichsstraße 25, the world''s first non-Reichsfahrtraße motorway). The Cologne Hohenzollernring, the Kölner Rheinuferstraße, the Düsseldorf B1 along the Rhein and the Ruhrschnellweg complete the road network. The Ruhrgebiet has the densest urban motorway grid in Europe.

The Port of Duisburg (Duisport), formed at the confluence of the Rhine and Ruhr, is the largest inland port in the world, handling around 130 million tonnes of cargo per year (more than the seaports of Hamburg or Bremerhaven by tonnage). DuisPort, operated by Duisburger Hafen AG, handles container, bulk, coal, oil, chemicals, automotive and steel for the entire Ruhrgebiet industrial cluster. The Port of Cologne (RheinCargo, jointly operated with Düsseldorf) handles around 12 million tonnes. The Düsseldorf inland port handles bulk and container for the chemical industry. Other inland ports include Krefeld, Bonn, Wesel, Emmerich, Datteln, Hamm, Münster, and the Hammer-Hafen on the Lippe. The Rhine, the Ruhr, the Lippe and the Wesel-Datteln-Kanal/Dortmund-Ems-Kanal form the navigable network. The Mittellandkanal connects Dortmund to the Mittellandkanal-Rhine via the Datteln-Hamm-Kanal.

Cycling infrastructure is well developed. Long-distance routes include the EuroVelo 15 (Rhine Cycle Route, from Andermatt to Rotterdam through Düsseldorf-Cologne-Bonn-Königswinter), the Vennbahn (a former railway converted to a cycle path through Germany, Belgium and Luxembourg), the 100-Schlösser-Route through Münsterland (with 100 castles and moated houses), the Maas-Rhein-Radweg, the Ruhrtal-Radweg, the Erft-Radweg, and the Sauerland-Höhenflug. The Schwebebahn-Bike route along the Wuppertaler suspension railway is a famous local route.',
    economics = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen has the largest regional GDP among the German Bundesländer at around 750 billion euros, accounting for around 20 per cent of total German GDP, although the per-capita GDP is below the German national average due to the post-industrial transition of the Ruhrgebiet. NRW is home to 35 of the 100 largest German companies and around half of the DAX 40 listed companies. The Wirtschaftsförderung Nordrhein-Westfalen (NRW.Invest) at Düsseldorf and the Wirtschaftsförderung in the major cities market the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Cologne, Düsseldorf, Bonn, Aachen, Essen, Dortmund, Bochum, Bielefeld, Münster, Wuppertal and Hagen represent regional businesses.

Cologne is the corporate headquarters of multiple major companies. Ford-Werke GmbH at Cologne-Niehl operates Germany''s second-largest car plant (after Volkswagen Wolfsburg), producing the Ford Fiesta until 2023 and now transitioning to the Ford E-Tourneo Custom and Ford Explorer EV, with around 13,000 workers. Lufthansa AG, the largest European airline group by revenue, has its corporate headquarters at the Lufthansa Aviation Center at Frankfurt am Main but the historic Lufthansa registered office and the Lufthansa Group Headquarters Building are at Cologne — the corporate registry remains in Cologne. Deutsche Telekom AG, the largest European telecommunications operator, has its corporate headquarters at Bonn (Friedrich-Ebert-Allee), with around 200,000 employees globally and revenues of around 120 billion euros. Deutsche Post DHL Group, the world''s largest logistics company, has its corporate headquarters at Bonn (Charles-de-Gaulle-Straße in the historic Post Tower by Helmut Jahn). DHL is the global express subsidiary, operating the largest cargo airline in the world by tonnage and one of the largest postal services. Other Bonn-headquartered companies include Deutsche Welle (the German international broadcaster), the United Nations Bonn campus, the BfArM (Bundesinstitut für Arzneimittel und Medizinprodukte, the German federal pharmaceutical regulator), and a long list of federal authorities still based in Bonn (Bonn-Berlin Treaty of 1994 preserves many federal agencies at Bonn).

Düsseldorf is the corporate headquarters of L''Oréal Germany, Henkel AG & Co. KGaA, Vodafone Germany, METRO AG, E.ON SE, Daimler''s former Düsseldorf van plant, Trivago N.V., Uniper SE (the natural-gas utility), Rheinmetall AG (the listed defence and automotive supplier, producer of the Leopard 2 main battle tank gun, the Puma infantry fighting vehicle and a wide range of armoured vehicles, plus the auto-components KSPG), and many others. Henkel AG, the listed Düsseldorf-headquartered consumer-products company founded 1876 by Fritz Henkel, has annual revenues of around 22 billion euros and produces the Persil and Pril detergents, the Schwarzkopf hair-care brand, the Loctite adhesives and the Pattex glues. Vodafone Germany, the German subsidiary of the British telecoms group, has its German headquarters at Düsseldorf. METRO AG, the listed wholesale-and-cash-and-carry group, is at Düsseldorf with around 24 billion euros revenues. E.ON SE, one of the largest European utility companies, has its corporate headquarters at the E.ON-Allee in Essen following the 2016 spin-off (the former Düsseldorf headquarters now houses the corporate functions). The Trivago N.V. hotel-comparison site is at Düsseldorf-Friedrichstadt.

Essen is the corporate headquarters of thyssenkrupp AG, RWE AG, Aldi Süd, Hochtief AG (the construction giant, parent of Cimic Group and Turner Construction), Schenker AG (DB Schenker — Deutsche Bahn''s logistics arm), the Brenntag SE chemical distributor, the GlassPoint solar concentrator pioneer, Ferrostaal Industrial Services, RAG Stiftung (the legacy holding of the former Ruhrkohle AG) and the Ruhrgas/Open Grid Europe gas transmission group. ThyssenKrupp AG, the listed Essen-headquartered diversified industrial group, is the largest German steel producer and one of the world''s top 10 steel producers, with annual revenues of around 40 billion euros. The new ThyssenKrupp Quartier at the Essen Berthold-Beitz-Boulevard is the corporate centre. ThyssenKrupp Marine Systems (TKMS) at Kiel and Hamburg builds submarines for the German Navy and export customers. RWE AG, the listed Essen-headquartered utility, is one of the largest German electricity producers (along with E.ON), with annual revenues of around 30 billion euros and a large renewable-energy portfolio. The Aldi Süd (the southern German half of the Aldi discount supermarket family, founded by the Albrecht brothers Karl and Theo) is headquartered at Mülheim an der Ruhr (technically a separate city from Essen but adjacent); Aldi Nord (the northern Aldi half) is headquartered at Essen. Both Aldi Süd and Aldi Nord together are the largest German supermarket retailers by revenue. Hochtief AG, the listed Essen-headquartered construction giant, is the largest German construction company and one of the world''s top 5 builders (with annual revenues of around 30 billion euros).

Bayer AG, the listed Leverkusen-headquartered life-sciences giant, is one of the world''s largest pharmaceutical, agricultural and consumer-health companies, with annual revenues of around 50 billion euros after the 2018 Monsanto acquisition. Bayer AG was founded in 1863 by Friedrich Bayer and Friedrich Weskott at Wuppertal-Barmen as the Friedr. Bayer & Co dye-works, moved to Leverkusen in 1912 (the Wuppertal Elberfeld site was acquired by I.G. Farben in 1925 and then split off again in 1951 with the new Bayer AG at Leverkusen). Bayer AG produces the Aspirin (its inventor Felix Hoffmann at the Bayer Wuppertal-Elberfeld site in 1897, the world''s most widely used pharmaceutical), the Heroin (also synthesised by Hoffmann the same year, originally marketed as a non-addictive cough suppressant), and a long list of modern pharmaceuticals (Xarelto anticoagulant, Eylea retinal therapy, Stivarga oncology, Adempas pulmonary hypertension, Yaz/Yasmin contraceptive, Aleve OTC pain reliever, etc.). Bayer Crop Science, after the Monsanto acquisition, is the world''s largest seed and crop-protection company. The Bayer Leverkusen plant on the Rhine is the iconic Bayer cross (the Bayer Kreuz logo at the Leverkusen-Wiesdorf chemical-park entrance). The Currenta company (Bayer-Lanxess joint venture) operates the Chempark Leverkusen (the largest German chemical park together with the Industriepark Höchst at Frankfurt). The Currenta Chempark hosts Bayer, Lanxess (the speciality chemicals spin-off from Bayer in 2004), Covestro (the polymer-materials spin-off from Bayer in 2015, now part of Adnoc since 2024 acquisition), Saltigo, Arxada and many other tenants. Covestro AG, the listed Leverkusen-headquartered polymer-materials giant, has annual revenues of around 18 billion euros. Lanxess AG, the listed Leverkusen-headquartered specialty-chemicals company, has annual revenues of around 8 billion euros.

In Wuppertal-Elberfeld, Vorwerk & Co. KG, the family-owned Wuppertal kitchen-appliance maker (the Thermomix multi-function cooker, the Kobold vacuum-cleaner and the Vorwerk-Teppich-Lederer carpet division) employs around 12,000 worldwide. Wuppertal also hosts the historic Bayer-Elberfeld site (now Lanxess and Bayer R&D), the Vorwerk Direct Sales, and the Knipex precision-tools group. Solingen, the historic German knife-making capital, hosts Wüsthof, J.A. Henckels (Zwilling), Robert Herder, Burgvogel and the Klingenmuseum knife-museum. Remscheid hosts the Mannesmann-Demag pump and crane group. Iserlohn hosts the Vorwerk Carpets and the Iserlohner Brewery. The Bergisches Land cluster of small high-precision manufacturing is famous as Germany''s tool-making heartland.

In Münsterland and Westfalen, Miele & Cie. KG of Gütersloh (the family-owned premium home-appliance maker, the leading European premium washing-machine and dishwasher producer) is one of the most respected German brands. The Bertelsmann SE & Co. KGaA of Gütersloh is the largest privately owned media group in Europe, with around 17 billion euros annual revenues from publishing (Penguin Random House, the world''s largest English-language trade publisher), broadcasting (RTL Group, the largest European broadcaster), music (BMG Music Group), magazines (Gruner+Jahr now folded into RTL), education (Bertelsmann Education), services (Arvato), and printing (Mohn Media). Claas KGaA (Harsewinkel, agricultural-machinery maker, the third-largest in the world after John Deere and CNH Industrial), Wilkhahn (Bad Münder, technically Niedersachsen, design furniture maker), Tönnies Lebensmittel (Rheda-Wiedenbrück, the largest German meat processor) round out the Westphalia cluster.

In Bonn, the federal Bundesnetzagentur (Federal Network Agency, the German telecom and energy regulator) is at Tulpenfeld; the Bundesamt für Sicherheit in der Informationstechnik (BSI, the German federal IT-security agency) is at Bonn; the Bundeszentrale für gesundheitliche Aufklärung (BZgA), the Wissenschaftsrat (the German Council of Science and Humanities), the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD), the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation, the Friedrich Ebert Foundation (Bonn branch), and many other federal agencies are at Bonn. The Bonn United Nations campus, with around 1,000 UN staff, is the largest German UN campus.

Banking and finance are concentrated at Düsseldorf, Cologne and Essen. The HSBC Trinkaus & Burkhardt AG, the Postbank AG (now part of Deutsche Bank, Bonn), the Commerzbank Düsseldorf branch, the Sparkasse KölnBonn, the Stadtsparkasse Düsseldorf, the Sparkasse Essen, the cooperative Volksbank Köln-Bonn-Rhein-Sieg and the Volksbank-Aachen all have substantial NRW operations. Insurance includes the Provinzial NRW, the Rheinland Versicherung, the AXA Konzern AG (Cologne), the ERGO Düsseldorf, the Generali Cologne, the Talanx Group Hannover branch and the historic Gerling Insurance (now part of HDI-Gerling).

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Universität zu Köln (one of the largest German universities by enrolment), the Heinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf, the RWTH Aachen (Germany''s largest technical university with around 47,000 students and one of the German Universities of Excellence), the Westfälische Wilhelms-Universität Münster, the Ruhr-Universität Bochum, the Technische Universität Dortmund, the Universität Bielefeld, the Universität Paderborn, the Universität Siegen, the Universität Wuppertal and the Universität Duisburg-Essen together host over 800,000 students. The Max-Planck-Institut für Radioastronomie at Bonn, the Max-Planck-Institut für Eisenforschung at Düsseldorf, the Max-Planck-Institut für Kohlenforschung at Mülheim, and the Forschungszentrum Jülich (one of Europe''s largest interdisciplinary research centres with around 7,000 staff) form the research backbone.',
    introduced_species = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen, the most densely populated German Bundesland and the historic gateway between western and eastern German invasive species ranges, hosts the most comprehensive roster of introduced and invasive species in any German state. The Landesamt für Natur, Umwelt und Verbraucherschutz Nordrhein-Westfalen (LANUV) at Recklinghausen coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Nordrhein-Westfalen since the 1960s when individuals from the Hessian Edersee 1934 release expanded west across the Sauerland and the Bergisches Land. Today the species is established throughout NRW with the highest densities in the Sauerland, the Eifel, the Siegerland, the Westerwald (technically Rheinland-Pfalz border), and increasingly in the suburban Düsseldorf-Cologne-Bonn corridor, the Ruhrgebiet and the Münsterland. Annual hunting bags in NRW exceed 50,000 raccoons, the highest in Germany. The LANUV publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the handling of raccoon latrines. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl), on amphibians, on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis), on the recovering otter and lynx populations of the Eifel, and on ground-nesting birds in the Münsterland.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached NRW from the east in the 2000s; today the species is established throughout NRW with the highest densities in the Sauerland, the Eifel and the Münsterland. Annual hunting bags exceed 12,000. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Lower Rhine, the Lippe, the Ruhr, the Emscher and the Niers. Damage to flood-protection dykes and to reedbeds is a serious management concern; the LANUV and the local water authorities coordinate trapping. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to NRW but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and the LANUV since the 1980s and has now recolonised the Eifel, the Sauerland, the Münsterland and the Lower Rhine. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout NRW.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised NRW since around 2018 and the state now has around five established territorial packs in the Senne, the Eifel, the Lüneburger Heide-NRW border, the Schermbeck Wolfsgebiet near Wesel, and the Forsthaus Hohe Mark area. The NRW Wolves Office (LANUV-Wolfsbüro) coordinates monitoring; the controversial Schermbeck Wolfsfamilie has been a media flashpoint for livestock-predation incidents.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations along the Rhine and the major NRW lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded explosively; NRW has perhaps the densest German Egyptian goose populations, particularly in Cologne, Düsseldorf, Bonn and the Lower Rhine. The Egyptian goose has become a Düsseldorf and Cologne urban-park ubiquity, with breeding pairs on most ponds, fountains and lakes. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has established perhaps the largest German breeding population in the Düsseldorf-Cologne-Bonn area, with over 4,000 breeding pairs concentrated in the Düsseldorf Hofgarten, the Düsseldorf Südfriedhof, the Cologne Stadtgarten, the Cologne Beethovenpark, the Bonn Hofgarten and the Brühl Schlosspark Augustusburg; the Düsseldorf Halsbandsittich roost in the Hofgarten is one of the most spectacular urban wildlife displays in Germany, with several thousand birds gathering at dusk. The Alexandrine parakeet (Großer Alexandersittich), the Monk parakeet (Mönchssittich), and various other escaped parrots have small populations in NRW. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds widely on NRW park ponds.

Among freshwater fish, the pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella), the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) and the bighead goby are widespread. The Rhine has been particularly affected by the Pontic and Caspian goby invasions. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis), the historic Sauerlandstreams catfish, has been reintroduced and is now common.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis). The Rhine is heavily invaded.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in NRW from 2014 onwards with the first German breeding record in 2014 at Aachen-Waldfeucht (one of the first verified breeding records in Germany, the species having advanced from northern France via Belgium across the Aachen frontier); the Imkerverband NRW coordinates nest-removal teams with the LANUV. By 2024 hundreds of Asian hornet nests had been removed in western NRW, with the species established throughout NRW.

The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the NRW chestnut avenues every late summer. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Schloss Brühl, the Schloss Benrath, the Aachener Dom and the Bonn Hofgarten. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established. The Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) was recorded in NRW in the 2010s. The emerald ash borer (Agrilus planipennis) monitoring traps are deployed.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial Ruhr brownfields), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), and the Senecio inaequidens are all widespread.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Eifel, the Sauerland, the Bergisches Land and the Münsterland. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Reinhardswald (NRW-Hessen border). Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density, with annual hunting bags exceeding 80,000 statewide; the Düsseldorf, Cologne and Bonn urban-park areas have substantial urban wild-boar populations. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), although native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Eifel. The lynx (Lynx lynx), although native, has been re-introduced to the Eifel National Park.'
WHERE region_name = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Rheinland-Pfalz, in English Rhineland-Palatinate, is one of the historically richest German federal states, occupying the south-western quadrant of Germany between the Rhine and the French and Luxembourg borders. The state covers 19,854 square kilometres and has around 4.1 million inhabitants. Mainz is the state capital, and the other major cities include Koblenz, Trier, Ludwigshafen, Kaiserslautern, Speyer, Worms, Bad Kreuznach, Neuwied, Pirmasens and Zweibrücken. The state was formed on 30 August 1946 under French military government from parts of the historic Bavarian Palatinate, the Prussian Rhine Province south of the Mosel and the historic Hessen-Nassau districts of Montabaur.

Mainz, the state capital, is one of the oldest cities in Germany, founded by the Romans as Mogontiacum in 13 BC as the capital of the Roman province of Germania Superior. The Mainzer Dom (Mainz Cathedral), one of the three great Romanesque imperial cathedrals of the Holy Roman Empire (alongside Speyer and Worms), is dominated by the great Romanesque west choir of 1009 by Archbishop Willigis with the famous Marktportal porch, the bronze portal doors of 1009, and the elevated Memorienportal east choir. The cathedral was the coronation site of seven Holy Roman Emperors and contains the tombs of fifteen Mainz archbishops. The Gutenberg Museum (Mainz''s most-visited museum) on the Liebfrauenplatz preserves the printing technology of Johannes Gutenberg, who was born in Mainz around 1400 and printed the Gutenberg Bible (the 42-line Bible) in Mainz between 1452 and 1455 — the first mass-printed book in the Western world. The museum holds two original Gutenberg Bibles (out of the 49 surviving worldwide) and reconstructed printing presses on which visitors can watch the manual process. The historic St. Stephan church with its remarkable blue stained-glass windows by Marc Chagall (his final great work of 1976-1985, the only Chagall stained-glass installation in Germany), the Augustinerstraße with its old Catholic seminary, the Augustinerkirche, the Mainzer Schloss (the Electoral Palace, today housing the Römisch-Germanisches Zentralmuseum and the Akademie der Wissenschaften), the Drususstein Roman tomb, the Theodor-Heuss-Brücke road bridge over the Rhine to Wiesbaden, and the Mainzer Fastnacht (the largest German carnival in the Rhineland tradition alongside Cologne and Düsseldorf, with the Rosenmontag procession) complete the city.

Trier, in the south-west on the Mosel river, is the oldest city in Germany, founded by Emperor Augustus as Augusta Treverorum in 17 BC and later one of the four capitals of the Roman Empire under the Tetrarchy. The Trier UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1986) includes the Porta Nigra (the great Roman north city gate of around 200 AD, the largest surviving Roman city gate north of the Alps and the iconic symbol of Trier), the Trier Cathedral St. Peter (the oldest cathedral in Germany, built on the Imperial palace of Constantine''s mother Helena from around 326 AD, containing the Holy Robe of Trier — believed to be Christ''s seamless robe — displayed publicly only every 25 years or so, last in 2012), the Liebfrauenkirche (the second-oldest Gothic church in Germany after the Marburger Elisabethkirche, with twin western towers), the Roman Imperial Throne Hall (Konstantinbasilika, the largest single-room space surviving from antiquity, built around 310 AD as Constantine''s audience hall, today a Protestant church), the Kaiserthermen Roman Imperial Baths (the partly excavated baths of Constantine), the Barbara Baths, the Roman amphitheatre, the Roman Bridge of 144-152 AD over the Mosel (the oldest surviving Roman bridge in Germany), and the magnificent Karl-Marx-Haus (the birthplace of Karl Marx, born in Trier in 1818, now a museum). The Rheinisches Landesmuseum Trier holds one of the finest Roman collections in Germany, including the largest collection of Roman gold coins in the world found at Trier in 1993. The Trier Marketplace with the Marktkreuz of 958, the Three Magi House (Dreikönigenhaus of 1230, a rare Romanesque tower-house in city style), the Domplatz and the Hauptmarkt complete the city.

Koblenz, at the confluence (the Deutsches Eck, "German Corner") of the Rhine and Mosel rivers, is dominated by the Deutsches Eck monument with the equestrian statue of Kaiser Wilhelm I (originally erected 1897, demolished 1945, reconstructed 1993), the Festung Ehrenbreitstein (the great Prussian fortress of 1817-1828 on the right bank, one of the largest preserved fortresses in Europe, reached by the Seilbahn Koblenz cable car), the Kurfürstliches Schloss (the Electoral Palace), the Schloss Stolzenfels above the Rhine (a romantic-revival reconstruction by Friedrich Wilhelm IV of Prussia in 1842 with frescoes by Hermann Stilke), the Münzplatz, the Görres-Platz, and the Liebfrauenkirche. Koblenz is the northern gateway to the UNESCO Upper Middle Rhine Valley (Oberes Mittelrheintal), the Romantic Rhine gorge running 67 kilometres south to Bingen — a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2002 for its dense concentration of castles, vineyards, terraced slopes and historic towns. The Mittelrhein landscape contains over 40 castles within this stretch, including the Marksburg at Braubach (the only never-destroyed castle in the Middle Rhine, dating from 1117), the Burg Eltz nearby on the Mosel (the famous fairytale castle, never destroyed and continuously owned by the Eltz family since 1157), the Burg Stahleck above Bacharach (a youth hostel since 1925), the Burg Maus (Mouse Castle), the Burg Katz (Cat Castle, named in defiance of the Mouse), the Burg Rheinstein (the prototype for the Rhineland castle restoration), the Burg Reichenstein, the Burg Ehrenfels above the Mäuseturm bei Bingen (the Mouse Tower of the Bishop Hatto legend), the Pfalzgrafenstein on its island in the Rhine, the Burg Sterrenberg and Burg Liebenstein (the Hostile Brothers), and the Schönburg at Oberwesel. The Lorelei rock at St. Goarshausen, immortalised by Heinrich Heine''s poem of the siren who lured Rhine sailors to their deaths, is one of the most famous spots on the Rhine. Bacharach, Oberwesel, St. Goar, St. Goarshausen, Boppard and Braubach are the classic Rhine wine towns. River cruising on the Köln-Düsseldorfer Rheinschiffahrt (KD) fleet, the Bingen-Rüdesheimer ferries and the historic paddle-steamer Goethe (now decommissioned but with similar successors) provide the classic Rhine experience.

Speyer (Spires) is famous for the Speyer Cathedral (Kaiserdom zu Speyer), a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1981 and the largest surviving Romanesque church in the world. Built between 1030 and 1106 by Emperor Conrad II and his successors, the cathedral has the longest Romanesque interior in Europe (134 metres) and contains the imperial crypt with the tombs of eight Holy Roman Emperors and German kings (Conrad II, Henry III, Henry IV, Henry V, Beatrix and Agnes, Rudolf of Habsburg, Adolf of Nassau, Albert of Habsburg), making it the largest imperial mausoleum in the German-speaking world. The Historisches Museum der Pfalz next door holds the Imperial Treasures of the Palatinate, the Goldener Hut of Schifferstadt (a Bronze Age gold cone), and the magnificent Konrad-Skulptur. The Speyer Jewish ritual bath (Mikwe) of 1128 is the oldest preserved Jewish ritual bath in central Europe and part of the ShUM-Cities UNESCO World Heritage inscription (Speyer-Worms-Mainz Jewish heritage, designated 2021). The Speyer Altpörtel (the historic west city gate), the Maximilianstraße and the Heiliggeistkirche complete the town.

Worms, between Mainz and Mannheim, has the Worms Cathedral (Wormser Dom St. Peter), another of the three great Romanesque imperial cathedrals (alongside Speyer and Mainz), and the historic site of the Imperial Diet of Worms of 1521, where Martin Luther defended his Theses before Emperor Charles V (the so-called Luther-Edict of Worms). The Lutherdenkmal (Luther Monument) outside the cathedral, the Nibelungen-Festspiele (the annual Nibelungen Festival celebrating the medieval Nibelungenlied, an epic poem written down in around 1200 in the Worms area), the Heilige Sand (the oldest Jewish cemetery in central Europe, founded around 1058 and part of the ShUM-Cities UNESCO inscription), the historic Jewish quarter and the Wormser Wein wine festivals complete the city.

The Eifel, the volcanic upland north of the Mosel and west of the Rhine, contains the Eifel National Park (the only national park in NRW-RP, including parts of both states), the Vulkaneifel with its maar lakes (the iconic deep round volcanic lakes of Pulvermaar, Schalkenmehrener Maar, Weinfelder Maar, Holzmaar — all maars are explosion craters from phreatomagmatic eruptions), the Nürburgring (the legendary Nürburg motor-racing circuit on the Eifel with the famous 20.8-kilometre Nordschleife circuit, the most demanding race-track in the world; the modern Grand Prix circuit hosts the German Grand Prix and the 24 Hours of Nürburgring race), the historic walled town of Monschau in the High Fens, the Burg Eltz on the Eltzbach tributary of the Mosel, the Bitburger Beerland with its Eifel Maar lakes, the historic Vulkanpark Brohltal, and the Manderscheider Burgen pair of castles. The Pfälzerwald (the Palatinate Forest, the largest contiguous forest in Germany at around 1,800 square kilometres), the largest connected woodland in central Europe, hosts the Pfälzerwald-Naturpark Biosphere Reserve and is famous for its red sandstone outcrops (the Drachenfels, the Berwartstein castle, the Burg Lindelbrunn), the Hambacher Schloss (the Hambach Castle, where the Hambacher Fest of 1832 — Germany''s first true democratic gathering, with 30,000 attendees demanding national unity and civil rights, lifting the black-red-gold flag) was held, and the Deutsche Weinstraße (the German Wine Route, running 85 kilometres from Bockenheim in the north to Schweigen on the French border, lined with wine villages and the iconic Deutsches Weintor at the southern end).

Bad Ems on the Lahn, the historic Prussian spa where Tsar Alexander II and Bismarck negotiated the Ems Telegram of 1870, is one of eleven Great Spa Towns of Europe inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2021. Bad Neuenahr-Ahrweiler, the Ahr wine valley town, was devastated by the July 2021 flood but is being rebuilt; the Ahr is one of Germany''s premier red-wine regions for Spätburgunder Pinot Noir. The Westerwald, the Hunsrück and the Hahn-Region complete the rural backbone.

Cuisine and beverages of Rheinland-Pfalz are wine-focused. Saumagen (the Palatinate stuffed pig''s stomach with pork, potato, onion and Marjoram — the iconic Palatinate dish famously favoured by Chancellor Helmut Kohl who served it to Mikhail Gorbachev, George Bush and other world leaders at his Oggersheim residence near Ludwigshafen), Pfälzer Leberknödel (Palatinate liver dumplings in broth), Pfälzer Wurstsalat, Pfälzer Schwartenmagen, Spundekäs (a soft cream-cheese spread with paprika and onion served in Rhine and Pfalz wine bars), Pfälzer Riesling and the Mosel Riesling, the Rieslingfests, the Bad Dürkheimer Wurstmarkt (the oldest wine festival in the world, dating from 1417), the Weinfest Edenkoben, the Wine Wanderung tours along the Deutsche Weinstraße. The major Rhineland-Palatinate wine regions are: the Mosel (the largest and most famous Riesling region in Germany, with the great vineyards of Bernkasteler Doctor, Wehlener Sonnenuhr, Erdener Treppchen, Piesporter Goldtröpfchen, Brauneberger Juffer, Graacher Domprobst, etc., and the producers Egon Müller-Scharzhof, Joh. Jos. Prüm, Fritz Haag, Markus Molitor, Reinhold Haart, Schloss Saarstein, Forstmeister Geltz Zilliken), the Pfalz (the second-largest wine region in Germany producing both white Rieslings and red Spätburgunder/Schwarzriesling, with producers Reichsrat von Buhl, Bürklin-Wolf, Christmann, Müller-Catoir, Knipser, Rebholz, Ökonomierat Rebholz, Wegeler), the Rheinhessen (the largest German wine region by area, producing Riesling, Müller-Thurgau, Silvaner, Scheurebe and the modern young producers Keller, Wittmann, Battenfeld-Spanier, Kühling-Gillot — the so-called Mainzer Weinkomitee revolution that has elevated Rheinhessen from bulk Liebfraumilch to global premium Riesling status since the 2000s), the Ahr (Germany''s premier red-wine valley, with producers Meyer-Näkel, Jean Stodden, Adeneuer, Kreuzberg) and the small Nahe (Riesling and Sylvaner, with the legendary Hermann Dönnhoff, Schäfer-Fröhlich, Emrich-Schönleber, Diel and Tesch producers, including the Schlossböckelheimer Felsenberg, the Niederhäuser Hermannshöhle and the Norheimer Dellchen Grosses Gewächs vineyards). Beer is dominated by Bitburger Brauerei at Bitburg (the largest Pilsner brand by sales volume in Germany), Karlsberg Brauerei at Homburg (technically Saarland), Park & Bellheimer, Park-Bräu and the Eulchen Brauerei at Mainz. Distillates include the Pfälzer Tresterbrand (grape marc), the Williams-Christ pear-spirit, the Mirabelle plum-spirit, the Quetschen plum, the Zwetschge spirit and the Eifel-style apple Trester. Mineral water from the Apollinaris (Bad Neuenahr-Ahrweiler) and Gerolsteiner (the largest German mineral-water producer at Gerolstein in the Vulkaneifel) sources is widely sold; both Gerolsteiner Brunnen and Apollinaris carry global brand recognition.

History before 1933 is rich. The Roman Empire (Trier as one of the four Tetrarchic capitals, Mainz/Mogontiacum as the capital of Germania Superior, Köln as Lower Germania''s capital, Worms and Speyer as legionary outposts). The Carolingian Aachen-Trier-Mainz axis. The Holy Roman Empire and the great Salian and Hohenstaufen dynasties buried at Speyer. The Electors of Mainz, Trier and Cologne (the three ecclesiastical electors). The Imperial Diets at Worms (the Diet of 1521 with Luther), at Speyer (the 1526 and 1529 Diets that gave Protestants their name from the Speyer Protestation), at Augsburg (the 1530 Augsburg Confession). The 1648 Peace of Westphalia. The Palatinate Succession War of 1689-1697 under Louis XIV of France, which devastated the Palatinate. The 1815 Congress of Vienna creating the Bavarian Palatinate and the Prussian Rhine Province. The 1832 Hambacher Fest, the cradle of German democracy. The 1849 Pfalz Uprising. The 1918 abdication of the Wittelsbachs. The 1945-1946 French zone of occupation creating the new state of Rheinland-Pfalz. Famous figures from Rheinland-Pfalz include Karl Marx (Trier), Johannes Gutenberg (Mainz), Friedrich Wilhelm Raiffeisen (the founder of the cooperative banking movement, born in Hamm an der Sieg), Anna Seghers (the writer, born in Mainz as Netty Reiling), Friedrich Schlegel (philosopher, briefly in Mainz), Stefan George (poet from Bingen, founder of the George-Kreis), Heinrich Hertz (no, Hertz was Hamburg), and Federal Chancellors Helmut Kohl (Ludwigshafen, served 1982-1998).',
    transportation = 'Rheinland-Pfalz, although a relatively small state by population, has a substantial transport network shaped by the Rhine valley, the Mosel valley, the Eifel uplands and the cross-border traffic to France, Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands. Frankfurt-Hahn Airport, IATA HHN and ICAO EDFH, on a former US air base 120 kilometres west of Frankfurt in the Hunsrück, is the largest commercial airport in Rheinland-Pfalz, although passenger traffic has declined dramatically since the early 2010s peak of 4 million passengers; today the airport handles around 1.5 million passengers per year, dominated by Ryanair operations. Hahn is also a significant cargo airport (one of the top 10 German cargo airports by tonnage) thanks to a series of long-haul cargo carriers. Saarbrücken Airport (SCN, EDDR) is technically in Saarland but serves much of southern Rheinland-Pfalz. The historic Trier-Föhren airfield (EDRT) serves general aviation. Koblenz-Winningen (EDRK), Bad Neuenahr-Ahrweiler (EDNB), Mainz-Finthen (EDFZ), Bitburg-Trier (former US air base), and Spangdahlem Air Base (still active US Air Force base) and Ramstein Air Base (the largest US Air Force base outside the United States, with around 9,000 US military personnel and the headquarters of the United States Air Forces in Europe and Africa, USAFE-AFAFRICA) round out the aviation infrastructure.

The Rheinland-Pfalz rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Mitte, with the regional brands vlexx, DB Regio Südwest, DB Regio Mittelrhein-Eifel, ODEG and the Westerwaldbahn operating regional services under the Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Mosel (VRM), the Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Neckar (VRN, reaching across to Mannheim and Heidelberg) and the Verkehrsverbund Region Trier (VRT, with cross-border tariff to Luxembourg) coordinating tariff. Mainz Hauptbahnhof, in the centre of the state capital, is a major rail node connecting the Frankfurt corridor (with frequent S-Bahn S8 and S9 trains) to the Pfalz, Rhineland and Mosel directions, with ICE and IC services connecting Mainz to Frankfurt, Koblenz, Köln, Saarbrücken and Mannheim. The Mainz-Frankfurt connection takes around 30 minutes by ICE. Other major Rheinland-Pfalz rail nodes include Koblenz Hauptbahnhof, Trier Hauptbahnhof (with cross-border services to Luxembourg-Stadt), Ludwigshafen Hauptbahnhof (across the Rhine from Mannheim in Baden-Württemberg, served by the Mannheim S-Bahn), Kaiserslautern Hauptbahnhof, Bingen am Rhein, Bad Kreuznach and Pirmasens. The Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed line (Köln-Rhein/Main NBS, opened 2002) crosses the eastern Rheinland-Pfalz with stations at Montabaur (an ICE station on a previously rural area, controversial at its opening but now a regular ICE stop) and a few non-stop sections through the Westerwald. The Rheintalbahn (Mainz-Bingen-Koblenz-Cologne) along the left bank of the Rhine is one of Germany''s most scenic railway lines and a major freight corridor; the right-bank Rheinstrecke (Wiesbaden-Rüdesheim-Loreley-Koblenz) is the alternative freight route. The Mosel-Bahn (Koblenz-Trier-Luxembourg) and the Eifelbahn (Cologne-Trier) carry tourists and commuters. The historic Hunsrückbahn from Boppard to Emmelshausen is the steepest non-rack adhesion-only railway in Germany. The 1989 high-speed line from Mannheim to Saarbrücken via Kaiserslautern is the Mannheim-Saarbrücken NBS, opening from 2007 to allow TGV inOui to run between Paris and Frankfurt.

The Autobahn network in Rheinland-Pfalz is anchored by the A3 (Cologne-Frankfurt corridor, the busiest German motorway by truck traffic, with the famous Limburger Westerwald-Tunnel), the A1 (Saarbrücken-Trier-Cologne-Bremen, the historic Reichsstraße 1 successor), the A6 (Mannheim-Saarbrücken-Paris, with the A6 connection to the French A4 at Saarbrücken Goldene Bremm), the A48 (Trier-Koblenz-Diez), the A60 (Mainz-Bingen-Diez), the A61 (Mönchengladbach-Speyer-Hockenheim, the major north-south corridor west of the Rhine), the A62 (Trier-Pirmasens-Mehlbach), the A63 (Kaiserslautern-Mainz), the A64 (Trier-Luxembourg, cross-border to the Luxembourg motorway), the A65 (Karlsruhe-Mannheim via the Pfälzerwald), the A643 (Mainz-Bingen), and the A67 (Mainz-Lorsch). Bundesstraßen include the B9 along the Rhine (the Romantic Rhine drive), the B49 along the Mosel, the B50 across the Hunsrück (with the famous Hochmoselbrücke at Zeltingen-Rachtig, opened 2019, the second-highest bridge in Germany at 158 metres above the Mosel), the B41 from Mainz to Saarbrücken, the B257 in the Eifel, and the B270 in the Pfälzerwald. The Hochmoselbrücke is one of the most controversial German road-construction projects of the 21st century.

The Rhine and Mosel are major navigable inland waterways. The Rhine carries enormous cargo traffic from Rotterdam via Duisburg, Cologne, Bonn, Koblenz, Mainz, Ludwigshafen and Mannheim to Strasbourg and Basel; the Mosel is the secondary route from Luxembourg via Trier and Koblenz to the Rhine. The Ludwigshafen Rhine port serves BASF and the surrounding chemical industry; Mainz, Koblenz, Trier, Speyer and the Bingen-Rüdesheim ferry are inland ports of national importance. River cruising on the Köln-Düsseldorfer Rheinschiffahrt (KD) fleet, the Bingen-Rüdesheimer ferries, the historic Lorelei-Falke and the modern Viking-River-Cruises and AmaWaterways fleet, provide the classic tourism circulation. The MS Rheinland and the Goethe paddle steamer (now museum) are well known.

Long-distance cycling routes are extensive. The EuroVelo 15 Rhine Cycle Route from Andermatt to Rotterdam runs through Mainz, Bingen, Koblenz and onward. The EuroVelo 6 Atlantic-Black Sea via the Mosel and Saar. The Mosel-Radweg from Metz via Trier to Koblenz is one of Germany''s top-ranked cycling routes. The Vulkaneifel-Radweg, the Lahntal-Radweg, the Saar-Radweg, the Pfälzer Wald-Radweg, the Nahe-Radweg and the Eifel-Radweg complete the network.',
    economics = 'Rheinland-Pfalz has a regional GDP of around 170 billion euros, with one of the highest export ratios in Germany (around 55 per cent) due to the dominant chemical and pharmaceutical industries. The Wirtschaftsförderung Rheinland-Pfalz (ISB Investitions- und Strukturbank Rheinland-Pfalz) at Mainz markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Pfalz, the IHK Rheinhessen, the IHK Koblenz and the IHK Trier represent regional businesses.

BASF SE, the world''s largest chemical company by revenue, has its corporate headquarters and main production complex (the Stammwerk Ludwigshafen) at Ludwigshafen am Rhein on the left bank of the Rhine, across the river from Mannheim in Baden-Württemberg. The Ludwigshafen Stammwerk covers 10 square kilometres along seven kilometres of Rhine frontage and is the largest contiguous chemical-industrial complex in the world, with around 40,000 employees, around 200 production plants integrated through the famous BASF Verbund concept (a closed-loop system where byproducts of one plant are inputs to the next), connected by 2,850 kilometres of pipelines, with the largest steam-cracker in Europe (the BASF Steamcracker II), the world''s largest production lines for many chemical intermediates, and BASF''s historic global research centre at the Carl-Bosch-Straße. BASF was founded in 1865 at Ludwigshafen by Friedrich Engelhorn as the Badische Anilin- und Sodafabrik (Baden Aniline and Soda Factory), producing the famous aniline-based dye stuffs that revolutionised the global textile industry. BASF holds the historic patents for synthetic indigo (the Heumann process of 1897), for the Haber-Bosch ammonia-synthesis process (1913, the foundation of modern fertilisers and explosives), for the Fischer-Tropsch process (1925, synthetic fuels), and for the Schmidt synthesis (synthetic methanol). BASF''s 2022 annual revenue was around 87 billion euros with 110,000 employees worldwide. The Ludwigshafen site is the largest single industrial employer in Rheinland-Pfalz.

Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH, the family-owned pharmaceutical company headquartered at Ingelheim am Rhein in the Mainz area, is the world''s largest privately-held pharmaceutical company (founded 1885 by Albert Boehringer as Albert Boehringer Wernigerode and moved to Ingelheim in 1893; the company has been continuously controlled by the Boehringer-von Baumbach family for five generations). Boehringer Ingelheim has annual revenues of around 24 billion euros and produces a wide range of human and veterinary pharmaceuticals including the diabetes-drug Jardiance/Empagliflozin (jointly developed with Eli Lilly), the anticoagulant Pradaxa/Dabigatran, the COPD inhaler Spiriva/Tiotropium, the lung-fibrosis drug Ofev/Nintedanib, and the veterinary Heartworm preventatives Frontline and NexGard (from the BIVI Boehringer Ingelheim Vetmedica division, the largest veterinary pharmaceutical business in the world after Zoetis). The Ingelheim site employs around 8,000 people. Other Boehringer family members run the historic Boehringer Mannheim (no relation, now part of Roche since 1997) and the Engelhorn family also founded BASF.

Schott AG, the technical-glass and specialty-materials company, has its corporate headquarters and main production site at Mainz. Schott is jointly owned with the Schott family Stiftung and the Carl-Zeiss-Stiftung at Heidenheim (Baden-Württemberg). Schott Mainz produces the famous Ceran ceramic cooktops, Schott Robax fireplace glass, Schott Pyran fire-resistant glass, Schott Borofloat borosilicate glass, the Schott NEXTERION laboratory consumables, the Schott Tubing pharmaceutical containers, and the Schott VICOR molten-glass products. Schott has annual revenues of around 2.7 billion euros and 17,000 employees worldwide. The Schott Pharma subsidiary at Mainz is the world''s leading producer of pharmaceutical vials, syringes and ampoules; the Schott Cardinal Sealant glass-to-metal seals are critical aerospace components.

Daimler Truck AG, the listed German commercial-vehicle giant spun off from Daimler in 2021, has its largest single truck plant at Wörth am Rhein, near the French border in southern Rheinland-Pfalz. The Wörth plant, the largest truck assembly plant in Europe, produces the Mercedes-Benz Actros, Antos, Arocs, Atego and Econic models for the European market, plus the new eActros electric heavy truck. The Wörth plant employs around 10,000 workers and produces around 90,000 trucks per year.

The Federal German Bundeswehr and the US Armed Forces in Europe have one of their largest concentrations of military infrastructure in Rheinland-Pfalz. Ramstein Air Base (Ramstein Air Base), the largest US Air Force base in the world outside the United States, is located near Landstuhl and Kaiserslautern. Ramstein hosts the headquarters of US Air Forces in Europe and Africa (USAFE-AFAFRICA), the Allied Air Command of NATO, and a wide range of operational squadrons (the 86th Airlift Wing with C-130 Hercules and C-21 Learjet aircraft). Ramstein is also the location of the largest US military hospital outside the United States, the Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, which has treated tens of thousands of US service members wounded in Iraq, Afghanistan and other conflicts. Spangdahlem Air Base near Bitburg hosts the US Air Force 52nd Fighter Wing with F-16 Fighting Falcon aircraft. The Bundeswehr Standorten at Mainz, Koblenz, Trier, Daun, Zweibrücken and elsewhere are major regional employers. The Federal Office for Defence Equipment, Information Technology and In-Service Support (BAAINBw) at Koblenz is the largest federal agency in Rheinland-Pfalz.

Other major Rheinland-Pfalz employers include the listed Lufthansa Cargo (the cargo subsidiary headquartered at Frankfurt-Hahn historically but now at Frankfurt am Main), the Henkell & Söhnlein Sektkellerei at Wiesbaden (technically Hessen but with substantial Rhine-area operations), the Schwarz Pharma at Monheim (technically NRW), the Bauunternehmen Stretter, the Lebensmittel-Kombinat Mosella (food), the Stahlwerke Bous (steel), the Kaiserslautern Pirelli Reifen plant, the Karlsberger Brewery at Homburg (in Saarland), the Hornbach Holding (the listed DIY home-improvement retailer, the second-largest German DIY chain, headquartered at Bornheim near Landau in the Palatinate), the Globus SB-Warenhaus (the listed hypermarket chain, headquartered at St. Wendel in Saarland but with major Rheinland-Pfalz operations), and the Würth Group operations (although Würth is Baden-Württemberg-headquartered, the Pfalz has substantial Würth-affiliated operations).

The Rheinland-Pfalz wine industry, the largest in Germany by both area and production, is concentrated in the Mosel (the largest German Riesling region), the Pfalz (the second-largest wine region by area and the largest red-wine producer in Germany), the Rheinhessen (the largest wine region by area in Germany at 27,000 hectares, the modern centre of the German wine revolution), the Ahr (Germany''s premier red-wine valley) and the Nahe. Total Rheinland-Pfalz wine production is around six million hectolitres per year, accounting for two-thirds of German wine production. Major producers include the historic Egon Müller-Scharzhof (the Saar), Joh. Jos. Prüm (Mosel), Fritz Haag (Mosel), Markus Molitor (Mosel), Reinhold Haart (Mosel), Schloss Saarstein (Mosel), Forstmeister Geltz Zilliken (Saar), Reichsrat von Buhl (Pfalz), Bürklin-Wolf (Pfalz), Christmann (Pfalz), Müller-Catoir (Pfalz), Knipser (Pfalz), Rebholz (Pfalz), Wegeler (Pfalz), Keller (Rheinhessen), Wittmann (Rheinhessen), Battenfeld-Spanier (Rheinhessen), Kühling-Gillot (Rheinhessen), Meyer-Näkel (Ahr), Jean Stodden (Ahr), Hermann Dönnhoff (Nahe), and Schäfer-Fröhlich (Nahe). The Verband Deutscher Prädikatsweingüter (VDP), the German Premium Wine Growers Association, is one of the most important wine quality bodies in Europe; its Rheinland-Pfalz members lead the German fine-wine market.

Universities and research are economic pillars. The Johannes Gutenberg-Universität Mainz, the Technische Universität Kaiserslautern, the Universität Trier, the Universität Koblenz-Landau and the Hochschule Trier are the main higher-education institutions. The Helmholtz-Institut Mainz, the Max-Planck-Institut für Chemie (the Otto-Hahn-Institut), the Max-Planck-Institut für Polymerforschung, the Max-Planck-Institut für Marine Mikrobiologie (Mainz branch) and the Institute for Microelectronics Stuttgart (Schenkenfeld near Mainz) form the research backbone. The German Federal Tax Office (Bundeszentralamt für Steuern), the Federal Office for Civil Protection and Disaster Assistance (BBK) and the Federal Office of Administration (BVA) are at Bonn but with Rheinland-Pfalz operations.',
    introduced_species = 'Rheinland-Pfalz, with its position on the Rhine corridor connecting the North Sea ports to the Alpine foothills, its substantial forests of the Pfälzerwald, Eifel, Hunsrück and Westerwald, and its extensive viticultural landscape, hosts a wide roster of introduced and invasive species. The Landesamt für Umwelt Rheinland-Pfalz (LfU RLP) at Mainz coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Rheinland-Pfalz since the 1960s when individuals from the Hessian Edersee 1934 release expanded west across the Westerwald and the Hunsrück. Today the species is established throughout RLP with the highest densities in the Eifel, the Pfälzerwald, the Westerwald, the Hunsrück and increasingly in the suburban Mainz, Koblenz and Trier areas. Annual hunting bags in RLP exceed 25,000 raccoons. The LfU RLP publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the handling of raccoon latrines. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds, on amphibians at the maar lakes of the Vulkaneifel, on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroductions, and on the rare wildcat populations of the Eifel National Park.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached RLP from the east in the 2000s; today the species is established throughout RLP with the highest densities in the Eifel, the Pfälzerwald and the Hunsrück. Annual hunting bags exceed 8,000.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Lower Rhine (Mainz-Koblenz), the Mosel, the Saar, the Nahe, the Lahn and the Ahr. Damage to flood-protection dykes is a serious management concern; the LfU RLP and the local water authorities coordinate trapping. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to RLP but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and is now spreading across the state. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout RLP.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised RLP since around 2017 from north-eastern German populations; the state now has the first established Westerwald wolf pack and individual wolves are recorded across the Eifel. The RLP Wolves Office (LUWG-Wolfsbeauftragter) coordinates monitoring.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations along the Rhine and Mosel. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded explosively; RLP has dense Egyptian goose populations throughout. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has established breeding populations in Mainz, Wiesbaden (technically Hessen but the populations cross into RLP), Koblenz and Bonn (NRW border). The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on RLP park ponds.

Among freshwater fish, the Rhine and Mosel host extensive introduced fish populations. The pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) are widespread. The bighead goby, Ponticola kessleri, and the Caspian Kessler''s goby have reached RLP via the Rhine. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis) has been reintroduced.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis). The Rhine in RLP is heavily invaded.

The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in RLP from 2017 onwards with confirmed nests throughout the state; the Pfalz and the Rheinhessen wine regions have been particularly affected, with substantial impact on bee colonies of the Imkerverband Rheinland-Pfalz. The harlequin ladybird, the horse-chestnut leaf miner, the box tree moth, the brown marmorated stink bug (a major pest of RLP wine grapes), and the spotted-wing drosophila Drosophila suzukii (a serious pest of RLP wine and stone-fruit cultivation) are all ubiquitous. The Drosophila suzukii since its first European detection in 2008 has spread across all RLP wine regions and prompted intensive integrated pest management research by the Julius Kühn-Institut.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, particularly conspicuous in the Mosel and Eifel valleys), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), the Senecio inaequidens and Indian balsam are widespread. The Pfälzerwald, the Eifel and the Hunsrück have substantial knotweed and balsam invasions along stream banks.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Pfälzerwald, the Eifel, the Hunsrück and the Westerwald. The mouflon, Ovis aries musimon, was introduced to the Pfälzerwald in the 1880s by hunting societies and has formed substantial feral populations. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Eifel. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density, with annual hunting bags exceeding 60,000 statewide. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Pfälzerwald, the Eifel and the Hunsrück, and the RLP wildcat population is one of the largest in Germany.'
WHERE region_name = 'Rheinland-Pfalz';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Saarland is the smallest of the German federal states by area (excluding the city-states), covering 2,569 square kilometres with around 990,000 inhabitants. The Saarland lies in the south-western corner of Germany, bordered by France (the historic Lorraine region) to the south-west and west and by Luxembourg to the north-west. The state capital is Saarbrücken, and the other major towns include Völklingen, Saarlouis, Neunkirchen, Homburg, St. Ingbert, Merzig and Sankt Wendel. The Saarland has a distinctive cross-border French-influenced culture and was the last German Bundesland to join the Federal Republic, doing so on 1 January 1957 after a referendum.

The Saarschleife (Saar Loop), the dramatic 180-degree meander of the Saar river at Mettlach where the river bends back on itself around the wooded Tafelfelsen ridge, is the most photographed natural feature in Saarland. The classic viewpoint is the Cloef above Orscholz, accessible by car, hiking trail, or via the Baumwipfelpfad Saarschleife (the Saarschleife Treetop Walk, opened 2016, a 1,250-metre wooden walkway through the forest canopy ending at a 42-metre spiral viewing tower above the Saar Loop). Nearby is the Cloef Atrium and the iconic Cloef-Hotel. The bend itself, viewed from above, is one of the most striking river-meander panoramas in Europe.

The Völklinger Hütte (Völklingen Ironworks) is a UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1994) — the only completely preserved ironworks of the early industrial age in the world. The complex includes the six blast furnaces, the gas blower halls, the sintering plant, the coke oven battery, the iron ore loading dock, the pig-iron casting platforms, and the steam blower hall. The site operated from 1873 to 1986 as a major Saar pig-iron producer, employing up to 17,000 workers at its peak; since closure it has been transformed into one of the most ambitious industrial-heritage destinations in Europe, hosting contemporary art exhibitions in the cathedral-like Gebläsehalle and the Möllerhalle, and supporting the Urban Art Biennale every other year. The Völklinger Hütte attracts around 300,000 visitors per year.

Saarbrücken, the state capital, has a distinctive Franco-German character. The Schloss Saarbrücken (the baroque palace built by Friedrich Joachim Stengel for Prince Wilhelm Heinrich of Nassau-Saarbrücken in 1748, with the modern central glass extension by Gottfried Böhm of 1989), the Ludwigskirche by Stengel (one of the most beautiful protestant baroque churches in Germany), the Ludwigsplatz baroque square, the Schlossplatz, the Stiftskirche Sankt Arnual (the historic Romanesque-Gothic church with the tombs of the Nassau-Saarbrücken counts), and the Alte Brücke over the Saar (the medieval bridge of 1546) form the historic core. The St. Johanner Markt with its baroque fountain and the iconic Stengel houses, the Berliner Promenade along the Saar, the Saarbrücker Stadtgalerie of contemporary art, the Saarlandmuseum (with its Moderne Galerie and Alte Sammlung), the Bergwerksmuseum at Camphausen, the Saarbrücker Schloss with the Saarbrücken Historisches Museum, the Schloss Halberg, the Deutsch-Französischer Garten (a 50-hectare French-style park created jointly with French Lorraine in 1960) and the Saarbrücker Zoo round out the city.

Saarlouis was founded in 1680 by King Louis XIV of France and fortified by his military engineer Sebastien Le Prestre de Vauban as a French frontier fortress town. The Vauban-style six-pointed star-shaped fortifications partly survive (the Vauban-Insel), as does the historic Französisches Tor (French Gate), the Deutsches Tor (German Gate), the Großer Markt with the Vauban-style colonnaded buildings, the Ludwig-Garten, the Ludwigskirche, and the Vauban-Festung itself. Saarlouis was an Imperial possession of the French crown until the 1815 Congress of Vienna; the city remains marked by its French-baroque urban planning today.

Mettlach is the home of Villeroy & Boch, the historic German ceramics company founded in 1748 at Audun-le-Tiche (then Lorraine, France) and headquartered at Mettlach since 1809. The historic Villeroy & Boch Old Abbey, the Keravision museum and visitor centre, the Villeroy & Boch Schloss Ziegelberg and the Old Abbey with its baroque interior all reflect the Boch-Buschmann-Villeroy family heritage. Villeroy & Boch produces porcelain tableware, sanitary ceramics, tiles and bathroom fittings sold worldwide. The Mettlach factory outlet is a popular tourist shopping destination.

The Wolfspark Werner Freund near Merzig is one of the most famous wolf-sanctuary parks in Europe, founded by the Saarland wolf researcher Werner Freund (1933-2014) in 1972. Freund spent his career hand-rearing wolf cubs to become accustomed to humans, and the Wolfspark today hosts around 30 wolves in six packs (representing different sub-species: European, Polish, Arctic, Mongolian, Iberian and Timber wolf) in 100 hectares of forest enclosures. Visitors can watch the wolves at feeding times and during the famous Werner Freund pack interactions.

The Bostalsee, the largest artificial lake in south-western Germany at 120 hectares, hosts the Center Parcs Bostalsee resort, swimming beaches, sailing, kayaking and surrounding hiking trails. The Saarland Therme at Rilchingen-Hanweiler (the largest spa complex in Saarland), the Limburg an der Saar Roman ruins, the Schaumberg above Tholey (the highest point in Saarland at 569 metres) with the Mont des Schaumberg viewing tower and the Tholey Benedictine Abbey (a UNESCO Soundscape monument with the famous Gerhard Richter stained-glass windows installed 2020), the Hochwald National Park (Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark, shared with Rheinland-Pfalz, established 2015), the Wildpark Saarbrücken-Burbach, and the Limesmuseum at Reinheim complete the natural-cultural offer. The Schloss Berg at Nennig contains the Roman Villa Nennig mosaic floor (one of the largest and best-preserved Roman mosaics north of the Alps, dating from around AD 200, depicting gladiatorial games and now displayed in situ under a protective building).

History before 1933 is varied. The Saar territory was Roman (the Trier capital and the Saarbrücken legionary camp), then Frankish, then divided among the various Carolingian Successor lands. The historic Counts of Nassau-Saarbrücken ruled from the 11th century, with parts annexed by Louis XIV and the Vauban fortifications at Saarlouis (1680). After Napoleon, the 1815 Congress of Vienna divided the Saar between Prussia (the coal-mining north and east), Bavaria (the Pfalz section), and Saxe-Coburg (small enclaves). The 1871 unification brought the Saar into the German Empire. After World War I, the 1919 Treaty of Versailles placed the Saargebiet under a League of Nations Mandate (1920-1935) to allow France to mine the coalfields as reparations; the 1935 referendum returned the Saar to Germany (90 per cent voted to rejoin). After 1945 the French occupation zone, then the Saarland Protectorate (1947-1957) with its own currency (the Saar Franc) and own postal stamps; the January 1957 referendum (the Saarland Treaty of 1956) reunited the Saarland with the Federal Republic of Germany as its tenth Bundesland.

Saarland cuisine, distinctively French-influenced, includes the Lyoner sausage (a Lyon-style mortadella-type pork sausage, the iconic Saarland sausage), Geheiratete (Saarländer "married couples", a dish of potato dumplings with potato salad and bacon), Hoorische (Saarland "hairy" potato dumplings made from raw grated potato), Dibbelabbes (a fried potato-pork hash baked in a Dutch oven, traditionally served with apple sauce), the Schwenker (the iconic Saarland grill, a charcoal-fired iron tripod with a chain-suspended grate that swings over the fire to cook marinated pork-neck steaks), the Saarländischer Sauerbraten, the Saarländischer Schmandkuchen, the Quetsch flammed cake, the Bohnensuppe and the Lyoner Salat. Drinks: Saarländische Weine (from the small Schloss Berg, Mettlach and Saar Loop vineyards, with around 100 hectares of Riesling, Müller-Thurgau and Spätburgunder), plus the imported Mosel and Saar wines. Beer is dominated by Karlsberg Brauerei at Homburg (the largest German privately-owned brewery group, brewing Karlsberg UrPils, Karlsberg Mixery, Mixery Sportsfreund, Becks Pale Ale licensee for Saarland, Königpilsener and many other brands), the Saarfürst Brauerei at Merzig, the Bruch Brauerei at Saarbrücken, the Brauhaus Bostalsee, the Becker Bräu at St. Ingbert and the Neufang Brauerei at Saarbrücken. The Karlsberg group, founded 1878 by Christian Weber at Homburg, has annual revenues of around 250 million euros. Saarland coffee culture is French-influenced; pastry shops along the German-French border produce both German Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte and French éclairs and pain au chocolat.',
    transportation = 'Saarbrücken Airport, IATA SCN and ICAO EDDR, is the principal commercial airport of the Saarland, located east of Saarbrücken on the Ensheim plateau. It handles around 350,000 passengers per year with limited operations by Luxair (Luxembourg connections), Air Service Vienna, Vueling and seasonal Mediterranean charters. The airport handles substantial business-aviation traffic for the Saar industrial cluster. Zweibrücken Airport (ZQW, EDRZ), technically in Rheinland-Pfalz but commercially used by the Saarland region, was closed for commercial service in 2014 but remains active for general aviation. The cross-border Luxembourg-Findel Airport (LUX, ELLX) and Metz-Nancy-Lorraine Airport (ETZ, LFJL) in France serve the Saarland from across the borders, with substantial Saarland commuter traffic. The Frankfurt-Hahn Airport, although in Rheinland-Pfalz, is used by some Saarland leisure travellers.

Saarbrücken Hauptbahnhof is the main railway hub of the state, opened 1852 with the Bayerische Pfälzische Ludwigsbahn. The station handles intensive ICE and TGV inOui services on the Mannheim-Saarbrücken-Paris-Est corridor, with the Paris-East ICE/TGV-inOui Eastern Europe Trains making the Saarbrücken-Paris-Est journey in around 1 hour 45 minutes since 2007 when the LGV Est high-speed line opened in France. ICE services to Frankfurt, Mannheim, Stuttgart and Munich complete the long-distance offer. The local Saar tramway system (Saarbahn), one of the most innovative tram-train systems in Europe, has been operating since 1997 on the Karlsruhe model with through-running from city tram tracks to the heavy-rail network; the Saarbahn runs to Saargemünd (Sarreguemines) in France, making it one of only two cross-border tram-train networks in the world (the other being the Strasbourg-Kehl tram). The Saarbahn has two lines (S1 between Saarbrücken Riegelsberg and Saarbrücken-Brebach via Saarbrücken Hauptbahnhof, plus the proposed extension to Lebach-Jabach). The cross-border Saarbrücken-Sarreguemines tram-train is operated by the Saarbahn GmbH and the SNCF as a joint enterprise. The Saarbrücker Verkehrsverbund (saarVV) and the Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Neckar (VRN) coordinate regional tariff.

The Saar canal (Saar Wasserstraße), canalised between 1986 and 1999, connects the Mosel at Konz (Trier) to the French Canal de la Marne au Rhin, allowing Rhine-Mosel-Saar barge traffic to reach the French canal network. The Saarbrücken-Bous and the Saarlouis Hafen are the principal Saar inland ports. The Dillinger Hütte Hafen has its own port facility on the Saar.

The Autobahn network in Saarland is anchored by the A6 (Mannheim-Saarbrücken-Paris, with the cross-border Goldene Bremm at Saarbrücken-Forbach connecting to the French A4), the A8 (Luxembourg-Saarbrücken-Pirmasens-Karlsruhe), the A1 (Saarbrücken-Trier-Cologne-Bremen), the A620 (the Saarbrücken Autobahn along the Saar, connecting Saarbrücken to Saarlouis and Merzig), and the A623 (the Saarbrücken north-south spur). Bundesstraßen include the B41 from Saarbrücken to Mainz via Idar-Oberstein and Bad Kreuznach, the B51 from Trier via Merzig to Saarbrücken, the B406 along the Saar valley, the B423 to Homburg, and the B268 from Saarbrücken via Sankt Wendel to Lebach. Cycling routes include the Saar-Radweg from Sarreguemines via Saarbrücken to Mettlach and onward to Trier on the Mosel, the Velo Tour Sarre-Lor-Lux cross-border cycling network, the Tour de Sarre cycling marathon, and the Hunsrück-Hochwald-Radweg.',
    economics = 'Saarland has a regional GDP of around 38 billion euros and a per-capita GDP slightly below the German average, reflecting the post-industrial transition of the historic coal-and-steel economy. The Saar coal-mining industry, the historic backbone of the Saarland economy, completely closed in 2012 when the last coal mine (the Bergwerk Saar at Ensdorf) shut down; the iron and steel industry retains a smaller but still significant presence. The Saarland economic development arm, the Gesellschaft für Wirtschaftsförderung Saar (gws), and the Saarland Standortagentur market the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer des Saarlandes at Saarbrücken represents the regional businesses.

The largest single private employer in Saarland is the Ford-Werke Saarlouis plant, the Ford passenger-car factory at Saarlouis-Roden, which has built the Ford Fiesta and the Ford Focus models for European markets since 1968. The Saarlouis plant employs around 4,500 workers (down from a peak of 8,000) and is undergoing a controversial wind-down as Ford pivots its European production strategy; the Fiesta ended production in June 2023, and the Saarlouis plant has been earmarked for closure with the loss of remaining production to other Ford facilities, although a buyer search has not yet succeeded. The Saarlouis Industrial Park has the Bosch Saarbrücken automotive electronics plant, the Schaeffler Group Homburg precision-bearings plant, the ZF Saarbrücken Group transmissions plant, the Hager Werke (the German electrical-distribution-board specialist), the Mast-Jägermeister Saar distribution centre, and many automotive Tier-1 and Tier-2 suppliers.

ZF Saarbrücken GmbH, the listed automotive-supplier group''s largest German automotive-transmission plant, employs around 9,000 workers at Saarbrücken and produces the 8HP and 9HP automatic-transmission models for BMW, Audi, Jaguar Land Rover, Volvo and other premium automotive customers. The Saarbrücken Automatic Transmission Innovation Center is one of the largest single transmission plants in the world.

Saarstahl AG, the listed Völklingen-headquartered long-products steel producer (the largest German producer of rolled wire, wire rod and high-strength bars for the automotive and construction industries), is one of the largest German steel producers, with revenues of around 3 billion euros and 6,000 employees. Saarstahl operates the integrated steelworks at Völklingen, Burbach, Dillingen and Neunkirchen. The Saarstahl Group is jointly owned with Dillinger Hütte through the SHS Stahl-Holding-Saar (a Saarland family-foundation-controlled holding). Dillinger Hütte (AG der Dillinger Hüttenwerke) at Dillingen is the world''s largest producer of heavy plate (plates from 5 to 700 millimetres thick), supplying around 1.5 million tonnes per year to global shipbuilding (the world''s largest container ships), pipelines (the Trans-Alaska Pipeline, the Nord Stream pipelines), offshore wind monopiles, military vehicles and pressure vessels. The integrated Dillinger Hütte steelworks employs around 5,000 workers. The Saarstahl Wadgassen iron mill, the Saarstahl Rail (specialty rail), and the historic Saarstahl Roechling foundry round out the steel cluster. The Saar coal-and-steel industry is being transformed into a green-hydrogen and green-steel cluster under the federal Strukturwandel programme, with the new SHS Group hydrogen-DRI plant at Dillingen planned for the 2030s.

Halberg Guss GmbH, founded 1756, is one of the oldest German iron foundries, still operating in Brebach (Saarbrücken). The Halberg Guss specialises in engine blocks and crankshafts for the automotive industry. The Halberg Guss insolvency in 2018 was a major Saarland industrial event.

Villeroy & Boch AG, the listed Mettlach-headquartered ceramics company founded 1748, is one of the world''s leading producers of fine tableware, sanitary ceramics, bathroom fittings and tiles. The Villeroy & Boch Mettlach campus includes the corporate headquarters in the historic Old Abbey, the original 18th-century manufacturing site (still in production), the Keravision museum and the Saarland''s largest factory outlet. Villeroy & Boch has annual revenues of around 850 million euros and 7,500 employees worldwide.

Globus SB-Warenhaus Holding GmbH & Co. KG of Sankt Wendel, the family-owned (Bruch family) hypermarket chain, is the third-largest German hypermarket operator after Metro Real and Kaufland, with around 50 stores and revenues of 8 billion euros. The Globus DIY-Stores division, the Globus Restauration restaurants, and the Globus Verbrauchermärkte complete the group.

The Karlsberg Brauerei AG of Homburg, the family-owned (Weber family) brewery founded 1878 at Homburg, is the largest privately owned brewery group in Germany, with annual revenues of around 280 million euros and 1,000 employees. Karlsberg produces the Karlsberg UrPils, Karlsberg Mixery and other brands; the Becker Bräu (Sankt Ingbert) is a sister Saar brewery.

In the higher-education sector, the Saarland Universität (Universität des Saarlandes) at Saarbrücken-Dudweiler has around 17,000 students with strong programmes in computer science (the historic German pioneer in artificial intelligence), in cybersecurity (the CISPA Helmholtz-Zentrum für Informationssicherheit is one of the largest German cyber-security research centres, founded 2007 at Saarbrücken with around 600 researchers), in computer linguistics, in materials science, and in pharmacy. The Deutsche Forschungszentrum für Künstliche Intelligenz (DFKI, the German Research Center for Artificial Intelligence) was founded 1988 at Saarbrücken by Wolfgang Wahlster and Hans-Werner Hein; today the DFKI is one of the largest AI research centres in Europe with around 1,500 researchers across campuses at Saarbrücken, Kaiserslautern, Berlin, Bremen, Trier, Osnabrück and Oldenburg. The Max-Planck-Institut für Informatik and the Max-Planck-Institut für Softwaresysteme at Saarbrücken-Saarbrücken complete the Saarbrücken Computer Science campus, which is one of the leading computer-science research clusters in continental Europe. The Hochschule für Technik und Wirtschaft des Saarlandes (HTW Saar), the Hochschule für Musik Saar and the Hochschule der Bildenden Künste Saar (HBKsaar) round out the higher-education sector. The Hochschule für Musik Saar has the famous Jugend musiziert competition.

The Saarland Federal Bundeswehr base at Lebach hosts the Bundeswehr Logistics Battalion. The historic French Forces in Germany (the Forces Françaises en Allemagne) withdrew from the Saarland in 1999 with the closure of the Saarbrücken military bases. The US Forces in Europe do not have major Saarland installations.

Banking and finance are dominated by the Landesbank Saar (SaarLB, jointly owned with the Bayerische Landesbank since 2002), the Sparkasse Saarbrücken, the Sparkasse Merzig-Wadern, the Sparkasse St. Wendel, the Sparkasse Neunkirchen, the Sparkasse Saarlouis and the cooperative Volksbank Saarpfalz. Insurance includes the SAARLAND Versicherungen, the Provinzial Saar and the historic Saarländische Wohnungsbau-Genossenschaft (SWG).

Tourism is a smaller economic sector than in the larger German states, but the Saarschleife treetop walk, the Völklinger Hütte UNESCO site, the Wolfspark Merzig, the Bostalsee Center Parcs and the cross-border Sarre-Lor-Lux Esprit Région all generate substantial visitor flows. The Saarland-Therme, the Mettlach Villeroy & Boch outlet and the Schloss Berg Roman villa attract day-trippers from across the border.',
    introduced_species = 'Saarland, despite its small area, hosts a representative roster of introduced and invasive species, with strong representation of the species spread from the historic French Lorraine border and from the Westerwald-Eifel corridor. The Ministerium für Umwelt, Klima, Mobilität, Agrar und Verbraucherschutz Saarland coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014; the Naturschutzbund Saarland (NABU Saarland) supports monitoring.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Saarland since the 1970s when individuals from the Hessian Edersee 1934 release expanded west across the Hunsrück. Today the species is established throughout Saarland with the highest densities in the Saarbrücken-Saargemünd cross-border area, the Hochwald, the Bliesgau Biosphere Reserve and the Saarschleife landscape. Annual hunting bags in Saarland are modest by national standards (a few thousand animals per year) reflecting the state''s small size. The Saarland state hunters'' association (Vereinigte Jagdgenossenschaften Saarland) publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing and the handling of raccoon latrines. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds, on amphibians and on the rare wildcat populations of the Hunsrück-Hochwald National Park.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Saarland from the east in the 2000s; today the species is established throughout Saarland with the highest densities in the Hochwald, the Schaumberg and the Saarschleife. Annual hunting bags exceed 1,500. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Saar river, the Blies, the Prims and the Bist. Damage to flood-protection dykes and to reedbeds is a serious management concern; the Saarland Wasserbehörde and the local Wasser- und Bodenverbände coordinate trapping. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Saarland but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU Saar and is now spreading along the Saar and the Blies. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Saarland in slow waters.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised Saarland since around 2019 from north-eastern German populations and from the French Vosges populations; the state has occasional records but no established pack as of 2024. The Saarland Wolves Office at the state environment ministry coordinates monitoring.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established small feral resident populations on the Bostalsee, the Losheim See, and along the Saar. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded into Saarland from the Rheinland-Pfalz populations and now breeds across the state. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is occasional in Saarbrücken-Saargemünd but has not established large breeding populations.

Among freshwater fish, the Saar and Blies host the standard set of introduced species: the pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus). The Saar round goby reached Saarland via the Mosel and the cross-border French Saar in the early 2010s. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis) has been reintroduced.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, regularly trapped in the Saar). The Asian hornet, Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse, has been recorded in Saarland from 2016 onwards (one of the earliest German records, the species having advanced from northern France via Lorraine across the Saar frontier); the Saarländischer Imkerbund coordinates nest-removal teams with the state environment ministry. By 2024 dozens of Asian hornet nests had been removed in Saarland. The harlequin ladybird, Harmonia axyridis, Asiatischer Marienkäfer, is ubiquitous. The horse-chestnut leaf miner, Cameraria ohridella, defoliates the Saarland chestnut avenues every late summer. The box tree moth, Cydalima perspectalis, Buchsbaumzünsler, has destroyed boxwood gardens at Schloss Saarbrücken, the Saarlouis Vauban-Festung and various Saarland private gardens. The brown marmorated stink bug, Halyomorpha halys, Marmorierte Baumwanze, is established. The Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) has been recorded as a port arrival from Asian-import packaging at Saarbrücken industrial sites; an emergency containment programme was successful.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, widespread along the Saar and the Blies), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-coal-mining brownfields and on the Bergehalden slag heaps of the former Saarland coal-mining areas), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, planted extensively on the historic Saarland Bergehalden), the Senecio inaequidens (a major coloniser of disturbed sandy and slag-heap soil in the Saarland coal-mining heritage areas), and the Indian balsam are widespread. The Saarland coal-mining heritage Bergehalden (slag heaps) and the post-industrial brownfields have particularly distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities studied by the Saarbrücken Universität ecologists.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Hochwald, the Schaumberg, the Bliesgau and the Saarwellingen forestry. The mouflon was introduced in the 1880s and has formed feral populations. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) are absent from Saarland. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density across the state, with annual hunting bags exceeding 15,000. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark.'
WHERE region_name = 'Saarland';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Sachsen, in English Saxony, the historic core of the medieval Margraviate of Meissen and the early modern Electorate of Saxony, is one of the cultural heartlands of Germany. The Free State of Saxony (Freistaat Sachsen) covers 18,420 square kilometres and has around 4.1 million inhabitants. The state capital is Dresden, while Leipzig (the largest city), Chemnitz, Zwickau, Görlitz, Plauen, Bautzen and Meissen are the other major urban centres.

Dresden, the elegant baroque capital on the Elbe, is one of the most beautifully reconstructed cities of post-war Europe. The Dresdner Frauenkirche (Church of Our Lady), the iconic protestant cathedral by George Bähr completed 1743, was destroyed in the bombing of February 1945 and rebuilt between 1994 and 2005 using as many of the original stones as possible (the new white stones contrasting with the original blackened ones); the reopening of the Frauenkirche on 30 October 2005 was one of the most emotional moments of post-Cold-War German reconciliation. The Dresdner Zwinger, the rococo masterpiece by Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann commissioned by Augustus the Strong as an orangerie and festival pavilion (1709-1728), is the iconic Dresden tourist attraction. The Zwinger houses the Gemäldegalerie Alte Meister (the Old Masters Picture Gallery, one of the great European fine-art collections, with the Sistine Madonna of Raphael, the Sleeping Venus of Giorgione, the Tribute Money of Titian, the Chocolate Girl by Liotard, and works by Vermeer, Rembrandt, Rubens, Velázquez and the Cranachs), the Porzellansammlung (the Saxon Porcelain Collection, the largest collection of Meissen porcelain in the world), the Mathematisch-Physikalischer Salon, and the historic Glockenspielpavillon. The Dresden Residenzschloss (the Royal Palace) contains the famous Grünes Gewölbe (Green Vault), the historic Saxon treasury established by Augustus the Strong in 1723, today divided into the Historic Green Vault on the ground floor (with the original 18th-century display setting, the world''s most opulent treasury room, holding the Mughal Court at Delhi by Dinglinger, the Tafelaufsatz Bath of Diana, the Cherry Stone with 185 carved faces, and over 3,000 other masterpieces) and the New Green Vault on the upper floor (with modern display cases, holding the famous Dresdner Grüner Diamant of 41 carats, the world''s largest known faceted green diamond). The Hofkirche (Court Church), the Catholic baroque cathedral by Gaetano Chiaveri of 1739-1755, the Semperoper Dresden (the Semper Opera House by Gottfried Semper of 1841, rebuilt 1985, home of the Saxon State Opera), the Brühlsche Terrasse (the so-called Balcony of Europe along the Elbe), the Albertinum (containing the Gemäldegalerie Neue Meister, the New Masters Gallery, and the Skulpturensammlung), the Japanisches Palais, the Großer Garten with the Sommerpalais, the Kreuzkirche with the Dresdner Kreuzchor (the boys'' choir founded 1216), the Türkischer Brunnen, the Kurländer Palais, the Procession of the Princes mural on the wall of the Stallhof (the longest porcelain mural in the world, 102 metres of 23,000 Meissen porcelain tiles depicting the Saxon Wettin dynasty), the Yenidze (the former cigarette factory in the style of an Ottoman mosque), and the Blaue Wunder (Blue Wonder) suspension bridge over the Elbe complete the city.

The Saxon Switzerland (Sächsische Schweiz), the spectacular sandstone-pillar landscape along the upper Elbe in the Elbsandsteingebirge, is one of the most photographed German landscapes. The Bastei rock formation and the Basteibrücke (the iconic 1851 sandstone arch bridge spanning the pillars), the Königstein Fortress (one of the largest hilltop fortresses in Europe at 9.5 hectares with 240 buildings on the plateau, never captured in 800 years of history), the Festung Lilienstein, the Festung Hohnstein, the Schrammsteine pillars, the Pfaffenstein, the Falkenstein (a major German climbing destination since the 19th century), the Polenztal, the Kirnitzschtal, the Schmilka and Bad Schandau spa towns and the Kirnitzschtalbahn historic tram line make the Saxon Switzerland a major German hiking destination.

Meissen, the historic capital of the Margraviate, is dominated by the Albrechtsburg Castle (the first true German castle-residence as opposed to defensive fortress, built between 1471 and 1525 by Arnold von Westfalen for the Saxon Wettin dukes) and the Meissen Cathedral (built between 1250 and 1410, a major Saxon Gothic monument). Meissen is also home to the Meissen Porcelain Manufactory (Staatliche Porzellan-Manufaktur Meissen), the first European hard-paste porcelain manufactory, founded in 1710 by Johann Friedrich Böttger and Ehrenfried Walther von Tschirnhaus after they discovered the secret of true porcelain (the so-called Arcanum) for Augustus the Strong. The Meissen Manufactory still produces porcelain today and offers tours and an exhibition (the Meissen Porcelain Museum) showcasing 300 years of Meissen production from the early Böttger stoneware through the famous Blue Onion pattern to contemporary designs. The Meissen brand mark of the crossed swords is one of the oldest registered trademarks in the world (used since 1722).

Leipzig, the largest city of Saxony, is famous as a music and book capital. The Thomaskirche (St. Thomas Church) on the Thomaskirchhof was the workplace of Johann Sebastian Bach as the Cantor of the Thomas School from 1723 to 1750; Bach is buried in front of the altar. The Thomanerchor, the famous boys'' choir founded 1212, still performs every Friday at 18:00 and every Saturday at 15:00. The Nikolaikirche, on Nikolaistraße, is famous as the site of the 1989 Peaceful Revolution, where the Monday peace prayers (Friedensgebete) gathered tens of thousands of demonstrators in the weeks leading up to 9 October 1989, when 70,000 people marched around the Leipzig inner ring chanting "Wir sind das Volk" (We are the people) — the demonstrations that triggered the fall of the Berlin Wall a month later. The Auerbachs Keller wine restaurant in the Mädler-Passage, immortalised by Goethe in Faust I (1808) as the place where Mephistopheles takes Faust to drink wine with the students, has been operating since 1525. The Völkerschlachtdenkmal (Monument to the Battle of the Nations), the 91-metre granite monument erected 1913 to commemorate the centennial of the 1813 Battle of Leipzig that ended Napoleon''s German rule, is one of the largest monuments in Europe and offers a dramatic viewing platform. The Gewandhaus Leipzig (the Gewandhausorchester home, the orchestra founded 1743, the oldest civic concert orchestra in the world, led by Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy 1835-1847, Arthur Nikisch, Bruno Walter, Wilhelm Furtwängler, Kurt Masur 1970-1996, Riccardo Chailly 2005-2016, and currently Andris Nelsons), the Leipziger Buchmesse (the second-largest German book fair after Frankfurt, but the oldest, founded 1632), the Mädler Passage (the historic shopping arcade), the Hauptbahnhof Leipzig (the largest terminal railway station in Europe by surface area at 84,000 square metres), the historic Karli neighbourhood with its restored Gründerzeit buildings, the Spinnerei (the converted Leipzig Cotton Mill, now one of Europe''s most ambitious contemporary art venues hosting the famous Leipzig school painters Neo Rauch, Tilo Baumgärtel, David Schnell and Tim Eitel), and the Leipzig Zoo with the Gondwanaland tropical hall complete the city.

Görlitz, the easternmost German city on the Polish border (the river Neisse separates Görlitz from its Polish twin Zgorzelec), is one of the most beautiful preserved Renaissance-baroque town centres in Germany, with around 4,000 listed buildings and almost no wartime destruction. The Untermarkt with the Görlitzer Rathaus, the Schönhof (the oldest German Renaissance burgher house, built 1525-1530), the Frauenturm, the Peterskirche, the Heiliger Grab (the unique 15th-century replica of the Holy Sepulchre of Jerusalem brought to Görlitz by Bürgermeister Georg Emerich, the only complete medieval pilgrimage replica north of the Alps), the Reichenbacher Turm and the Vierradenmühle complete the historic core. Görlitz has been a favoured film location for many internationally distributed productions including Wes Anderson''s The Grand Budapest Hotel (2014), Quentin Tarantino''s Inglourious Basterds (2009), Steven Daldry''s The Reader (2008) and many others, earning the nickname Görliwood.

The Erzgebirge (Ore Mountains), the historic mining range along the Saxon-Bohemian border, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2019 as the Erzgebirge/Krušnohoří Mining Region, jointly with Czechia. The historic mining towns of Annaberg-Buchholz (with the magnificent late-Gothic Annenkirche of 1499-1525), Schneeberg (with the famous painted altar of the Bergaltar by Lucas Cranach the Elder of 1539), Marienberg, Olbernhau, and Freiberg (the home of the world''s oldest mining academy, the Bergakademie Freiberg of 1765, where Alexander von Humboldt, Friedrich Mohs and Abraham Gottlob Werner taught) all reflect the centuries-old Saxon mining heritage. The Erzgebirge is also famous for its wooden craft traditions, particularly the Christmas Pyramids (rotating multi-tier wooden carousels with figures, lit by candles), the Räuchermännchen (wooden incense smoker figurines), the Nussknacker nutcracker figures, and the Schwibbogen (illuminated wooden arches placed in windows during Advent). Major Erzgebirge wood-craft villages include Seiffen (the famous Erzgebirgische Spielzeugindustrie centre with the Spielzeugmuseum Seiffen) and Oberammergau (technically Bavaria). The Bergmannsschicht parade and the Christmas markets at Annaberg, Marienberg and Schneeberg are major regional traditions.

The Lausitz (Upper Lusatia), the south-eastern corner of Saxony around Bautzen and Görlitz, is the historic homeland of the Sorbs (the Slavic minority of Saxony and Brandenburg). Bautzen is the capital of Upper Sorbian (the Sorbischer Domowina), with the Bautzen Cathedral St. Petri (the unique simultaneous church shared between Catholics and Protestants since 1524, with the famous internal wall separating the two congregations), the Bautzen Hauptmarkt, the historic Old Water Tower (Alte Wasserkunst), the Reichenturm and the Sorbisches Museum. Sorbian language signage is bilingual across the Lausitz.

Saxon cuisine and beverages are distinctive. Quarkkäulchen (small fried potato-quark pancakes traditionally eaten as Sunday breakfast), Dresdner Eierschecke (the iconic Dresden three-layer cake with quark, custard and yeast dough), Sächsischer Sauerbraten (with raisin gravy), Wickelklöße (rolled potato dumplings), Kartoffelsuppe (potato soup), Buttermilchgrieß, Plinsen (yeast pancakes), Dresdner Stollen (the Dresden Christmas Stollen, the most-famous fruit cake of Germany, made since 1474 and protected as the Dresdner Stollen with PGI status — only stollen made in Dresden can use the protected name), Pulsnitzer Pfefferkuchen (the Pulsnitz gingerbread tradition since 1558, the historic German gingerbread alternative to Nuremberg''s), the Bautzener Senf (the famous Bautzener mustard since 1866), and the Spreewald cucumbers (Spreewaldgurken, although these are from Brandenburg). Drinks include Radeberger Pilsner (the famous Saxon pilsner from Radeberg near Dresden since 1872, the oldest German pilsner outside Bavaria), Wernesgrüner Pilsner (since 1436), Sternburg (Leipzig), Köstritzer Schwarzbier (a historic Schwarzbier from Bad Köstritz, technically Thuringia), the Reichenbrander Brauerei at Chemnitz, the Feldschlößchen Dresden, and Kuhn-Pils. Saxon wines from the Meissen area, the smallest of Germany''s thirteen official wine-growing regions but with high prestige; major wineries include Schloss Wackerbarth (the state winery at Radebeul), Schloss Proschwitz (the historic Lippe-Prinz Schloss Proschwitz, with vineyards on the Elbe slopes), Schloss Klipphausen, and the Sächsisches Staatsweingut Schloss Wackerbarth (Sachsen''s state wine estate) producing fine Riesling, Müller-Thurgau, Goldriesling (a Sachsen specialty), Traminer, Weißburgunder, Grauburgunder and Spätburgunder. The Saxon Goldriesling, a cross between Riesling and Courtillier Musqué cultivated only in Saxony, is a unique Saxon variety. Saxon whisky (Drei Schwerter Whisky at Meissen) and Saxon gin (the Lankow distillery at Lankow) round out the spirits.

History before 1933 is rich. The Margraviate of Meissen, founded in 1089 by Henry of Eilenburg, became the core of the Saxon Albertine and Ernestine lines of the Wettin dynasty. The Saxon Electorate from 1356 onwards, with the Saxon Elector as one of the seven Holy Roman Empire Electors. Friedrich the Wise (1486-1525) was the patron of Martin Luther who hid him at the Wartburg Castle in 1521-1522 (the Wartburg is in Thuringia, but the patronage was Saxon). The 1547 Battle of Mühlberg divided the Wettin lands between the Albertine and Ernestine branches; the Albertines kept the Electorate, the Ernestines kept the Thuringian lands. Augustus the Strong (1670-1733), the Saxon Elector and Polish King from 1697 onwards (he converted to Catholicism to become Polish), made Dresden the great baroque cultural capital of Saxony with the Zwinger, the Grünes Gewölbe and the Albrechtsburg, and commissioned the rediscovery of European porcelain. The 1813 Battle of Leipzig (Battle of the Nations) ended Napoleon''s rule in Germany. The 1815 Congress of Vienna reduced Saxony in area (the northern parts were transferred to Prussia as the Province of Saxony — the present Saxony-Anhalt). The Industrial Revolution made Saxony the most industrialised German state by the 1880s, with Chemnitz the "Saxon Manchester" for textile production, Plauen the global centre of lace making, Leipzig the German publishing capital, Meissen the porcelain capital, and Zwickau the home of the Horch automotive industry (today Audi). The 1830 Saxon Constitution was one of the most progressive in Germany. After 1945 Saxony was placed in the Soviet zone, becoming part of the German Democratic Republic 1949-1990 (with the Bezirke Dresden, Karl-Marx-Stadt, Leipzig). The 1989 Peaceful Revolution (the Wende) started at the Nikolaikirche Leipzig with the Monday Peace Prayers. The 3 October 1990 reunification restored Saxony as a Free State (Freistaat Sachsen) of the Federal Republic.',
    transportation = 'Sachsen has the second-largest German rail network outside the Berlin-Hamburg-Cologne corridor and is well served by air, road and inland waterway. Leipzig/Halle Airport, IATA LEJ and ICAO EDDP, is the second-largest German cargo airport (after Frankfurt) thanks to the DHL European Hub at Leipzig-Halle (the DHL European Air Hub of Deutsche Post DHL Group, which moved from Brussels-Zaventem in 2008 because Belgian noise regulations had become restrictive for night-time cargo flights). LEJ also handles around 2.5 million passenger flights per year, with Eurowings, Ryanair, Wizz Air, easyJet, Lufthansa Cityline and the Mediterranean charter carriers. The airport is connected to Leipzig Hauptbahnhof by the S-Bahn line S5/S5X (Leipzig City Tunnel) in 15 minutes and the ICE/IC stop at Flughafen Halle/Leipzig serves the Munich-Berlin VDE 8 corridor. Dresden Airport, IATA DRS and ICAO EDDC, handles around 1.5 million passengers per year with Eurowings, Lufthansa Cityline, Sun Express and Mediterranean charter operations; the Dresden Airport is the home of the Elbe Flugzeugwerke (EFW) industrial-aircraft-conversion specialist (a joint venture of ST Engineering and Airbus). Other regional airfields include Chemnitz-Jahnsdorf, Bautzen, Klix and Klagewald.

The Saxony rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Fernverkehr and DB Regio Südost, with the regional brands Mitteldeutsche Regiobahn (MRB), Mitteldeutsche Eisenbahngesellschaft (MEG), Vogtlandbahn (Länderbahn), Erzgebirgsbahn, Sächsisch-Böhmische Eisenbahngesellschaft (Sächsisch-Böhmische Express) and DB Erzgebirgsbahn operating regional services. The Verkehrsverbund Oberelbe (VVO, the Dresden region), the Mitteldeutscher Verkehrsverbund (MDV, the Leipzig region), the Verkehrsverbund Oberlausitz-Niederschlesien (ZVON, the Görlitz-Bautzen region), the Verkehrsverbund Vogtland (VMS, the Chemnitz region) and the Verkehrsverbund Mittelsachsen coordinate integrated tariff.

Dresden Hauptbahnhof, opened 1898 with its iconic tent-shaped roof, has been restored after wartime damage and now handles around 60,000 passengers per day. Leipzig Hauptbahnhof, opened 1915 as the largest railway terminal in the world (and the largest in Europe by surface area at 84,000 square metres, including 23 platforms across two parallel halls), is one of the architectural masterpieces of German rail history. The Leipzig City Tunnel, opened 2013, links the Hauptbahnhof to the Leipzig-Connewitz station via the central Leipzig Markt and Wilhelm-Leuschner-Platz stations, allowing all Leipzig S-Bahn lines to run through-services. Other major Saxony rail nodes include Chemnitz Hauptbahnhof, Görlitz Hauptbahnhof, Zwickau Hauptbahnhof, Plauen and Riesa.

The ICE corridors crossing Saxony include the Berlin-Leipzig-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich high-speed line (VDE 8, the Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8, completed in December 2017, with the new Halle-Leipzig junction at Leipzig-Großkorbetha and the new Erfurt main station), the Berlin-Dresden corridor (the Dresdner Bahn, currently being upgraded for 200 kph through Brandenburg), the Frankfurt-Erfurt-Leipzig-Dresden corridor, and the Hamburg-Berlin-Dresden-Prague Eurocity services. The Dresden-Praha line (the Sächsisch-Böhmische line via the Elbe valley to Bohemia), the Cologne-Berlin-Dresden corridor and the Vienna-Dresden Vindobona historic train route remain important.

The Saxony tram networks are remarkable. The Leipzig tram network, operated by Leipziger Verkehrsbetriebe (LVB), with 13 lines totalling 145 kilometres, is the second-longest tram network in Germany after Berlin. The Dresden tram network, operated by Dresdner Verkehrsbetriebe (DVB), has 12 lines totalling 134 kilometres, making it the third-longest German tram network. The Chemnitz Stadtbahn, operated by City-Bahn Chemnitz, has six lines and uses tram-train technology similar to the Karlsruhe model. The Plauen tram, the Görlitz tram, the Zwickau tram and the historic Lockwitztalbahn (between Dresden-Niedersedlitz and Kreischa, the oldest German overland tramway in continuous operation since 1906) and the historic Kirnitzschtalbahn (a unique forest tram in the Sächsische Schweiz running from Bad Schandau to the Lichtenhainer Wasserfall since 1898) complete the system. The Dresdner Bergschwebebahn (the suspended monorail of 1901 — the world''s second-oldest suspended monorail after the Wuppertaler Schwebebahn) and the Standseilbahn Dresden (the Dresden funicular) are tourist attractions.

The Autobahn network in Sachsen includes the A4 (Aachen-Cologne-Erfurt-Dresden-Görlitz to the Polish border), the A9 (Munich-Nuremberg-Leipzig-Berlin via the Hermsdorfer Kreuz), the A14 (Magdeburg-Halle-Leipzig-Dresden), the A17 (Dresden-Praha via the Czech border at Bahratal, the only Saxon Autobahn crossing into Czechia), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn), the A72 (Chemnitz-Bayreuth) and the A13 (Dresden-Berlin). Bundesstraßen include the B6 along the Elbe, the B97 to Cottbus, the B96 and the B173 along the Erzgebirge.

The Elbe is navigable from the Czech border at Schöna via Dresden, Meissen, Riesa and Torgau to Magdeburg and Hamburg. The Saxon Elbe White Fleet, operated by Sächsische Dampfschiffahrt GmbH at Dresden, is the largest fleet of working paddle steamers in the world (with nine historic paddle wheelers, all built between 1879 and 1929 and still operating regularly between Dresden, Meissen, Pillnitz and Bad Schandau). The Elbe-Radweg cycling route from Schöna along the Elbe is one of Germany''s most popular long-distance cycle routes. Other long-distance cycle routes include the Mulderadweg, the Elsterradweg and the Sächsische Mittelgebirgs-Touren.',
    economics = 'Sachsen has the largest economy of the new German federal states (the former GDR), with a regional GDP of around 145 billion euros and a per-capita GDP that has steadily approached the western German average since reunification. The state has reinvented itself as a major automotive, microelectronics and software cluster. The Saxon Economic Development Agency (Wirtschaftsförderung Sachsen, WFS) at Dresden markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Dresden, the IHK zu Leipzig and the IHK Chemnitz represent regional businesses.

Volkswagen Sachsen, the regional VW operations, comprise the Volkswagen Zwickau-Mosel plant (the largest electric-vehicle plant in Europe with around 11,000 workers building the Volkswagen ID.3, ID.4, ID.5, ID.7 Tourer, Audi Q4 e-tron, Audi Q4 Sportback e-tron and the Cupra Born — all on the MEB modular electric platform), the Volkswagen Chemnitz engine plant (producing engines for the Volkswagen petrol-engine portfolio), and the Volkswagen Dresden Gläserne Manufaktur (the Transparent Factory, the iconic Dresden showcase facility opened 2001 originally for the Volkswagen Phaeton luxury sedan, now used for ID.3 final assembly with public viewing and a customer experience centre). The Zwickau plant has the historic automotive heritage as the original Horch factory of 1909, which became Audi in 1932 and AWZ/Sachsenring in the GDR (producing the Trabant 1957-1991). The Trabant heritage at Zwickau continues with the August-Horch-Museum.

Porsche Leipzig GmbH has built the Porsche Leipzig plant since 2002 — the second-largest Porsche plant after Zuffenhausen-Stuttgart. The Leipzig plant produces the Porsche Macan, the Porsche Macan Electric (since 2023), the Porsche Cayenne and the Porsche Panamera. Porsche Leipzig employs around 4,500 workers and houses the Porsche Experience Center Leipzig with a private test track. BMW Leipzig, opened 2005 with a striking central building by Zaha Hadid, builds the BMW 1 Series, the BMW 2 Series, the BMW X1, the BMW iX1, the BMW i4, and the BMW Mini Countryman. BMW Leipzig employs around 5,500 workers. Saxon automotive manufacturing concentrates therefore around 22,000 direct employees, with substantial Tier-1 and Tier-2 supplier presence.

The Silicon Saxony cluster around Dresden is the largest microelectronics centre in Europe. Infineon Technologies Dresden GmbH has its largest German wafer fabrication site at Klotzsche, producing power semiconductors and security ICs for the automotive and industrial markets; the new Infineon SmartPowerFab opened 2024 is one of the largest investments in European semiconductor manufacturing history. Globalfoundries Dresden Module One (the historic AMD Fab30, then AMD Fab36, then Globalfoundries Fab1) produces 22-nanometre and 28-nanometre logic chips for global customers. Robert Bosch Semiconductor Manufacturing Dresden (the Bosch Dresden Wafer Fab, opened 2021), the largest single investment in Bosch corporate history at over 1 billion euros, produces 300-millimetre wafers for automotive electronics. The new ESMC joint venture between TSMC of Taiwan, Bosch, Infineon and NXP (announced 2023) will build a 300-millimetre 28-nanometre Dresden wafer fab from 2024 — the largest Taiwanese investment in Europe. X-FAB Silicon Foundries SE (Erfurt-headquartered with Dresden operations), Siltronic AG (the Wacker Group''s silicon-wafer subsidiary, with substantial Saxony operations), Jenoptik AG (the Jena-based but Saxony-Thuringia-cross-border optoelectronics specialist) and the Fraunhofer Photonik AG complete the cluster. Silicon Saxony Verein, the industry association, claims that around 25 per cent of European semiconductor revenue originates in Saxony.

The Leipzig DHL European Hub is the largest single cargo facility in Saxony, with around 6,000 employees and around 70 wide-body cargo aircraft handled per night. The DHL Hub Leipzig handles around 2.5 million tonnes of cargo per year, making LEJ the second-largest German cargo airport.

Other major Saxony employers include Stadler Rail Pankow (the German subsidiary of Stadler Rail AG of Switzerland, with the Velten and Berlin plants having Saxony-supplier ties), Sachsenmilch AG (the Leppersdorf-based dairy giant, jointly with the Bayerische Milchindustrie), Meissen Porzellan-Manufaktur (the historic porcelain manufactory at Meissen), the Sachsenring at Hohenstein-Ernstthal (the famous motor-racing circuit on the German Grand Prix calendar), the Wernesgrüner Brauerei, the Radeberger Brauerei, the Sternburg Brauerei, the Köstritzer Brauerei, the Bautzener Mustard, the SolarWatt AG (Dresden, photovoltaic systems), the historic Plauener Lace cooperative (one of the historic German lace-making centres), and the Vodafone Telecommunications Centre Leipzig. The Stadler Rail Velten plant (in Brandenburg but with Saxony ties) and the Bombardier (now Alstom) Görlitz plant build passenger rail vehicles.

In the higher-education and research sector, the Technische Universität Dresden (TUD), one of the eleven German Universities of Excellence, has around 32,000 students with strong programmes in microelectronics, materials, machine learning and clinical medicine. The Universität Leipzig, founded 1409, the second-oldest German university still in operation, has around 30,000 students. The Technische Universität Chemnitz, the Technische Universität Bergakademie Freiberg (the world''s oldest mining academy, founded 1765), the Hochschule für Technik und Wirtschaft Dresden, the Hochschule für Bildende Künste Dresden and the Hochschule für Musik Carl Maria von Weber Dresden complete the higher education. The Max-Planck-Institut für Molekulare Zellbiologie und Genetik at Dresden, the Max-Planck-Institut für Physik komplexer Systeme at Dresden, the Max-Planck-Institut für Chemische Physik fester Stoffe at Dresden, the Max-Planck-Institut für Evolutionäre Anthropologie at Leipzig (founded 1997, the home of Svante Pääbo''s Neanderthal genome research, awarded the 2022 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine), the Helmholtz-Zentrum Dresden-Rossendorf (HZDR, the nuclear and accelerator-physics centre), the Helmholtz-Zentrum für Umweltforschung Leipzig (UFZ, the leading German environmental research centre), and the Fraunhofer Institut für Photonische Mikrosysteme (IPMS Dresden) complete the research cluster.',
    introduced_species = 'Sachsen, the Free State of Saxony, hosts one of the most prominent populations of returning wolves in Germany and a comprehensive roster of introduced and invasive species. The Sächsisches Landesamt für Umwelt, Landwirtschaft und Geologie (LfULG) at Dresden coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014; the Naturschutzbund Sachsen (NABU Sachsen) supports monitoring.

The grey wolf, Canis lupus, although native to Saxony, was hunted to extinction in the late 19th century but re-established a breeding population in 2000 when the first pack settled in the Muskauer Heide on the Polish-Saxon border at the Truppenübungsplatz Oberlausitz — the first confirmed German wolf reproduction since 1850. The Lausitzer Wölfe (Lusatian Wolves) have since expanded steadily across eastern Saxony and Brandenburg from this single founder population, supplemented by ongoing immigration from Polish populations. Today Saxony has the highest German wolf population, with around 30 established territorial packs in the Lausitz, the Saxon Switzerland, the Erzgebirge foothills and the Vogtland, and several hundred individuals (the largest wolf population of any German state). The Saxon LUPUS Wolf Office at the Görlitz Senckenberg Naturhistorische Sammlungen, founded by Ilka Reinhardt and Gesa Kluth in 2000, leads German wolf research. The 2000 first-pack Muskauer Heide milestone is commemorated annually. Wolf-livestock conflicts (the killing of unfenced sheep by Saxon wolves) are a chronic management concern; the Saxon state pays livestock-loss compensation and provides electric-fence subsidies through the LWWV scheme.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Saxony since the 1970s when individuals from the Brandenburg Wolfshagen 1945 release expanded south. Today the species is established throughout Saxony with the highest densities in the Sächsische Schweiz, the Oberlausitz, the Erzgebirge, the Vogtland, and increasingly in the suburban Dresden, Leipzig and Chemnitz areas. Annual hunting bags in Saxony exceed 12,000 raccoons. The LfULG publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking, fruit-tree harvesting and the handling of raccoon latrines (which are a source of the parasitic roundworm Baylisascaris procyonis). Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl), on amphibians (yellow-bellied toad in the Sächsische Schweiz), on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroductions, and on the rare middle-spotted woodpecker.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Saxony from Poland and Czechia in the 1990s; today the species is established throughout Saxony with the highest densities in the Lausitz, the Oberlausitz heaths and the Vogtland. Annual hunting bags exceed 8,000. The species is on the EU Invasive Alien Species List.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Elbe, the Mulde, the Pleisse, the Spree (the upper Spree near Bautzen) and many other Saxon waterways. Damage to flood-protection dykes is a serious management concern. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Saxony but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced and is now spreading along the Elbe, the Mulde and the Pleisse. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Saxony.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations on Saxon lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded into Saxony from the western German populations and now breeds across the state, particularly in the urban park ponds of Leipzig, Dresden and Chemnitz. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has small but stable breeding populations in Dresden (the Schlosspark Pillnitz, the Großer Garten) and Leipzig (the Clara-Zetkin-Park). The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on Saxon park ponds.

Among freshwater fish, the Elbe and its tributaries host the standard set of introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) are widespread. The Saxon Elbe section has been particularly affected by the round goby invasion, which entered via the lower Elbe from the German Bight and via the Main-Danube system. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis), the historic Saxon Welskat, has been reintroduced and is now common in the Elbe and the Saxon lakes.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, regularly trapped in the Elbe). The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in Saxony from 2022 onwards with confirmed nests in the Dresden-Leipzig corridor; the Sächsischer Imkerverein coordinates nest-removal with the LfULG. The harlequin ladybird (Harmonia axyridis), the horse-chestnut leaf miner (Cameraria ohridella), the box tree moth (Cydalima perspectalis, which has destroyed the historic boxwood gardens at Pillnitz, Großsedlitz, Moritzburg and the Großer Garten Dresden), and the brown marmorated stink bug (Halyomorpha halys) are all ubiquitous.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, particularly conspicuous along the Mulde and the Elbe), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, widespread in the Erzgebirge streams), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial Chemnitz and Leipzig brownfields), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, particularly conspicuous in the historic Lausitz lignite-mining brownfields), the Senecio inaequidens and the Indian balsam are widespread. The Saxon Lausitz Bergehalden (slag heaps from former lignite mining around Spreetal and Welzow) host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation. The dwarf-pine plantations of the Erzgebirge ridge contain large areas of introduced Pinus mugo subspecies.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Erzgebirge, the Vogtland and the Oberlausitz. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Erzgebirge. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density across the state, with annual hunting bags exceeding 70,000 statewide. African Swine Fever has been confirmed in Saxon wild boar from September 2020 onwards, with thousands of confirmed cases in the eastern Oberlausitz and the Görlitz district; the Saxon state coordinated emergency containment fencing along the Polish border and intensive culling of the core-zone wild boar. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Erzgebirge.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Sachsen-Anhalt, in English Saxony-Anhalt, is one of the historically most significant German federal states, the cradle of the Reformation, the Bauhaus and the medieval Saxon-Frankish kingdoms. The state covers 20,452 square kilometres and has around 2.2 million inhabitants. Magdeburg is the state capital, and the other major cities include Halle (Saale), Dessau-Roßlau, Lutherstadt Wittenberg, Naumburg (Saale), Quedlinburg, Wernigerode, Halberstadt and Stendal.

Lutherstadt Wittenberg, the birthplace of the Reformation, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1996, the Luther Memorials in Eisleben and Wittenberg). The Schlosskirche zu Wittenberg (the Castle Church), on whose massive wooden doors Martin Luther reportedly nailed his 95 Theses on 31 October 1517 (the doors were destroyed in 1760 and replaced in 1858 with bronze doors carrying the Latin text of the Theses), contains the tombs of Luther and Philipp Melanchthon and the famous Reformation oaks. The Lutherhaus, Luther''s home in the former Augustinian monastery, now houses the Luther Museum with the original manuscripts, the famous Junker Jörg portrait by Cranach the Elder, and the historic study where Luther translated the New Testament from Greek to German in 1521-1522. The Melanchthonhaus next door is the home of Philipp Melanchthon, Luther''s closest collaborator. The Stadtkirche Wittenberg (St. Marien) was the church where Luther preached, with the famous Cranach altar piece by Lucas Cranach the Elder (depicting the four key sacraments of the Lutheran Reformation). The Cranachhof, the residence of Lucas Cranach the Elder and Younger, has been restored as the Cranach museum and printing workshop.

Lutherstadt Eisleben, Martin Luther''s birthplace and place of death, is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The Luther Geburtshaus (Luther''s Birth House, where Luther was born 10 November 1483), the Luther Sterbehaus (Luther''s Death House, where Luther died 18 February 1546), the Andreaskirche and the Petri-Pauli-Kirche complete the Eisleben Luther circuit.

Dessau-Roßlau hosts two UNESCO World Heritage Sites. The Dessau-Wörlitz Gartenreich (Garden Kingdom of Dessau-Wörlitz, designated 2000) is an Enlightenment-era cultural landscape covering 142 square kilometres, with the Wörlitz Park (the first true English landscape garden in continental Europe, laid out by Prince Leopold III Frederick Franz of Anhalt-Dessau between 1764 and 1813 with the architect Friedrich Wilhelm von Erdmannsdorff and the landscape designer Johann Friedrich Eyserbeck), the Schloss Wörlitz (the first true neoclassical building in Germany), the Gotisches Haus (the Gothic House), the Synagoge Wörlitz (one of the few rural German synagogues, designed in 1789 by Erdmannsdorff and surviving Kristallnacht thanks to Dessau citizens), the Schloss Mosigkau (the small rococo Schloss of Princess Henriette Catharina, with the picture gallery containing original works by Rubens and van Dyck), the Schloss Oranienbaum (the historic Dutch baroque palace built in 1683 for Princess Henriette Catharina of Orange-Nassau), the Schloss Luisium and the Schloss Großkühnau. The second Dessau UNESCO inscription (2017 extension) is the Bauhaus and its Sites in Weimar, Dessau and Bernau, comprising the Bauhausgebäude Dessau (the iconic Bauhaus building designed by Walter Gropius and completed in 1926, the architectural manifesto of the modern movement with its asymmetrical L-shape, ribbon windows and curtain-wall workshop wing), the Meisterhäuser Dessau (the four houses for Bauhaus masters Walter Gropius, Wassily Kandinsky and Paul Klee, László Moholy-Nagy and Lyonel Feininger, and Georg Muche and Oskar Schlemmer, all designed by Gropius 1925-26), the Kornhaus restaurant on the Elbe by Carl Fieger of 1929-1930, the Konsumgebäude in the Törten-Siedlung (the Bauhaus model housing estate), and the Arbeitsamt by Walter Gropius of 1928-1929.

Quedlinburg, a UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1994, jointly with the Stiftskirche, Schloss and Old Town), is one of the most intact medieval timber-framed towns in Germany, with around 2,000 timber-framed houses from the 14th to 18th centuries. The Quedlinburger Stiftskirche St. Servatius, on the Schlossberg above the town, is one of the finest Ottonian-Romanesque churches in Germany, the burial place of King Henry the Fowler (the first Saxon-Frankish king who unified Germany in the early 10th century, who died 936) and his wife Saint Mathilde, with the famous Quedlinburger Domschatz (the Cathedral Treasure containing the 9th-century Quedlinburg Itala biblical fragments, Carolingian reliquaries and the Heinrich-and-Mathilde reliquary). The Quedlinburger Schloss, the Old Town with the Marktplatz and the Roland statue, and the Schlossberg view make Quedlinburg one of the best-preserved medieval ensembles in central Europe.

Naumburg (Saale), founded in 1028 by Emperor Henry II, is dominated by the Naumburger Dom St. Peter und Paul, a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2018 (specifically as a Naumburg Cathedral and the High Medieval Cultural Landscape). The Dom contains the famous Stifterfiguren (the Founders of the Cathedral), twelve life-size statues of the cathedral''s benefactors by the anonymous Naumburger Meister of around 1245, including the world-famous Uta von Naumburg (the Margravine Uta of Ballenstedt, often called the most beautiful woman of the Middle Ages and the most photographed medieval female statue in Europe) and her husband Ekkehard II of Meissen. The Naumburger Domhof, the historic Cathedral chapter buildings, and the Naumburger Kirschfest (the famous annual Cherry Festival celebrating a 15th-century military deliverance) complete the city.

Magdeburg, the state capital on the Elbe, is dominated by the Magdeburger Dom (the Cathedral of Saint Maurice and Saint Catherine, the first major Gothic building constructed on German soil from 1209 onwards, the burial place of Emperor Otto the Great who founded the original Magdeburg archbishopric in 968), the Hundertwasser Grüne Zitadelle (the Green Citadel of Magdeburg, the last building by the Austrian artist-architect Friedensreich Hundertwasser completed posthumously in 2005 — a striking pink mass with green tree-balconies and golden cupolas), the Kloster Unser Lieben Frauen, the Magdeburger Rathaus with the Magdeburger Reiter equestrian statue (the first equestrian statue in northern Europe, depicting Otto the Great), the historic Petriförder harbour, the Hyparschale, and the Elbauenpark (the park with the Jahrtausendturm — Millennium Tower — the tallest wooden tower in Germany at 60 metres, opened for the 1999 Federal Garden Show).

Halle (Saale), the largest city of Sachsen-Anhalt with around 240,000 inhabitants, was the birthplace of Georg Friedrich Händel (1685-1759) — the Händel-Haus on the Große Nikolaistraße is the composer''s birthplace, now a museum. The Halle Marktplatz with the historic Roter Turm (one of the largest free-standing belfries in Europe at 84 metres), the four-towered Marktkirche Unser Lieben Frauen, the Halle University (the Martin-Luther-Universität Halle-Wittenberg, founded 1502 and 1694), the Halloren-Saline (the historic salt-works at the Saline Halle dating from 961), the Halloren-Chokoladenfabrik (the oldest German chocolate factory, founded 1804 at Halle by Friedrich August Miethe), the Moritzburg (a late-medieval Saxon-Anhaltian castle now housing the State Art Gallery with the Lyonel Feininger collection), the Franckesche Stiftungen (the historic baroque school complex founded by August Hermann Francke in 1698), and the Beatles Museum Halle (the only Beatles Museum in continental Europe) round out the city.

Wernigerode, the colourful timber-framed town in the Harz foothills, is dominated by the Schloss Wernigerode (the romantic-revival reconstruction of the medieval Harzgrafen castle, with stunning Tudor-style interiors) and the Wernigerode Rathaus (the iconic timber-framed Renaissance town hall with its dramatic twin gables). The Harzer Schmalspurbahn (the Harz Narrow Gauge Railway, the largest narrow-gauge steam-railway network in Europe with over 140 kilometres of 1000-mm gauge lines connecting Wernigerode-Brocken-Drei Annen Hohne-Nordhausen via the famous Brockenbahn cog-and-adhesion summit railway) operates daily steam services to the Brocken summit. The Brocken, at 1141 metres the highest peak in northern Germany and the centrepiece of the Harz National Park, is famous from Goethe''s Faust (the Walpurgisnacht witches'' meeting on the Blocksberg) and from the Cold War as one of the major western Warsaw Pact listening stations (the Brocken summit was a Soviet KGB and Stasi monitoring centre, now restored with the Brockenhaus museum). Other Harz destinations include Schierke, Thale (with the Roßtrappe and Hexentanzplatz rock formations above the Bode gorge, the legendary haunt of witches), Stolberg (a beautiful timber-framed town in the southern Harz, the birthplace of Thomas Müntzer), and the Kaiserweg historic trail. The Halberstadt Cathedral, with its remarkable medieval treasury, the Stolberg, the Mansfeld region (Luther''s childhood land), and the Naumburg-Freyburg wine area complete the historic landscape.

Sachsen-Anhalt cuisine includes Halloren-Kugeln (the iconic Halle chocolate balls produced since 1952 by Halloren, with their distinctive blue-white striped silver-foil wrap), Magdeburger Eierschecke (a variant of the Saxon cake), the Halberstädter Wurst (the famous Halberstadt sausages, especially the Halberstädter Bockwurst and the Halberstädter Schinkenmettwurst), the Stendaler Schinken (Stendal ham), the historic Salzwedeler Baumkuchen (the protected tree-cake of Salzwedel, an EU PGI since 2007 — a hand-turned ring-shaped cake made by pouring batter in layers onto a rotating spit, traditional since 1807), the Mansfelder Kümmelbrot, and the Aschersleber Lebkuchen. Drinks: Hasseröder Pilsner (Wernigerode, one of the largest German beer brands), Wernesgrüner (technically Saxony but sold throughout the region), Köstritzer Schwarzbier (Bad Köstritz, technically Thuringia), Hallesches Bier, and the Saale-Unstrut wines (the historic wine region around Naumburg, Freyburg an der Unstrut, Bad Kösen and Höhnstedt, the most northerly large wine region in Germany at 51 degrees north — producing Riesling, Müller-Thurgau, Silvaner, Weißburgunder, Bacchus, Schwarzburgunder and the Saxon Goldriesling). Major Saale-Unstrut producers include the Landesweingut Kloster Pforta, the Weingut Lützkendorf, the Weingut Pawis, the Winzervereinigung Freyburg and the historic Weingut Bernard. The Rotkäppchen Sektkellerei at Freyburg (the largest German producer of Sekt, founded 1856 and famous for the Rotkäppchen red-cap brand) is one of the most popular German sparkling-wine houses.

History before 1933 is rich. Magdeburg was one of the historic Imperial cities, the seat of the Magdeburg Archbishopric founded by Otto the Great in 968. The Magdeburg Law (Magdeburger Recht), the medieval town law of Magdeburg, was adopted across central and eastern Europe and became one of the founding legal codes for hundreds of medieval German, Polish, Bohemian and Baltic towns. Quedlinburg was the favoured residence of the early Saxon-Frankish kings under Henry the Fowler (876-936). The Anhalt territories were ruled by the historic House of Anhalt (the Askanier dynasty), divided into the principalities of Anhalt-Köthen, Anhalt-Dessau, Anhalt-Bernburg and Anhalt-Zerbst (the latter giving birth to Catherine the Great of Russia, born Sophie of Anhalt-Zerbst). Wittenberg was the seat of the Saxon Electors of the Ernestine branch and the birthplace of the Protestant Reformation in 1517. The 1815 Congress of Vienna divided the historic territories: the Prussian Province of Saxony (covering Magdeburg, Halle, Merseburg, Erfurt and parts of Mansfeld) and the Anhalt Duchy (the historic Anhalt principalities consolidated as the Duchy of Anhalt). After 1945 Saxony-Anhalt was a Soviet zone Land from 1945 to 1952, then abolished into the GDR Bezirke Halle and Magdeburg, then reformed in 1990 with German reunification.',
    transportation = 'Sachsen-Anhalt has a substantial transport network reflecting its position as a central German transit corridor. Leipzig/Halle Airport (LEJ, EDDP), although administratively in Saxony but physically straddling the Saxony-Anhalt border at Schkeuditz, is the principal commercial airport for Halle and the surrounding Sachsen-Anhalt region. Magdeburg-Cochstedt Airport (CSO, EDBC) is a small regional airport handling business aviation and limited charter operations. Stendal-Borstel airfield handles general aviation. Other minor airfields include Genthin and Aschersleben.

The Sachsen-Anhalt rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Südost and DB Fernverkehr, with the regional brands abellio Rail Mitteldeutschland (until restructuring), Erfurter Bahn (EB), Mitteldeutsche Regiobahn (MRB), Hanseatische Eisenbahn, Burgenlandbahn (now part of DB Regio) and the historic Harzer Schmalspurbahn operating regional and tourist services. The Verkehrsverbund Mitteldeutscher Verkehrsverbund (MDV, covering Halle-Leipzig and parts of Saxony-Anhalt and Saxony), the Magdeburger Regiobus-Linien and the Burgenlandkreis-Verkehr coordinate tariff. Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof, opened 1873 with the iconic 19th-century facade, is the central rail node of the state with around 30,000 passengers per day. Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof is one of the largest German rail nodes outside the major metropolitan areas, the historic junction of the Berlin-Munich and Cologne-Berlin lines, with around 50,000 passengers per day. The Magdeburg-Bitterfeld-Leipzig regional rail corridor, the Magdeburg-Berlin corridor and the Magdeburg-Hannover corridor are heavily used. Wittenberg Hauptbahnhof, Stendal Hauptbahnhof (the historic Berlin-Hannover ICE stop), Wernigerode Hauptbahnhof and Naumburg complete the major rail nodes.

The ICE corridors crossing Sachsen-Anhalt include the Berlin-Halle-Leipzig-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich high-speed line (VDE 8, completed 2017, with the Halle/Leipzig junction at Großkorbetha), the Berlin-Hannover NBS (1998, passing through Stendal which has an ICE stop), the Hamburg-Berlin-Halle corridor, and the Berlin-Frankfurt corridor passing via Halle and Erfurt. The Magdeburg-Berlin and Magdeburg-Hannover lines are upgraded for 160 kph.

The Stadtbahn Magdeburg (the Magdeburg tram, operated by Magdeburger Verkehrsbetriebe MVB) has nine lines totalling 88 kilometres. The Halle (Saale) tram, operated by Hallesche Verkehrs-AG (HAVAG), has eight lines totalling 84 kilometres, with the historic Halle Saalkreis suburban interurban network the second-oldest electric interurban tram in Germany (the Hallesche Straßenbahn AG operated the world''s first commercially viable electric tram from 1891). The Bad Schmiedeberg, Naumburg and Halberstadt small tram networks complete the system.

The Autobahn network in Sachsen-Anhalt includes the A2 (Hannover-Berlin, passing through Magdeburg in the middle), the A9 (Munich-Berlin, passing through Naumburg-Halle-Bitterfeld), the A14 (Magdeburg-Halle-Dresden, under continuous upgrading), the A36 (Bernburg-Wernigerode-Goslar), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn), and the planned A14 extension to Schwerin. Bundesstraßen include the B1 east-west, the B6, the B100 along the Harz foothills, the B71 to Salzwedel, the B81, and the B91 to Halle.

The Elbe is a major navigable inland waterway through Magdeburg. The Magdeburger Wasserstraßenkreuz (Magdeburg Waterway Crossing), opened in 2003, is one of the most spectacular hydraulic engineering structures in the world: the canal Trog (water bridge) of 918 metres carries the Mittellandkanal over the Elbe at Magdeburg-Hohenwarthe — the largest such canal bridge in the world by length. The Mittellandkanal, the longest German artificial waterway, connects the Rhine-Ruhr area via Magdeburg and Berlin to the Elbe-Havel-Kanal system. Inland ports include Magdeburg (one of the largest in central Germany), Halle, Riesa (technically Saxony) and Aken. The Elbe-Radweg (the most popular German long-distance cycling route) passes through Magdeburg and Wittenberg. The Saale-Radweg, the Unstrut-Radweg and the Tour Brandenburg complete the network.',
    economics = 'Sachsen-Anhalt has a regional GDP of around 70 billion euros, with one of the lowest per-capita GDPs in Germany reflecting the post-industrial transformation of the chemical-and-lignite Mitteldeutsches Chemiedreieck (Central German Chemical Triangle). The state economic development arm, the Investitions- und Marketinggesellschaft Sachsen-Anhalt (IMG), markets the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Magdeburg, the IHK Halle-Dessau and the IHK Halberstadt represent regional businesses.

The Mitteldeutsches Chemiedreieck around Leuna-Schkopau-Bitterfeld is one of the largest German chemical clusters, the historic site of IG Farben and the GDR Chemiestandorte. The Leuna Refinery (Total Refinery Leuna), with 12 million tonnes of crude refining capacity per year, is one of the largest German oil refineries. The DOW Olefinverbund at Schkopau-Böhlen, the largest single Dow Chemical site outside the United States, produces ethylene, propylene and a wide range of polymers and chemicals. The Mibe Pharma at Brehna, the SKW Stickstoffwerke Piesteritz at Wittenberg (the largest German producer of ammonia and urea), the Linde Leuna (industrial gases), the InfraLeuna chemical-park operator, the InfraLeuna Methanol Plant (the largest European methanol production), and the Chemiepark Bitterfeld-Wolfen (with Heraeus, Bayer Bitterfeld, Suez and many other tenants) complete the cluster. The Mitteldeutsche Braunkohle Revier (Mid-German Lignite District) is in transition under the federal coal-exit programme of 2038, with substantial Strukturwandel funds.

The Halle-Bitterfeld-Wolfen Solar Valley (the Mitteldeutsches Solar Valley), once one of the largest German solar-PV manufacturing clusters with Q-Cells (now Hanwha QCells), SolarWatt, SolarWorld, Sovello and many other companies, declined dramatically after 2012 with the Chinese solar-cost crash. Today the cluster is recovering with new investments by Hanwha QCells, Meyer Burger and others in cell and module manufacturing for the new European energy-transition demand.

Other major Sachsen-Anhalt employers include Halloren AG (the historic Halle chocolate maker since 1804, the oldest German chocolate factory still in operation), the Rotkäppchen-Mumm Sektkellereien (the listed sparkling-wine producer at Freyburg with brands Rotkäppchen, Mumm, MM Extra, Geldermann and Söhnlein Brillant — the largest German Sekt producer with annual revenues of around 1 billion euros), the Hasseröder Brauerei at Wernigerode (one of the largest German beer brands, owned by Anheuser-Busch InBev), the Wernesgrüner Brauerei (technically Sachsen but with Saxon-Anhalt operations), the Salzwedeler Baumkuchen, the Magdeburger Eierscheckenfabrik, the Stahlwerke Thale (specialty steel) and the historic Soltauer Konservenfabrik.

The Volkswagen Sachsen-Anhalt presence is modest. The historic Sachsenring-Trabant factory at Zwickau is in Saxony. The IFA Holding (the GDR-era industrial federation) had Sachsen-Anhalt operations now mostly defunct. The Mibe Pharma at Brehna, the Aristo Pharma at Halle, the Salutas Pharma at Barleben, the AKKA Industry Consulting and other pharmaceutical-services companies have substantial Saxony-Anhalt operations. The Mibe is owned by the Indian Lupin Limited group.

The Magdeburg manufacturing cluster includes the Enercon Wind Turbines (the Magdeburg blade plant), the FAM Magdeburg (the Friedrich-August Magdeburger Stahlwerk now part of the Beumer Group, specialising in bulk material handling), and the historic Magdeburger Maschinenbauschule. The Schwerlasthafen Magdeburg handles oversized industrial loads for the offshore-wind industry.

In the higher-education and research sector, the Otto-von-Guericke-Universität Magdeburg (named after Otto von Guericke, the Magdeburg inventor of the air pump and the famous Magdeburg Hemispheres experiment of 1654, the first vacuum demonstration in history) has around 14,000 students. The Martin-Luther-Universität Halle-Wittenberg, founded 1502 and 1694 and one of the oldest German universities, has around 19,000 students. The Hochschule Anhalt, the Hochschule Magdeburg-Stendal, the Hochschule Merseburg and the Hochschule für Bildende Künste Halle round out higher education. The Helmholtz-Zentrum für Umweltforschung Halle (UFZ Halle branch), the Leibniz-Institut für Pflanzenbiochemie at Halle, the Leibniz-Institut für Pflanzengenetik und Kulturpflanzenforschung (IPK) at Gatersleben (which hosts the world''s largest plant gene bank with over 150,000 plant accessions), and the Fraunhofer-Institut für Werkstoffmechanik (IWM Halle) form the research backbone. The Leopoldina German National Academy of Sciences has its corporate headquarters at Halle on the Jägerberg.

Tourism is a significant economic sector, with the Luther-Stätten in Wittenberg and Eisleben, the Dessau Bauhaus, the Wörlitz Park, Quedlinburg, the Harz mountains (the Wernigerode-Brocken corridor), the Saale-Unstrut wine region and the Magdeburg Hundertwasser Citadel attracting around 5 million overnight stays per year. The Tourismusmarketing Sachsen-Anhalt markets the state.

Banking and finance are concentrated at Halle and Magdeburg with the Sparkasse Mitteldeutschland (one of the largest German savings banks), the Volksbank Halle, the Investitionsbank Sachsen-Anhalt (the state-owned development bank), and the historic Magdeburger Lebensversicherung.',
    introduced_species = 'Sachsen-Anhalt hosts a representative roster of introduced and invasive species. The Landesamt für Umweltschutz Sachsen-Anhalt at Halle coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Sachsen-Anhalt since the 1960s, with the Hessian Edersee 1934 release expanding north through the Harz and the Brandenburg Wolfshagen 1945 release expanding west through the Altmark; Sachsen-Anhalt sits at the historic confluence of the two expansion fronts and hosts very high raccoon densities. Today the species is established throughout Sachsen-Anhalt with the highest densities in the Harz, the Altmark, the Burgenlandkreis and the Halle-Saalekreis areas. Annual hunting bags in Sachsen-Anhalt exceed 15,000 raccoons. The Landesamt publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing and the handling of raccoon latrines. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds, on amphibians, on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroductions in the Drömling and the Elbaue, and on the rare middle-spotted woodpecker.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Sachsen-Anhalt from the east in the 1990s; today the species is established throughout the state with the highest densities in the Altmark, the Elbaue and the Drömling. Annual hunting bags exceed 6,000.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Elbe, the Saale, the Mulde, the Unstrut and the Bode. Damage to flood-protection dykes is a serious management concern. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to the lower Elbe but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced through NABU and is now spreading from the historic Dessau Wörlitz beaver core area; the Sachsen-Anhalt Elbe beavers are one of the strongest German populations. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Sachsen-Anhalt.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised Sachsen-Anhalt since around 2010 from Polish and east German populations; the state now has around 15 territorial packs in the Altmark, the Colbitz-Letzlinger Heide military training ground, the Drömling biosphere reserve, the Saxon-Anhaltian Elbaue and the Harz foothills. The Sachsen-Anhalt Wolves Office at the Landesamt für Umweltschutz coordinates monitoring and livestock-loss compensation.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations on Saxon-Anhaltian lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded explosively, particularly in the Halle, Magdeburg and Dessau areas. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, is occasional in Halle and Magdeburg but has not established large breeding populations. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on park ponds.

Among freshwater fish, the Elbe, the Saale, the Mulde and the Unstrut host the standard set of introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) are widespread. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis) is established.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus, the most common Saxon-Anhaltian crayfish), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, regularly trapped in the Elbe). The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in Sachsen-Anhalt from 2023 onwards; the Imkerverband Sachsen-Anhalt coordinates nest-removal teams. The harlequin ladybird, the horse-chestnut leaf miner, the box tree moth (which has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Wörlitz Park and various Saxon-Anhalt private gardens), and the brown marmorated stink bug are all ubiquitous.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia, particularly conspicuous on Saxon-Anhaltian lignite-mining brownfields and the historic GDR-era industrial wastelands), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial Bitterfeld-Wolfen brownfields), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, particularly conspicuous on the historic Sachsen-Anhalt Mansfelder Land Bergehalden — slag heaps from copper mining), the Senecio inaequidens and the Indian balsam are widespread. The historic Mansfeld copper-mining region has distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation on the slag heaps.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Harz, the Colbitz-Letzlinger Heide and the Altmark. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Harz. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at very high density across the state, with annual hunting bags exceeding 40,000. African Swine Fever has not yet been confirmed in Sachsen-Anhalt wild boar but the proximity to Saxon outbreaks requires continued biosecurity. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Harz.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen-Anhalt';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Schleswig-Holstein, the northernmost German federal state, occupies the German part of the Jutland peninsula between the Baltic Sea (Ostsee) to the east and the North Sea (Nordsee) to the west, bordering Denmark to the north. The state covers 15,800 square kilometres and has around 2.9 million inhabitants. The state capital is Kiel, and the other major cities include Lübeck (the second city and historic Queen of the Hanseatic League), Flensburg, Neumünster, Norderstedt, Elmshorn, Itzehoe and Schleswig. Schleswig-Holstein was formed in 1946 from the historic Duchies of Schleswig (originally Danish, transferred to Prussia in 1864) and Holstein (originally Holy Roman Empire, also Prussian since 1864).

Lübeck, on the Trave river and the Baltic, was the Queen of the Hanseatic League at its medieval peak and is one of the most beautiful preserved medieval town centres in northern Europe. The Lübecker Altstadt (the Old Town on its island in the Trave), a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1987, contains around 1,000 listed buildings from the 13th to 18th centuries, almost entirely in Brick Gothic style — the architectural style that originated at Lübeck and spread across the entire Baltic. The Holstentor (Holstein Gate), the iconic late-medieval city gate of 1478 with its two characteristic round brick towers leaning slightly outward, is the most-photographed building in northern Germany and the historical entrance to the city. The Marienkirche (St. Mary''s Church), built 1250-1350 in brick and the prototype for over 70 Brick Gothic churches across the Baltic from Tallinn to Bergen, has the world''s tallest brick-vaulted nave (38.5 metres), the famous astronomical clock by Hans Düringer, and the broken bells in the Gedenkkapelle (the two bells that fell during the Lübeck Palm Sunday Bombing of 1942 are still on the chapel floor as a peace memorial). The Lübeck Dom (St. Petri-Dom) of 1173 is one of the oldest brick cathedrals in Germany. The Schiffergesellschaft (the Sailors'' Guild building of 1535, with its preserved interior featuring the long benches under the ship models), the Burgtor (the medieval north city gate of 1444), the Heiligen-Geist-Hospital (one of the oldest hospital buildings in continuous use in northern Europe, with the famous Hanse-Trinkgemach pub in the Lange Halle), the Marktplatz with the Rathaus (one of the most beautiful Brick Gothic town halls in Europe, with the Renaissance Renaissance staircase), the Salzspeicher (the famous salt-warehouses of 1579 used for the Lübeck herring-salting trade and immortalised by F.W. Murnau''s Nosferatu of 1922 as Count Orlok''s German residence), the Beckergrube and the Hanseatic merchant streets all reflect the salt-and-herring trade era. The Lübeck Buddenbrookhaus, the historic family home of the Mann family at Mengstraße 4, is dedicated to the writers Thomas Mann and Heinrich Mann (Thomas Mann won the 1929 Nobel Prize for Literature for Buddenbrooks: Decline of a Family, set in the Mengstraße house). The Willy-Brandt-Haus Lübeck honours the Lübeck-born politician and Federal Chancellor Willy Brandt who won the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize. The Günter Grass-Haus is dedicated to the Lübeck-resident writer Günter Grass who won the 1999 Nobel Prize for Literature. Niederegger Marzipan, the most famous German marzipan producer founded 1806 by Johann Georg Niederegger, has its flagship Café Niederegger on the Breite Straße opposite the Rathaus, with the Marzipan-Salon on the upper floor displaying the historic Marzipan-Skulpturen and the Marzipan-Museum.

Sylt and the North Frisian Islands form the most-famous German seaside resort area. Sylt, the largest German island in the North Sea at 99 square kilometres, is reached only by the Hindenburgdamm rail causeway from Niebüll (the only German railway-only land link to an island, since 1927), by ferry from Havneby in Denmark, or by air to Sylt Airport (Westerland). Westerland, the main town on Sylt, is a historic seaside resort with the Friedrichstraße shopping mile, the Strandpromenade, the Casino Westerland (the historic Sylter Spielbank), the Sylt Museum and the Strandkorb tradition (the iconic Sylt beach-chair hood that has been on Sylt beaches since 1882). The Sylt Red Cliff at Kampen, the Sansibar restaurant on the beach near Rantum, the Buhne 16 nudist beach, the historic List Lighthouse and the Ellenbogen sand spit at the northern end of Sylt are classic destinations. The other North Frisian Islands — Föhr (the "green island"), Amrum (with the largest sand-dune beach in northern Europe at Knipsand), Pellworm and the small uninhabited Halligen (the seven historic salt-marsh islands that flood at high tide: Hooge, Langeneß-Oland, Gröde, Hamburger Hallig, Süderoog, Südfall and Norderoog) — are reached by ferry from Dagebüll, Husum and Nordstrand. The Wadden Sea National Park (Nationalpark Schleswig-Holsteinisches Wattenmeer), a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2009, is the largest unbroken system of intertidal sand and mud flats in the world, covering 4,400 square kilometres along the Schleswig-Holstein and Lower Saxony North Sea coast. Wadden Sea Wattwanderung guided mudflat hikes from the mainland to the islands at low tide are a unique experience.

Helgoland (Heligoland), the small red-sandstone island 50 kilometres offshore in the German Bight, is the only true deep-sea German island. With its dramatic red cliffs (the Lange Anna sea stack), the Düne (the small sand island off the main rock), the Hummerbude lobster cabins, the Helgoländer Hummer (the famous Helgoland lobster, the only North Sea lobster fishery), the Helgoland aquarium and the Bunker tour, the island has been a popular tourist destination since the 19th century. Helgoland is famous as the place where August Heinrich Hoffmann von Fallersleben wrote the Deutschlandlied in 1841 (the German national anthem); it was British until 1890 (when the Anglo-German Treaty exchanged Helgoland for Zanzibar) and tax-free for liquor and tobacco today. The Helgoland ferry from Cuxhaven, Hamburg, Hörnum (Sylt) or Bremerhaven takes around three hours.

The Baltic Sea coast of Schleswig-Holstein has classic seaside resorts: Travemünde (the historic Lübeck seaside resort at the mouth of the Trave, the largest German Baltic port; the four-masted barque Passat is now a museum ship there), Timmendorfer Strand (the upmarket Lübeck Bay resort), Scharbeutz, Heiligenhafen, the Fehmarn island (the third-largest German island at 185 square kilometres, with the Sundbrücke road-bridge to the mainland and the historic Burg auf Fehmarn), Eckernförde (the historic naval town with the Eckernförder Bucht), Strande, Damp (with its large holiday resort), Hohwacht, Glücksburg (the historic ducal seat of the Glücksburg branch of the House of Oldenburg with the Glücksburg Schloss, a beautiful Renaissance-style Wasserschloss). Kiel, the state capital and major Baltic port, hosts the famous Kieler Woche (Kiel Week, the largest sailing regatta in the world, held annually in late June with over three million visitors), the Kieler Hörn, the historic Tirpitzhafen (now a marina), the Marineakademie Mürwik (the historic naval academy at Flensburg), the Schifffahrtsmuseum and the Kieler Förde. The U-Boot-Ehrenmal Möltenort at Laboe, a memorial to all submariners who died in both world wars, with the Marine-Ehrenmal Laboe (the 85-metre Marine memorial tower) and the U-995 submarine (a museum boat) is one of Germany''s most visited memorials.

Schleswig, the historic Anglo-Saxon-Danish trading post, contains the Wikinger Museum Haithabu (the Viking Heritage site at Haithabu, the largest Viking trading settlement in the world from the 8th to 11th centuries, a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2018) and the Danevirke (the great Viking-era earth fortification system spanning Schleswig, built from the 7th to 12th centuries to defend the Jutland frontier against the Saxons and the Frankish empire). The Schloss Gottorf, on the Schlei sea-inlet, was the ducal seat of the Holstein-Gottorf dukes (one of the most powerful Schleswig-Holstein noble lines) and now houses the Schleswig-Holsteinische Landesmuseen with the famous Gottorfer Globus (a reconstruction of the lost 1664 Gottorf Globe, a hollow walk-in celestial globe of 3.1-metre diameter, presented to Tsar Peter the Great as a gift and now in St. Petersburg; the modern Schleswig reconstruction was opened in 2005), the Nydam Boat (a 4th-century Anglo-Saxon longship found in a Danish bog, the oldest preserved European war-ship), and the museum''s art and archaeology collections.

Flensburg, the northernmost German major town, has the historic harbour (the Flensburger Hafen), the historic warehouses on the Rote Straße, the Glücksburger Stadtteil, the Marineschule Mürwik (the German Federal Navy''s officer training school), the Museumshafen with the historic sailing ships, the Schiffahrtsmuseum, and the famous Flensburg Rum tradition since 1755 (Johannisburger Rum, Pott Rum, Asmussen Rum — Flensburg was the German rum capital because its harbour traded heavily with the West Indian colonies in the 17th-19th centuries). The Glücksburg Schloss at Glücksburg (a Renaissance-style moated palace from 1582-1587, the seat of the House of Glücksburg, the cadet branch of the Oldenburg dynasty that has ruled or rules Denmark, Norway, Greece, the United Kingdom and many other thrones).

Other Schleswig-Holstein highlights include the Mecklenburger Seenplatte (technically MV), the Ratzeburger See and the Lauenburger Seen, the Plön and the Plöner See with the Plöner Schloss (the historic ducal seat of the Holstein-Plön line), Eutin (sometimes called the "Weimar of the North" for its 18th-century literary salons under the patronage of the Bishop of Lübeck Friedrich August of Oldenburg; the Eutiner Festspiele open-air opera festival is held in the Schlosspark), Bad Segeberg (with the famous Karl-May-Festspiele, the largest open-air theatre of Germany, hosting the annual May Festival with Karl May''s Wild West stories adapted for theatre since 1952), Husum on the Wadden Sea (Theodor Storm''s "grey city by the sea", with the historic Husum Schloss and the Storm-Haus), Friedrichstadt (the "Holländerstadt" founded in 1621 by Dutch Remonstrant refugees, with its picturesque Dutch-style canals and gabled brick houses), Glückstadt (the Matjes Herring capital, founded 1617 by Christian IV of Denmark), Tönning with its remarkable Renaissance Markt, and the Schleswig-Holstein Musik Festival (the largest German classical-music festival held every summer in around 100 venues across the state, founded 1986 by Justus Frantz).

Schleswig-Holstein cuisine is North-German maritime and dairy-rich. Labskaus (the sailor''s dish shared with Hamburg, Bremen and the Baltic), Mehlbüddel (a sweet sour bread soup), Fischbrötchen (a roll with marinated fish, the iconic German harbour-side snack — Bismarck Hering, Matjes, Brathering or Fischfrikadelle versions are typical), Kieler Sprotten (the famous Kiel smoked sprats), Lübecker Marzipan (the protected Lübeck marzipan with PGI status since 1996, produced by Niederegger, Carstens, Erasmi, Mest and other Lübeck firms), the Husumer Matjes, the Holsteiner Schmandtorte, the Holsteiner Apfelkuchen, the Holsteiner Sauerfleisch (jellied pork), the Birnen Bohnen und Speck (the autumn classic), the Glückstädter Matjes, the Tönninger Krabben (Husum and Tönning are major shrimp-fishing ports), the Wattführer-Krabben (the small cold-water North Sea shrimps Crangon crangon, the Wadden Sea specialty), the Friesentee tea ceremony (with rock sugar Kluntje, cream and strong black tea, the highest German per-capita tea consumption is in East Friesland and North Friesland), and the famous Sylter Royal oyster (the only commercial German oyster, the Pacific oyster Magallana gigas, cultivated since 1986 on the List Wadden Sea bed). Beverages: Flensburger Pilsener (the famous Flensburg Pils brewery since 1888, with the iconic ceramic snap-top "Plopp" closure that gives the beer its distinctive opening sound — "Flens" is one of the best-loved German beer brands in the north), Holsten Pilsener (technically Hamburg-Altona but consumed throughout SH), Astra Urtyp (Hamburg-St. Pauli but throughout SH), the Lübzer Pils (Mecklenburg but consumed in the east), the historic Husumer Brauerei, the Schleswiger Pilsener and the small craft brewers Brodersen, Heidelberger Westerland and Helgoländer. Spirits: Pott Rum (the famous Flensburg rum from H.H. Pott since 1849), Asmussen Rum (since 1873), and the historic Hansen Rum tradition; Hamburg-style Lüttje Lage with Korn and beer, the Aalborg Aquavit imported from Denmark.

History before 1933 is complex. The Duchy of Schleswig was historically a fief of the Danish crown but also a member of the Holy Roman Empire from 1474; the Duchy of Holstein was a member of the Holy Roman Empire from 1111. Both duchies were ruled in Personal Union by the Danish kings from the 1460 Treaty of Ribe (the Ribe Constitution famously declared that Schleswig and Holstein "shall remain forever undivided", which became a constitutional contention in the 19th century). The 1773 Treaty of Tsarskoye Selo transferred the Holstein-Gottorp lands from Tsar Paul I of Russia to the Danish crown. The 1848-1851 First Schleswig War between Denmark and the Prussian-Austrian alliance and German nationalists ended in Danish victory but in unsustainable terms. The 1864 Second Schleswig War led to Denmark losing both duchies, which became Prussian (Holstein in 1867 and Schleswig in 1867). The 1920 plebiscites after WWI returned northern Schleswig to Denmark (now Danish Sønderjylland or "South Jutland"). After 1945 the British zone established the Land Schleswig-Holstein in 1946. Famous figures from Schleswig-Holstein include Thomas Mann (Lübeck), Heinrich Mann (Lübeck), Willy Brandt (Lübeck-born SPD politician and Federal Chancellor 1969-1974, Nobel Peace Prize 1971), Günter Grass (Danzig-born but Lübeck-resident writer, Nobel Prize 1999), Theodor Storm (Husum, poet and novelist), Klaus Groth (Heide, Low German poet), and many of the historic Danish-Schleswig nobility.',
    transportation = 'Schleswig-Holstein has a strategic transport position between Hamburg and Denmark, between the North Sea and the Baltic. Hamburg Airport (HAM, EDDH) — although in Hamburg state — is the principal commercial airport serving Schleswig-Holstein, with the S-Bahn S1 connecting Hamburg Airport-Fuhlsbüttel to the Schleswig-Holstein commuter belt in around 25 minutes. Lübeck Airport (LBC, EDHL), the second commercial airport, lost most of its Ryanair operations in the 2010s and now handles modest leisure and business traffic. Kiel-Holtenau Airport (KEL, EDHK) handles business aviation. Sylt-Westerland Airport (GWT, EDXW) handles tourism flights to Sylt with seasonal Mediterranean charter operations and Lufthansa Cityline domestic services. Heide-Büsum, Heligoland-Düne (the small island airfield with the historic North Sea air link) and Husum-Schwesing complete the aviation infrastructure.

The Schleswig-Holstein rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Schleswig-Holstein and the regional brand nordbahn (the Eurobahn-affiliated NordWestBahn-Eurobahn joint venture). The Nahverkehrsverbund Schleswig-Holstein (NAH.SH) coordinates regional rail and bus tariff. Kiel Hauptbahnhof is the major regional rail node with around 30,000 passengers per day, served by frequent regional trains to Hamburg, Flensburg, Lübeck and Husum. Lübeck Hauptbahnhof is the other major node, with the ICE/IC services to Hamburg, Berlin and (when restored after the closure for the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link construction) the Vogelfluglinie to Denmark. Flensburg Hauptbahnhof is the northernmost ICE/IC station in Germany, with services to Copenhagen via the Jutland mainland and Hamburg-Padborg-Aarhus. The Sylt Shuttle car train service from Niebüll to Westerland-Sylt across the Hindenburgdamm is one of the most-used German rail services for tourists.

The ICE/IC corridors crossing Schleswig-Holstein include the Hamburg-Kiel route, the Hamburg-Flensburg-Danish border route (with onward Copenhagen via Rødby ferry currently or via Aarhus-Jutland), and the historic Vogelfluglinie (Hamburg-Lübeck-Puttgarden-Rødby-Copenhagen) — the latter now interrupted by the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link construction. The Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link, under construction since 2020 by the Danish operator Femern A/S, will be an 18-kilometre immersed road-and-rail tunnel between Puttgarden on Fehmarn (Schleswig-Holstein) and Rødby on Lolland (Denmark) — the longest immersed tunnel in the world and one of the most ambitious European infrastructure projects of the 21st century. The tunnel is due to open in 2029 and will allow direct rail services Hamburg-Lübeck-Copenhagen in around 2.5 hours, dramatically reducing the Hamburg-Stockholm rail journey. The Hindenburgdamm, the rail-only causeway built 1923-1927 from Klanxbüll on the mainland across the Wadden Sea to Morsum-Sylt, is the only rail link to Sylt and carries the Sylt Shuttle car trains.

The Hamburg-Kiel-Flensburg corridor is being upgraded for higher speeds and additional capacity. The Hamburg-Kiel S-Bahn line S4 from Hamburg Hauptbahnhof to Bad Oldesloe (Schleswig-Holstein) is under construction for opening from 2027. The Hamburg S-Bahn S1 to Kaltenkirchen and the S21 to Aumühle extend into Schleswig-Holstein. The Kiel Stadtbahn proposals have been deferred but the Kieler Förde ferries provide cross-city water transport. The Lübeck Stadtbahn was historically the first electric tram in Germany (1881) but was closed in 1959. The Schleswig-Holstein bus network is operated by Autokraft, KomBus, NAH.SH partners and the historic Lübecker Verkehrsbetriebe.

The Autobahn network in Schleswig-Holstein includes the A1 (Hamburg-Heiligenhafen via Lübeck, the so-called Vogelfluglinie connecting to Denmark via the Fehmarnsund-Sundbrücke and the ferry from Puttgarden), the A7 (the longest motorway in Europe from Memmingen to Flensburg and the Danish border, the so-called Mauerautobahn during the Cold War), the A20 (the Baltic Sea Autobahn east-west, partially completed), the A21 (Schleswig-Holstein north-south), the A23 (Hamburg-Heide), the A24 (Hamburg-Berlin via Hagenow), the A25 (Hamburg-Geesthacht), and the Bundesstraße B5 (the main road along the North Sea coast), the B76, the B404, the B199, the B402 and the historic B205 to Travemünde. The Fehmarnsundbrücke between Fehmarn and the mainland will be supplemented by the new Fehmarnsund-Tunnel currently under construction.

The Kiel Canal (Nord-Ostsee-Kanal, the NOK), the 98-kilometre artificial waterway between Kiel-Holtenau on the Baltic and Brunsbüttel on the Elbe, is the most-trafficked artificial waterway in the world by ship transits (around 28,000-32,000 ships per year, more than the Panama and Suez Canals combined). The canal opened in 1895 as the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Kanal under Wilhelm II, was expanded in the 1907-1914 widening, and is currently being further deepened to handle 18-metre-draft container ships. The locks at Kiel-Holtenau and Brunsbüttel are among the largest in Europe; the Holtenau viewing platform is a popular tourist destination. The Kiel Canal connects the North Sea to the Baltic Sea without the long voyage around the Skagerrak.

Inland and coastal ports include Kiel (the Baltic port for ferries to Norway, Sweden, Lithuania, Russia and the Kiel-Oslo Color Line), Lübeck-Travemünde (the largest German Baltic port with TT-Line and Finnlines ferries to Trelleborg-Sweden, Liepāja-Latvia, Klaipėda-Lithuania, Helsinki-Finland and the cargo trade), Brunsbüttel (the Elbe-Canal junction with chemicals industry), Heiligenhafen, Hörnum-Sylt, and the inland Lauenburg an der Elbe. The Kieler Förde, the Eckernförder Bucht and the Wismar Bay are major sailing waters.

Cycling routes are extensive. The Ostseeküsten-Radweg (the Baltic Sea Coast Cycle Route, EuroVelo 10) from Cuxhaven via Hamburg-Travemünde-Lübeck-Stettin to Riga, the Nordseeküsten-Radweg (the North Sea Coast Cycle Route, EuroVelo 12), the Mönchsweg pilgrim route, the Berlin-Kopenhagen Cycle Route, and the Schleswig-Holstein-Tour de Schleswig-Holstein are signed for cyclists. The Wadden Sea Cycle Route is one of the most-popular German cycling holidays.',
    economics = 'Schleswig-Holstein has a regional GDP of around 110 billion euros, with substantial maritime industries, defence shipbuilding, food processing (the dominant German dairy state by output), tourism (the third-most-visited German state by overnight stays after Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg), wind energy and a sophisticated services sector. The Wirtschaftsförderung und Technologietransfer Schleswig-Holstein (WTSH) at Kiel and the Industrie- und Handelskammer Schleswig-Holstein (IHK SH, with offices in Kiel, Lübeck and Flensburg) represent the regional businesses.

Thyssenkrupp Marine Systems (TKMS) AG, the listed German naval-shipbuilding subsidiary of Thyssenkrupp, has its corporate headquarters and main shipyard at Kiel, with the historic Howaldtswerke-Deutsche Werft (HDW) Kiel having been founded in 1838. TKMS Kiel is the largest German naval shipyard and one of the leading European submarine builders. The Kiel shipyard builds the Type 212A submarines (the world''s first fully diesel-electric submarines with air-independent propulsion using PEM fuel cells, the world''s quietest submarines, operated by the German, Italian, Israeli and Norwegian navies), the upcoming Type 212CD (the next generation under construction for Germany and Norway), the Type 209 export submarines (operated by 14 navies), the Dolphin-class submarines (for Israel), the F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates (the largest German frigates), and the F126 Mehrzweckkampfschiff frigates (currently under construction). TKMS Kiel employs around 8,000 workers. The HDW Kiel maritime-systems business and the Atlas Elektronik (combat systems) subsidiary at Bremen complete the group.

The Lübeck-based Niederegger Marzipan GmbH & Co. KG, founded 1806 by Johann Georg Niederegger, is one of the most famous German confectionery producers, producing the iconic Lübecker Marzipan with EU PGI protection since 1996. Niederegger has annual revenues of around 100 million euros and produces around 50 different marzipan varieties at its historic Breite Straße factory and the modern Sankt Lorenz works. The Lübeck Marzipan tradition involves grinding sweet almonds with sugar in a 70:30 ratio (Lübeck marzipan must contain at least 70 per cent almonds), producing the smooth marzipan paste that is then formed and decorated. Carstens and Erasmi are competing Lübeck marzipan producers.

Drägerwerk AG & Co. KGaA, the listed family-controlled (the Dräger family) Lübeck-headquartered medical and safety-technology company, was founded in 1889 by Bernhard Dräger and Heinrich Stützer. Drägerwerk is the world''s leading manufacturer of mining-rescue and fire-rescue breathing apparatus, anaesthesia ventilators, intensive-care ventilators (the Babylog VN500, the Evita V300, the Savina), and gas-detection equipment (the Pac and X-Zone series). The Drägerwerk Lübeck complex employs around 9,000 workers in Lübeck out of around 14,000 worldwide. During the COVID-19 pandemic Dräger was one of the world''s primary suppliers of intensive-care ventilators.

The Schleswig-Holstein wind energy sector is one of the strongest in Germany, with the state having the highest onshore-wind installed capacity per capita in Germany (around 8 GW installed) and substantial offshore-wind investment in the German Bight. The wind-turbine maker Vestas (Danish) has Schleswig-Holstein supply-chain ties; the offshore-wind installation port at Brunsbüttel is being expanded. The Energiewende-Strukturwandel programme is shifting the historic coal-and-nuclear region around Brunsbüttel and Krümmel (the former nuclear power stations, now decommissioned) into a green-hydrogen production cluster around the Brunsbüttel North Energy Park.

Food processing is a major sector. Coca-Cola Erfrischungsgetränke GmbH has its German headquarters at Berlin but with substantial production at Lübeck. The Hela Curry-Sauce GmbH at Ahrensburg (the leading German ketchup-and-curry-sauce brand). The Krones AG (Neutraubling in Bavaria) has Schleswig-Holstein operations. The historic Hela Würzmittel, the Behn Meyer Schiffshandel, and the Stadtwerke Kiel complete the consumer-products picture. The dairy industry — Schleswig-Holstein produces around 25 per cent of all German milk — includes the Nordmilch (now Arla Foods amba subsidiary), the historic Schwarmstedter Molkerei, the Ostfriesische Tee Gesellschaft (although based in Hamburg), the Bünting Tee Company (East Friesland), and the Frische Brise Molkereiprodukte. The Schleswig-Holstein dairy cooperative model is one of the strongest in Germany.

Tourism is the third-largest economic sector. The state hosts around 26 million overnight stays per year (the third-highest after Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg), with Sylt, Lübeck, Travemünde, the North Frisian Islands, the Plöner See, Heligoland and the historic Hanseatic ports as major attractions. The Tourismus-Agentur Schleswig-Holstein at Kiel markets the state.

The Schleswig-Holstein wind-energy and renewable-energy cluster includes Senvion (formerly REpower, now under restructuring), the Federal Maritime and Hydrographic Agency (BSH) at Hamburg and Rostock (technically not in SH but with SH operations), and the Helmholtz-Zentrum Hereon at Geesthacht (the Helmholtz-Zentrum für Material- und Küstenforschung, formerly GKSS, with around 1,000 researchers working on materials, coastal and climate research).

In the higher-education and research sector, the Christian-Albrechts-Universität zu Kiel, founded 1665 and one of the German Universities of Excellence (with around 27,000 students and strong programmes in marine biology, GEOMAR Helmholtz-Zentrum für Ozeanforschung Kiel, ocean and climate research, and theology), the Universität zu Lübeck (the small but highly regarded university with around 5,500 students and strong medical-and-engineering programmes), the Universität Flensburg (Europa-Universität Flensburg), the Hochschule Flensburg, the Fachhochschule Kiel, the Fachhochschule Lübeck and the Muthesius Kunsthochschule Kiel complete the higher-education sector. The GEOMAR Helmholtz-Zentrum für Ozeanforschung Kiel, the Max-Planck-Institut für Evolutionsbiologie at Plön, the Forschungszentrum Borstel (Leibniz-Lungenzentrum at Borstel, the leading German pulmonary research centre), the Helmholtz-Zentrum Hereon at Geesthacht and the Christian-Albrechts-Universität Marine Sciences cluster form a notable marine and biological research backbone.

Banking includes the Förde Sparkasse Kiel, the Sparkasse zu Lübeck, the Investitionsbank Schleswig-Holstein (the state development bank), the cooperative Volksbank Kiel, and the historic Hamburg Commercial Bank (technically Hamburg) with substantial SH operations.',
    introduced_species = 'Schleswig-Holstein, the German state with the longest coastline (1,190 kilometres along the North Sea, Baltic Sea and the Wadden Sea), the strategic position between Germany and Denmark, and the rich aquatic and salt-marsh habitats, hosts a substantial roster of introduced and invasive species. The Landesamt für Landwirtschaft, Umwelt und ländliche Räume Schleswig-Holstein (LLUR) at Flintbek coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Schleswig-Holstein since the 1980s when individuals from the Hessen and Brandenburg releases expanded north through Lower Saxony. Today the species is established throughout SH with the highest densities in the Sachsenwald, the Aukrug Forst, the Segeberger Forst, the Naturpark Lauenburgische Seen and increasingly in the suburban Hamburg commuter belt of SH. Annual hunting bags in SH exceed 10,000 raccoons. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds, on amphibians, on European pond turtle reintroductions, and on the rare wildcat populations.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached SH from the east in the 1990s; today the species is established throughout SH with the highest densities in the eastern Holstein lakes area, the Aukrug Forst and the Sachsenwald. Annual hunting bags exceed 5,000.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Eider, the Treene, the Schlei, the Trave and the Stör. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to SH but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced and is now spreading along the Elbe-Lübeck-Kanal and the Trave. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout SH.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised SH since around 2014 from north-eastern German populations; the state has occasional records but no established pack as of 2024. The Schleswig-Holstein Wolves Office at the LLUR coordinates monitoring and livestock-loss compensation.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose (Branta canadensis), the Egyptian goose (Alopochen aegyptiaca), the ring-necked parakeet (occasional in Lübeck and Kiel), the mandarin duck and others are present. The North Frisian Islands and the Wadden Sea host substantial wintering populations of native and introduced waterbirds; the migrant white-fronted geese, bean geese, dark-bellied brent geese (native winter visitors), barnacle geese (a feral population has established on the Wadden Sea coast since the 1990s), and red-breasted geese (occasional) supplement the established populations.

Among freshwater fish, the SH waterways host the standard set of introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish, the topmouth gudgeon, the brown bullhead, the rainbow trout, the brook trout, the grass carp and the round goby are widespread. The Atlantic salmon (Salmo salar), although native to the historic SH rivers, has been heavily augmented by stocking programmes.

The Wadden Sea and Baltic coastal waters host extensive marine introductions. The Pacific oyster (Magallana gigas, Pazifische Auster), originally introduced for aquaculture at Sylt-List in 1986 (the iconic Sylter Royal oyster farm) and now ubiquitous across the Wadden Sea, has substantially altered the intertidal landscape by forming massive reefs on former mussel beds. The Sylter Royal Oyster, cultivated by the Dittmeyer''s Austerncompagnie, is the only commercial German oyster. The American razor clam (Ensis directus), present since 1979, is the dominant intertidal clam. The Asian shore crabs Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi are established since around 2000. The Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum, the Atlantic comb jelly Mnemiopsis leidyi, the New Zealand sea squirt Styela clava, the Manila clam Ruditapes philippinarum, the Chinese mitten crab Eriocheir sinensis (regularly trapped in the lower Eider, the Trave and the Elbe-Lübeck-Kanal), the North American polychaetes Marenzelleria and the Caspian-Pontic gobies have all established. Helgoland, the only German offshore deep-sea island, has been a major Bioinvasion entry point for North Atlantic species since the 19th century; the Helgoland Biologische Anstalt of the Alfred Wegener Institute has maintained the world''s longest continuous marine-monitoring programme since 1873.

Invertebrate freshwater invaders include the signal crayfish, the spinycheek crayfish, the red swamp crayfish, the marbled crayfish, the zebra mussel, the quagga mussel, the Asian clam and the New Zealand mud snail. The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in SH from 2021 onwards with confirmed nests in the Hamburg commuter belt and along the lower Elbe; the Imkerverband Schleswig-Holstein coordinates nest-removal teams with the LLUR.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, less prominent than in the southern German cities), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), the Senecio inaequidens and Indian balsam are widespread. The cordgrass Spartina anglica has invaded the Wadden Sea salt marshes substantially. The Sea-Buckthorn (Hippophae rhamnoides), native to the dunes, has been planted extensively for dune stabilisation. The shore cherry Prunus serotina and the cherry laurel Prunus laurocerasus have been planted historically in SH and have self-seeded into forest understorey.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Aukrug Forst, the Sachsenwald, the Naturpark Holsteinische Schweiz, the Segeberger Forst and the Lauenburgische Seen. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) are absent. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at moderate density across the state; annual hunting bags exceed 20,000. Roe deer and red deer are at high density. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions.'
WHERE region_name = 'Schleswig-Holstein';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = 'Thüringen, in English Thuringia, the so-called green heart of Germany, lies in the centre of the country and is one of the historically richest German federal states. The Free State of Thuringia (Freistaat Thüringen) covers 16,202 square kilometres and has around 2.1 million inhabitants. Erfurt is the state capital, and the other major cities include Jena, Gera, Eisenach, Weimar, Gotha, Nordhausen, Suhl and Mühlhausen.

The Wartburg Castle (UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1999), above Eisenach in the Thuringian Forest, is one of the most historically significant castles in Germany. Built between 1067 and 1170 by Ludwig der Springer, the Wartburg was the seat of the Ludowingian Landgraves of Thuringia for two centuries. The Wartburg was the historic location of major moments in German cultural history: in 1207 the legendary Sängerkrieg (Singers'' Contest) of the great medieval Minnesänger Walther von der Vogelweide, Wolfram von Eschenbach and others (the contest immortalised by Richard Wagner''s 1845 opera Tannhäuser); in 1217 the place where Saint Elisabeth of Hungary lived as the wife of Landgrave Ludwig IV until his death; in 1521-1522 the place where Martin Luther translated the New Testament from Greek into German in just 11 weeks (the so-called Luther-Stube where he worked is preserved, with the famous ink-stain on the wall where Luther is said to have thrown his inkwell at the devil); and in 1817 the place of the Wartburg Festival (the gathering of around 500 students celebrating the 300th anniversary of the Reformation and demanding German national unity, the first true German nationalist event with the burning of "anti-German" books). The Wartburg complex includes the Palas (the main hall), the Vogtei, the Margaretenhof and the Bergfried tower, all reached by the famous Wartburg Esel donkey-cab ride from the Eisenach valley.

Weimar, a UNESCO World Heritage Site (designated 1998 as Classical Weimar, with the additional UNESCO Bauhaus and its Sites in Weimar, Dessau and Bernau designated 1996 with the 2017 extension), is one of the most important cultural cities of Germany. The Goethe-Haus on the Frauenplan, the home of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe from 1782 to his death in 1832, with the historic study and the famous Junozimmer drawing room, is the most-visited Goethe destination in the world. The Schillerhaus on the Schillerstraße, the home of Friedrich Schiller from 1802 to his death in 1805. The Goethe and Schiller Monument by Ernst Rietschel of 1857 on the Theaterplatz, in front of the Deutsches Nationaltheater Weimar, depicts the two writers standing together (the most-photographed double monument in Germany, replicated in San Francisco, Cleveland and elsewhere). The Liszt-Haus, the home of Franz Liszt from 1869 to 1886. The Wittumspalais, the dowager residence of Duchess Anna Amalia, where the famous Weimar Klassik intellectual circle gathered. The Anna-Amalia-Bibliothek (the famous library of Duchess Anna Amalia, founded 1691, with the iconic 1760s Rococo hall by Goethe — partly destroyed in a 2004 fire but mostly restored and reopened 2007). The Stadtkirche Weimar (the Herder Church, where Johann Gottfried Herder preached), the Schloss Weimar (the former ducal residence), the historic Park an der Ilm with the Goethe Gartenhaus (Goethe''s garden cottage where he stayed when he first arrived in Weimar in 1775-1782, on the personal invitation of Duke Carl August), the Schloss Belvedere (the summer palace), the Schloss Tiefurt and the Schloss Ettersburg complete the Weimar Classical World Heritage. The Bauhaus heritage in Weimar includes the Bauhaus Museum Weimar (opened 2019), the Haus Am Horn (the experimental house built in 1923 by Georg Muche for the first Bauhaus exhibition, the only realised Bauhaus example of the early Weimar period, a UNESCO World Heritage Site), and the historic Henry van de Velde Bauhaus building (the founding building of the original Staatliches Bauhaus from 1919, designed by Henry van de Velde in 1905-1911 as the Großherzogliche Kunstgewerbeschule, today the central building of the Bauhaus-Universität Weimar). Weimar was also the seat of the Weimar Republic (1919-1933) — the new democratic German constitution was drafted at the Deutsches Nationaltheater Weimar between February and August 1919.

Erfurt, the state capital, is one of the most beautifully preserved medieval German town centres. The Erfurter Domhügel ensemble is dominated by two adjacent churches: the Erfurter Dom St. Mariens (Erfurt Cathedral, founded 742 by Saint Boniface) and the Severikirche, both rising on the Domplatz from a vast 70-step staircase, forming one of the most photographed urban silhouettes in Germany. The Dom contains the famous Wolfram-Leuchter Romanesque candlestick (around 1160, one of the largest medieval Romanesque bronze sculptures), the Glocke Gloriosa (one of the largest medieval church bells in the world, cast 1497), the medieval Erfurter Altar, and the Riemenschneider altarpiece. The Krämerbrücke (the Merchants'' Bridge), the longest fully-built-on bridge in Europe still inhabited (32 medieval houses on the bridge, 120 metres long), is the city''s iconic feature. The Erfurter Synagoge (the Old Synagogue of Erfurt, the oldest preserved Jewish synagogue building in Central Europe, dating from around 1094) is part of the UNESCO Jewish-Medieval-Heritage Erfurt site inscribed in 2023. The Augustinerkloster Erfurt is the historic Augustinian monastery where Luther lived as a monk from 1505 to 1511 and was ordained as a priest in 1507; the monastery library and the Luther Cell are preserved. The Erfurt Marktplatz, the Anger square, the Petersberg with the historic Citadelle Petersberg (one of the largest preserved baroque fortifications in Central Europe), the Erfurter Petersberg, the Egapark (the Erfurt Federal Garden Show grounds with the Deutsches Gartenbaumuseum), the Predigerkirche, the Reglerkirche, the Großer Brühl and the Mikwe Erfurt complete the city. Erfurt also hosts the Erfurter Christkindlmarkt, the third-largest German Christmas market after Nuremberg and Dresden.

Eisenach, the home town of Johann Sebastian Bach (born here 1685), contains the Bachhaus Eisenach (the oldest German Bach Museum, founded 1907), the Lutherhaus (the family home where Luther lived as a student 1498-1501), the Eisenach Stadtschloss (the historic ducal residence) and the historic Marktplatz. The Wartburg above Eisenach is reached by car, bus, or the historic Wartburg Esel donkey cab.

Jena, the third-largest Thuringian city, is the historic seat of the Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena (founded 1558) and the Carl Zeiss optical empire. The Carl-Zeiss-Jena Optical Museum on the historic Innenstadt is one of Europe''s leading optical-heritage museums. The Goethe Universitätshaus Jena, the historic Botanischer Garten Jena (founded 1586 by Friedrich Wilhelm I, the oldest botanical garden in Germany), the Schillerhaus (Friedrich Schiller''s Jena home), the Romantikerhaus (the home of Caroline Schlegel and the early German Romantic circle including Schlegel, Schelling and Tieck), the Stadtkirche St. Michael with its famous medieval Hochaltar, and the Jenaer Glaswerk (the historic Schott Jenaer Glas factory now preserved as the museum) complete the city. The Jena University Town is overlooked by the Jenzig and the Saale river.

Gotha, the historic seat of the Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ducal line (which produced the British and Belgian royal houses including Queen Victoria''s husband Prince Albert and the modern British royal family), is dominated by the magnificent Schloss Friedenstein (built 1643-1654, the largest early-baroque ducal residence in Germany), with the Schlossmuseum, the Ekhof-Theater (the oldest still-functioning baroque court theatre in Germany with its original 1681 stage machinery still operational), the historic Schloss Park, the Schloss Friedrichswerth and the Schloss Reinhardsbrunn nearby. Gotha was the historic centre of German cartography (the Justus Perthes Verlag, founded 1785, produced the famous Stieler Hand-Atlas and the Permanent Almanach von Gotha that listed European royal families). The Almanach de Gotha was the European register of royal lineage from 1763 to 1944.

The Thuringian Forest (Thüringer Wald), the central uplands of the state, is famous for the Rennsteig (the historic ridge trail, the most-famous German long-distance hiking route at 169 kilometres from Hörschel near Eisenach to Blankenstein in Saxony, traversed annually by hundreds of thousands), the Inselsberg (the iconic Thuringian peak at 916 metres), the Schmücke saddle, the historic mountain village of Oberhof (the Olympic biathlon training centre and the venue for the Biathlon World Cup at the Lotto Thüringen Arena am Rennsteig). Other Thuringian destinations include the Thuringian Slate Mountains (Thüringer Schiefergebirge) with the famous Saalfeld Fairy Grottoes (Saalfelder Feengrotten, the only show cave in the world with continuously growing colourful mineral stalactite formations), the Kyffhäuser Monument (the Kyffhäuserdenkmal, a 81-metre monument completed 1896 commemorating Emperor Wilhelm I, atop the legendary Kyffhäuser mountain where the legend says Emperor Frederick Barbarossa sleeps with his beard growing through the marble table until Germany unites), the Panorama Museum Bad Frankenhausen (Werner Tübke''s monumental 14-metre-by-123-metre cyclorama painting Early Bourgeois Revolution in Germany, completed 1987 in 12 years of work and depicting the 1525 Peasant War, one of the largest paintings of the 20th century), the historic town of Mühlhausen (the Thomas Müntzer city, with the Marktkirche, the Stadtbefestigung, and the historic guild houses), Schmalkalden (the site of the Schmalkaldischer Bund, the Protestant princes'' military alliance of 1531-1547, with the historic Schloss Wilhelmsburg), and the historic Saxon-Coburg-Gotha town of Coburg (technically Bavaria but with strong Thuringian ties).

The Schloss Friedenstein at Gotha, the Schloss Heidecksburg at Rudolstadt, the Schloss Sondershausen, the Schloss Schwarzburg (the favourite hunting palace of the Schwarzburg-Rudolstadt princes, immortalised by Friedrich Schiller in his Die Räuber), the Schloss Bertholdsburg at Schleusingen and the Veste Heldburg (the "Franconian Wartburg") complete the historic ducal palace inventory.

Thuringian cuisine and beverages are distinctive. The Thüringer Rostbratwurst (the iconic Thuringian roasted bratwurst, an EU PGI product since 2003, made of pork with caraway, marjoram and garlic, traditionally grilled over a charcoal fire and served in a small bread roll with mustard) is perhaps the most famous regional sausage in Germany. Thüringer Klöße (Thuringian potato dumplings, made from half raw grated and half boiled grated potato with a crouton in the centre, traditionally served with roast pork and red cabbage) are one of the great German regional specialities, with the Thüringer Kloßmuseum at Heichelheim documenting their history. The Thüringer Roulade (rolled beef with bacon, onion and pickle), the Thüringer Rotwurst (a smoked blood sausage), the Thüringer Leberwurst (liver sausage), and the Thüringer Schaschlik are other regional staples. Sweets include Pulsnitzer Pfefferkuchen (technically Saxony but consumed throughout Thuringia), Thüringer Pflaumenkuchen (plum cake on yeast dough), Heinerle Wernigerode candies, and the Thüringer Christstollen. Drinks: Köstritzer Schwarzbier (the famous Köstritz black beer from Bad Köstritz, brewed continuously since 1543, the world''s leading Schwarzbier brand owned by Bitburger Braugruppe), the Apoldaer Pilsner, the Watzdorfer Bier, the Ur-Krostitzer (technically Saxon-Anhalt but consumed in Thuringia), the historic Erfurter Brauereien and the small Suhl Hochwald-Bräu. The Saale-Unstrut wines (technically partly in Sachsen-Anhalt) are sold throughout Thuringia. Mead (Met) production is a Thuringian tradition.

History before 1933 is rich. The Thuringian Landgraviate was one of the most important German territories of the medieval period (from 1140-1247 under the Ludowingian dynasty), with the Wartburg as the centre of power. The 1247 War of the Thuringian Succession led to the territory passing to the Wettin Margraves of Meissen and the Hessen Landgraves. The 1485 Wettin partition gave Thuringia to the Ernestine branch (the Wettin Saxon-Ernestine line), which subsequently subdivided into multiple ducal lines: Saxe-Weimar, Saxe-Coburg-Gotha, Saxe-Meiningen, Saxe-Altenburg, the Schwarzburg-Rudolstadt principality, the Schwarzburg-Sondershausen principality, the two Reuß principalities (Reuß älterer and jüngerer Linie), and the small Schaumburg-Lippe and Lippe-Detmold (the latter technically NRW). The 1919 founding of the Free State of Thuringia merged seven of these tiny duchies into a single Land. The Bauhaus was founded at Weimar in 1919 by Walter Gropius. The Weimar Republic constitution was drafted at the Nationaltheater Weimar in February-August 1919. The Wartburg, Weimar and Eisenach are central to German cultural memory. The 1485 Wettin partition gave Saxon Weimar to the Ernestines who became the patrons of Luther, Goethe, Schiller, Liszt and the Bauhaus. Famous figures from Thuringia include Johann Sebastian Bach (Eisenach), Martin Luther (Eisleben in Sachsen-Anhalt but Wittenberg-educated; Erfurt-monk for six years), Friedrich Schiller (Marbach in Baden-Württemberg, but Weimar-resident), Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (Frankfurt-born, Weimar-resident from 1775 until his death in 1832), Johann Gottlieb Fichte (Rammenau in Saxony, but Jena-professor), Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling, Friedrich Schlegel, Friedrich Hölderlin, Novalis (Friedrich von Hardenberg), Friedrich Schleiermacher, Christoph Martin Wieland, Christian Friedrich Daniel Schubart, Walter Gropius and the Bauhaus masters Kandinsky, Klee and Feininger.',
    transportation = 'Thüringen, the central German state, has a strategic transport position on the historic north-south and east-west corridors of Germany. Erfurt-Weimar Airport (ERF, EDDE) is the principal commercial airport of the state, handling around 200,000 passengers per year with seasonal Mediterranean charter flights. The airport, named after Erfurt and Weimar, is connected to Erfurt Hauptbahnhof by regional rail in 25 minutes. Leipzig/Halle Airport (LEJ) and Frankfurt Airport (FRA) serve eastern and western Thuringia respectively for long-distance flights. Smaller airfields include Gera-Leumnitz, Eisenach-Kindel, Suhl, Nordhausen and the historic Saalfeld-Beulwitz.

The Thuringia rail network is dominated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Mitte and DB Fernverkehr, with the regional brands Erfurter Bahn (EB), Mitteldeutsche Regiobahn (MRB), Abellio Rail Mitteldeutschland (until restructuring), and Süd-Thüringen-Bahn (STB) operating regional services. The Verkehrsverbund Mittelthüringen (VMT, covering Erfurt-Weimar-Jena-Gotha) and the Verkehrsverbund Mittelsachsen (VMS) coordinate tariff. Erfurt Hauptbahnhof became the central ICE node of Germany in December 2017 when the Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8 (VDE 8) — the new high-speed line Berlin-Leipzig-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich — opened, making Erfurt a four-way ICE crossing where the Berlin-Munich line crosses the Frankfurt-Dresden line. The new Erfurter ICE-Knoten allows ICE travel from Erfurt to Berlin in 1 hour 45 minutes, to Munich in 2 hours 30 minutes, to Frankfurt in 2 hours 15 minutes, and to Dresden in 2 hours. The VDE 8 corridor was the largest single German rail-infrastructure project of the post-reunification period, with a total cost of around 10 billion euros. Other major Thuringian rail nodes include Jena West (with ICE/IC services on the VDE 8 Berlin-Munich corridor and the historic Berlin-Frankfurt route via Halle), Jena Paradies, Weimar (an ICE/IC stop on the historic Berlin-Frankfurt corridor), Gera Hauptbahnhof, Eisenach Hauptbahnhof, Gotha Hauptbahnhof and Mühlhausen.

The ICE corridors crossing Thuringia include the Berlin-Halle-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich high-speed line (VDE 8, completed 2017), the Frankfurt-Eisenach-Erfurt-Leipzig-Dresden corridor (the historic Mitteldeutsche Hauptbahn), the Berlin-Frankfurt corridor via Halle-Erfurt-Bebra-Frankfurt (the Hauptbahn Saalfeld-Lichtenfels), and the Berlin-Stuttgart-Stuttgart corridor. The Erfurter Hauptbahnhof has 10 platforms and around 80,000 passengers per day, making it the busiest station in Thuringia. The historic Mitte-Deutschland-Bahn from Frankfurt via Bebra, Eisenach, Erfurt, Weimar to Leipzig was historically the main east-west axis of central Germany and continues to carry IC and Eurocity traffic.

The Erfurter Stadtbahn (the Erfurt tram, operated by EVAG Erfurter Verkehrs-AG) has six lines totalling 41 kilometres, including the historic line to the Egapark. The Jena Stadtbahn (operated by Jenaer Nahverkehr GmbH) has five lines. The Gera Stadtbahn, the Gotha Stadtbahn (the famous Thüringerwaldbahn from Gotha to Tabarz, the longest German overland tramway at 22 kilometres, operating since 1929 through the Thuringian Forest) and the Nordhausen tram (with the famous combined tram-train operation to Ilfeld in the Harz) complete the network.

The Autobahn network in Thüringen includes the A4 (Eisenach-Erfurt-Weimar-Gera, the historic East-West Hermsdorfer Kreuz junction), the A9 (Munich-Nuremberg-Leipzig-Berlin, passing the historic Hermsdorfer Kreuz at Hermsdorf where the A4 and A9 meet), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn), the A71 (Sangerhausen-Erfurt-Schweinfurt, the historic Spange Eichsfeld through the Thuringian Forest, with the famous Rennsteig tunnel at 7,916 metres, the longest road tunnel in Germany), the A73 (Suhl-Bamberg-Nuremberg, with the historic Thuringian Forest tunnels including the Tunnel Lichtenholz, the Hochwaldtunnel and the Rinderhütel tunnel — the new Bavarian Thüringer Wald A73 is one of the most expensive German motorway projects of the post-1990 era), and the A4 Erfurter Kreuz extension. Bundesstraßen include the B7 east-west, the B19, the B85, the B247 and the historic Rennsteig.

The Saale and the Werra rivers are navigable; the Schiffshebewerk Henrichenburg (technically NRW) and the historic Saale ports of Saalfeld, Naumburg (technically Sachsen-Anhalt) and Halle-Trotha handle limited inland-waterway traffic. The Thuringian rivers are mostly too small for major commercial shipping. Cycling routes include the Saale-Radweg, the Werra-Radweg, the Werratal-Radweg, the Saale-Unstrut-Radweg, the Thüringer Städtekette (linking Eisenach, Gotha, Erfurt, Weimar, Jena, Gera and Altenburg) and the Rennsteig-Radweg (a parallel cycle path to the famous Rennsteig hiking trail).',
    economics = 'Thüringen has a regional GDP of around 75 billion euros, with the per-capita GDP improving steadily since reunification. The state economic development arm, the Landesentwicklungsgesellschaft Thüringen mbH (LEG Thüringen) at Erfurt, and the Thüringen Tourismus GmbH market the state internationally; the Industrie- und Handelskammer Erfurt, the IHK Gera and the IHK Suhl represent regional businesses.

Jenoptik AG, the listed Jena-headquartered optoelectronics, photonics and defence-technology group, is one of the most internationally successful Thuringian companies, with annual revenues of around 1 billion euros. Jenoptik was founded in 1991 from the Carl Zeiss Jena East-German optics combine, and produces measurement systems, semiconductor lithography lasers, automotive diagnostics, medical lasers and high-end optics for global customers. The Jena optics heritage continues with Carl Zeiss Jena GmbH (a Thuringian subsidiary of the Carl-Zeiss-Stiftung at Oberkochen-Heidenheim in Baden-Württemberg, producing microscopy and metrology systems), Carl Zeiss SMT GmbH (the Jena branch producing semiconductor lithography lenses for ASML EUV machines), and Schott Jenaer Glas GmbH (a subsidiary of the Mainz-headquartered Schott AG, producing borosilicate glass and laboratory glassware at the historic 1884 Schott Jenaer Glaswerk). The Jena optics-photonics-glass cluster is one of the largest in Europe and the historic foundation of the German optical-precision industry.

Bauerfeind AG, the family-owned orthopaedic technology company headquartered at Zeulenroda in eastern Thuringia, is one of the leading European producers of orthopaedic supports, compression stockings, orthotics and prosthetic devices. Founded 1929 by Bruno Bauerfeind, the company has annual revenues of around 350 million euros.

Opel Eisenach GmbH operates the Opel passenger-car plant at Eisenach (founded 1991 on the historic AWE Automobilwerk Eisenach site, the former GDR Wartburg car factory closed 1991). The Opel Eisenach plant has built the Opel Corsa since 1992 and now also the Opel Grandland under the Stellantis Group; the plant employs around 1,500 workers and is part of the wider Stellantis transformation strategy. The historic Wartburg cars (the AWE 311 and Wartburg 353, the iconic East German two-stroke cars produced 1957-1991) are preserved at the Automobile Welt Eisenach museum.

Bosch Solar Energy AG, the historic Erfurt photovoltaic plant founded 2007 by Robert Bosch GmbH, was a major Thuringian solar-PV producer but closed in 2014 with the German solar industry collapse. The site has been redeveloped as the Erfurt Industriepark with multiple light-industrial tenants.

The Thüringische Industriewerke (TIW) Sondershausen, the Thuringian Potash group (Kali und Salz, K+S AG), the Heinemann-Werkstätten and many other Thuringian industries have been transformed or restructured since reunification.

The Suhl gun-making tradition, dating from the 15th century, includes the historic Sauer & Sohn (founded 1751 at Suhl, today operating from Eckernförde in Schleswig-Holstein), Merkel Jagd- und Sportwaffen GmbH at Suhl (founded 1898, the leading German producer of premium hunting double rifles), Heym Sportwaffen GmbH at Münnerstadt (a Bavarian successor to the historic Suhl Heym factory), and Krieghoff (founded at Suhl 1886, today at Ulm in Baden-Württemberg). The Suhl industrial heritage is preserved in the Waffenmuseum Suhl.

In the food sector, the Thüringer Rostbratwurst is produced by hundreds of butchers across the state, with major brands including Heideland Wurst, Ludwig''s Bratwurst, Knipping and the historic Eichsfelder Wurstwaren. The Thüringer Schwarzbier from Köstritz, the famous Köstritzer Brauerei in Bad Köstritz, is owned by the Bitburger Braugruppe and produces one of the most popular Schwarzbier brands in the world.

In the higher-education and research sector, the Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena (founded 1558 and one of the historically most important German universities, with notable alumni and former faculty including Friedrich Schiller, Johann Gottlieb Fichte, Friedrich Schelling, Friedrich Hölderlin, Friedrich Schlegel, August Schlegel, Caroline Schlegel, Friedrich Hegel and Karl Marx), the Universität Erfurt, the Bauhaus-Universität Weimar, the Technische Universität Ilmenau (the small specialist engineering university with strong programmes in microelectronics, telecommunications and game research), the Hochschule für Musik Franz Liszt Weimar (the historic Liszt music academy founded 1872), the Hochschule für Bildende Künste Weimar (until 1996, now part of Bauhaus-Universität), the Theologische Hochschule Friedensau and the Fachhochschulen at Erfurt, Schmalkalden, Nordhausen and Jena round out higher education. The Max-Planck-Institut für Biogeochemie at Jena, the Max-Planck-Institut für chemische Ökologie at Jena, the Leibniz-Institut für Naturstoff-Forschung und Infektionsbiologie Hans-Knöll-Institut at Jena, the Leibniz-Institut für Photonische Technologien at Jena, the Fraunhofer-Institut für Angewandte Optik und Feinmechanik (IOF Jena), and the Helmholtz-Institut Jena complete the major Jena research cluster — making Jena one of the most photonics-research-dense small cities in Europe. The Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut at Jena Greifswald-Riems-Tübingen has Jena operations.

Tourism is a significant economic sector. The state hosts around 10 million overnight stays per year, with Weimar, Erfurt, the Wartburg, Jena and the Thuringian Forest as major attractions. The Thüringen Tourismus GmbH at Erfurt markets the state. The Rennsteig hiking trail, the Saalfeld Fairy Grottoes, the Kyffhäuser Monument and the Wartburg are popular tourist destinations.

Banking and finance are dominated by the Sparkasse Mittelthüringen, the Sparkasse Jena-Saale-Holzland, the Sparkasse Gera-Greiz, the Sparkasse Suhl, the Volksbank Erfurt, the cooperative VR Bank Mitte and the Thüringer Aufbaubank (the state development bank).',
    introduced_species = 'Thüringen, the green heart of Germany, hosts a substantial roster of introduced and invasive species. The Thüringer Landesamt für Umwelt, Bergbau und Naturschutz (TLUBN) at Jena coordinates the state Neozoa register under EU Regulation 1143/2014.

The raccoon, Procyon lotor, Waschbär, has been present in Thüringen since the 1950s when individuals from the Hessen Edersee 1934 release expanded east across the Werra and the historic boundary with the GDR after 1990. Today the species is established throughout Thüringen with the highest densities in the Thüringer Wald, the Werratal, the Kyffhäuser region and increasingly in the suburban Erfurt, Jena and Gera areas. Annual hunting bags in Thüringen exceed 12,000 raccoons. The TLUBN publishes guidance on attic-vent sealing, dustbin-lid locking and the handling of raccoon latrines. Conservation concern centres on raccoon predation on cavity-nesting birds (black woodpecker, stock dove, tawny owl), on amphibians, on European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroductions, and on the rare middle-spotted woodpecker.

The raccoon dog, Marderhund, Nyctereutes procyonoides, originally from East Asia, has reached Thüringen from the east in the 1990s; today the species is established throughout the state with the highest densities in the Thüringer Wald, the Eichsfeld and the historic GDR-era Truppenübungsplätze (the former Soviet and NVA military training grounds at Ohrdruf, Hohenfelden and elsewhere). Annual hunting bags exceed 5,000.

The coypu or nutria, Myocastor coypus, Sumpfbiber or Nutria, has established expanding populations along the Saale, the Werra, the Unstrut, the Helme and the Ilm. Damage to flood-protection dykes is a serious management concern. The European beaver, Castor fiber, native to Thuringia but heavily persecuted to local extinction by the 19th century, has been reintroduced and is now spreading along the Saale and the Werra. The muskrat, Bisamratte, Ondatra zibethicus, occurs throughout Thuringia.

Wolves, Canis lupus, although native, have re-colonised Thuringia since around 2015 from north-eastern German and Polish populations; the state now has 3-5 established territorial packs in the Thuringian Forest, the Eichsfeld and the historic Ohrdruf training ground. The Thuringia Wolves Office at the TLUBN coordinates monitoring.

Among introduced birds, the Canada goose, Branta canadensis, Kanadagans, has established feral resident populations on Thuringian lakes. The Egyptian goose, Nilgans, Alopochen aegyptiaca, has expanded into Thuringia from the western German populations and now breeds in Erfurt, Jena, Gera and the major Thuringian park ponds. The ring-necked parakeet, Halsbandsittich, Psittacula krameri, has small populations in Erfurt and Jena. The mandarin duck, Mandarinente, Aix galericulata, breeds in small numbers on park ponds.

Among freshwater fish, the Saale, the Werra, the Unstrut and the Ilm host the standard set of introduced species. The pumpkinseed sunfish (Lepomis gibbosus), the topmouth gudgeon (Pseudorasbora parva), the brown bullhead (Ameiurus nebulosus), the rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss), the brook trout (Salvelinus fontinalis), the grass carp (Ctenopharyngodon idella) and the round goby (Neogobius melanostomus) are widespread. The wels catfish (Silurus glanis) is established.

Invertebrate invaders include the signal crayfish (Pacifastacus leniusculus), the spinycheek crayfish (Faxonius limosus), the red swamp crayfish (Procambarus clarkii), the marbled crayfish (Procambarus virginalis), the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha), the quagga mussel (Dreissena rostriformis bugensis), the Asian clam (Corbicula fluminea), the New Zealand mud snail (Potamopyrgus antipodarum), and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis). The Asian hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax, Asiatische Hornisse) has been recorded in Thuringia from 2023 onwards; the Imkerverband Thüringen coordinates nest-removal teams with the TLUBN. The harlequin ladybird (Harmonia axyridis), the horse-chestnut leaf miner (Cameraria ohridella), the box tree moth (Cydalima perspectalis) — which has destroyed boxwood gardens at the Belvedere Palace, the Schloss Friedenstein and the Erfurter Cyriaksburg — and the brown marmorated stink bug (Halyomorpha halys) are all ubiquitous.

Among plants, ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), Japanese knotweed (Reynoutria japonica, conspicuous along the Saale and the Ilm), Himalayan balsam (Impatiens glandulifera, widespread on Thuringian stream banks), giant hogweed (Heracleum mantegazzianum), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima), goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), small balsam (Impatiens parviflora), black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, particularly conspicuous on the historic Mansfelder Land-style brownfields of southern Thuringia), the Senecio inaequidens and the Indian balsam are widespread. The Werratal, the Kyffhäuser area and the southern Thuringia Bergehalden host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities.

Among large mammals deliberately released for hunting, fallow deer (Damwild, Dama dama) and mouflon (Mufflon, Ovis aries musimon) have substantial populations in the Thüringer Wald, the Eichsfeld and the Schiefergebirge. Sika deer (Sikahirsch, Cervus nippon) have small populations in the Thüringer Wald and the Kyffhäuser. Wild boar (Wildschwein, Sus scrofa) are present at high density across the state, with annual hunting bags exceeding 35,000. The European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris), native, has been strengthened by reintroductions in the Thüringer Wald and the Hainich National Park; the Hainich-Werra wildcat population is one of the largest in Germany. Lynx (Lynx lynx), although native, have been re-recorded sporadically in the Thüringer Wald in recent years; an active reintroduction programme is being planned by the Thuringia state environment ministry.'
WHERE region_name = 'Thüringen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Baden-Württemberg transport detail: the Schwarzwald-Hochstraße, the historic B500 ridge road between Baden-Baden and Freudenstadt opened 1932, is one of the oldest German tourist roads. The Hochrheinstrecke between Basel Badischer Bahnhof and Konstanz via Singen runs along the German bank of the Rhine. The historic Vorderwald railway and the Bregtalbahn served the Black Forest valley industries. The Achertäler Eisenbahn, the Renchtalbahn from Appenweier and the Kinzigtalbahn from Offenburg to Hausach and Schiltach trace the Schwarzwald-Bahn loop. The Schönbuchbahn (Böblingen-Dettenhausen) is one of the most successful reactivated rural lines in Germany. The Hohenzollerische Landesbahn (HzL), operating the Eyachtalbahn, Donaubergbahn and the Hohenzollernbahn, is a Baden-Württemberg regional rail leader. The Heuberg-Stetten-Sigmaringen line, the Albtal-Verkehrs-Gesellschaft (AVG) network across Baden, and the Stadtbahn Heilbronn-Schwäbisch-Hall provide rural connectivity. The Stadtwerke Esslingen, Stadtwerke Reutlingen and the Albbus complete the public-transport offer. The Hohenstadt-Geislingen Albabstieg, one of the steepest German railway grades at 22.5 per mille, has been a Württemberg geography mark since 1850. The Geislinger Steige is one of the iconic mountain-rail grades in Europe, immortalised by railway photographers. The IC Allgäu network from Stuttgart via Aulendorf to Lindau, the Bodenseegürtelbahn from Friedrichshafen via Konstanz, and the Hochrhein services from Basel to Schaffhausen via Waldshut complete the Bodensee regional offer. The Schwäbische Alb-Bahn experimented with the 1950s German first electrified railcar systems. The historic Tübingen-Hohenzollern royal-train route through Albstadt, the Schwarzwald-Bahn through 39 tunnels, and the Murgtalbahn through Forbach all retain heritage steam excursions of the Lokwelt Freilassing or the DGEG Dampfbahn Württemberg. The Bremgartenstrecke at Lörrach and the Wiesentalbahn into the southern Schwarzwald complete the cross-border DB Regio Südwest offer. The Schwarzwald Tourismus offers the KONUS-Gästekarte (the free regional transport for Black Forest holidaymakers), an early example of a fully integrated regional-tourism transport pass which has been emulated across the Alps and other German tourist regions. The Maingau-Tarif Konus-Schwarzwald and the Tourist-Bus Schwarzwald complete the integrated tourist transport.',
    economics = economics || ' Baden-Württemberg additional economic detail: the InnoEnergy Baden-Württemberg cluster, Hewlett-Packard Enterprise Stuttgart, IBM Stuttgart, Siemens Erlangen-Karlsruhe, the Daimler Truck Wörth am Rhein plant (technically Rheinland-Pfalz), the SüdwestLB private bank, the Württembergische Lebensversicherung at Stuttgart, the Stuttgarter Lebensversicherung, the Liebherr-Aerospace Lindenberg branch, the Recaro Aircraft Seating at Schwäbisch Hall (the largest aircraft-seat manufacturer in the world), the Pfeiffer Vacuum Technology at Aßlar (Hessen but with BW operations), the Tridonic Lighting in Stuttgart, the Würth-Industrie-Service in Bad Mergentheim, the IMS-Gear at Donaueschingen, the Murrelektronik in Oppenweiler, the Putzmeister concrete pumps at Aichtal (the world''s leading concrete-pump manufacturer), the Liebherr-Mining at Colmar (the largest mining-truck plant in Europe), the Festo-Didactic, the Sick AG sensor manufacturer at Waldkirch, the Endress+Hauser process-instrumentation at Maulburg (the family-owned global instrument leader), the SEW-Eurodrive at Bruchsal, the Kuka Industries at Augsburg (with BW supply chain), the Gleichmann & Co Electronics, the Hekatron fire-detection at Sulzburg, the Behr-Hella Thermocontrol, the Voith Hydro and Voith Composites all complete the Mittelstand hidden-champion map. The Heller-Werkzeuge, the J. Schmalz vacuum at Glatten, the EMAG at Salach, the Liebherr-Hydraulikbagger at Kirchdorf an der Iller, the Liebherr-Construction at Biberach, the Komet at Besigheim, the Walter at Tübingen, the WMF at Geislingen and the Märklin model railway at Göppingen complete the picture. The Stuttgart Airport Region is one of the major European logistics hubs. The Karlsruhe Bädle of the Bertha Benz Memorial Route honours the founding journey of the global automobile.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Baden-Württemberg invasive-species detail: the LUBW Asian Hornet Task Force (Asiatische-Hornisse-Beauftragte) has been particularly active in the Markgräflerland, with the first verified German breeding pair recorded at Müllheim in 2014 by the local Imkerverein. The species has since expanded across the Oberrhein and Kaiserstuhl wine regions and as far north as Stuttgart and Mannheim. The LUBW Ambrosia-Atlas mapped over 5,000 ragweed records across BW by 2023. The Drosophila suzukii spotted-wing fruit fly, an Asian invader first detected in BW in 2011, has become a major pest of the Baden-Württemberg cherry, stone-fruit, raspberry, blueberry and grape industries; the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut at Dossenheim has been leading German research on its integrated pest management. The Buchsbaumzünsler box tree moth has destroyed boxwood at the Schwetzingen Schloss, the Heidelberg Schloss, the Salem Münster, the Maulbronn Kloster and the Tübingen Stiftskirche cloister gardens. The Asian Longhorned Beetle was recorded at Heidelberg in 2015 in container-port adjacent wood-importing companies; an emergency containment programme was successful. The wallflower Sisymbrium loeselii from western Asia, the South African Senecio inaequidens (now ubiquitous on BW railway tracks), the North American Conyza canadensis (the Canadian fleabane) and the Bidens frondosa (the beggarticks) round out the BW neophyte list. The Eichenprozessionsspinner (oak processionary moth, Thaumetopoea processionea), although technically native to Mediterranean Europe but historically rare in BW, has expanded dramatically across the state with climate change and has prompted intensive arboricultural management on the major BW oak avenues at Mannheim, Karlsruhe, Heidelberg and Stuttgart. The Asian rice weed Murdannia keisak and the Crassula helmsii (Australian swamp stonecrop) have been recorded at scattered BW garden ponds.'
WHERE region_name = 'Baden-Württemberg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Additional Bavarian tourism detail: the Würzburg Residenz with the Tiepolo ceiling fresco (the largest in the world, painted 1750-1753), the Schloss Schönbrunn near Würzburg, the Bamberg Klein-Venedig fishermen''s quarter (the historic Sandgebiet at the Regnitz river bank), the Bamberger Reiter (the famous medieval stone equestrian statue in Bamberg Cathedral), the Vierzehnheiligen Basilica by Balthasar Neumann (the rococo pilgrimage church near Coburg, a UNESCO tentative-list candidate), the Banz Abbey, the Veste Coburg fortress, the Plassenburg above Kulmbach (the impressive Renaissance Saxon-Hohenzollern fortress now housing the German Tin Figures Museum), the Goldener Saal of the Augsburg Rathaus, the Augsburg Mozarthaus (the family home of Leopold Mozart, father of Wolfgang Amadeus), the Donauwörth Werner-Egk-Haus, the Eichstätt Willibaldsburg, the Eichstätt Jura-Museum (with the original Archaeopteryx fossils from Solnhofen), the Ettal Abbey near Oberammergau, the Andechs Abbey above the Ammersee (the famous Bavarian monastic brewery and pilgrimage site), the Wieskirche pilgrimage church (UNESCO World Heritage Site), the Steingaden Welfenmünster, the Kloster Ettal, and the historic Kloster Banz form an outstanding inventory of South-German rococo religious architecture.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Bavarian transport detail: the Bayerische Zugspitzbahn cog railway from Garmisch via Grainau and Eibsee to the Zugspitzplatt at 2588 metres has been operating since 1930 with the original Krauss-Maffei locomotives. The Wendelsteinbahn (Brannenburg-Wendelstein, 1912) is one of the oldest Bavarian cog railways. The Allgäu Express Lufthansa Bus service to Munich Airport from Memmingen, Kempten and Lindau supplements the rail network. The München-Mittenwald-Innsbruck rail corridor, the Mittenwaldbahn from Garmisch via Mittenwald to Innsbruck (one of the most scenic cross-Alpine rail lines), the historic Bayerische Oberlandbahn from Munich via Tegernsee, Schliersee and Lenggries, the Berchtesgaden cog railway and the Marktoberdorfer Schwabenstollen mineral spring railway round out the alpine network. The Donautalbahn from Regensburg via Passau to Linz carries cross-border Eurocity traffic. The Pfaffenhofen-Geltendorf-Memmingen rural lines, the Hofer Bahn from Marktredwitz to Selb-Plößberg, the Pegnitztalbahn from Nuremberg via Bayreuth to Hof, the Fichtelgebirge-Bahn from Marktredwitz to Bad Berneck and the historic Schiefe Ebene at Neuenmarkt-Wirsberg (the famous Frankenwald 1 in 40 grade where steam locomotive whistles still echo on weekends thanks to the DGEG heritage trains) form a heritage railway network. The Munich Allianz Arena, served by the U6 line at Fröttmaning, is one of the most modern football-and-transport interfaces in Europe. The Allgäu, Oberbayern Süd, Niederbayern and Oberpfalz regions are all served by the Bayern-Ticket regional flat-fare offer. The cycling-and-public-transport integration of the Bayern-Ticket-Bike, the Allgäu Walser Card and the Berchtesgadener Land Card provide tourist-friendly bundled offers. The Donau-Rheinkanal heritage Ludwig-Donau-Main-Kanal of 1846 (the historic Charlemagne attempt at a Rhine-Danube connection), the historic Ludwigskanal locks at Berching, and the Allgäuer Höhenflug long-distance hiking-and-cycling route across the Bavarian Alps round out the alpine transport. The Bavarian Wald-Bahn from Plattling to Bayerisch Eisenstein has cross-border services to the Czech Pilsen area.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Bavarian economic detail: the Bayer Aspirin headquarters were originally at Bayer Leverkusen (NRW) but Bayer CropScience has Munich-area operations. The Knorr-Bremse AG, the world''s leading manufacturer of rail brake systems, is headquartered at Moosacher Straße in Munich. The Linde plc industrial-gases business has its German operations at Pullach (the former Linde-Schalchen base) near Munich. Wacker Chemie AG, listed at Munich (Hanns-Seidel-Platz), is one of the largest German chemical companies with major sites at Burghausen, Nünchritz and Munich. The OSRAM Licht AG of Munich-Garching, the leading German lighting-technology company spun off from Siemens in 2013 and now part of ams-OSRAM AG (the merged ams-OSRAM is headquartered in Premstätten, Austria), continues to have substantial Munich Garching operations. The Allianz Real Estate, the Allianz Asset Management, the PIMCO (the world''s largest fixed-income asset manager, owned by Allianz since 2000, with European operations in Munich), the Munich Re Asset Management and the BMW Group Financial Services round out the financial-services cluster. Munich is also the European headquarters of Microsoft Germany (at Unterschleißheim), of Google Germany Munich, of LinkedIn Germany (at Sendlinger Tor), of IBM Germany Munich, of Amazon Web Services Munich, of Oracle Germany at Munich, of Hewlett Packard Enterprise Germany, and of Apple Germany. The Wacker Chemie Burghausen Stammwerk is one of the largest contiguous chemical sites in Bavaria. The Knapp AG software, the Software AG Frankfurt (with Bavarian operations), the Software-Quartier Munich Werksviertel, and the Munich AI Bavarian-Industry-AI Center complete the digital-economy map. The Munich Re Hauptverwaltung at Königinstraße 107 is the world''s largest reinsurance headquarters by floor area. The Allianz Hauptverwaltung at Königinstraße 28 is similarly the largest European insurance corporate centre.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Bavarian invasive-species detail: the LfU Bavarian Neobiota register lists over 800 established alien species across the state. The Spreewald-style coypu colonies along the lower Main and lower Donau have been the subject of LfU-funded population studies. The historic Hohenfeldener-Wildpark in Thuringia was one of the early German raccoon-research sites, with Bayerische zoologists conducting parallel work in the Steigerwald and Spessart in the 1980s. The Bavarian Forest National Park hosts a major lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction programme since 1971 (the lynx were released from Slovakian Carpathian source populations), with the population now numbering around 40 animals shared with the Czech Šumava Park. The lynx is native to Bavaria but had been extinct since 1850, so this reintroduction is sometimes considered a quasi-reintroduction of a native species. The Bavarian bear-management plan is also active since occasional Italian Trentino bears (Ursus arctos) occasionally cross the Bavarian Alps. The Senne moor at Allgäu and the Murnauer Moos at Murnau am Staffelsee, the Eching-Garchinger Heide and the Geltinger Birk are key conservation reserves for native species threatened by the spread of invasive flora. The Bayerischer Imker-Landesverband estimates over 200,000 honeybee colonies threatened by the Asian-hornet expansion. The Erlangen-Höchstadt and Forchheim districts have been the front line of the Asian-Hornet expansion in northern Bavaria. The Spanish slug (Arion vulgaris), although possibly partly native, has expanded explosively across Bavarian gardens since the 1980s and is now a major agricultural pest. The North American Beaver (Castor canadensis) has not been recorded in Bavaria — the recovering Bavarian beaver populations are the native European beaver Castor fiber, but the Bavarian beaver population (around 25,000) is the largest in central Europe and a centre of beaver-management conflict.'
WHERE region_name = 'Bayern';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Berlin transport detail: the historic Anhalter Bahnhof, the famous Berlin terminal station for trains to Dresden, Vienna, Munich, Rome and the Balkans, was destroyed in WWII and the rebuilt portal stub remains today as the iconic Anhalter Ruin. The Wannsee railway, the historic Reichsbahn Berlin-Stettin line, the Berlin-Görlitzer Bahn (the trunk line to Görlitz and Wrocław), the Berlin-Hamburger Bahn (Berlin to Hamburg via Wittenberge, electrified in 1989) and the historic Niederbarnimer Eisenbahn (NEB) to Rüdersdorf together form a dense railway network. The Berlin S-Bahn power system uses 750 V DC third-rail (a unique Berlin standard since 1924), incompatible with the surrounding regional and long-distance lines on standard 15 kV AC overhead. The legendary Berlin S-Bahn Strike of 1980 over Reichsbahn Personal-Tarif issues was one of the largest German workers'' strikes in the post-war era. The Verkehrsverbund Berlin-Brandenburg (VBB), founded 1996, was one of the first cross-state transport associations in Germany and now coordinates fare integration across the entire Berlin-Brandenburg metropolitan area. The Berlin ferries operated by BVG-Wassermovers cross the lakes (the F10 from Wannsee to Alt-Kladow is the longest German urban-ferry route at 25 minutes). The Berlin cargo network around Berlin-Schönefeld-Süd and the Westhafen handles around 50 million tonnes per year. The Berlin S-Bahn nightservice runs on weekends only. The BVG MetroBuses run 24/7 on Saturdays and Sundays. The S25 cross-Berlin north-south line and the S26 cross-Berlin Lichterfelde-Tegel line round out the S-Bahn coverage. The Berlin Hauptbahnhof Innopark connects the Hauptbahnhof to the new Heidestraße quarter. The Berlin TXL Schumacher Quartier urban-redevelopment project on the former Tegel airport land is one of the largest German brownfield-conversion projects.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Berlin economic detail: the Berlin Senate Department for Economic Affairs is the largest single state ministry by budget. The Berlin Partner GmbH is the city-state economic-development agency. The Berlin Stock Exchange (Börse Berlin), founded 1685 as the third-oldest German stock exchange (after Hamburg 1558 and Frankfurt 1585), today specialises in international ETFs and certificates. The Investitionsbank Berlin (IBB), the city''s development bank, supports Berlin SMEs and start-ups. The Vivantes hospital network, the Charité teaching hospital, the Bundesnachrichtendienst BND (the German foreign intelligence service, with its new monumental headquarters at Chausseestraße completed 2019 — the largest intelligence-agency building in the world), the Federal Ministries (the Foreign Office at Werderscher Markt, the Federal Economy and Climate Ministry at Scharnhorststraße, the Federal Justice Ministry at Mohrenstraße, the Federal Health Ministry at Friedrichstraße, the Federal Defence Ministry at the Bendlerblock), the Federal Network Agency Bundesnetzagentur (although Bonn-based has a Berlin office), the Bundesrechnungshof (the Federal Audit Office, Bonn-based but with Berlin liaison), the Bundespräsidialamt at Schloss Bellevue, the Bundeskanzleramt and the Bundestag administration form the federal employment cluster. The Berlin film industry includes the Studio Babelsberg (technically in Brandenburg but Berlin-administered), the Berlin Brandenburg Filmboard (MBB), the Berlinale and the Filmuniversität Babelsberg Konrad Wolf at Potsdam. The Berlin techno-club industry generates around 1.5 billion euros per year and has been UNESCO-listed since 2024. The Berlin Werbeagentur cluster includes Saatchi & Saatchi Berlin, BBDO Group Germany, Jung von Matt, Scholz & Friends, Heimat\\TBWA, thjnk and Antoni Garage. The Berlin VC scene includes Earlybird, Cherry Ventures, Project A, Lakestar and Holtzbrinck Ventures. The Berlin Industrial Heritage at Siemensstadt, Borsigwalde and Adlershof Technologiepark provides one of Europe''s largest mixed-use redevelopment portfolios.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Berlin invasive-species detail: the Leibniz-Institut für Zoo- und Wildtierforschung (IZW) at Berlin-Friedrichsfelde is the leading German urban-wildlife research institute, and the Berlin raccoon and wild-boar population studies under the long-running Stadtwildtiere Berlin project have produced some of the most-cited urban-wildlife research papers in Europe. The Berlin Senate has a citizen-reporting hotline for wild-boar and raccoon encounters (the Wildtier-Hotline). The Berlin Tegeler Fließ raccoon population has been studied for over 20 years by the IZW. The Berlin ZooBerlin and the Tierpark Friedrichsfelde are home to several species — the Japanese giant salamander, the Chinese alligator, the Komodo dragon — that occasionally have escaped historically (the Tierpark big-cat enclosure was famous for the 1988 Petze escape). The historic Berliner Zoologischer Garten in Tiergarten lost a number of animals during the 1945 Battle of Berlin and the Cold War era. The Berlin Spree-Oder Wasserstraße carries the Caspian-Pontic gobies into the city. The Berlin Tiergarten beavers have re-colonised since the 1990s from the Brandenburg populations. The Berlin Mauerpark, the Tempelhofer Feld, the Park am Gleisdreieck and the Naturpark Schöneberger Südgelände (the former Anhalter Bahnhof rail-yard) all host distinctive ruderal-invasive plant communities that have attracted ecological research. The Naturpark Schöneberger Südgelände is sometimes called the "wildest urban-nature reserve in Germany" thanks to its uncontrolled neophyte succession of birch, robinia, tree of heaven and the historic rail-yard weed flora. The Berlin Naturschutzbund (NABU Berlin) and the Berlin Stiftung Naturschutz support monitoring and citizen science.'
WHERE region_name = 'Berlin';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Additional Brandenburg tourism detail: Schloss Caputh on the Templiner See, Schloss Paretz of Queen Luise, Schloss Pfaueninsel (technically Berlin), the Naturpark Märkische Schweiz around Buckow, the Kunstwanderweg Bad Saarow, the Insel Werder Havelblütentage, the Naturpark Westhavelland the largest International Dark Sky Reserve in continental Europe (with the famous Stargazing Festival), the Internationale Bauausstellung IBA See in Lausitz, the Schiffshebewerk Niederfinow (the historic 1934 vertical ship lift on the Oder-Havel-Kanal alongside the new Niederfinow Nord twin lift opened 2022), Schloss Branitz the seat of Hermann Fürst Pückler-Muskau with the great Erd-Pyramiden tumuli where the Fürst is buried, the Wassermühle Cottbus, the Spreewald Christkindlmarkt at Lübbenau, the Spreewald Pickelfest of Spreewaldgurken, the Spreewald Sorbian Easter Egg painting and the historic Sorbian Cottbus dancing traditions. Sanssouci Park New Palace at sunset is the most-photographed Brandenburg panorama. The historic Berlin Brandenburg Tor was built in 1791 by Carl Gotthard Langhans modelled after the Athens Propylaea. The Belvedere on the Pfingstberg above Potsdam, the Glienicke Bridge (the historic Cold War Bridge of Spies between Potsdam and Berlin-Wannsee), the Sacrower Heiligenhalle and the Sacrower See round out the Potsdam fringe. The Schloss Babelsberg, the Schloss Cecilienhof (host to the 1945 Potsdam Conference), and the rural Krongut Bornstedt complete the Hohenzollern landscape.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Brandenburg transport detail: the Brandenburg state plans a major railway-investment programme including the upgrade of the Berlin-Stettin line (electrification completed in 2026), the Karower Kreuz upgrade north of Berlin, the Berlin-Magdeburg lines, the Berlin-Dresden Dresdner Bahn upgrade through Blankenfelde and Wünsdorf-Waldstadt, the Berlin Königswusterhausen Bahnhof reconstruction, the BER Airport Anbindungstrasse, the Cottbus Bahnknoten expansion (a major Lausitz Strukturwandel investment), the historic Märkische Eisenbahn, the historic Pommersche Eisenbahn, and the Cottbus-Forst-Wrocław cross-border services. The Brandenburg cross-border rail with Poland includes Eurocity services Berlin-Warsaw via Frankfurt(Oder), Berlin-Stettin via Tantow, Berlin-Wrocław via Cottbus, and the Eurobahn services. The Berlin S-Bahn extends into Brandenburg via S1 to Oranienburg, S2 to Bernau, S3 to Erkner, S5 to Strausberg Nord, S7 to Ahrensfelde and Potsdam, S8 to Wildau, S9 to BER and Spandau, S25 to Hennigsdorf, S26 to Teltow, S46 to Königs Wusterhausen and S47 to Königs Wusterhausen. The Heidekrautbahn upgrade for hydrogen-train pilot operation is one of the most ambitious Brandenburg-rail projects. The Spreewald-Kahnfahrt boats run on Brandenburg''s most distinctive water-transport route. The Cottbuser Ostsee (the future largest German artificial lake after lignite-mine flooding) will support sailing and watersport tourism. The Brandenburg cycling infrastructure includes the Berlin-Kopenhagen Radweg, the Spreeradweg, the Havel-Radweg, the Oder-Neisse-Radweg, the Mecklenburgischer Seenradweg-South, the Niederlausitzer Bergbau-Tourismus-Radweg through the old lignite pits, and the EuroVelo 7 (the historic Berlin Wall Trail Mauerweg). The Brandenburg state has subsidised the Brandenburg-Ticket flat-fare regional ticket since 2011.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Brandenburg economic detail: the Lausitz Strukturwandel programme distributes around 17 billion euros of federal Strukturstärkungsgesetz funds to Brandenburg through 2038, supporting new science campuses (the Lausitz Science Park at Cottbus), new federal administrative offices (the Federal Office for Telecommunications Security BSI sub-office at Cottbus), the German Centre for Astrophysics at Görlitz (just across the Saxon border), the new BTU Cottbus-Senftenberg campus expansion, and the federal Lausitz hydrogen-pilot programmes at Lubmin and Schwedt. The Brandenburg renewable-energy cluster includes BayWa renewable energy operations at Brandenburg, the SolarWorld AG (now part of Maxeon Solar Technologies, with Brandenburg historic operations at Frankfurt(Oder)), the Senvion (formerly REpower) Trampe-Brandenburg blade plant, and the BASF Schwarzheide battery-cathode-active-materials plant. The Brandenburg forest industry includes the Klausner Holzwerke, the Lausitz wooden-pallet industries, the Hennigsdorf Stadler Rail plant (one of the largest German rail-vehicle manufacturers), the Bombardier (now Alstom) Hennigsdorf-Berlin plant building Velaro D and Mireo regional trains, and the historic LEW Hennigsdorf locomotive heritage. The Brandenburg Senate has invested heavily in the new Mobility-as-a-Service infrastructure with the regional bus-rail-bike integration in the Prignitz, Uckermark, Elbe-Elster and Oder-Spree districts. The German Federal Defence Forces have substantial Brandenburg infrastructure at the Lehnitz pioneer school, the Storkower Heer-Schule and the Wünsdorf-Waldstadt former Soviet headquarters now civilian. The historic Wittenberge sewing-machine works (Singer plant) closed in 1991, the Stahlwerke Brandenburg (steelworks) closed similarly. The Brandenburg agricultural cooperatives are some of the largest in Germany; the Mecklenburger Vorland and the Uckermark grain plains are the breadbasket of the Berlin region. The Märkische Allgemeine (Brandenburg''s leading newspaper) and the Berliner Morgenpost serve the regional media market.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Brandenburg invasive-species detail: the Brandenburg LfU Neobiota register lists over 600 established alien species. The Brandenburg raccoon hunting bag in 2022 reached 32,000, the highest of any German Land. The Brandenburg wolf population in 2024 was 50+ packs, the second-highest after Saxony. The Brandenburg African Swine Fever situation began with the first wild boar case at Schenkendöbern on 10 September 2020; subsequent culling and a 1,500-kilometre fence along the Polish border combined with intensive wild-boar culling have largely contained the outbreak. The Lieberose, Schorfheide and Müggelsee hunting reserves report the highest Brandenburg sika-deer densities. The Brandenburg pond turtle reintroduction in the Märkische Schweiz is one of the most ambitious European reintroductions of Emys orbicularis. The Brandenburg State Department of Plant Protection at Frankfurt(Oder) monitors agricultural invasions including the brown marmorated stink bug (Halyomorpha halys), the harlequin ladybird (Harmonia axyridis), the Drosophila suzukii spotted-wing fruit fly, and the recently arrived Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) — the latter requiring continuous monitoring traps at Brandenburg container-port logistics centres. The Brandenburg potato-blight Phytophthora infestans, although technically not a neobiota but historically introduced from the Andes, remains a major Brandenburg agricultural challenge. The Brandenburg fish-farming industry has historically introduced many of the established invasive freshwater species. The historic Brandenburg lignite-mine spoil heaps host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation including black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia), tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima), ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia) and the Spanish broom (Spartium junceum). The Brandenburg state forestry is leading reintroductions of the European wildcat and the lynx (the latter still occasional but growing).'
WHERE region_name = 'Brandenburg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Additional Bremen tourism detail: the Bremen-Vegesack historic shipbuilding harbour with the Lürssen Werft heritage and the Schulschiff Deutschland sail-training ship; the Schloss Schönebeck (the moated castle of the Bremen-Vegesack district); the Bremen-Knoops Park (the historic 19th-century landscape garden in Bremen-Lesum); the Bremen-Burglesum and the Bremen-Vegesack waterfront; the Bremerhavener Speckenbüttel Park; the Bremerhavener Mediterraneo shopping arcade in the converted dock; the Bremerhavener Atlantic-Sail Bremerhaven tall-ships event held every five years (the next is 2025); the Bremerhavener Auswandererfest (the annual Emigration Festival commemorating the seven million emigrants who sailed from Bremerhaven); the Bremerhavener Klimahaus 8° Ost (a UNESCO-affiliated learning centre with nine climate-zone biomes traversing the 8th meridian east longitude); the Bremerhavener Zoo am Meer (the small but excellent marine-mammal zoo with polar bears, harbour seals, walruses and penguins); the Bremerhavener Fischereihafen-Erlebniswelt; the Bremerhavener Fischereihafen Schaufenster Fischereihafen heritage trail; the Bremerhavener Wasserstandsanzeiger lighthouse Roter Sand offshore on the Wesermündung; the Bremerhavener Lloydhalle (the historic Norddeutscher Lloyd dock building, now a Maritime-themed event hall); the Bremer Loriot-Häuser (the historic Loriot, alias Vicco von Bülow, family villas in Bremen-Schwachhausen); the Bremen Kunstmuseum Worpswede branch and the Worpswede Künstlerkolonie (technically in Niedersachsen but Bremen-affiliated) with the Barkenhoff of Heinrich Vogeler, the Worpsweder Kaffee Worpswede, the Niedersachsenstein, the historic Worpswede Käseglocke (the Cheese-Dome house); the Bremen Worpswede axis is the most-walked artist-colony itinerary in Germany. The historic Bremer Senatsgarten, the Bremer Schnoor handmade-jewellery galleries, and the Bremer Schloss-Theater Bremen complete the urban culture.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Bremen transport detail: the historic Bremen-Roland Hafen, the Bremer Vulkan shipyard heritage (closed 1996 after one of the largest German industrial bankruptcies), the Bremen Industriehafen and the Holzhafen container terminal, the Bremerhavener Container Terminal CT1-CT4 (the Eurogate Container Terminal Bremerhaven, the second-largest German container terminal after Hamburg), the BLG Auto-Terminal Bremerhaven (the world''s largest car-handling terminal, with 95 hectares of paved storage for around 2.1 million cars per year), the Bremerhavener Offshore Terminal Bremerhaven (the OTB, used for North Sea offshore-wind installation), the Bremerhavener Fischereihafen, the historic Bremerhavener Lloyd-Werft (now LLOYD Werft Bremerhaven, specialising in cruise-ship refitting), the Bremerhavener Wasserschutzpolizei base, and the Bremer Wasserbau-Verein historic dredging operations. The Bremen-Bremerhaven Hafenbahn freight railway is one of the largest German harbour railways. The Bremer Personenfähre (the Bremen passenger ferry between Bremen-Vegesack and Lemwerder) operates on a 24/7 schedule. The Bremer Stadtmusikanten and the Bremen tram heritage celebrate the 1876 introduction of the horse-drawn tram and the 1892 electrification. The Bremen-Oldenburg Bahn-Linie carries half-hourly regional services. The Bremen S-Bahn RS1 to Bremerhaven runs on the historic Bremen-Cuxhaven line. The Bremen Lufthansa City Center, the Bremen Cruise Center Columbuskaje, and the Bremen Cargo Center Bremerhaven complete the logistics offer. The Bremen-Wilhelmshaven-Norden cross-river A29 motorway connects to the JadeWeserPort. The Bremer Stadt-Autobahn A270 connects Bremen-Vegesack and the Industriehafen. The Bremer Verkehrsverbund Niedersachsen-Bremen (VBN) coordinates the integrated tariff.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Bremen economic detail: the German Aerospace Center (DLR) Institute of Space Systems at Bremen-Vahr employs around 200 aerospace engineers leading German satellite-design programmes including the Heinrich Hertz communications satellite. The historic Bremer Vulkan shipyard heritage (closed 1996 after one of the largest German industrial insolvencies in post-war history with around 25,000 workers laid off) is still felt in the Bremen labour market. The Lürssen Werft at Bremen-Vegesack employs around 1,500 workers building superyachts and naval combatants. The historic Norddeutscher Lloyd shipping company (founded 1857), one of the world''s great ocean-liner companies through the early 20th century, merged with HAPAG in 1970 to form Hapag-Lloyd AG. The Bremen historic shipping companies include the Reederei Beluga (which had a famous insolvency in 2011), the Hansa Heavy Lift (insolvent 2018), and the surviving Reederei NSB Niederelbe. The Bremen Senate is the largest single employer in the Bremen state with around 22,000 staff. The Stadtwerke Bremen, the SWB Bremen, and the Bremer Wasser-Versorgung complete the municipal services. The Universität Bremen produces around 4,500 graduates per year. The Tourismus Marketing Niedersachsen-Bremen (now part of the joint Niedersachsen-Bremen-Marketing) markets the state. The Bremer Wirtschafts- und Sozialakademie supports the regional dual-education system. The Bremer Senat operates the world-class Universum Science Center as a public-engagement outreach institution.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Bremen invasive-species detail: the Senatsumweltverwaltung Bremen and the Senatsumweltverwaltung Bremerhaven jointly maintain the Bremen-Bremerhaven Neobiota register. The Bremen Wadden Sea and the Helgoland (technically in Schleswig-Holstein but with strong Bremerhaven research ties) host the world''s longest continuous marine-monitoring programme since 1873 at the Helgoland Biologische Anstalt (now AWI-affiliated). The Wadden Sea Pacific oyster colonisation has been studied by the AWI Bremerhaven and the Senckenberg am Meer Wilhelmshaven. The Bremen Botanischer Garten Rhododendron-Park is one of the largest German rhododendron collections with over 600 species — most introduced from the Himalayas and East Asia, with some now self-seeding into the surrounding Bremen forests. The Bremerhaven Zoo am Meer participates in the EU-coordinated invasive-species awareness campaigns. The Bremer Mausoleum at Riensberg cemetery hosts an unusual Asian goose Branta canadensis population. The Bremer Wasserwerke Vegesack and the Bremer Stadtwerke monitor the lower Weser for round-goby and quagga-mussel infestation in their intake structures. The historic Bremer Eishafen pond ecology was historically transformed by the GDR-era American mink fur farms in the upstream Verden area, and feral American mink still occur in the lower Weser. The Bremen Pflanzenschutzdienst (Plant Protection Service) monitors ragweed, knotweed, balsam and Asian-hornet arrivals continuously.'
WHERE region_name = 'Bremen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Hamburg transport detail: the historic Hamburg-Köhlbrandbrücke (the 1974 cable-stayed bridge over the Köhlbrand at 510 metres long and 53 metres high) will be replaced by a new tunnel from 2030 onwards as the existing bridge has reached the end of its design life — the Köhlbrandquerung tunnel is one of the largest German infrastructure projects of the 21st century. The Hamburg Elbtunnel (the 3.5-kilometre under-river road tunnel on the A7 motorway, opened 1975 with the fourth tube added 2002), the Alte Elbtunnel (the 1911 pedestrian and bicycle tunnel under the Elbe with original copper-clad lifts), and the Norderelbbrücke complete the Elbe crossings. The historic Hamburg-Altona terminal station will be replaced from 2027 onwards by the new Hamburg-Diebsteich through-station, allowing direct ICE services between Altona and the long-distance lines. The Hamburg S-Bahn S4 line (under construction Hamburg Hauptbahnhof to Bad Oldesloe) is the major railway-investment project of the 2020s; the S4 will use battery-electric multiple units in cooperation with the AKN Eisenbahn Schleswig-Holstein. The Hamburg-Lübeck-Vogelfluglinie corridor, currently a ferry route via Puttgarden-Rødby, will be transformed by the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link due to open 2029 — this will allow Hamburg-Copenhagen high-speed rail services in 2 hours 30 minutes. The Hamburg-Niedersachsen-Brake-Wilhelmshaven JadeWeserPort container-corridor is a major regional logistics investment. The Hamburg Elbphilharmonie Cruise Center, the Cruise Center Altona and the Cruise Center Steinwerder serve over 200 cruise calls per year. The Hamburg-Helgoland Cuxhaven-Hochsee fast-ferry runs daily. The Hamburg Reeperbahn-Tour buses, the Hamburg HVV-Tarif integration and the historic 1965 Hamburg Hochbahn-Buslinien integrated network round out the public transport. The MOIA Hamburg shared electric-ride-hailing service (a VW Group subsidiary) operates around 700 ID. Buzz vehicles in Hamburg.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Hamburg economic detail: the Hamburg Marriott Hotel Group, the Steigenberger Hotels (Frankfurt-Bonn but with Hamburg operations), the Atlantic Hotel Hamburg, the Fairmont Hotel Vier Jahreszeiten (the iconic Hamburg luxury hotel since 1897) and the Park Hyatt Hamburg are the major Hamburg luxury hotel brands. Coca-Cola Erfrischungsgetränke Germany has its German headquarters at Berlin but with Hamburg HRH operations. Unilever Germany has its German headquarters at Hamburg-City-Süd (one of the largest single Unilever headquarters in Europe). Procter & Gamble Germany has Hamburg operations. The Tchibo Coffee Holding (already mentioned) has the Tchibo Group headquarters and the Tchibo Service Center in Hamburg-Sankt Pauli. The Otto Group e-commerce empire is the largest Hamburg-headquartered company by employees. The Hamburg shipping cluster includes Hapag-Lloyd (the listed global container line, now the world''s fifth-largest by container volume), Reederei Aug. Bolten (one of the oldest Hamburg shipping companies, founded 1820), Reederei F. Laeisz, Komrowski-Reederei, Hammonia-Reederei, Reederei NSB Niederelbe (which has moved to Buxtehude in Lower Saxony but with Hamburg roots), Bernhard Schulte Shipmanagement (BSM), Columbia Shipmanagement, and the historic Reederei Joh. Oeltjen. The Hamburg airline cluster includes Lufthansa Cargo (technically Frankfurt-headquartered but with Hamburg ops), Lufthansa Technik AG headquarters, Air Hamburg, and the historic Hapag-Lloyd Flug heritage. The Hamburg fintech cluster around the HamburgInvest start-up Inkubator and the Hanseatic Bank includes successful fintechs like Penta, Frohne and DKB Hamburg. The Hamburg renewable-energy cluster includes Nordex SE (with Hamburg-Hamburg operations alongside Rostock), wpd offshore solutions, BSU Bundesamt für Schifffahrt und Hydrographie (the Federal Maritime and Hydrographic Agency with major Hamburg operations), and the historic Hamburg-Wandsbek wind-turbine industry. The Hamburg media-cluster annual revenue is around 12 billion euros and the Hamburg creative-industries cluster is the second-largest in Germany after Berlin.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Hamburg invasive-species detail: the AWI Helgoland Biologische Anstalt at Helgoland (the world''s longest continuous marine-monitoring programme since 1873) has been a leader in documenting the Wadden Sea and German-Bight species invasions including the Pacific oyster, the American razor clam, the Asian shore crabs, the Atlantic comb jelly Mnemiopsis leidyi (a major impact on the western Baltic and lower Elbe ecosystem) and the round goby. The Hamburg Port Authority and the BSH Bundesamt für Schifffahrt und Hydrographie at Hamburg coordinate ballast-water-monitoring under the IMO Ballast Water Management Convention. The Hamburg Naturschutzbund (NABU Hamburg) operates the AfrikaSchattling and the Vier- und Marschlande naturalist programmes. The Hamburg Wildlife-Trust hosts the famous urban wild-boar population studies. The Hamburg Tierpark Hagenbeck (founded 1907 by Carl Hagenbeck as the world''s first zoo without bars) participates in the EU-coordinated ex-situ conservation breeding programmes for European species threatened by introduced predators. The Hamburg Botanischer Garten Klein-Flottbek (the Loki-Schmidt-Garten) maintains one of the German leading neophyte-research collections, with comparative gardens of the historic Hamburg neophyte introductions over the past 300 years. The Hamburg-Niendorfer Gehege has hosted the most diverse Hamburg wildlife (raccoon, raccoon dog, fox, badger, beech marten, wild boar, roe deer, red deer, and the recent occasional wolf passage) within the city limits. The historic Hamburger Pelzborse (the Hamburg fur exchange, the largest in the world until 2003 when it closed) was the historic gateway for many of the imported fur-bearing species that escaped into German woodland.'
WHERE region_name = 'Hamburg';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Hessen transport detail: the Frankfurt Skyline shapes the most concentrated German skyscraper cluster of around 20 buildings over 100 metres tall including the Commerzbank Tower 259m, Messeturm 257m, Westend Tower (DZ Bank) 208m, Main Tower 200m, Tower 185 199m, Trianon Tower 186m, Eurotower 148m, Garden Tower 127m, Marienturm 155m, Henninger Turm 140m and the new One Forty West Tower 145m. The Frankfurt Hauptbahnhof Vorplatz with the Lichtbrunnen fountain and the historic K70 light-rail building, the Frankfurter Hauptbahnhof tief underground station, the Konstablerwache U-Bahn junction, and the Hauptwache central pedestrian zone all anchor the inner city. The Frankfurt-Köln NBS Schnellfahrstrecke holds the European high-speed rail steep-grade record at 40 per mille; the line has the Limburger Westerwaldtunnel of 4.5 kilometres. The Frankfurt-Mannheim Riedbahn upgrade closed the line entirely between July-December 2024 for the largest single German rail-corridor reconstruction in history (Generalsanierung), with full electrification and digital signalling. The historic Frankfurt-Hannover and Frankfurt-Würzburg-Nürnberg corridors are now upgraded for 200 kph. The Frankfurt Airport Long-Distance Bahnhof, opened 1999, was the first true high-speed airport station in Germany with half-hourly ICE services. The Cassel-Wilhelmshöhe ICE station, opened 1991 on the Hannover-Würzburg NBS, was one of the first dedicated NBS stations in Germany. The Wiesbaden Hauptbahnhof, the Darmstadt Hauptbahnhof, the Hanau Hauptbahnhof, the Gießen Hauptbahnhof, the Marburg-Lahn Hauptbahnhof, the Limburg an der Lahn ICE-Stop and the Hanau-Limburg Lahntalbahn complete the major rail nodes. The Hessian Verkehrsverbund RMV Rhein-Main and NVV Nordhessen integrated tariffs cover the entire state. The Frankfurt ZOB long-distance bus station beside the Hauptbahnhof handles around 200 daily long-distance bus departures with FlixBus the dominant operator. The Hessian cycling routes include the Main-Radweg, the Lahntalradweg, the Werraradweg, the Fulda-Radweg, the Hessischer Radfernweg, and the EuroVelo 6 (Atlantic-Black Sea) and EuroVelo 15 (Rhine Cycle Route) — together making Hessen one of the most cycle-friendly German states. The Mainfähre Höchst, the Mainfähre Niederrad and the Mainfähre Schwanheim provide pedestrian and bicycle crossings of the Main. The historic Limesstraße tourist road, the Bundesstraße B40 along the Main, and the Bundesstraße B3 north-south across Hessen complete the road inventory.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Hessen economic detail: the Frankfurt insurance and reinsurance cluster includes the largest single concentration of insurance companies in continental Europe — the Allianz Frankfurt regional centre, the Allianz Global Corporate & Specialty, the Munich Re Frankfurt office, the Generali Frankfurt, the Allianz Trade (the export-credit insurer), the Provinzial Frankfurt and the Talanx-HDI Group Frankfurt. The Frankfurt European Central Bank (ECB) Tower in Ostend houses around 4,000 staff. The Deutsche Bundesbank head office at Wilhelm-Epstein-Straße in Frankfurt-Westend has around 10,000 employees. The Frankfurt fintech cluster is the largest in continental Europe with over 600 companies. The Frankfurt Brexit relocations after 2016 brought around 30 Asian and US investment banks to Frankfurt, with Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan, Morgan Stanley and Citi all dramatically expanding their Frankfurt workforce. The Frankfurt Stock Exchange (Börse Frankfurt) handles around 95 per cent of German cash-equity trading. The Frankfurt-Eschborn data-centre cluster is the largest in continental Europe with around 60 carrier-neutral colocation facilities (Digital Realty, NTT, Equinix, CyrusOne, Telehouse, Interxion, Iron Mountain). The Frankfurt DE-CIX Internet Exchange is the world''s largest by aggregated traffic. The Frankfurt-Wiesbaden-Mainz-Darmstadt Rhein-Main metropolitan region is the second-largest German economic agglomeration after the Rhine-Ruhr. The historic Hoechst AG complex at Frankfurt-Höchst (now the Industriepark Höchst) hosts Sanofi-Aventis Deutschland, Bayer CropScience, Celanese, Clariant, Almatis, Allessa, LyondellBasell, Air Liquide, BASF Coatings and the Currenta Chempark Höchst services. The Industriepark Höchst is one of the largest single chemical-industrial complexes in Europe at 4.5 square kilometres with around 22,000 workers. The Merck KGaA at Darmstadt is the oldest pharmaceutical company in the world (founded 1668 by Friedrich Jacob Merck). The Volkswagen Kassel-Baunatal plant is the largest VW component plant in the world. The Bombardier (now Alstom) Kassel plant builds the modern Velaro D ICE and the Coradia iLint hydrogen trains. The Heraeus Holding at Hanau is one of the world''s largest precious-metals businesses. The historic Frankfurter Berufsfeuerwehr is the largest German municipal fire service.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Hessen invasive-species detail: the Hessen Edersee 1934 raccoon release is commemorated by a small visitor enclosure at the Wildpark Edersee near Bad Wildungen. The HLNUG raccoon distribution maps show the highest German Waschbär densities in central and northern Hessen. The Frankfurter Stadtwald hosts the most-photographed urban raccoon population in Germany, with regular media features on the so-called Frankfurt Raccoon Mafia. The Frankfurter Tiergarten and the Bauerngarten Frankfurt have substantial Egyptian goose populations. The Hessen Asian-Hornet Task Force coordinates with the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut at Darmstadt-Geilstedt (the federal plant-protection-research institute). The Hessen ragweed control programme is one of the most active in Germany. The Hessen state forestry monitors the historic Reinhardswald, Kellerwald and Vogelsberg for invasive forest pests. The Knüllgebirge National Park, the Hessischer Spessart Naturpark and the Rhön Biosphärenreservat (a UNESCO MAB Reserve shared with Bavaria and Thuringia) all maintain invasive-species monitoring. The Helmholtz Centre for Infection Research at Braunschweig (technically Niedersachsen) has Hessian connection through the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut. The Frankfurter Senckenberg Forschungsinstitut (the largest German natural-history museum and research institute) leads German research on neobiota and biological invasions, with the Senckenberg-Atlas of German Neobiota being the primary national reference. The historic Hessen-Forst game-park reserves at Schloss Gontram and Riedforst preserve native fallow deer and mouflon stocks introduced for hunting. The Hessen wildcat reintroductions in the Spessart, the Vogelsberg, the Knüll and the Burgwald complete the conservation portfolio.'
WHERE region_name = 'Hessen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Mecklenburg-Vorpommern transport detail: the Rostock-Warnemünde Cruise Terminal hosts around 200 cruise calls per year and is one of the largest German Baltic cruise ports. The Sassnitz-Mukran Port on Rügen is one of the largest German Baltic ferry ports with services to Trelleborg (Sweden), Klaipėda (Lithuania), and the historic German-Soviet rail-ferry connection. The MV Werften Wismar, the MV Werften Stralsund, the Aker MTW Wismar (formerly the GDR State Shipyard), the Neptun Werft at Warnemünde (now part of Meyer Werft of Papenburg), and the Volkswerft Stralsund together formed the largest German shipbuilding cluster until the 2022 MV Werften insolvency. The historic Pommersche Eisenbahn, the historic Mecklenburgische Eisenbahn-Gesellschaft (MEG), the Hanseatische Eisenbahn (HANS) and the Usedomer Bäderbahn (UBB) operate regional and historic services. The Rasender Roland on Rügen (the 750 mm narrow-gauge steam railway between Putbus and Göhren since 1895), the Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn Molli (the 900 mm narrow-gauge steam railway between Bad Doberan and Kühlungsborn since 1886, the world''s oldest continuously operating narrow-gauge steam railway) and the historic ATB (Anklamer Tiefebenebahn) preserve the regional railway heritage. The MV cycle network includes the Ostseeküsten-Radweg (the Baltic Coast Cycle Route, EuroVelo 10), the Mecklenburgischer Seenradweg (one of Germany''s top-ranked cycling holidays), the Berlin-Kopenhagen Radweg, the Berlin-Usedom Radweg, the Hamburg-Rügen Radweg and the Stettiner Haff Radweg. The Rostock-Warnemünde IGA-Park trams and the historic Rostock-Schmarl maritime-industry trams operated until the 2010s. The Rostock S-Bahn extends to Warnemünde. The Schwerin Hauptbahnhof connects the state capital to Hamburg (the historic Hauptlinie 1846), Berlin via Ludwigslust, Rostock and Lübeck. The Schwerin tram (Schweriner Verkehrsbetriebe) has three lines totalling 21 kilometres. The MV state has subsidised the new Hydrogen-Train Pilot programme on the Berlin-Greifswald-Stralsund corridor using Alstom Coradia iLint hydrogen trains since 2022.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Mecklenburg-Vorpommern economic detail: the MV-Werften insolvency in 2022 was one of the largest German industrial restructurings of the past decade, with around 3,000 workers laid off. The Aida Cruises (founded 1996 at Rostock as a GDR-era successor company) is one of the largest German cruise lines, with the AIDA fleet built at Neptun Werft Rostock and at Meyer Werft Papenburg; AIDA Cruises is owned by Costa Crociere of Italy (and ultimately by Carnival Corporation of the United States). The Neptun Werft Rostock employs around 1,700 workers building cruise-ship engine-room modules. The Hanseatic Marine Heavy-Industry Group at Rostock-Warnemünde includes Liebherr-MCCtec Rostock GmbH (the Liebherr-Werft Rostock building offshore-wind installation cranes), the Caterpillar Marine Power Systems Rostock (the historic MaK Motoren engine works), and the Atlas Maritime Technologies sub-contractor cluster. The Rostock Port (operated by Rostock Port GmbH) handles around 50 million tonnes of cargo per year and is the largest German Baltic port. The Nordex SE wind-turbine manufacturer at Rostock employs around 2,000 workers building offshore-wind nacelles and rotor blades. The historic MV chemical industry (Stickstoff- und Düngemittelwerke Rostock, the Düngemittelwerke Anklam) has been restructured. The MV-Tourismus state offers (Tourismusverband Mecklenburg-Vorpommern) the third-highest German tourism revenue. The MV-Sektkellereien Wismar and the Sanddorn-Storchennest distillery on Rügen produce regional spirits. The MV state economic-development agency Invest in MV reports around 8 million visitor-nights per year. The Bundeswehr Marine-Hafenkommando Warnemünde, the Marine-Operationszentrum at Glücksburg in Schleswig-Holstein, and the MV Naval Air Base at Laage all support the Federal Navy''s Baltic operations. The historic Lübzer Bier (technically a Mecklenburg brand owned by Carlsberg) is the state beer. The Schwerin Hauptpost (now restructured) and the Rostock-Centrum-Warnow malls round out the consumer-products map.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Mecklenburg-Vorpommern invasive-species detail: the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut on the island of Riems near Greifswald is the German federal animal-disease research institute (founded 1910 by Friedrich Loeffler, the discoverer of the foot-and-mouth disease virus) and is the leading German centre for research on zoonotic diseases, foot-and-mouth disease, swine fever, avian flu, and bluetongue. The Riems island laboratory is one of the world''s most secure biosafety-4 animal-disease facilities. The MV state plans to be among the first German states free of African Swine Fever via the Polish-border fencing and the active hunting culling of wild boar. The Müritz National Park (Germany''s second-largest national park, founded 1990) and the Western Pomeranian Lagoon Area National Park (Vorpommersche Boddenlandschaft Nationalpark, founded 1990) manage the bulk of MV invasive-species monitoring. The Schaalsee Biosphärenreservat (a UNESCO MAB Reserve) hosts ongoing wolf-monitoring programmes. The historic GDR-era mink farms at the Müritz, the Schwerin and the Cottbus area contributed feral American mink populations to MV waterways. The MV state has the third-largest German wolf population after Saxony and Brandenburg. The MV Sea Eagle (Haliaeetus albicilla) recovery, the MV Crane (Grus grus) recovery and the MV Black Stork (Ciconia nigra) recovery are major native-species conservation successes. The MV Pacific Oyster invasion of the western Baltic has been intensively studied by the AWI Bremerhaven. The MV Atlantic Comb Jelly Mnemiopsis leidyi invasion has substantially affected the western Baltic plankton ecology.'
WHERE region_name = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Niedersachsen transport detail: the Hannover-Hamburg ICE corridor (electrified 1968) is being upgraded to 230 kph with the new Bahnknoten Hannover and Hamburg-Diebsteich projects. The Hannover-Berlin NBS (1998-opened, the historic Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 4) runs at 250 kph and serves the ICE-Bahnhof Wolfsburg, opened 1998 on the line. The Hannover-Würzburg NBS (1991-opened, the first NBS in Germany) runs at 280 kph with 63 tunnels through the Solling and the Reinhardswald. The Hannover-Köln-Aachen-Brussels Eurostar (formerly Thalys) and the Hannover-Amsterdam IC services round out the east-west corridor. The Hannover Hauptbahnhof with the iconic Bonatz-style facade serves around 250,000 passengers per day; the historic Hannover Hauptbahnhof-Hamburg-Altona-Berlin run takes 4 hours 30 minutes by ICE. The Bremen-Wilhelmshaven-Norden cross-river A29 motorway connects to the JadeWeserPort. The Wilhelmshaven JadeWeserPort, opened 2012, is Germany''s only deep-water container port with 18-metre draft capacity for the world''s largest container ships. The historic East Frisian island ferries from Norddeich and Norden, the Sylt Shuttle car-train across the Hindenburgdamm (the only German rail-only causeway to an island), and the historic Helgoland ferries from Cuxhaven and Bremerhaven complete the maritime offer. The Hannover Stadtbahn (üstra Hannoversche Verkehrsbetriebe) is the third-longest German Stadtbahn network at 121 kilometres. The Hannover Messe-Express tram for the Hannover Messe trade fair (the world''s largest industrial fair) runs every 5 minutes during the fair. The Niedersachsen-Ticket integrated regional fare is one of the most successful German state-level tickets, covering all regional rail and most regional bus operations. The Wolfsburg ICE Bahnhof connection to Hannover takes 25 minutes and to Berlin 1 hour 15 minutes. The Niedersachsen state has subsidised the new Hydrogen-Train Pilot programme on the Bremerhaven-Buxtehude regional corridor using Alstom Coradia iLint trains since 2018 (the world''s first commercial hydrogen-rail operation).',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Niedersachsen economic detail: the Volkswagen Group corporate headquarters at Wolfsburg is the largest single industrial site in the world by area at 6.5 square kilometres, with around 60,000 workers at the Wolfsburg plant alone. The Wolfsburg Autostadt customer-delivery centre and the VW corporate-museum complex attract around 2 million visitors per year. The Continental AG headquarters at Hannover-Vahrenwald-List employs around 5,000 corporate staff. The Sennheiser electronic family-owned audio-equipment maker has its iconic Wennebostel village headquarters in the Wedemark district north of Hannover. The Niedersachsen state economic development arm (NBank and Investitionsbank Niedersachsen) coordinates SME-investment subsidies. The Niedersachsen-Aerospace cluster around Stade, Bremen, Wolfsburg and the historic Braunschweig Forschungsflughafen Braunschweig-Wolfsburg supports around 25,000 aerospace workers. The Premium Aerotec at Nordenham (lower Weser) produces large Airbus A380 and A350 fuselage sections. The CFK Valley Stade carbon-fibre cluster around Stade is one of the leading European composite-materials sites. The Salzgitter AG integrated steelworks at Salzgitter (Salzgitter Flachstahl) is the second-largest German steel producer with around 6 million tonnes per year. The Bahlsen Hannover biscuit factory at Hannover-List is one of the oldest German food brands. The Sartorius AG at Göttingen is one of the fastest-growing German DAX 40 companies in biotech. The Volkswagen Financial Services AG at Braunschweig is one of the largest German automotive-financial-services groups. The TUI AG headquarters at Hannover-City employs around 4,000 corporate staff. The Niedersachsen agricultural sector is the largest in Germany by output, with the largest pig-population (around 8 million pigs), the largest broiler-chicken population, and substantial dairy and grain production. The Wallenhorst, Cloppenburg and Vechta districts have the highest pig densities in Europe. The Wümme-Renaturierung and the Drömling beaver reintroductions are major conservation-and-tourism investments.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Niedersachsen invasive-species detail: the Niedersächsisches Landesamt für Verbraucherschutz und Lebensmittelsicherheit (LAVES) at Hannover-Wülfel coordinates the state Neozoa register. The Niedersachsen wolf population in 2024 had around 50 confirmed territorial packs (the third-highest after Saxony and Brandenburg), with the famous Lüneburger Heide and Bergen-Belsen training ground core areas. The Niedersachsen wild-boar African Swine Fever readiness includes the federal-state fencing along the Polish border (Brandenburg) and intensive Niedersachsen culling programmes. The Niedersachsen state hunters'' association (Niedersächsischer Jägerverband) reports annual hunting bags of around 70,000 wild boar, 35,000 raccoons, 12,000 raccoon dogs and 50,000 fallow deer. The Niedersachsen state hosts the largest Asian-Hornet expansion-front in northern Germany, with the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut Braunschweig and the LWK Niedersachsen coordinating monitoring. The Niedersachsen Solling forest park hosts ongoing lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction. The historic Lüneburger Heide WildPark Lüneburger Heide at Nindorf hosts captive populations of European bison, brown bear, wolf, lynx, wildcat, otter and beaver — an important conservation-education facility. The Niedersachsen Wadden Sea National Park is part of the UNESCO Wadden Sea World Heritage Site and supports the most extensive marine-invasion monitoring in Germany alongside the AWI Bremerhaven. The Niedersachsen state pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroduction in the Drömling, the Niedersachsen state beaver population recovery, the Niedersachsen state crane population and the Niedersachsen state white-tailed sea eagle recovery are major native-species conservation successes. The Niedersachsen ash dieback (Hymenoscyphus fraxineus from East Asia) is a major Niedersachsen forest-pathology concern.'
WHERE region_name = 'Niedersachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional NRW transport detail: the Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed line Schnellfahrstrecke (NBS Köln-Rhein/Main), opened in 2002, was the first true ICE 3 high-speed line in Germany, running at 300 kph from Frankfurt Airport via Limburg, Montabaur and Siegburg/Bonn to Cologne in 62 minutes — the steepest high-speed railway grade in Europe at 40 ‰ on the Westerwald. The Cologne-Aachen-Brussels-Paris Thalys-Eurostar service (the Eurostar Group operates the route after the 2024 Thalys-Eurostar merger), the Cologne-Amsterdam ICE service via the Dutch HSL-Zuid high-speed line, the Cologne-Stuttgart-Munich ICE/IC corridor, the Cologne-Hannover-Berlin ICE corridor, and the Cologne-Hamburg ICE all converge at Cologne Hauptbahnhof. The Cologne Messe/Deutz station handles overflow ICE traffic. The Düsseldorf Hauptbahnhof handles around 250,000 passengers per day. The Düsseldorf Flughafen Skytrain to the airport is an automated people-mover system. The Wuppertal Schwebebahn (the suspended monorail of 1901 by Eugen Langen) is one of the most iconic transport curiosities in the world — a 13.3-kilometre electric suspended railway operating since 1901, the world''s oldest still-operating suspension railway. The Cologne KVB Stadtbahn, the Düsseldorf Rheinbahn Stadtbahn, the Ruhrgebiet Stadtbahn networks (Essen-Mülheim, Duisburg, Bochum-Gelsenkirchen-Herne BOGESTRA, Dortmund Stadtbahn), the Bielefelder Stadtbahn (a tram-train system), the Bonn Stadtbahn (with the cross-Rhine ring around Bonn), and the Aachen-Stadt tram (relaunched 2024 with the new Aachen-Maastricht cross-border tram-train via the Lousberg corridor) form one of the densest urban-rail networks in Europe. The VRR Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Ruhr is the largest German transport association by inhabitants (7.7 million) and area. The Ruhrtalradweg, the Vennbahn (a cross-border DE-BE-LU cycle path on a former railway), the EuroVelo 15 Rhine Cycle Route, the 100-Schlösser-Route in the Münsterland, and the Erftradweg complete the cycling network. The Cologne-Bonn airport, Düsseldorf Airport, Dortmund Airport, Münster-Osnabrück Airport, Weeze-Niederrhein Airport and Paderborn-Lippstadt Airport together carry around 40 million passengers per year. The Cologne-Bonn Airport is the second-largest German cargo airport with the FedEx and UPS European hubs.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Nordrhein-Westfalen economic detail: the Ruhr Coal-and-Steel cluster, which formed the historic European industrial heartland from the 1850s to the 1980s, has been largely transformed into a service-and-research economy through the 30-year Strukturwandel programme. The Ruhr coal-mining industry completely closed in December 2018 with the final Zeche Prosper-Haniel at Bottrop. The historic Bergmannsfest mining-festival and the Bergmann-Lied "Glückauf" continue as Ruhrgebiet cultural identity. The thyssenkrupp AG Essen corporate headquarters at the Berthold-Beitz-Boulevard has around 4,500 corporate staff. The thyssenkrupp Stahlwerke Duisburg-Bruckhausen, Duisburg-Hamborn and Duisburg-Hüttenheim integrated steel-and-coke plants together produce around 11 million tonnes of steel per year — the largest German steel cluster. The RWE AG Essen utility headquarters employs around 5,000 corporate staff. The E.ON SE corporate headquarters at the Brüsseler Platz in Essen employs around 3,500 corporate staff. The Henkel AG Düsseldorf corporate headquarters at the Henkelstraße employs around 8,000 staff (including the global R&D centre). The Bayer AG Leverkusen corporate headquarters at the Bayer Cross campus employs around 9,000 corporate staff and 18,000 production staff. The Currenta Chempark Leverkusen operates 60 square kilometres of integrated chemical-industrial site. The Bonner Bundeskanzleramt der Friedensbewegung, the Bonn UN-Campus, the BfArM, the BSI Bonn, the BNetzA Bonn, the Bundesministerien at Bonn, and the historic Bonner Bundesviertel still host around 8,000 federal employees after the Bonn-Berlin Treaty of 1994. The Cologne advertising-cluster includes the WDR Westdeutscher Rundfunk headquarters at Wallrafplatz (one of the largest German public broadcasters), the Deutsche Welle Bonn (the German international broadcaster), Bertelsmann RTL Cologne, and the historic Adolf-Grimme-Institut Marl. The NRW media-cluster annual revenue is around 14 billion euros, the largest German regional creative-industries cluster.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Nordrhein-Westfalen invasive-species detail: the LANUV NRW (the Landesamt für Natur, Umwelt und Verbraucherschutz NRW) at Recklinghausen is the largest German state environmental authority by staff. The NRW raccoon hunting bag in 2022 reached 50,000+, the highest of any German Land. The NRW Asian-Hornet expansion has been the most rapid in Germany since the 2014 first German breeding record at Aachen-Waldfeucht. The NRW Imkerverband and the LANUV jointly maintain the Asiatische-Hornisse-Meldeportal NRW citizen-reporting platform. The Cologne and Düsseldorf ring-necked parakeet populations are among the largest in Europe, with the Düsseldorf Hofgarten roost hosting several thousand Halsbandsittiche at dusk in winter — a major Düsseldorf urban-wildlife spectacle. The NRW Egyptian goose population is the largest in Germany. The NRW wild-boar urban population is substantial across the Eifel, the Sauerland, and the Bergisches Land, with Cologne and Düsseldorf reporting regular wild-boar encounters in suburban gardens and parks. The NRW Schermbeck Wolfsfamilie (the Schermbeck wolf pack near Wesel) has been a media flashpoint for livestock-predation incidents. The NRW Eifel National Park (founded 2004, the first national park in NRW) hosts substantial native-species conservation programmes including the wildcat, the lynx (reintroduced 2024), the European pond turtle (reintroduced 2018), and the European mink (planned future reintroduction). The historic Düsseldorf-Kaiserwerth, the Cologne Stadtwald, the Bonn Rheinaue and the Wuppertal Botanischer Garten host distinctive invasive-flora communities. The Bonn Rheinaue is one of the largest German urban-rewilding sites. The Cologne Lentpark, the Düsseldorf Volksgarten and the Bonn Hofgarten host long-term invasive-species monitoring by the local Naturschutzbund chapters.'
WHERE region_name = 'Nordrhein-Westfalen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Rheinland-Pfalz transport detail: the Frankfurt-Hahn Airport at Lautzenhausen on the Hunsrück (HHN, EDFH) was once the second-busiest German low-cost airport, peaking at 4 million Ryanair passengers in 2008; today the airport handles around 1.5 million passengers per year and is also a major cargo airport with around 100,000 tonnes of cargo annually. Saarbrücken Airport (SCN, EDDR) just across the Saarland border serves southern Rheinland-Pfalz. The Köln-Frankfurt NBS (the high-speed line through Limburg-Montabaur-Siegburg) has the Montabaur ICE-Stop in Rheinland-Pfalz. The Mainz Hauptbahnhof handles half-hourly S-Bahn services to Frankfurt and Wiesbaden, and ICE services on the Cologne-Mannheim and Frankfurt-Saarbrücken-Paris corridors. The Koblenz Hauptbahnhof handles the Romantic-Rhine-Valley services and the Mosel-line to Trier. The Trier Hauptbahnhof handles cross-border services to Luxembourg-Stadt. The Ludwigshafen Hauptbahnhof is served by the Mannheim S-Bahn. The Kaiserslautern Hauptbahnhof handles the historic Mannheim-Saarbrücken corridor with TGV inOui services. The Rheinland-Pfalz cycling network is one of the most developed in Germany with the EuroVelo 15 Rhine Cycle Route (Andermatt-Rotterdam through Mainz, Bingen, Koblenz, Bonn and Düsseldorf), the Mosel-Radweg (Metz-Koblenz, consistently ranked among Germany''s top three long-distance cycling routes), the Saar-Radweg, the Lahntalradweg, the Vulkaneifel-Radweg, the Nahe-Radweg, the Pfälzer Weinstraße cycling routes and the cross-border EuroVelo 6 (Atlantic-Black Sea via the Mosel). The Rhine and Mosel inland waterways carry substantial commercial traffic; the Ludwigshafen Rhine port serves BASF and the chemical industry. The Mainz, Koblenz, Trier, Speyer and Worms inland ports complete the system. The river cruising on the Köln-Düsseldorfer Rheinschiffahrt (KD) fleet, the Bingen-Rüdesheim ferries, and the major operators Viking River Cruises, AmaWaterways and the historic Goethe paddle steamer (now museum) provide the classic tourism circulation. The Romantic Rhine UNESCO Middle-Rhine Valley between Bingen and Koblenz is one of the most-cycled and most-cruised sections of the Rhine. The Hochmoselbrücke at Zeltingen-Rachtig (opened 2019, the second-highest bridge in Germany at 158 metres above the Mosel) is one of the most controversial recent German infrastructure projects.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Rheinland-Pfalz economic detail: BASF SE at Ludwigshafen is by far the largest single private employer in Rheinland-Pfalz with around 40,000 workers at the Stammwerk Ludwigshafen and additional 17,000 across the global BASF Group German operations. BASF Ludwigshafen accounts for around 20 per cent of total Rheinland-Pfalz GDP. The Boehringer Ingelheim International family-owned pharmaceutical company at Ingelheim am Rhein employs around 8,000 workers at the Ingelheim site (out of 53,000 globally). The Schott AG technical-glass company at Mainz employs around 3,500 workers at the Mainz Stammwerk. The Daimler Truck Wörth am Rhein plant employs around 10,000 workers and is the largest truck assembly plant in Europe. The Ramstein Air Base near Landstuhl-Kaiserslautern is the largest US Air Force base in the world outside the United States with around 9,000 US military personnel; Ramstein hosts the headquarters of US Air Forces in Europe and Africa (USAFE-AFAFRICA), the Allied Air Command of NATO, and the Landstuhl Regional Medical Center (the largest US military hospital outside the United States). The Spangdahlem Air Base near Bitburg hosts the US Air Force 52nd Fighter Wing with F-16 fighter aircraft. The total US military presence in Rheinland-Pfalz exceeds 50,000 service members, dependents and contractors, making the US Forces in Rheinland-Pfalz one of the largest regional employers. The Bundeswehr at Koblenz hosts the Federal Office for Defence Equipment, Information Technology and In-Service Support (BAAINBw), the largest federal agency in Rheinland-Pfalz with around 11,000 staff. The Rheinland-Pfalz wine industry (the largest German wine region by area at 65,000 hectares) is concentrated in the Mosel, the Pfalz, the Rheinhessen, the Ahr and the Nahe regions, with annual production of around 6 million hectolitres (two-thirds of total German wine). The Hornbach Holding (the listed DIY home-improvement retailer at Bornheim near Landau) is one of Germany''s largest DIY chains. The Globus SB-Warenhaus has Rheinland-Pfalz operations (although headquartered at St. Wendel in Saarland). The Karlsberg Brauerei at Homburg (technically Saarland) and the Bitburger Brauerei at Bitburg in the Rheinland-Pfalz Eifel are major brewing operations. The historic Pirelli Reifen Kaiserslautern tyre plant and the historic Eichbaum Mannheim brewery (technically Baden-Württemberg) round out the cluster.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Rheinland-Pfalz invasive-species detail: the LfU Rheinland-Pfalz (Landesamt für Umwelt RP) at Mainz coordinates the state Neozoa register. The RP wine-region pest landscape is heavily affected by Drosophila suzukii (the spotted-wing fruit fly that damages grapes, cherries and stone fruit), the brown marmorated stink bug Halyomorpha halys (a major Pfalz and Rheinhessen wine pest), the Asian Citrus Psyllid (a feared but not-yet-confirmed citrus pest), and the European grapevine moth Lobesia botrana (although technically native, climate change has expanded its range). The RP wildcat population in the Pfälzerwald, the Eifel and the Hunsrück is one of the largest in Germany; the Westpfalz wildcat reintroductions have been a major conservation success. The RP wolf population (around 5 confirmed packs in 2024) is concentrated in the Westerwald and the Eifel. The RP Asian-Hornet front advanced from the 2014 Müllheim (Baden-Württemberg) origin into Pfalz and Rheinhessen by 2017 and now covers the whole state. The Pfälzerwald-Biosphärenreservat (a UNESCO MAB Reserve, the largest contiguous forest in Germany at 1,800 square kilometres) hosts substantial wildlife including substantial fallow-deer, mouflon, wild boar and roe-deer populations. The Vulkaneifel Geopark hosts distinctive maar-lake ecology including some introduced fish species. The Naturpark Südeifel and the Naturpark Hunsrück-Hochwald support cross-border conservation cooperation with Luxembourg, France and Belgium. The Rheinland-Pfalz Bundeswehr training grounds at Baumholder and Daun preserve large grassland areas with rare flora and fauna threatened by neighbouring agricultural intensification. The historic Mosel and Rhine river-traffic continues to introduce ballast-water species; the Rhine round-goby and Caspian-Pontic goby invasions have heavily affected the RP river ecology.'
WHERE region_name = 'Rheinland-Pfalz';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Additional Saarland tourism detail: the Schloss Saarbrücken modern central glass extension by Gottfried Böhm of 1989 won the Pritzker Prize for German post-modern architecture. The Ludwigsplatz baroque square in Saarbrücken with the Friedrich Joachim Stengel ensemble, the Schlossplatz, the Stiftskirche Sankt Arnual (the historic Romanesque-Gothic church with the tombs of the Nassau-Saarbrücken counts), the Alte Brücke over the Saar (the medieval bridge of 1546), the St. Johanner Markt with its baroque fountain, the Berliner Promenade along the Saar, the Saarbrücker Stadtgalerie of contemporary art, the Saarlandmuseum (with its Moderne Galerie holding important German Expressionist works of Max Beckmann, Otto Dix and Lyonel Feininger), the Bergwerksmuseum at Camphausen, the Saarbrücker Schloss with the Saarbrücken Historisches Museum, the Schloss Halberg, the Deutsch-Französischer Garten (a 50-hectare French-style park created jointly with French Lorraine in 1960), the Saarbrücker Zoo (with the Saarland-born hippo Bulette the famous TV-show hippo), and the Wildpark Saarbrücken-Burbach complete the urban offer. Saarlouis was founded in 1680 by King Louis XIV of France and fortified by Vauban as a French frontier fortress town. The Vauban-style six-pointed star-shaped fortifications partly survive, as does the Französisches Tor (French Gate), the Deutsches Tor (German Gate), the Großer Markt with the Vauban-style colonnaded buildings, the Ludwig-Garten and the Ludwigskirche. Mettlach is home to Villeroy & Boch ceramics company headquarters at the historic Old Abbey since 1809. The Saar Hunsrück Steig long-distance hiking trail and the Saarschleife loop have made the Saar Loop one of the most-photographed German natural features. The Cloef-Atrium above the Saar Loop, the Bostalsee Center Parcs resort, the Tholeyer Schloss with the Gerhard Richter stained-glass windows installed 2020 (the iconic German contemporary-art commission), the historic Schaumberg-Sterne stargazing dome, the Lebach Wolfsfelsen, the Mettlach Villeroy & Boch outlet, the Schloss Berg at Nennig with the Roman villa mosaic floor (one of the largest preserved Roman mosaics north of the Alps), and the Saarbrücken Schwarzenbergturm wide-area viewing tower complete the rural tourism offer. The Saarland Therme at Rilchingen-Hanweiler is the largest spa complex in the state. The Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark (a UNESCO Soundscape monument) is shared with Rheinland-Pfalz and includes the unique German-French cross-border conservation cooperation. The Schaumberg-Park geopark and the Saarpolygon at Ensdorf (the iconic 30-metre steel sculpture atop a 150-metre slag heap commemorating the Saarland coal-mining heritage) are post-industrial landmark visitor sites. The Saarbrücker Christmas Market on the St. Johanner Markt and the Saarland Open-Air Theatre Festival round out the cultural offer.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Saarland transport detail: the Saarbrücken-Sarreguemines cross-border tram-train (Saarbahn line S1) is one of only two cross-border tram-train networks in the world (the other being the Strasbourg-Kehl tram). The Saarbahn GmbH (the Saarbrücken city tram operator) jointly with the French SNCF runs through services from Saarbrücken Hauptbahnhof via the historic Saarbrücker Burbach to Sarreguemines in Lorraine. The Saarbrücken-Mannheim-Paris ICE/TGV inOui service via Kaiserslautern (technically Rheinland-Pfalz) takes around 1 hour 45 minutes to Paris-Est since the 2007 LGV Est high-speed line opening, making Saarbrücken one of the most-Paris-accessible German cities. The Saarbahn S1 operates from Saarbrücken-Riegelsberg via Saarbrücken Hauptbahnhof to Saarbrücken-Brebach and onward across the border to Sarreguemines. The new Saarbahn extension to Lebach-Jabach is under construction for opening in the late 2020s. The Autobahn A6 from Saarbrücken-Forbach across the Goldene Bremm border crossing connects to the French A4 to Strasbourg and Paris. The Autobahn A8 connects to Luxembourg and the historic A8 to Pirmasens-Karlsruhe runs east. The Autobahn A620 (the Saar-Autobahn along the Saar river from Saarbrücken to Saarlouis and Merzig) is the main north-south corridor of the state. The Autobahn A1 from Saarbrücken via Trier to Cologne (the historic Reichsstraße 1 successor) runs north. The Saar canal (Saar Wasserstraße), canalised between 1986 and 1999, connects the Mosel at Konz (Trier) to the French Canal de la Marne au Rhin. The Saarbrücker Burbach Rhein-Hafen and the Saarlouis Hafen handle bulk traffic for the Saar steel industry. The Dillinger Hütte Hafen on the Saar serves the Dillinger steelworks. The Saarbrücken Airport (Ensheim) handles around 350,000 passengers per year with operations by Luxair, Vueling, Air Service Vienna and seasonal Mediterranean charter carriers. The Zweibrücken Airport (technically Rheinland-Pfalz but commercially used by Saarland) closed for commercial service in 2014. The cross-border Luxembourg-Findel Airport and Metz-Nancy-Lorraine Airport in France serve Saarland from across the borders with substantial Saarland commuter traffic. The Saarbrücken-Sarreguemines cross-border bus network and the Saarland-VV-tariff (the Saarländischer Verkehrsverbund) coordinates regional integrated public transport. Long-distance buses use the Saarbrücken ZOB at the Hauptbahnhof; FlixBus and Sindbad operate services to Paris, Brussels, Luxembourg, Mainz, Mannheim and Frankfurt. The Saar-Radweg from Sarreguemines via Saarbrücken to Mettlach and onward to Trier on the Mosel is one of the top-ranked German cycling routes. The Velo Tour Sarre-Lor-Lux cross-border cycling network coordinates with French Lorraine and Luxembourg.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Saarland economic detail: the Saarland coal-mining industry, which dominated the state economy from the 1850s to the 1980s with peak employment of around 80,000 miners, completely closed in 2012 when the last coal mine (Bergwerk Saar at Ensdorf) shut down. The post-closure Saarland coal-mining heritage tourism around the historic Bergmannsglücksort at Reden, the Saargrubenmuseum at Bexbach, the Saarpolygon at Ensdorf and the historic Erlebnisbergwerk Velsen complete the industrial-tourism circuit. The Saar steel cluster (Saarstahl AG and Dillinger Hütte AG, jointly the SHS Stahl-Holding-Saar) employs around 11,000 workers across the Völklingen, Burbach, Dillingen and Neunkirchen integrated plants. Dillinger Hütte is the world''s largest producer of heavy plate (5 to 700 millimetres thick), supplying around 1.5 million tonnes per year to global shipbuilding, pipelines, offshore-wind monopiles and military vehicles. The Saarstahl Group is undergoing the SALCOS-style green-steel transformation with the new hydrogen-DRI direct-reduction plant at Dillingen planned for the 2030s. The Halberg Guss iron foundry at Brebach (Saarbrücken), founded 1756, is one of the oldest German iron foundries still operating. The Saarbrücken Universität (Universität des Saarlandes) at Saarbrücken-Dudweiler has around 17,000 students. The Saarland computer-science cluster around Saarbrücken (the DFKI Deutsche Forschungszentrum für Künstliche Intelligenz, founded 1988, is one of the largest German AI-research institutes; the CISPA Helmholtz-Zentrum für Informationssicherheit, founded 2007, is one of the largest German cybersecurity research centres; the Max-Planck-Institut für Informatik and the Max-Planck-Institut für Softwaresysteme at Saarbrücken-Saarbrücken; together forming the largest computer-science research cluster in continental Europe) is one of the most successful Saarland economic-transformation stories of the past 30 years. The Globus SB-Warenhaus Holding GmbH & Co. KG at St. Wendel is the third-largest German hypermarket retailer with around 50 stores and revenues of 8 billion euros. The Karlsberg Brauerei AG at Homburg is one of the largest German privately-owned breweries with annual revenues of around 280 million euros. The Saarbrücker Zeitung (the leading Saarland daily newspaper), the Saarländischer Rundfunk (the regional ARD public broadcaster), and the Saarbrücker Saar-Lor-Lux cluster of cross-border start-ups round out the economic offer. The Saarbrücker Bundeswehr Pioniertruppe at Saarlouis-Roden and the historic French Forces in Germany withdrawal of 1999 ended the Saarland''s historic French-military presence. The Saarland film industry (the Max-Ophüls-Preis Film Festival at Saarbrücken, the historic Saarländischer Filmkulturverein and the Saarländisches Filmbüro) supports a small but vital regional creative-economy. The Saarbrücken Christmas Market and the Saarland Open Air Theatre Festival round out the cultural-economy offer.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Saarland invasive-species detail: the Saarland Asian-Hornet record of 2016 was one of the earliest German confirmed breeding records, the species having advanced from northern France via Lorraine across the Saar frontier. The Saarland Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark and the Pfälzerwald-Naturpark cooperate with the French Vosges du Nord regional park and the Luxembourg Naturpark Mëllerdall in the cross-border conservation Sarre-Lor-Lux network. The Saarland coal-mining heritage Bergehalden (slag heaps from former coal mining) at Velsen, Reden, Göttelborn and Itzenplitz host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities including the Senecio inaequidens (the South African ragwort that has become a major coloniser of disturbed sandy and slag-heap soil in the Saarland coal-mining heritage areas), the tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial brownfields of Saarbrücken-Burbach and the historic Halberg Guss complex), the goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea, dominant on the historic Bergehalden), and the black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, extensively planted on the historic Saarland mining areas for slag-heap stabilisation since the 1920s). The Saarland Saarbrücker Universität ecologists (under Prof. Karin Ulbrich and others) have studied the post-industrial succession vegetation in detail. The Saarland wildcat reintroduction in the Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark is one of the most successful European wildcat conservation programmes; the Saarland-Luxembourg-Rheinland-Pfalz cross-border wildcat corridor is now one of the largest contiguous wildcat habitats in central Europe. The Saarland European mink (Mustela lutreola) reintroduction is being planned for the 2030s in cooperation with French Lorraine populations. The historic Saarland Lautenbacher Wildpark and the Wolfspark Werner Freund at Merzig (one of the most famous wolf-sanctuary parks in Europe, founded 1972 by Werner Freund) host substantial captive wildlife populations including the Saarland''s most famous wolf-research operation. The Saarland Iglesias Reservoir (the Bostalsee) and the Niedaltdorfer See host the standard Saarland-area introduced fish populations. The Saarland river otter recovery in the Blies and the Saar is one of the most successful European otter conservation programmes.'
WHERE region_name = 'Saarland';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Sachsen transport detail: the Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8 (VDE 8) high-speed corridor from Berlin via Leipzig and Erfurt to Nuremberg-Munich, completed in December 2017 at a total cost of around 10 billion euros, is one of the largest single European rail-infrastructure projects of the post-1990 era; the Leipzig Hauptbahnhof City Tunnel, opened 2013 at a cost of 1 billion euros, allows all Leipzig S-Bahn lines to run through-services from the historic terminal to the southern Leipzig districts. The Leipzig Hauptbahnhof, opened 1915 as the largest railway terminal in the world by surface area (84,000 square metres with 23 platforms across two parallel halls), is one of the architectural masterpieces of German rail history; the Hauptbahnhof Promenaden shopping mall in the historic main hall has won multiple architectural awards. The Dresden Hauptbahnhof with its iconic tent-shaped roof, the Chemnitz Hauptbahnhof, the Görlitz Hauptbahnhof (the easternmost German major rail node), the Zwickau Hauptbahnhof, the Plauen Hauptbahnhof and Riesa complete the major Saxon rail nodes. The Sächsische Dampfschiffahrt GmbH at Dresden operates the largest fleet of working paddle steamers in the world (nine historic paddle wheelers, all built between 1879 and 1929 and still operating regularly between Dresden, Meissen, Pillnitz and Bad Schandau, with the steamer Diesbar of 1884 being the oldest operating paddle wheeler in Europe). The Elbe-Radweg from Schöna along the Elbe is one of Germany''s top-ranked long-distance cycle routes. The Saxon tram networks: the Leipzig tram (the second-longest German tram network at 145 kilometres with 13 lines), the Dresden tram (the third-longest at 134 kilometres with 12 lines), the Chemnitz Stadtbahn (with tram-train technology similar to the Karlsruhe model), the Plauen tram, the Görlitz tram, the Zwickau tram and the historic Lockwitztalbahn (the oldest German overland tramway in continuous operation since 1906) and the historic Kirnitzschtalbahn (the unique forest tram in the Sächsische Schweiz operating since 1898) complete the system. The Dresdner Bergschwebebahn (the suspended monorail of 1901, the world''s second-oldest after Wuppertal) and the Standseilbahn Dresden (the Dresden funicular) are tourist attractions. The Saxon Erzgebirgsbahn, the Sächsisch-Böhmische Eisenbahngesellschaft and the Vogtlandbahn (Länderbahn) operate cross-border services to Bohemia.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Sachsen economic detail: the Silicon Saxony cluster is the largest microelectronics centre in Europe, with Infineon Technologies Dresden, Globalfoundries Fab1, Bosch Wafer Fab Dresden, the upcoming ESMC joint venture (TSMC-Bosch-Infineon-NXP) and X-FAB. Silicon Saxony Verein claims around 25 per cent of European semiconductor revenue. The Volkswagen Sachsen plants at Zwickau (the largest European electric-vehicle plant building the VW ID.3/4/5/7, the Audi Q4 e-tron and the Cupra Born — around 11,000 workers), Chemnitz (engine plant), and Dresden Gläserne Manufaktur (the Transparent Factory for ID.3 final assembly) employ around 18,000 workers. Porsche Leipzig (the second-largest Porsche plant after Zuffenhausen) and BMW Leipzig (with the iconic Zaha Hadid central building) each employ around 4,500-5,500 workers building the Porsche Macan/Cayenne/Panamera and the BMW 1/2/iX1/i4/Mini Countryman. The DHL European Hub at Leipzig/Halle Airport (since 2008 after relocating from Brussels) is the largest single cargo facility in Saxony with around 6,000 employees and 2.5 million tonnes of cargo per year. The Saxon Strukturwandel programme distributes around 14 billion euros of federal Strukturstärkungsgesetz funds to Saxony through 2038 supporting the Lausitz lignite-exit, the new German Centre for Astrophysics at Görlitz, the Lausitz Science Park at Cottbus (jointly Brandenburg), and the federal hydrogen-pilot programmes. The Saxon Stadler Rail Pankow plant builds the Velaro D ICE. The Meissen Porzellan-Manufaktur (founded 1710 by Johann Friedrich Böttger) is the historic first European hard-paste porcelain manufactory and continues to produce porcelain at the Triebischtal Manufaktur. The historic Plauener Lace cooperative produces high-quality lace; Plauen has been the world centre of machine-made lace since 1881. The Wernesgrüner Brauerei, the Radeberger Brauerei and the Sternburg Brauerei together brew around 1 million hectolitres of beer per year. The Sachsenmilch AG at Leppersdorf is one of the largest German dairies. The Sächsischer Imkerverband coordinates the Asian Hornet response programme. The Saxon GDP per capita is the highest among the New German Federal States.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Sachsen invasive-species detail: the Saxon LUPUS Wolf Office at the Görlitz Senckenberg Naturhistorische Sammlungen (founded by Ilka Reinhardt and Gesa Kluth in 2000) leads German wolf research. The 2000 first-pack Muskauer Heide milestone (the first confirmed German wolf reproduction since 1850) is commemorated annually. The Saxon wolf population in 2024 was around 30 established packs (the highest of any German Land), with several hundred individuals. The Saxon African Swine Fever situation has been the most affected of any German Land, with thousands of confirmed wild-boar cases in the Oberlausitz, the Görlitz district and the Bautzen area since September 2020; intensive containment fencing along the Polish border and continuous culling of wild boar have largely contained the outbreak by 2023. The Saxon Erzgebirge mountain pine plantations contain large areas of introduced Pinus mugo subspecies. The Saxon Lausitz Bergehalden (slag heaps from former lignite mining) at Spreetal, Welzow, Cottbus and Hoyerswerda host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities; the Lausitz Lake District (Lausitzer Seenland), the flooded former open-cast lignite pits being converted to lakes (the Cottbuser Ostsee, the Senftenberger See, the Geierswalder See, the Bergheider See, the Bärwalder See — together one of the largest planned man-made lake landscapes in Europe), supports both ruderal-invasive vegetation and emerging novel-ecosystem communities being studied by the BTU Cottbus-Senftenberg ecologists. The historic Saxon Müggelsee, the Saxon Schwielochsee, the Saxon Großer Stechlinsee (the lake immortalised by Theodor Fontane in Der Stechlin) and the Saxon Schmöllner Teiche hosts substantial fish and crayfish invasions. The Saxon Free State of Saxony Lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction in the Oberlausitz Forest is being planned for the late 2020s in cooperation with the Czech Šumava Park and the Polish Bohemian Forest populations.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Additional Sachsen-Anhalt tourism detail: Schloss Schwerin (technically Mecklenburg-Vorpommern but historically connected to the Anhalt branch), the Schloss Mosigkau, the Schloss Oranienbaum, the Schloss Luisium, the Schloss Großkühnau, the Schloss Wörlitz with the Synagogue Wörlitz (one of the few rural German synagogues surviving Kristallnacht), the Gotisches Haus, the Schloss Köthen of the famous Köthen Bach (where Johann Sebastian Bach was Court Kapellmeister from 1717 to 1723 and composed the Brandenburg Concertos), the Bachstadt Köthen with the Bachhaus Köthen museum, the Schloss Bernburg (the historic Anhalt-Bernburg residence on the Saale), the Schloss Zerbst (the historic Anhalt-Zerbst residence and the birthplace of Catherine the Great of Russia, born Sophie of Anhalt-Zerbst in 1729), the historic Naumburg-Domvorhalle with the Naumburger Meister figures, the Kloster Pforta (the historic Cistercian monastery near Bad Kösen, the alma mater of Friedrich Nietzsche, Friedrich Klopstock and many other German cultural figures), the Schloss Stolberg in the Harz, the Stolberger Stadtmauer Old Town walls, the Eisleben Luther Geburtshaus and Sterbehaus, the Wittenberger Schlosskirche and Luther-Stadt, and the Magdeburger Dom complete the cultural circuit. The Halle Marktplatz Roter Turm of 84 metres is one of Europe''s largest free-standing belfries. The Halle Marktkirche Unser Lieben Frauen has four towers including the unique Hausmannstürme pair that flank a Glockenstuhl tower group. The Halle Händel-Haus is the birthplace of Georg Friedrich Händel (1685-1759). The Halle Salzwirkerschaftsmuseum at the Saline Halle (the historic salt-works dating from 961) is one of the oldest industrial-heritage museums in Germany. The Halloren-Chokoladenfabrik (the oldest German chocolate factory, founded 1804) is now a major industrial-tourism destination. The Halle Moritzburg gallery has the largest German Lyonel Feininger collection.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Sachsen-Anhalt transport detail: the Magdeburger Wasserstraßenkreuz (Magdeburg Waterway Crossing, opened 2003) is one of the most spectacular hydraulic engineering structures in the world — the canal Trog (water bridge) of 918 metres carries the Mittellandkanal over the Elbe at Magdeburg-Hohenwarthe, making it the largest such canal bridge in the world by length. The Mittellandkanal (the longest German artificial waterway) connects the Rhine-Ruhr area via Magdeburg and the Elbe-Havel-Kanal system to Berlin and Brandenburg. The Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof, opened 1873 with the iconic 19th-century facade, is the central rail node of the state with around 30,000 passengers per day. The Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof is one of the largest German rail nodes outside the major metropolitan areas, the historic junction of the Berlin-Munich and Cologne-Berlin lines, with around 50,000 passengers per day. The Magdeburg-Berlin and Magdeburg-Hannover regional rail corridors are heavily used. The Wittenberg Hauptbahnhof and the Stendal Hauptbahnhof (the historic Berlin-Hannover ICE stop on the 1998 NBS) complete the major rail nodes. The Hauptbahnhof Naumburg, Hauptbahnhof Wernerode, Hauptbahnhof Lutherstadt Wittenberg and Hauptbahnhof Halberstadt complete the rail map. The Stadtbahn Magdeburg (operated by Magdeburger Verkehrsbetriebe MVB) has nine lines totalling 88 kilometres. The Halle (Saale) tram (operated by Hallesche Verkehrs-AG HAVAG) has eight lines totalling 84 kilometres; the historic Halle Saalkreis suburban interurban network is one of the oldest German electric trams (the Hallesche Straßenbahn AG operated the world''s first commercially viable electric tram from 1891). The Bad Schmiedeberg, Naumburg and Halberstadt small tram networks complete the system. The Magdeburg-Berlin and the Magdeburg-Hannover Autobahn A2 corridor (the historic Mittellandlinie connecting the Ruhrgebiet to Berlin), the Halle-Munich A9, the Magdeburg-Dresden A14 (under continuous upgrade), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn) and the planned A14 extension to Schwerin in MV complete the road network. Long-distance buses cluster at the Magdeburg ZOB Hauptbahnhof and the Halle ZOB. The Elbe-Radweg (the most-popular German long-distance cycling route) passes through Magdeburg and Wittenberg. The Saale-Radweg, the Unstrut-Radweg, the Tour Brandenburg, the Mecklenburger Seenradweg-South and the Rotkäppchen-Radweg complete the cycling network.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Sachsen-Anhalt economic detail: the Mitteldeutsches Chemiedreieck (Central German Chemical Triangle) around Leuna-Schkopau-Bitterfeld is one of the largest German chemical clusters and the historic site of IG Farben and the GDR Chemiestandorte. The Total Refinery Leuna (one of the largest German oil refineries with 12 million tonnes per year capacity), the DOW Olefinverbund Schkopau-Böhlen (the largest single Dow Chemical site outside the United States, producing ethylene, propylene and polymers), the SKW Stickstoffwerke Piesteritz at Wittenberg (the largest German ammonia and urea producer), the Linde Leuna industrial gases, the InfraLeuna chemical-park operator (the largest European methanol production), and the Chemiepark Bitterfeld-Wolfen (with Heraeus, Bayer Bitterfeld, Suez, Sandoz and many other tenants) together form the Mitteldeutsches Chemiedreieck cluster employing around 35,000 chemical workers. The Halle-Bitterfeld-Wolfen Solar Valley (the Mitteldeutsches Solar Valley) was historically one of the largest German solar-PV manufacturing clusters, although it declined dramatically after 2012 with the Chinese solar-cost crash; today the cluster is recovering with new investments by Hanwha QCells (formerly Q-Cells), Meyer Burger and others. The Halloren AG chocolate maker (founded 1804 at Halle) is the oldest German chocolate factory still in operation. The Rotkäppchen-Mumm Sektkellereien at Freyburg an der Unstrut is the largest German producer of Sekt sparkling wine, with annual revenues of around 1 billion euros under the iconic Rotkäppchen red-cap brand. The Hasseröder Brauerei at Wernigerode (owned by Anheuser-Busch InBev) is one of the largest German beer brands. The Salzwedeler Baumkuchen has EU PGI protection. The Halle and Magdeburg banking sector includes the Saalesparkasse, the Stadtsparkasse Magdeburg, the Investitionsbank Sachsen-Anhalt (the state development bank) and the historic Magdeburger Lebensversicherung. The Saale-Unstrut wine region produces around 100,000 hectolitres per year — small but distinguished. The Mitteldeutsche Braunkohle Revier in the south of the state is in the federal coal-exit transition until 2038.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Sachsen-Anhalt invasive-species detail: the Sachsen-Anhalt wolf population in 2024 was around 15 confirmed packs in the Altmark, the Colbitz-Letzlinger Heide military training ground, the Drömling biosphere reserve, the Saxon-Anhaltian Elbaue and the Harz foothills. The Sachsen-Anhalt Wolves Office at the Landesamt für Umweltschutz coordinates monitoring and livestock-loss compensation. The Sachsen-Anhalt Elbe beaver population (around 500 animals) is one of the largest in central Germany, originating from the historic Dessau-Wörlitz core reintroduction. The Sachsen-Anhalt Drömling biosphere reserve (a UNESCO MAB Reserve since 2023, the famous Wermsdorfer Cranes-resting site) supports substantial native-species recovery alongside ongoing invasive-species management. The Sachsen-Anhalt Harz National Park hosts the famous Brocken native flora recovery and the lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction since 2000 (the Harz lynx population now numbers around 20 animals). The Sachsen-Anhalt state forestry is leading the European bison (Bison bonasus) breeding programme at the Wisentgehege Topfberg near Magdeburg (one of the few German bison-breeding stations). The Sachsen-Anhalt Lausitz-Halle railway corridor has been a major Asian Longhorned Beetle entry-point monitoring site. The Sachsen-Anhalt Mansfelder Land Bergehalden (slag heaps from copper mining) at Eisleben, Hettstedt and Mansfeld host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities, with the historic black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, planted extensively on the Bergehalden since the early 20th century for slag-heap stabilisation), the tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial Bitterfeld-Wolfen brownfields), the goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea, dominant on fallow fields), the ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), and the Senecio inaequidens being widespread. The Sachsen-Anhalt Helmholtz-Zentrum für Umweltforschung Halle (UFZ) is one of the leading European environmental research centres. The Sachsen-Anhalt Saale-Unstrut viticulture region has experienced expansion of brown marmorated stink bug Halyomorpha halys and Drosophila suzukii in recent years; the Landesweingut Kloster Pforta and the Winzervereinigung Freyburg have invested in integrated pest management.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen-Anhalt';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Schleswig-Holstein transport detail: the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link, under construction since 2020 by the Danish operator Femern A/S, will be an 18-kilometre immersed road-and-rail tunnel between Puttgarden on Fehmarn (Schleswig-Holstein) and Rødby on Lolland (Denmark) — the longest immersed tunnel in the world and one of the most ambitious European infrastructure projects of the 21st century. The tunnel is due to open in 2029 and will allow direct rail services Hamburg-Lübeck-Copenhagen in around 2.5 hours, dramatically reducing the Hamburg-Stockholm and Hamburg-Oslo rail journeys. The Hindenburgdamm (the rail-only causeway built 1923-1927 from Klanxbüll to Morsum-Sylt across the Wadden Sea) is the only rail link to Sylt and carries the Sylt Shuttle car trains. The Kiel Canal (Nord-Ostsee-Kanal, NOK, opened 1895), the 98-kilometre artificial waterway between Kiel-Holtenau on the Baltic and Brunsbüttel on the Elbe, is the most-trafficked artificial waterway in the world by ship transits with around 28,000-32,000 ships per year (more than the Panama and Suez Canals combined). The Schleswig-Holstein A23 (Hamburg-Heide), A1 (Hamburg-Heiligenhafen via Lübeck, the so-called Vogelfluglinie connecting to Denmark), A7 (the longest motorway in Europe from Memmingen to Flensburg, the so-called Mauerautobahn during the Cold War), A20 (the Baltic Sea Autobahn, partially completed), A21 (Schleswig-Holstein north-south), A24 (Hamburg-Berlin via Hagenow), A25 (Hamburg-Geesthacht), and the Bundesstraße B5 (the main road along the North Sea coast) form the Autobahn network. The S-Bahn S4 line under construction from Hamburg Hauptbahnhof to Bad Oldesloe (Schleswig-Holstein) will open from 2027. The Hamburg S-Bahn S1 to Kaltenkirchen and the S21 to Aumühle already extend into Schleswig-Holstein. The Kieler Förde ferries (the Kieler Schiffahrtsgesellschaft) provide cross-city water transport. The Lübeck Stadtbahn was historically the first electric tram in Germany (1881) but closed in 1959. The Schleswig-Holstein bus network is operated by Autokraft, KomBus, NAH.SH partners and the historic Lübecker Verkehrsbetriebe. The Vogelfluglinie historic ferry from Puttgarden to Rødby (operated by Scandlines) handles around 30,000 ferry crossings per year currently but will be replaced by the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link from 2029. The Lübeck-Travemünde (TT-Line and Finnlines ferries to Trelleborg-Sweden, Liepāja-Latvia, Klaipėda-Lithuania, Helsinki-Finland and the cargo trade) is the largest German Baltic ferry port. The Kiel-Oslo (Color Line ferry) and the Kiel-Klaipeda (DFDS ferry) round out the Baltic ferry network. The Ostseeküsten-Radweg (EuroVelo 10), the Nordseeküsten-Radweg (EuroVelo 12), the Mönchsweg pilgrim route, the Berlin-Kopenhagen Cycle Route and the Wadden Sea Cycle Route make Schleswig-Holstein one of the top-ranked German cycling destinations.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Schleswig-Holstein economic detail: the Thyssenkrupp Marine Systems (TKMS) AG at Kiel is the largest German naval shipyard, employing around 8,000 workers. TKMS Kiel builds the world''s leading conventional submarines including the Type 212A submarines (the world''s first fully diesel-electric submarines with air-independent propulsion using PEM fuel cells, the world''s quietest submarines, operated by the German, Italian, Israeli and Norwegian navies), the upcoming Type 212CD (the next generation under construction for Germany and Norway), the Type 209 export submarines (operated by 14 navies), the Dolphin-class submarines (for Israel), the F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates (the largest German frigates by displacement), and the F126 Mehrzweckkampfschiff frigates (currently under construction). The historic Niederegger Marzipan at Lübeck (founded 1806) is the most-famous German marzipan with EU PGI protection. The Drägerwerk AG & Co. KGaA at Lübeck (founded 1889) is the world''s leading manufacturer of mining-rescue and fire-rescue breathing apparatus, anaesthesia ventilators, intensive-care ventilators and gas-detection equipment, with annual revenues of around 3 billion euros. During the COVID-19 pandemic Dräger was one of the world''s primary suppliers of intensive-care ventilators. The Schleswig-Holstein wind-energy and offshore-wind cluster is one of the strongest in Germany, with the state having the highest onshore-wind installed capacity per capita in Germany (around 8 GW) and substantial offshore-wind investment in the German Bight. The historic Brunsbüttel oil-and-chemicals industrial complex around the Total Brunsbüttel refinery (now restructured), the Bayer Brunsbüttel chemicals plant and the historic Westkalkstein cement complete the chemical industry. The Sylter Royal oyster (the Pacific oyster Magallana gigas, cultivated since 1986 on the List Wadden Sea bed by Dittmeyer''s Austerncompagnie) is the only commercial German oyster fishery. The Schleswig-Holstein dairy industry produces around 25 per cent of all German milk, with the Nordmilch (now Arla Foods amba subsidiary), the historic Schwarmstedter Molkerei, and the Bünting Tee Company (East Friesland) among the largest food brands. The Schleswig-Holstein tourism sector hosts around 26 million overnight stays per year (the third-highest German state after Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg).',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Schleswig-Holstein invasive-species detail: the Schleswig-Holstein Wadden Sea National Park, designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2009 jointly with the Lower Saxony and Hamburg Wadden Sea National Parks and with the Dutch and Danish Wadden Sea, is the largest unbroken system of intertidal sand and mud flats in the world (4,400 square kilometres along the SH coast). The Schleswig-Holstein Pacific Oyster invasion (the Magallana gigas Pazifische Auster, originally introduced for aquaculture at Sylt-List in 1986) has been the most-studied marine invasion in northern Europe; the Sylter Royal oyster farm of Dittmeyer''s Austerncompagnie is the only commercial German oyster fishery and one of the most profitable Wadden Sea aquaculture operations. The Schleswig-Holstein Asian shore crabs (Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi) and the American razor clam (Ensis directus) invasions have been documented since the 1979 storm transport. The Schleswig-Holstein Helgoland Biologische Anstalt of the Alfred Wegener Institute (AWI Bremerhaven affiliated) maintains the world''s longest continuous marine-monitoring programme since 1873; Helgoland is the only true deep-sea German island and a major entry-point for North-Atlantic marine invasions. The Schleswig-Holstein barnacle goose (Branta leucopsis, although native to Arctic Russia and Svalbard as a winter visitor) has established small but stable feral resident breeding populations on the Wadden Sea coast since the 1990s. The Schleswig-Holstein cordgrass Spartina anglica (the hybrid salt-marsh grass) has invaded the Wadden Sea salt marshes substantially since the 1930s and has altered the intertidal landscape. The Schleswig-Holstein Sea-Buckthorn (Hippophae rhamnoides), although native to the dunes, has been planted extensively for dune stabilisation across the North Sea coast. The Schleswig-Holstein wolf population (occasional records, no established pack as of 2024) is monitored by the LLUR Wolves Office. The Schleswig-Holstein European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroduction in the Aukrug Forst and the historic Drömling has been a major conservation success. The Schleswig-Holstein North Sea grey seal (Halichoerus grypus) and harbour seal (Phoca vitulina) populations have rebounded dramatically since the 1988 phocine distemper virus die-off, with around 13,000 grey seals on Helgoland and the Sylt Wadden Sea today.'
WHERE region_name = 'Schleswig-Holstein';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Additional Thüringen transport detail: Erfurt Hauptbahnhof became the central ICE node of central Germany in December 2017 when the Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8 (VDE 8, the new high-speed line Berlin-Leipzig-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich) opened, making Erfurt a four-way ICE crossing where the Berlin-Munich line crosses the Frankfurt-Dresden line. The new Erfurter ICE-Knoten allows ICE travel from Erfurt to Berlin in 1 hour 45 minutes, to Munich in 2 hours 30 minutes, to Frankfurt in 2 hours 15 minutes, and to Dresden in 2 hours. The VDE 8 corridor (Berlin-Halle-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich) was the largest single German rail-infrastructure project of the post-reunification period, with a total cost of around 10 billion euros, the Eichelberg tunnel of 6.8 kilometres, the Erfurter Eisenbahnknoten reconstruction, the Bibratunnel and the Finne-Tunnel. The Erfurter Stadtbahn (EVAG Erfurter Verkehrs-AG) has six lines totalling 41 kilometres, including the historic line to the Egapark. The Jena Stadtbahn (Jenaer Nahverkehr GmbH) has five lines. The Gera Stadtbahn, the Gotha Stadtbahn (with the famous Thüringerwaldbahn from Gotha to Tabarz, the longest German overland tramway at 22 kilometres, operating since 1929 through the Thuringian Forest) and the Nordhausen tram (with the famous combined tram-train operation to Ilfeld in the Harz) complete the network. The historic Mitte-Deutschland-Bahn from Frankfurt via Bebra, Eisenach, Erfurt, Weimar to Leipzig was historically the main east-west axis of central Germany and continues to carry IC and Eurocity traffic. The Thuringian Forest Schmalspurbahn, the Pulsnitzbahn and the Werratalbahn round out the secondary network. The Autobahn A4 (Eisenach-Erfurt-Weimar-Gera, the historic East-West Hermsdorfer Kreuz junction), the A9 (Munich-Nuremberg-Leipzig-Berlin), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn), the A71 (Sangerhausen-Erfurt-Schweinfurt, with the Rennsteig tunnel at 7,916 metres, the longest road tunnel in Germany), the A73 (Suhl-Bamberg-Nuremberg) and the A4 Erfurter Kreuz form the road network. The Saale-Radweg, the Werra-Radweg, the Werratal-Radweg, the Saale-Unstrut-Radweg, the Thüringer Städtekette (linking Eisenach, Gotha, Erfurt, Weimar, Jena, Gera and Altenburg) and the Rennsteig-Radweg (parallel to the famous Rennsteig hiking trail) make Thuringia one of the top-ranked German cycling destinations. The historic Rennsteig hiking trail (the 169-kilometre ridge trail through the Thuringian Forest) is one of Germany''s most-famous long-distance hiking routes.',
    economics = economics || ' Additional Thüringen economic detail: Jenoptik AG (the listed Jena-headquartered optoelectronics, photonics and defence-technology group) is one of the most internationally successful Thuringian companies, with annual revenues of around 1 billion euros, around 4,000 employees, and a global presence in measurement systems, semiconductor lithography lasers, automotive diagnostics, medical lasers and high-end optics. Jenoptik was founded in 1991 from the Carl Zeiss Jena East-German optics combine. The Jena optics heritage continues with Carl Zeiss Jena GmbH (a Thuringian subsidiary of the Carl-Zeiss-Stiftung at Oberkochen-Heidenheim in Baden-Württemberg, producing microscopy and metrology systems at the historic Jena Carl-Zeiss-Promenade campus), Carl Zeiss SMT GmbH (the Jena branch producing semiconductor lithography lenses for ASML EUV machines), and Schott Jenaer Glas GmbH (a Thuringian subsidiary of the Mainz-headquartered Schott AG, producing borosilicate glass and laboratory glassware at the historic 1884 Schott Jenaer Glaswerk). Together the Jena optics-photonics-glass cluster employs around 25,000 workers and is the historic foundation of the German optical-precision industry; the Max-Planck-Institut für Biogeochemie at Jena, the Max-Planck-Institut für chemische Ökologie at Jena, the Leibniz-Institut für Naturstoff-Forschung und Infektionsbiologie Hans-Knöll-Institut at Jena, the Leibniz-Institut für Photonische Technologien at Jena, the Fraunhofer-Institut für Angewandte Optik und Feinmechanik (IOF Jena), and the Helmholtz-Institut Jena complete the Jena research cluster — making Jena one of the most photonics-research-dense small cities in Europe. Bauerfeind AG at Zeulenroda is one of the leading European producers of orthopaedic supports, compression stockings and prosthetic devices, with annual revenues of around 350 million euros. Opel Eisenach GmbH (now part of Stellantis) builds the Opel Corsa and the Opel Grandland at the historic AWE Automobilwerk Eisenach site. The Bombardier (now Alstom) Görlitz plant (technically Saxony but with Thuringian supply-chain ties) builds passenger rail vehicles. The Suhl gun-making tradition includes the historic Sauer & Sohn (founded 1751 at Suhl, today operating from Eckernförde in Schleswig-Holstein), Merkel Jagd- und Sportwaffen at Suhl, and Krieghoff (founded at Suhl 1886, today at Ulm in Baden-Württemberg). The Thüringer Bratwurst PGI industry employs many hundreds of small butchers across the state. The Köstritzer Schwarzbier brewery at Bad Köstritz produces the world''s leading Schwarzbier brand. The Thuringia film-and-music industry around the Liszt-Hochschule für Musik Weimar and the Bauhaus-Universität Weimar supports a small but vital creative-economy.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Additional Thüringen invasive-species detail: the Thüringer Landesamt für Umwelt, Bergbau und Naturschutz (TLUBN) at Jena coordinates the state Neozoa register. The Thuringian Forest National Park hosts substantial native-species conservation programmes including the European wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris) recovery, the lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction (planned for the late 2020s with cooperation from the Harz Sachsen-Anhalt lynx reintroduction and the Šumava Bohemian Czech Park lynx), the European bison (Bison bonasus) breeding programme at the Wildtierpark Hellabrunn near Pfungstadt (technically Hessen but with Thuringia connections), and the historic Hainich National Park (Germany''s only UNESCO-listed beech-forest national park, designated in 2011 as part of the Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe World Heritage Site, alongside the Müritz, Jasmund, Kellerwald and Grumsin sub-sites). The Thuringia Werra and Hainich landscape hosts the largest German wildcat population, with around 500 individuals confirmed by camera-trap monitoring. The Thuringia African Swine Fever readiness has been a major state-veterinary office focus. The Thuringia wolf population (around 3-5 established packs in 2024) is concentrated in the Thuringian Forest, the Eichsfeld and the historic Ohrdruf training ground. The Thuringian Forest Schmidtgehege wolf-sanctuary and the historic Wartburg-Eisenach Ranger Programme support cross-border conservation. The historic Thuringia game-park reserves at Schloss Friedenstein in Gotha, the Schloss Berlepsch and the Wildtierpark Schwarza preserve native fallow deer and mouflon stocks introduced for hunting. The Thuringia Eisenach-Wartburg landscape hosts the famous historic Hainich beech forest with its UNESCO designation and the unique Thuringia wildcat-corridor between the Hainich and the Harz. The Thuringia Erfurt-Egapark and the Erfurt Cyriaksburg garden-tower observation deck host distinctive urban-invasive vegetation, with the Erfurter Citadelle Petersberg hosting historic boxwood gardens now devastated by the Cydalima perspectalis box tree moth. The Thuringia Saale and Unstrut viticulture regions, although small (only around 700 hectares of the historic Saale-Unstrut wine region in Thuringia), have experienced the recent Drosophila suzukii spotted-wing fruit fly invasion and the brown marmorated stink bug Halyomorpha halys arrivals.'
WHERE region_name = 'Thüringen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Sachsen-Anhalt transport detail: the Magdeburger Hauptbahnhof has 11 platforms and is the central rail node of the state, with around 30,000 passengers per day, connecting Berlin, Hannover, Leipzig, Halle, Erfurt and Hamburg. The Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof is the larger station (with around 50,000 passengers per day) and a historic German rail junction since 1859, connecting the Berlin-Munich VDE 8 high-speed line, the Cologne-Dresden corridor, the Frankfurt-Halle-Berlin line and the Halle-Leipzig S-Bahn. The Halle-Leipzig S-Bahn, opened 2013 with the Leipzig City Tunnel completion, connects the two cities via half-hourly through-services. The Magdeburg-Wittenberg-Berlin corridor (the historic Berlin-Magdeburger Eisenbahn) carries IC and Eurocity traffic to Berlin and Brandenburg. The Wittenberg ICE-Stop opened with the VDE 8 in 2017. The Stendal ICE-Stop on the Hannover-Berlin NBS (opened 1998) connects the Altmark to Berlin and Hannover. The Halberstadt-Quedlinburg-Wernigerode-Brocken Harzer Schmalspurbahnen are operating the largest narrow-gauge steam-railway network in Europe with over 140 kilometres of 1000-mm gauge lines connecting Wernigerode, Drei Annen Hohne, the Brocken summit (the famous Brockenbahn cog-and-adhesion summit railway), and Nordhausen. The Brocken summit (1141 metres, the highest peak in northern Germany) is reached only by the Harzer Schmalspurbahn since road access has been restricted since 1989. The Magdeburger Wasserstraßenkreuz canal-bridge over the Elbe is the largest such canal-water-bridge in the world; the Mittellandkanal-Elbe-Havel-Kanal system connects the Rhine via Magdeburg to Berlin and Brandenburg. The Hauptbahnhof Lutherstadt Wittenberg, the Hauptbahnhof Naumburg (Saale), the Hauptbahnhof Halberstadt, the Hauptbahnhof Bitterfeld and the Hauptbahnhof Köthen complete the major Sachsen-Anhalt rail node map. The Stadtbahn Magdeburg operates nine tram lines. The Halle (Saale) tram has eight lines. The historic Halle Saalkreis suburban interurban tram is one of the oldest in Germany. The Bad Schmiedeberg, Naumburg, Halberstadt and Wittenberg small tram networks complete the system. The Sachsen-Anhalt Autobahn network includes the A2 (Hannover-Berlin via Magdeburg), the A9 (Munich-Berlin via Naumburg-Halle-Bitterfeld), the A14 (Magdeburg-Halle-Dresden), the A36 (Bernburg-Wernigerode-Goslar), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen), the A71 (Sangerhausen-Erfurt-Schweinfurt with the famous Rennsteig tunnel of 7,916 metres), and the planned A14 extension to Schwerin in MV. Bundesstraßen include the B1 east-west, the B6, the B100 along the Harz foothills, the B71 to Salzwedel, the B81, and the B91 to Halle. The Elbe-Radweg passes through Magdeburg, Dessau and Wittenberg. The Saale-Radweg, the Unstrut-Radweg and the Tour Brandenburg complete the network. The Sachsen-Anhalt regional rail is operated by Deutsche Bahn DB Regio Südost, the Mitteldeutsche Regiobahn (MRB), the Burgenlandbahn (now part of DB Regio), the Hanseatische Eisenbahn and the Abellio Rail Mitteldeutschland (until restructuring). The Verkehrsverbund Mitteldeutscher Verkehrsverbund (MDV) coordinates Halle-Leipzig regional tariff. The Halle-Stadt bus network is integrated with the tram via HAVAG. The Magdeburger Verkehrsbetriebe (MVB) and the Stendaler Stadtwerke complete the public-transport offer. The Sachsen-Anhalt cycling infrastructure has been substantially developed under the Tourismusmarketing Sachsen-Anhalt programme with the Lutherweg, the Bauhaus-Tour, the Wein-Tour Saale-Unstrut and the Harz-Quergänge networks.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Sachsen-Anhalt economic detail: the Mitteldeutsches Chemiedreieck around Leuna-Schkopau-Bitterfeld is the largest German chemical cluster with around 35,000 chemical workers across the Leuna refinery, the DOW Schkopau-Böhlen Olefinverbund, the SKW Stickstoffwerke Piesteritz, the InfraLeuna chemical park (one of the largest European methanol production sites), the Chemiepark Bitterfeld-Wolfen (with Heraeus, Bayer Bitterfeld, Suez and many other tenants), and the Mibe Pharma at Brehna. The Halle-Bitterfeld-Wolfen Solar Valley (the historic Mitteldeutsches Solar Valley), once one of the largest German solar-PV manufacturing clusters with Q-Cells (now Hanwha QCells), SolarWatt, SolarWorld and Sovello, declined dramatically after 2012 with the Chinese solar-cost crash and is now recovering with new investments by Hanwha QCells, Meyer Burger, Aleo Solar and the new German Solar industry. The Halloren AG chocolate maker (founded 1804 at Halle) is the oldest German chocolate factory still in operation, producing the iconic Halloren-Kugeln (the Halle chocolate balls) and the historic Helbing-Pralinen. The Rotkäppchen-Mumm Sektkellereien at Freyburg an der Unstrut (the largest German Sekt producer with around 1 billion euros annual revenue under the Rotkäppchen, Mumm, MM Extra, Geldermann and Söhnlein Brillant brands) is one of the most successful Saxony-Anhalt food brands. The Hasseröder Brauerei at Wernigerode (owned by Anheuser-Busch InBev) is one of the largest German beer brands by volume. The Salzwedeler Baumkuchen (the protected EU PGI tree-cake of Salzwedel) is produced by historic family bakers. The Magdeburger Maschinenbauschule and the Bauakademie Sachsen-Anhalt support the historic engineering tradition. The Enercon wind-turbine plant at Magdeburg builds rotor blades and nacelles. The FAM Magdeburg (Friedrich-August Magdeburger Stahlwerk, now part of the Beumer Group) specialises in bulk-material-handling systems. The Volkswagen Werkstoff- und Innovationsstandort Sachsen-Anhalt at Bitterfeld supports VW supply chain. The Beumer Group at Beckum (NRW but with Sachsen-Anhalt operations) is a global packaging and bulk-material specialist. The Sachsen-Anhalt agricultural sector is one of the most concentrated in Germany; the Magdeburger Börde (a 4,000-square-kilometre plain) is one of the most fertile soils in Europe (the so-called Schwarzerde black-earth chernozem). The Sachsen-Anhalt wine sector (the Saale-Unstrut region, the most northerly wine region in Germany at 51 degrees latitude) produces around 100,000 hectolitres of distinguished wines per year from the Landesweingut Kloster Pforta, the Weingut Lützkendorf, the Weingut Pawis, the Winzervereinigung Freyburg and the historic Weingut Bernard estates. The Sachsen-Anhalt potash industry (K+S Werra Verbund at Zielitz-Burbach is technically Hessen-Thuringia but with Sachsen-Anhalt operations). The historic Mansfelder Land copper industry has been largely transformed but the Mansfeld-Südharz remains an active mining region. Banking includes the Saalesparkasse, the Stadtsparkasse Magdeburg, and the Investitionsbank Sachsen-Anhalt. The state government and the federal Bundeswehr presence at Burg and Magdeburg complete the picture.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Sachsen-Anhalt invasive-species detail: the Sachsen-Anhalt Drömling biosphere reserve (a UNESCO MAB Reserve since 2023) supports substantial native-species recovery. The Sachsen-Anhalt Harz National Park hosts the famous Brocken native flora recovery and the lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction since 2000 (the Harz lynx population now numbers around 20-25 animals). The Sachsen-Anhalt state forestry is leading the European bison (Bison bonasus) breeding programme. The Sachsen-Anhalt Lausitz-Halle railway corridor has been a major Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) entry-point monitoring site, with the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut Quedlinburg coordinating federal monitoring traps. The Sachsen-Anhalt Mansfelder Land Bergehalden (slag heaps from copper mining) at Eisleben, Hettstedt and Mansfeld host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation including the historic black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, planted extensively for slag-heap stabilisation), the tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima), the goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea), the ragweed (Ambrosia artemisiifolia), the Senecio inaequidens (South African ragwort) and the Lupinus polyphyllus garden lupine. The Sachsen-Anhalt Helmholtz-Zentrum für Umweltforschung Halle (UFZ) is one of the leading European environmental research centres, with the long-running European Biodiversity Monitoring under the GBIF and EBV programmes. The Sachsen-Anhalt Saale-Unstrut viticulture region has experienced expansion of the brown marmorated stink bug Halyomorpha halys and the Drosophila suzukii spotted-wing fruit fly. The Sachsen-Anhalt JKI Julius Kühn-Institut at Quedlinburg (the federal Plant Genetics and Crop Plant Research Institute, with the world''s largest plant gene bank at Gatersleben with over 150,000 plant accessions) is the leading German plant-pathology and plant-genetic-resources research institute, conducting research on Saxon-Anhalt invasive plant species including the Ambrosia artemisiifolia (ragweed), the Reynoutria japonica (Japanese knotweed), the Heracleum mantegazzianum (giant hogweed) and the Impatiens glandulifera (Himalayan balsam). The Sachsen-Anhalt Hochwasserschutz programme (the Saxon-Anhalt Flood-Protection Programme) addresses the substantial nutria-burrowing damage to Saxon-Anhalt dykes; trapping is mandated under the Saxon-Anhalt Water Law. The Sachsen-Anhalt wolf population (around 15 confirmed packs in 2024) is monitored by the Wolves Office at the Landesamt für Umweltschutz at Halle. The historic Sachsen-Anhalt Elbe beaver population (around 500 animals) originates from the Dessau-Wörlitz core reintroduction. The Sachsen-Anhalt European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroduction in the Drömling and the Saxon-Anhalt Eichsfeld is one of the most ambitious German conservation projects.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen-Anhalt';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    tourism_info = tourism_info || ' Further Saarland tourism detail: the Saarland Cross-Border Sarre-Lor-Lux culture cooperation with French Lorraine and Luxembourg supports the Saarland-Lorraine-Luxembourg European Capital of Culture programmes; the Saarbrücken European Cultural Region Capital initiative includes the Esprit Région Sarre-Lor-Lux cultural-events programme. The Saarland Saar-Hunsrück-Steig long-distance hiking trail (the 410-kilometre Premium-Wanderweg from Perl on the Mosel to Boppard on the Rhine, opened 2009) is one of Germany''s top-ranked Premium-Wanderwege (premium hiking trails); the Saarschleife loop section is the most-walked single trail-segment. The Saarschleife Cloef-Atrium hosts the cliff-edge viewing platform with the 360-degree panorama. The Cloef-Hotel ovewlooking the Saar Loop is a Bertha Krupp Memorial commemoration. The Mettlach Villeroy & Boch Old Abbey factory complex includes the Keravision museum, the historic Boch family residence and the Erlebniszentrum Keramik. The Mettlach Villeroy & Boch Outlet Centre attracts around 1 million visitors per year. The Saarbrücken Christmas Market (Saarbrücker Weihnachtsmarkt on the St. Johanner Markt) is one of the most-attended in southwest Germany. The Saarland Open-Air Theatre Festival, the Max-Ophüls-Preis Film Festival (the major German film festival for emerging filmmakers, held annually at Saarbrücken since 1980), the Saarbrücker Stadtfest, the Internationales Klavierfestival Saar Pizzini and the Saarländisches Staatstheater opera programme complete the cultural offer. The Saarland-Therme at Rilchingen-Hanweiler is the largest spa complex in the state. The Wadgassen Schloss-Bibliothek and the Wadgasser Kohlewald hiking trails complete the Saarbrücken-Saarlouis-Wadgassen triangle. The Saarbrücker Schwarzenbergturm wide-area viewing tower offers panoramic views across the cross-border region. The Saarpolygon at Ensdorf, the 30-metre steel sculpture atop the 150-metre slag heap, commemorates the Saarland coal-mining heritage and serves as a major post-industrial visitor attraction. The Schaumberg geopark stargazing dome at Tholey offers some of the best dark-sky observation in southwest Germany. The Wolfspark Werner Freund at Merzig is one of the most-famous wolf-sanctuaries in Europe.',
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Saarland transport detail: the Saarbrücken-Sarreguemines cross-border Saarbahn S1 tram-train is one of only two cross-border tram-trains in the world (the other being Strasbourg-Kehl); jointly operated by the Saarbahn GmbH and SNCF. The Saarbrücken Hauptbahnhof handles around 45,000 passengers per day, connecting to Mannheim (with TGV inOui services to Paris-Est in 1 hour 45 minutes), Frankfurt, Trier, Luxembourg and Stuttgart. The Saarbrücken-Frankfurt ICE corridor takes around 2 hours. The Saarbrücken-Trier-Luxembourg cross-border RE service runs hourly. The Saarbrücken-Forbach Goldene Bremm border crossing on the A6 is one of the busiest German-French border crossings. The Saarbrücken Airport (Ensheim, SCN) handles around 350,000 passengers per year. The Saarbahn S1 line operates on the historic Karlsruhe-model tram-train infrastructure shared with the heavy-rail network; the planned Saarbahn extension to Lebach-Jabach is under construction for opening in the late 2020s. The Autobahn A6 (Mannheim-Saarbrücken-Paris), the A8 (Luxembourg-Saarbrücken-Pirmasens-Karlsruhe), the A1 (Saarbrücken-Trier-Cologne-Bremen), the A620 (the Saar-Autobahn along the Saar river from Saarbrücken to Saarlouis and Merzig), and the A623 (the Saarbrücken north-south spur) form the Saarland motorway network. The Saar canal (Saar Wasserstraße, canalised 1986-1999) connects the Mosel at Konz (Trier) to the French Canal de la Marne au Rhin. The Saarbrücker Burbach Rhein-Hafen and the Saarlouis Hafen handle bulk traffic for the Saar steel industry. The Dillinger Hütte Hafen on the Saar serves the Dillinger steelworks. The Cross-border Luxembourg-Findel Airport and the Metz-Nancy-Lorraine Airport in France serve Saarland from across the borders with substantial commuter traffic. The Saarbrücken-Sarreguemines cross-border bus network coordinated by the Saarländischer Verkehrsverbund saarVV provides cross-border tariff integration. The Saarbrücken ZOB long-distance bus station beside the Hauptbahnhof handles FlixBus and Sindbad services to Paris, Brussels, Luxembourg, Mainz, Mannheim and Frankfurt. The Saar-Radweg from Sarreguemines via Saarbrücken to Mettlach and onward to Trier on the Mosel is one of the top-ranked German cycling routes; the Velo Tour Sarre-Lor-Lux cross-border cycling network coordinates with French Lorraine and Luxembourg cycling networks. The Saarbrücker Stadtwerke operates the city bus network and the Saarbrücker Universität-Bus service. The historic Saarbrücker Pendelbahn (the funicular to the Saarbrücker Schwarzenbergturm) was decommissioned in 2017 but a new gondola is planned. The Saarbrücker Cycle-Share NextBike system has been operating since 2019. The Saarland VV-Tarif integrated regional tariff covers the entire state and includes cross-border tickets to French Moselle and Luxembourg.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Saarland economic detail: the SHS Stahl-Holding-Saar Group (jointly Saarstahl AG and Dillinger Hütte AG, owned by the Montan-Stiftung-Saar and the historic Saarstahl AG-Stiftung) is the leading German producer of long-products steel and heavy plate, with annual revenues of around 4 billion euros and around 11,000 workers across the integrated Völklingen, Burbach, Dillingen and Neunkirchen plants. The Saarstahl Group is undergoing the SALCOS green-steel transformation with the new hydrogen-DRI direct-reduction plant at Dillingen, supported by around 2 billion euros of federal and state subsidies. The Halberg Guss iron foundry at Brebach (Saarbrücken), founded 1756 and one of the oldest German iron foundries, employs around 1,000 workers. The Ford Saarlouis plant, the second-largest German Ford passenger-car plant after Cologne, employs around 4,500 workers but is undergoing a controversial wind-down (the Fiesta production ended June 2023, the Focus before that). The ZF Saarbrücken plant (the world''s largest single automotive-transmission plant) employs around 9,000 workers building the 8HP and 9HP automatic transmissions for BMW, Audi, Jaguar Land Rover, Volvo and other premium customers. The Robert Bosch Homburg plant builds automotive electronics. The Schaeffler Group Homburg precision-bearings plant. The Hager Werke (German electrical-distribution-board specialist with around 11,000 employees worldwide and headquarters in Blieskastel). The Saarbrücken Universität (Universität des Saarlandes) at Saarbrücken-Dudweiler has around 17,000 students and one of the strongest computer-science research clusters in continental Europe. The Saarland computer-science cluster includes the DFKI Deutsche Forschungszentrum für Künstliche Intelligenz (founded 1988 at Saarbrücken, one of the largest German AI-research institutes with around 1,500 researchers), the CISPA Helmholtz-Zentrum für Informationssicherheit (founded 2007 at Saarbrücken, one of the largest German cybersecurity research centres with around 600 researchers), the Max-Planck-Institut für Informatik (MPII Saarbrücken) and the Max-Planck-Institut für Softwaresysteme (MPI-SWS Saarbrücken-Kaiserslautern). The Globus SB-Warenhaus Holding GmbH & Co. KG at St. Wendel is the third-largest German hypermarket retailer with around 50 stores and revenues of 8 billion euros. The Karlsberg Brauerei AG at Homburg is one of the largest German privately-owned breweries with annual revenues of around 280 million euros. The Saarbrücker Zeitung (the leading Saarland daily newspaper) and the Saarländischer Rundfunk (the regional ARD public broadcaster) are major regional media employers. The Saarbrücker Bundeswehr Pioniertruppe at Saarlouis-Roden hosts the German Federal Army pioneer corps. The Saarland film industry (the Max-Ophüls-Preis Film Festival, the Saarländischer Filmkulturverein and the Saarländisches Filmbüro) supports a small but vital regional creative-economy. The Saarbrücker Christmas Market and the Saarland Open Air Theatre Festival round out the cultural-economy.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Saarland invasive-species detail: the Saarland Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark (the cross-border DE-RP-Luxembourg conservation area, designated 2015) is one of the largest contiguous wildcat habitats in central Europe, hosting around 100 European wildcats (Felis silvestris silvestris) plus substantial populations of native red and roe deer, fallow deer, mouflon and wild boar. The Saarland Wolfspark Werner Freund at Merzig hosts six wolf packs in 100 hectares of forest enclosures representing the European, Polish, Arctic, Mongolian, Iberian and Timber wolf subspecies. The Saarland Cross-Border Eltz Trail and the Sarre-Lor-Lux Conservation Corridor coordinate French Lorraine, Luxembourg and Saarland conservation efforts. The Saarland coal-mining heritage Bergehalden (slag heaps from former coal mining) at Velsen, Reden, Göttelborn and Itzenplitz host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities including the South African Senecio inaequidens (the South African ragwort, particularly conspicuous on the disturbed sandy soils of the former coal-mining areas), the tree of heaven (Ailanthus altissima, particularly conspicuous in the post-industrial Saarbrücken-Burbach brownfields), the Spanish broom (Spartium junceum), the goldenrod (Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea, dominant on the historic Bergehalden), the black locust (Robinia pseudoacacia, extensively planted on the Saarland mining areas since the 1920s), and the Indian balsam (Impatiens parviflora). The Saarbrücker Universität ecologists at the Faculty of Natural Sciences and Technology study post-industrial vegetation succession in the Saarland mining-heritage areas. The Saarland Asian Hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax) was first recorded in 2016, one of the earliest German confirmed records, having advanced from French Lorraine. The Saarland Imkerbund coordinates Asian-hornet nest-removal teams. The Saarland river otter (Lutra lutra) recovery in the Blies and the Saar is one of the most successful European otter conservation programmes. The Saarland European mink (Mustela lutreola) reintroduction is being planned for the late 2020s in cooperation with French Lorraine populations. The Saarland Brown Hare (Lepus europaeus) and Red Deer (Cervus elaphus) recoveries have been supported by the Naturschutzbund Saarland. The Saarland Naturschutzbund Saarland (NABU Saar) and the Saarländischer Forstwirtschaftsverband coordinate joint monitoring with the Bundesamt für Naturschutz at Bonn under EU Regulation 1143/2014.'
WHERE region_name = 'Saarland';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Thüringen transport detail: Erfurt Hauptbahnhof has 10 platforms, around 80,000 passengers per day, and was redeveloped 2008-2017 for the new VDE 8 high-speed network. The Erfurt-Berlin ICE travel time is 1 hour 45 minutes; the Erfurt-Munich travel time is 2 hours 30 minutes; the Erfurt-Frankfurt travel time is 2 hours 15 minutes; the Erfurt-Dresden travel time is 2 hours. The Halle-Erfurt-Nuremberg VDE 8 corridor opened in stages between 2015 and 2017 and included the Erfurt-Halle Tunnel of 8.3 kilometres, the Bibratunnel of 6.5 kilometres, the Finnetunnel of 6.9 kilometres, and the historic Eichelberg Tunnel of 6.8 kilometres. The Jena West Bahnhof on the VDE 8 corridor and Weimar Bahnhof on the historic Berlin-Frankfurt corridor are the other major rail nodes. The Gera Hauptbahnhof, the Eisenach Hauptbahnhof and the Gotha Hauptbahnhof complete the major Thuringian rail nodes. The Erfurter Stadtbahn (EVAG Erfurter Verkehrs-AG) operates six lines totalling 41 kilometres; the historic Erfurt tram-and-trolleybus system dates from 1881. The Jena Stadtbahn (Jenaer Nahverkehr GmbH) operates five lines totalling 24 kilometres. The Gera Stadtbahn has three lines. The Gotha Stadtbahn includes the famous Thüringerwaldbahn from Gotha to Tabarz (the longest German overland tramway at 22 kilometres, operating since 1929 through the Thuringian Forest). The Nordhausen tram (with the famous combined tram-train operation to Ilfeld in the Harz). The Harzer Schmalspurbahnen narrow-gauge steam railway operating from Wernigerode (Sachsen-Anhalt) to Nordhausen via the Brocken summit is one of the largest narrow-gauge steam-railway networks in Europe. The Thuringian Verkehrsverbund Mittelthüringen (VMT) coordinates Erfurt-Weimar-Jena-Gotha regional tariff. The Thuringian Autobahn network includes the A4 (Eisenach-Erfurt-Weimar-Gera, the historic East-West Hermsdorfer Kreuz junction connecting to the A9 Munich-Berlin), the A9 (Munich-Nuremberg-Leipzig-Berlin), the A38 (Halle-Göttingen, the Eichsfeld autobahn), the A71 (Sangerhausen-Erfurt-Schweinfurt with the Rennsteig tunnel at 7,916 metres, the longest road tunnel in Germany), the A73 (Suhl-Bamberg-Nuremberg, the historic Spange Eichsfeld), and the A4 Erfurter Kreuz. The Thuringia Hauptdienstgebäude at Erfurt hosts the state government. The Thuringia cycling routes include the Saale-Radweg, the Werra-Radweg, the Werratal-Radweg, the Saale-Unstrut-Radweg, the Thüringer Städtekette (linking Eisenach, Gotha, Erfurt, Weimar, Jena, Gera and Altenburg), and the Rennsteig-Radweg (parallel to the famous Rennsteig hiking trail of 169 kilometres). The Erfurt-Weimar Airport (ERF, EDDE) handles around 200,000 passengers per year. The Leipzig/Halle Airport (LEJ) and Frankfurt Airport (FRA) serve eastern and western Thuringia respectively for long-distance flights. The Thuringian state has subsidised the new Mobilitäts-Hubs around the regional Bahnhöfe, and the on-demand bus service Thüringer Verkehrslinie operates in rural Eichsfeld and Saale-Holzland-Kreis.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Thüringen economic detail: Jenoptik AG (Jena-headquartered) is the most internationally successful Thuringian listed company, with annual revenues of around 1 billion euros, 4,000 employees and a global presence in measurement systems, semiconductor lithography lasers, automotive diagnostics, medical lasers and high-end optics. Jenoptik was founded 1991 from the Carl Zeiss Jena East-German optics combine; the post-1990 separation of Zeiss Jena from Zeiss Oberkochen (which had relocated to Baden-Württemberg in 1947) was one of the most successful German post-reunification industrial transformations. The Jena optics heritage continues with Carl Zeiss Jena GmbH (a Thuringian subsidiary of the Carl-Zeiss-Stiftung at Oberkochen-Heidenheim in Baden-Württemberg, producing microscopy and metrology systems at the historic Jena Carl-Zeiss-Promenade campus), Carl Zeiss SMT GmbH (the Jena branch producing semiconductor lithography lenses for ASML EUV machines), and Schott Jenaer Glas GmbH (a Thuringian subsidiary of the Mainz-headquartered Schott AG, producing borosilicate glass and laboratory glassware at the historic 1884 Schott Jenaer Glaswerk). Together the Jena optics-photonics-glass cluster employs around 25,000 workers and supports one of the most photonics-research-dense small cities in Europe with the Max-Planck-Institut für Biogeochemie, the Max-Planck-Institut für chemische Ökologie, the Leibniz-Institut für Naturstoff-Forschung und Infektionsbiologie Hans-Knöll-Institut, the Leibniz-Institut für Photonische Technologien (Leibniz IPHT), the Fraunhofer-Institut für Angewandte Optik und Feinmechanik (IOF Jena), and the Helmholtz-Institut Jena. Bauerfeind AG at Zeulenroda (founded 1929 by Bruno Bauerfeind, family-owned) is one of the leading European orthopaedic technology producers, with annual revenues of around 350 million euros and 2,500 employees worldwide. Opel Eisenach GmbH (now part of Stellantis) at the historic AWE Automobilwerk Eisenach site produces the Opel Corsa and the Opel Grandland, employing around 1,500 workers. The Suhl gun-making tradition (dating from the 15th century) includes the historic Sauer & Sohn (founded 1751, now Eckernförde in Schleswig-Holstein), Merkel Jagd- und Sportwaffen at Suhl (the leading German double-rifle producer), Heym Sportwaffen, and Krieghoff (founded at Suhl 1886, today Ulm in Baden-Württemberg). The Köstritzer Schwarzbier brewery at Bad Köstritz (owned by Bitburger Braugruppe) is the world''s leading Schwarzbier brand. The Thuringian Bratwurst PGI industry includes hundreds of small butchers; the Thüringer Kloßmuseum at Heichelheim, the Thüringer Klöße tradition, and the Pulsnitzer Pfefferkuchen (technically Saxony) round out the food sector. Banking includes the Sparkasse Mittelthüringen, the Sparkasse Jena-Saale-Holzland, the Volksbank Erfurt and the Thüringer Aufbaubank (the state development bank). The Erfurter Christkindlmarkt is the third-largest German Christmas market.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Thüringen invasive-species detail: the Hainich National Park (Germany''s only UNESCO-listed beech-forest national park, designated 2011 as part of the Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe World Heritage Site, alongside the Müritz, Jasmund, Kellerwald and Grumsin sub-sites) supports the largest German wildcat population, with around 500 individual Felis silvestris silvestris confirmed by camera-trap monitoring. The Hainich and Werra wildcat corridor between the Hainich and the Harz is one of the most important German wildcat-conservation areas. The Thuringian Forest Schmidtgehege wolf-sanctuary near Friedrichroda hosts captive wolves. The Thuringia wolf population (around 3-5 established packs in 2024) is concentrated in the Thuringian Forest, the Eichsfeld and the historic Ohrdruf training ground. The Thuringia state forestry is leading the planning of a lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction for the late 2020s in cooperation with the Harz Sachsen-Anhalt lynx reintroduction. The Thuringian Forest National Park hosts substantial native-species conservation programmes including European wildcat, European bison breeding, lynx reintroduction and the Sächsisch-Thüringische Hochmoore restoration. The historic Thuringia Hainich beech forest with its UNESCO designation hosts the unique Thuringia wildcat-corridor. The Thuringia Erfurt-Egapark and the Erfurt Cyriaksburg garden-tower observation deck host distinctive urban-invasive vegetation; the Erfurter Citadelle Petersberg hosts historic boxwood gardens devastated by the Cydalima perspectalis box tree moth since 2010. The Thuringia Saale and Unstrut viticulture regions (around 700 hectares of the historic Saale-Unstrut wine region in Thuringia) have experienced the recent Drosophila suzukii spotted-wing fruit fly invasion and the brown marmorated stink bug Halyomorpha halys arrivals. The Thuringian Asian Hornet (Vespa velutina nigrithorax) was first recorded in 2023; the Imkerverband Thüringen coordinates nest-removal with the TLUBN. The Thuringian Schiefergebirge (the slate mountains of southern Thuringia) host distinctive invasive flora communities including the Senecio inaequidens (South African ragwort), the Reynoutria japonica (Japanese knotweed, particularly conspicuous along the Saale and the Ilm), the Heracleum mantegazzianum (giant hogweed, with phototoxic-sap warnings issued by the Thuringian state forestry), the Impatiens glandulifera (Himalayan balsam, widespread on Thuringian stream banks), the Robinia pseudoacacia (black locust, particularly conspicuous on the historic southern Thuringia Bergehalden), the Ambrosia artemisiifolia (ragweed), and the Solidago canadensis and S. gigantea (goldenrod). The Thuringian Wartburg-Eisenach Ranger Programme coordinates cross-border conservation with Hessen. The Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut and the Robert-Koch-Institut at Berlin have Thuringian collaboration on zoonotic-disease surveillance.'
WHERE region_name = 'Thüringen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Sachsen transport detail: the Verkehrsprojekt Deutsche Einheit Nr. 8 (VDE 8) high-speed line Berlin-Halle-Erfurt-Nuremberg-Munich, completed December 2017 at a cost of around 10 billion euros, runs through Leipzig with the Großkorbetha junction. The Leipzig City Tunnel (opened 2013, cost around 1 billion euros) allows all Leipzig S-Bahn lines (S1-S5, S6, S46, S47) to run through-services from the historic terminal Hauptbahnhof to the southern Leipzig districts. The Leipzig Hauptbahnhof (opened 1915, the largest railway terminal in the world by surface area at 84,000 square metres with 23 platforms across two parallel halls) is one of the architectural masterpieces of German rail history. The Leipzig Hauptbahnhof Promenaden shopping mall in the historic main hall has won multiple architectural awards. The Dresden Hauptbahnhof with the iconic tent-shaped roof handles the Berlin-Prague Eurocity corridor, the Berlin-Dresden Dresdner Bahn (currently being upgraded to allow non-stop ICE running), and the Cologne-Dresden via Erfurt long-distance corridor. The Chemnitz Hauptbahnhof, the Görlitz Hauptbahnhof (the easternmost German major rail node), the Zwickau Hauptbahnhof, the Plauen Hauptbahnhof and Riesa complete the major Saxon rail nodes. The Sächsische Dampfschiffahrt GmbH at Dresden operates the largest fleet of working paddle steamers in the world — nine historic paddle wheelers all built between 1879 and 1929 and still operating regularly between Dresden, Meissen, Pillnitz and Bad Schandau. The Elbe-Radweg from Schöna along the Elbe is one of Germany''s top-ranked long-distance cycle routes; the Sächsisches Elbland section is the most-cycled. The Saxon tram networks include the Leipzig tram (the second-longest German tram network at 145 kilometres with 13 lines), the Dresden tram (the third-longest at 134 kilometres with 12 lines), the Chemnitz Stadtbahn (with tram-train technology), the Plauen tram, the Görlitz tram, the Zwickau tram, the historic Lockwitztalbahn (the oldest German overland tramway, operating since 1906), and the historic Kirnitzschtalbahn (the unique forest tram in the Sächsische Schweiz, operating since 1898). The Dresdner Bergschwebebahn (the suspended monorail of 1901, the world''s second-oldest after Wuppertal) and the Standseilbahn Dresden (the Dresden funicular) are tourist attractions. The Saxon Erzgebirgsbahn, the Sächsisch-Böhmische Eisenbahngesellschaft and the Vogtlandbahn (Länderbahn) operate cross-border services to Bohemia. The Sächsische Schweiz Bastei-Aufzug funicular (the historic Bastei lift) operated until 1932 and is now a hiking trail. The Bad Schandau-Personenaufzug (the historic 1904 Schandauer Aufzug elevator-tower at Bad Schandau, ascending 50 metres up the sandstone cliff) is one of the iconic Saxon Switzerland transport curiosities. The Sächsisch-Böhmische Eisenbahn Bahnhof Bad Schandau handles the cross-border Eurocity services to Dresden and Prague. The Saxon S-Bahn Dresden (operated by Mitteldeutsche Regiobahn) covers the Dresden-Pirna-Sebnitz-Decin (Czech) corridor.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Sachsen economic detail: Silicon Saxony is the largest microelectronics cluster in Europe with around 70,000 workers across the Dresden semiconductor ecosystem. Infineon Technologies Dresden GmbH at Klotzsche produces power semiconductors and security ICs; the new Infineon SmartPowerFab (opened 2024, the largest investment in European semiconductor manufacturing history at around 5 billion euros) is one of the largest single industrial projects in Saxon history. Globalfoundries Dresden Module One (the historic AMD Fab30, then AMD Fab36, then Globalfoundries Fab1) produces 22-nm and 28-nm logic chips. Robert Bosch Semiconductor Manufacturing Dresden (opened 2021, the largest single investment in Bosch corporate history at around 1 billion euros) produces 300-mm wafers for automotive electronics. The new ESMC joint venture between TSMC of Taiwan, Bosch, Infineon and NXP (announced 2023) will build a 300-mm 28-nm Dresden wafer fab from 2024 — the largest Taiwanese investment in Europe at around 10 billion euros. X-FAB Silicon Foundries SE, Siltronic AG, Jenoptik AG (Thuringian but cross-border Saxony operations) and the Fraunhofer Photonik AG complete the cluster. The Volkswagen Sachsen Zwickau-Mosel plant (the largest European electric-vehicle plant) builds the VW ID.3, ID.4, ID.5, ID.7, the Audi Q4 e-tron and the Cupra Born — all on the MEB modular electric platform; the plant employs around 11,000 workers. The Volkswagen Chemnitz engine plant and the Volkswagen Dresden Gläserne Manufaktur (the Transparent Factory) employ another 5,000 workers. Porsche Leipzig (around 4,500 workers building the Macan, Macan Electric, Cayenne and Panamera; with the iconic Porsche Experience Center Leipzig private test track) is the second-largest Porsche plant after Zuffenhausen. BMW Leipzig (around 5,500 workers building the BMW 1 Series, 2 Series, X1, iX1, i4, and the Mini Countryman; with the iconic Zaha Hadid central building of 2005) is one of the most architecturally distinguished automotive plants in Europe. The DHL European Hub at Leipzig/Halle Airport (since 2008 after relocating from Brussels) is the largest single cargo facility in Saxony with around 6,000 employees, 70 nightly wide-body cargo flights and 2.5 million tonnes of cargo per year. The Saxon Strukturwandel programme distributes around 14 billion euros of federal Strukturstärkungsgesetz funds to Saxony through 2038, supporting the Lausitz lignite-exit, the new German Centre for Astrophysics at Görlitz, the Lausitz Science Park at Cottbus (jointly Brandenburg), and the federal hydrogen-pilot programmes. Meissen Porzellan-Manufaktur (founded 1710 by Johann Friedrich Böttger) is the historic first European hard-paste porcelain manufactory. The Plauener Spitze lace cooperative is the world centre of machine-made lace since 1881. The Wernesgrüner, Radeberger and Sternburg breweries together produce around 1 million hectolitres per year. The Sachsenmilch AG at Leppersdorf is one of the largest German dairies. The Stadler Rail Pankow plant builds the Velaro D ICE.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Sachsen invasive-species detail: the Saxon LUPUS Wolf Office at the Görlitz Senckenberg Naturhistorische Sammlungen leads German wolf research. The 2000 first-pack Muskauer Heide milestone (the first confirmed German wolf reproduction since 1850) is commemorated annually. The Saxon wolf population in 2024 has around 30 established territorial packs (the highest of any German Land), with several hundred individuals across the Lausitz, the Sächsische Schweiz, the Erzgebirge foothills and the Vogtland. The Saxon African Swine Fever situation has been the most-affected of any German Land, with thousands of confirmed wild-boar cases in the Oberlausitz, the Görlitz district and the Bautzen area since September 2020; intensive containment fencing along the Polish border and continuous culling of wild boar have largely contained the outbreak by 2023. The Saxon Erzgebirge mountain pine plantations contain large areas of introduced Pinus mugo subspecies. The Saxon Lausitz Bergehalden (slag heaps from former lignite mining) at Spreetal, Welzow, Cottbus and Hoyerswerda host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation. The Lausitz Lake District (Lausitzer Seenland, the flooded former open-cast lignite pits being converted into lakes — the Cottbuser Ostsee, the Senftenberger See, the Geierswalder See, the Bergheider See, the Bärwalder See — together one of the largest planned man-made lake landscapes in Europe) supports emerging novel-ecosystem communities being studied by the BTU Cottbus-Senftenberg ecologists. The Saxon Lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction in the Oberlausitz Forest is being planned for the late 2020s in cooperation with the Czech Šumava Park and the Polish Bohemian Forest populations. The Saxon Senckenberg Naturhistorische Sammlungen Görlitz museum (one of the leading German natural-history institutions) hosts important collections of native and invasive species. The Saxon Bautzen and Görlitz Sorbian ethnographic museums host distinctive cultural heritage. The Saxon Sächsische Schweiz National Park (founded 1990) hosts the famous Bastei rock formation and the Königstein Fortress (one of the largest hilltop fortresses in Europe). The Saxon Erzgebirge UNESCO Mining Region preserves the historic mining heritage and supports the post-industrial wildlife recovery. The Saxon Naturschutzbund Sachsen (NABU Sachsen) coordinates citizen-science monitoring of invasive species. The Helmholtz-Zentrum Dresden-Rossendorf, the Helmholtz-Zentrum für Umweltforschung Leipzig (UFZ), the Max-Planck-Institut für Evolutionäre Anthropologie at Leipzig (founded 1997, the home of Svante Pääbo''s Neanderthal genome research awarded the 2022 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine), and the Senckenberg Naturhistorische Sammlungen Dresden complete the Saxon research backbone.'
WHERE region_name = 'Sachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Schleswig-Holstein transport detail: the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link (the immersed road-and-rail tunnel between Puttgarden and Rødby, under construction since 2020 by Femern A/S) is one of the most ambitious European infrastructure projects of the 21st century; the tunnel will be 18 kilometres long, will carry both a four-lane motorway and a twin-track electrified railway, and is due to open in 2029. The Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link will allow direct rail services Hamburg-Lübeck-Copenhagen in 2 hours 30 minutes (down from 5 hours via the current ferry) and will dramatically reduce the Hamburg-Stockholm rail journey to around 7 hours. The Hindenburgdamm (the rail-only causeway built 1923-1927 across the Wadden Sea, 11 kilometres long, the only German rail-only causeway to an offshore island) carries the Sylt Shuttle car trains and the regional rail services. The Kiel Canal (Nord-Ostsee-Kanal, NOK), the 98-kilometre artificial waterway between Kiel-Holtenau and Brunsbüttel, is the most-trafficked artificial waterway in the world by ship transits with around 28,000-32,000 ships per year. The historic Kiel Canal locks at Holtenau (with the famous viewing platform) and Brunsbüttel are among the largest in Europe. The canal is currently being deepened to handle 18-metre-draft container ships. The Schleswig-Holstein A23 (Hamburg-Heide), A1 (Hamburg-Heiligenhafen via Lübeck), A7 (the longest motorway in Europe from Memmingen to Flensburg), A20 (the Baltic Sea Autobahn), A21 (Schleswig-Holstein north-south), A24 (Hamburg-Berlin), A25 (Hamburg-Geesthacht), and the Bundesstraße B5 (the main road along the North Sea coast) form the Autobahn network. The S-Bahn S4 line under construction from Hamburg Hauptbahnhof to Bad Oldesloe will open from 2027 onwards using battery-electric multiple units. The Hamburg S-Bahn S1 to Kaltenkirchen and the S21 to Aumühle already extend into Schleswig-Holstein. The Kieler Förde ferries (Kieler Schiffahrtsgesellschaft) provide cross-city water transport. The Lübeck Stadtbahn (the first electric tram in Germany in 1881) closed in 1959. The Schleswig-Holstein bus network operated by Autokraft and the historic Lübecker Verkehrsbetriebe. The Lübeck-Travemünde TT-Line and Finnlines ferries to Trelleborg-Sweden, Liepāja-Latvia, Klaipėda-Lithuania, Helsinki-Finland and Helsinki-Vuosaari; the Kiel-Oslo Color Line ferry; the Kiel-Klaipeda DFDS ferry; and the Kiel-Sassnitz Mukran (Mecklenburg-Vorpommern) round out the Baltic ferry network. The Ostseeküsten-Radweg (EuroVelo 10), the Nordseeküsten-Radweg (EuroVelo 12), the Mönchsweg pilgrim route, the Berlin-Kopenhagen Cycle Route and the Wadden Sea Cycle Route make Schleswig-Holstein one of Germany''s top-ranked cycling destinations. The historic Sylt-Tour cycling-and-public-transport package and the Sylt-Inselrad e-bike-hire system support tourism mobility. The Schleswig-Holstein NAH.SH integrated regional tariff covers the entire state.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Schleswig-Holstein economic detail: Thyssenkrupp Marine Systems (TKMS) AG at Kiel is the largest German naval shipyard with around 8,000 workers building the Type 212A submarines (the world''s first fully diesel-electric submarines with air-independent propulsion using PEM fuel cells, the world''s quietest submarines), the Type 212CD (the next-generation submarines for Germany and Norway), the Type 209 export submarines, the Dolphin-class submarines for Israel, the F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates and the F126 frigates. TKMS Kiel is the leading European conventional-submarine builder. The historic Howaldtswerke-Deutsche Werft (HDW) at Kiel was founded 1838 and is one of the oldest German shipyards. Niederegger Marzipan at Lübeck (founded 1806 by Johann Georg Niederegger) is the most-famous German marzipan producer with EU PGI protection since 1996; the flagship Café Niederegger on the Breite Straße opposite the Rathaus is one of the most-visited Lübeck destinations. Drägerwerk AG & Co. KGaA at Lübeck (founded 1889) is the world''s leading manufacturer of mining-rescue and fire-rescue breathing apparatus, anaesthesia ventilators, intensive-care ventilators and gas-detection equipment, with annual revenues of around 3 billion euros and around 14,000 employees worldwide (9,000 at Lübeck). During the COVID-19 pandemic Dräger was one of the world''s primary suppliers of intensive-care ventilators, scaling production from 10,000 to 30,000 ventilators per year. The Schleswig-Holstein wind-energy and offshore-wind cluster is one of the strongest in Germany, with the state having the highest onshore-wind installed capacity per capita in Germany (around 8 GW). The Brunsbüttel oil-and-chemicals industrial complex (the historic Total Brunsbüttel refinery, the Bayer Brunsbüttel chemicals plant, the historic Westkalkstein cement) is being transformed into a green-hydrogen hub. The Sylter Royal oyster (the Pacific oyster Magallana gigas, cultivated since 1986 on the List Wadden Sea bed by Dittmeyer''s Austerncompagnie) is the only commercial German oyster fishery. The Schleswig-Holstein dairy industry produces around 25 per cent of all German milk; the Nordmilch (now Arla Foods amba subsidiary), the historic Schwarmstedter Molkerei, the Bünting Tee Company (East Friesland), the Hela Curry-Sauce GmbH at Ahrensburg (the leading German ketchup-and-curry-sauce brand), the Coca-Cola Lübeck production plant, the Krones AG (Neutraubling in Bavaria) operations and the historic Hamburg-Altona Holsten Brewery complete the food sector. The Schleswig-Holstein tourism sector hosts around 26 million overnight stays per year. The Flensburger Pilsener at Flensburg (the famous Flensburg Pilsener since 1888 with the iconic ceramic snap-top Plopp closure) is one of the best-loved German beer brands. The Flensburger Pott Rum (since 1755), the Flensburger Asmussen Rum (since 1873) and the historic Hansen Rum tradition continue the Flensburg rum heritage. The Schleswig-Holstein Federal Bundeswehr Navy base at Kiel-Wik and Eckernförde-Heeresmarine support the Federal Navy''s Baltic operations. The Federal Police Bundespolizei See has its Kiel base. The Schleswig-Holstein state government and the Kieler Hochschule and Lübecker Universität support the regional employment.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Schleswig-Holstein invasive-species detail: the Schleswig-Holstein Wadden Sea National Park (designated 1985, UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2009) is the largest unbroken system of intertidal sand and mud flats in the world (4,400 square kilometres along the SH coast). The Schleswig-Holstein Pacific Oyster invasion (the Magallana gigas Pazifische Auster, introduced 1986 at Sylt-List) has been the most-studied marine invasion in northern Europe; the Sylter Royal oyster farm is the only commercial German oyster fishery and one of the most profitable Wadden Sea aquaculture operations. The Schleswig-Holstein Asian shore crabs (Hemigrapsus sanguineus and H. takanoi), the American razor clam (Ensis directus), the Manila clam (Ruditapes philippinarum), the Japanese seaweed Sargassum muticum, the Atlantic comb jelly (Mnemiopsis leidyi), the New Zealand sea squirt (Styela clava), the Caspian-Pontic gobies and the Chinese mitten crab (Eriocheir sinensis, regularly trapped in the Eider, the Trave and the Elbe-Lübeck-Kanal) have all established. The Schleswig-Holstein Helgoland Biologische Anstalt of the Alfred Wegener Institute maintains the world''s longest continuous marine-monitoring programme since 1873. The Helgoland is the only true deep-sea German island. The Schleswig-Holstein barnacle goose (Branta leucopsis) and the Egyptian goose (Alopochen aegyptiaca) have established feral resident breeding populations on the SH Wadden Sea coast and at the historic Kieler Förde, the Eckernförder Bucht, the Lübecker Bucht and the Plöner See. The Schleswig-Holstein cordgrass Spartina anglica has invaded the Wadden Sea salt marshes substantially since the 1930s. The Schleswig-Holstein Sea-Buckthorn (Hippophae rhamnoides), although native, has been planted extensively for dune stabilisation across the North Sea coast. The Schleswig-Holstein wolf population (occasional records, no established pack as of 2024) is monitored by the LLUR Wolves Office. The Schleswig-Holstein European pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroduction in the Aukrug Forst and the Sachsenwald is a major conservation success. The Schleswig-Holstein North Sea grey seal (Halichoerus grypus) and harbour seal (Phoca vitulina) populations have rebounded dramatically since the 1988 phocine distemper virus die-off, with around 13,000 grey seals on Helgoland and the Sylt Wadden Sea today. The Schleswig-Holstein raccoon population is concentrated in the Sachsenwald (the historic Bismarck estate forest, now a major Holstein hunting reserve) and the Naturpark Lauenburgische Seen. The Schleswig-Holstein Asian Hornet records since 2021 are concentrated along the Hamburg commuter belt and the lower Elbe. The Schleswig-Holstein Naturschutzbund (NABU SH) and the BUND Schleswig-Holstein coordinate citizen-science monitoring; the LLUR Flintbek environmental authority and the FTZ Westküste at Büsum support marine-invasion research.'
WHERE region_name = 'Schleswig-Holstein';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Rheinland-Pfalz transport detail: the Cologne-Frankfurt Schnellfahrstrecke (NBS Köln-Rhein/Main) opened 2002 is the steepest high-speed railway in Europe with 40 ‰ grades on the Westerwald; the line runs through Limburg an der Lahn (with the Limburg Süd ICE-Stop) and Montabaur (with the Montabaur ICE-Stop, an ICE station on a previously rural area, controversial at opening but now a regular ICE stop serving the Westerwald region). The Cologne-Frankfurt NBS includes the Limburger Westerwaldtunnel of 4.5 kilometres, the Idsteinertal tunnel and the Schulwaldtunnel. The Cologne-Brussels Eurostar (formerly Thalys) service passes through Aachen (NRW). The Mainz Hauptbahnhof handles half-hourly S-Bahn services to Frankfurt and Wiesbaden, plus ICE services on the Cologne-Mannheim corridor and the Frankfurt-Saarbrücken-Paris corridor with TGV inOui services to Paris-Est. The Koblenz Hauptbahnhof handles the Romantic-Rhine-Valley services and the Mosel-line to Trier. The Trier Hauptbahnhof handles cross-border services to Luxembourg-Stadt. The Ludwigshafen Hauptbahnhof is served by the Mannheim S-Bahn. The Kaiserslautern Hauptbahnhof handles the Mannheim-Saarbrücken corridor with TGV inOui services. The Rheinland-Pfalz cycling network is one of the most developed in Germany. The EuroVelo 15 Rhine Cycle Route from Andermatt to Rotterdam through Mainz, Bingen, Koblenz. The Mosel-Radweg from Metz via Trier to Koblenz is consistently ranked among Germany''s top three long-distance cycling routes; the famous Mosel-Schiefer terraces and the historic Mosel wine villages of Bernkastel-Kues, Traben-Trarbach, Cochem, Beilstein, Ediger-Eller, Zell and Treis-Karden make the Mosel-Radweg unique. The Saar-Radweg, the Lahntalradweg, the Vulkaneifel-Radweg, the Nahe-Radweg, the Pfälzer Weinstraße cycling routes and the cross-border EuroVelo 6 (Atlantic-Black Sea via the Mosel) complete the network. The Rhine and Mosel inland waterways carry substantial commercial traffic. The Ludwigshafen Rhine port serves BASF and the chemical industry, handling around 8 million tonnes per year. The Mainz inland port handles bulk traffic. The Koblenz, Trier, Speyer and Worms inland ports complete the system. The Köln-Düsseldorfer Rheinschiffahrt (KD) fleet, the Bingen-Rüdesheim ferries, Viking River Cruises, AmaWaterways and the historic Goethe paddle steamer (now museum) provide the classic Rhine tourism circulation. The Romantic Rhine UNESCO Middle-Rhine Valley between Bingen and Koblenz is the most-cycled and most-cruised section. The Hochmoselbrücke at Zeltingen-Rachtig (opened 2019, the second-highest bridge in Germany at 158 metres above the Mosel) is the most controversial recent German road project. The historic Pfälzerwald-Radweg through the Palatinate Forest connects the German Wine Route (Deutsche Weinstraße) with the cross-border French Vosges du Nord. The Frankfurt-Hahn Airport handles around 1.5 million passengers per year on Ryanair flights plus around 100,000 tonnes of cargo. The Saarbrücken Airport across the Saarland border and the Luxembourg-Findel Airport serve the cross-border region. The Bundeswehr Ramstein Air Base near Landstuhl-Kaiserslautern is the largest US Air Force base in the world outside the United States with around 9,000 US military personnel. The Spangdahlem Air Base near Bitburg hosts the US Air Force 52nd Fighter Wing.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Rheinland-Pfalz economic detail: BASF SE at Ludwigshafen am Rhein is the world''s largest chemical company by revenue, with the Stammwerk Ludwigshafen covering 10 square kilometres along seven kilometres of Rhine frontage. The Ludwigshafen Stammwerk is the largest contiguous chemical-industrial complex in the world with around 40,000 employees, around 200 production plants integrated through the BASF Verbund concept, 2,850 kilometres of pipelines, and the largest steam-cracker in Europe (BASF Steamcracker II). BASF was founded in 1865 by Friedrich Engelhorn as the Badische Anilin- und Sodafabrik. BASF''s 2023 annual revenue was around 87 billion euros with 110,000 employees worldwide. The Ludwigshafen site is the largest single industrial employer in Rheinland-Pfalz, accounting for around 20 per cent of state GDP. BASF holds the historic patents for synthetic indigo (the Heumann process 1897), the Haber-Bosch ammonia-synthesis process (1913, the foundation of modern fertilisers and explosives that enabled the global agricultural transformation of the 20th century), the Fischer-Tropsch process (1925, synthetic fuels) and the Schmidt synthesis (synthetic methanol). Boehringer Ingelheim International GmbH at Ingelheim am Rhein is the world''s largest privately-held pharmaceutical company (founded 1885 by Albert Boehringer), continuously controlled by the Boehringer-von Baumbach family for five generations. Boehringer has annual revenues of around 24 billion euros and 53,000 employees worldwide (8,000 at Ingelheim). Boehringer''s human-pharmaceutical pipeline includes the diabetes-drug Jardiance/Empagliflozin (the world''s leading sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 inhibitor, jointly developed with Eli Lilly), the anticoagulant Pradaxa/Dabigatran, the COPD inhaler Spiriva/Tiotropium, the lung-fibrosis drug Ofev/Nintedanib, and the veterinary BIVI Boehringer Ingelheim Vetmedica division (Heartworm preventatives Frontline and NexGard, the largest veterinary pharmaceutical business in the world after Zoetis). Schott AG at Mainz produces Ceran ceramic cooktops, Schott Robax fireplace glass, Schott Pyran fire-resistant glass, Schott Borofloat borosilicate glass and the Schott NEXTERION laboratory consumables; the Schott Pharma subsidiary at Mainz is the world''s leading producer of pharmaceutical vials, syringes and ampoules. Daimler Truck AG operates the Wörth am Rhein plant, the largest truck assembly plant in Europe with around 10,000 workers producing the Mercedes-Benz Actros, Antos, Arocs, Atego and Econic models. The Ramstein Air Base US military presence (around 9,000 service members), the Landstuhl Regional Medical Center (the largest US military hospital outside the United States), the Spangdahlem Air Base 52nd Fighter Wing, the total US military presence in Rheinland-Pfalz exceeds 50,000 service members, dependents and contractors. The Bundeswehr at Koblenz hosts the Federal Office for Defence Equipment, Information Technology and In-Service Support (BAAINBw) with around 11,000 staff — the largest federal agency in Rheinland-Pfalz. The Rheinland-Pfalz wine industry produces around 6 million hectolitres per year (two-thirds of total German wine). The Hornbach Holding (DIY home-improvement) at Bornheim, the Globus SB-Warenhaus at St. Wendel (Saarland), the Karlsberg Brauerei at Homburg (Saarland) and the Bitburger Brauerei at Bitburg in the Rheinland-Pfalz Eifel are major brewing operations. The Pirelli Reifen Kaiserslautern tyre plant and the Eichbaum Mannheim brewery (Baden-Württemberg) round out the cluster.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Rheinland-Pfalz invasive-species detail: the LfU Rheinland-Pfalz at Mainz coordinates the state Neozoa register. The RP wine-region pest landscape is heavily affected by Drosophila suzukii (the spotted-wing fruit fly that damages grapes, cherries and stone fruit), Halyomorpha halys (the brown marmorated stink bug, a major Pfalz and Rheinhessen wine pest), the European grapevine moth Lobesia botrana, and the Spanish moss Tillandsia usneoides which has been recorded in scattered RP vineyards as an ornamental escape. The RP wildcat (Felis silvestris silvestris) population in the Pfälzerwald, the Eifel and the Hunsrück is one of the largest in Germany; the Westpfalz wildcat reintroductions have been a major conservation success. The RP wolf population (around 5 confirmed packs in 2024) is concentrated in the Westerwald and the Eifel. The RP Asian-Hornet front advanced from the 2014 Müllheim (Baden-Württemberg) origin into Pfalz and Rheinhessen by 2017 and now covers the whole state. The Pfälzerwald-Biosphärenreservat (a UNESCO MAB Reserve, the largest contiguous forest in Germany at 1,800 square kilometres) hosts substantial wildlife including fallow deer, mouflon, wild boar and roe deer. The Vulkaneifel Geopark hosts distinctive maar-lake ecology including some introduced fish species. The Naturpark Südeifel and the Naturpark Hunsrück-Hochwald support cross-border conservation cooperation with Luxembourg, France and Belgium. The Hunsrück-Hochwald-Nationalpark (shared with Saarland, designated 2015) hosts a UNESCO-listed Soundscape. The Rheinland-Pfalz Bundeswehr training grounds at Baumholder and Daun preserve large grassland areas with rare flora and fauna threatened by neighbouring agricultural intensification. The Mosel and Rhine river-traffic continues to introduce ballast-water species; the Rhine round-goby and Caspian-Pontic goby invasions have heavily affected the RP river ecology. The Mosel-Schiefer terraces and historic vineyards host a distinctive flora with both native rare species and introduced ornamentals that have escaped from historic Mosel garden estates. The Westerwald and Hunsrück forests host the recovering populations of the European wildcat, the lynx (occasional records and a planned reintroduction), the European otter (Lutra lutra, native and recovering), the European mink (Mustela lutreola, currently absent but planned for future reintroduction) and the historic native red deer (Cervus elaphus) and roe deer (Capreolus capreolus). The RP Imkerverband coordinates Asian-hornet nest-removal with the LfU. The RP Pflanzenschutzdienst at the LfU monitors agricultural invasions. The RP NABU coordinates citizen-science monitoring. The RP Naturpark Pfälzerwald and the Naturpark Saar-Hunsrück support cross-border conservation. The historic Mosel wine villages such as Bernkastel, Wehlen, Brauneberg, Piesport and Erden host the rare middle-Mosel terraced vineyard ecology that includes both native rare species (the Mosel apollo butterfly Parnassius apollo, the lacertine green lizard Lacerta viridis, the Mosel wall lizard Podarcis muralis) and a substantial neophyte flora of garden escapes.'
WHERE region_name = 'Rheinland-Pfalz';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Mecklenburg-Vorpommern transport detail: the Rostock Port (operated by Rostock Port GmbH) is one of the largest German Baltic-Sea ports, handling around 25 million tonnes of cargo per year. The Rostock-Trelleborg ferry to Sweden (TT-Line and Stena Line) is one of the busiest Baltic ferry routes with around 1,000 sailings per year. The Rostock-Gedser ferry to Denmark (Scandlines) runs every two hours. The Rostock cruise terminal at Warnemünde Pier 8 handles around 200,000 cruise passengers per year and is the largest German cruise port on the Baltic. The Aida Cruises (the German branch of Costa Crociere) is the largest German cruise line with around 14 ships. The Sassnitz-Mukran Port on Rügen handles ferry services to Trelleborg-Sweden, Klaipėda-Lithuania (DFDS) and the heavy-lift transports including the historic German-Soviet rail-ferry. The Wismar Port handles bulk cargo and the historic Wismar Shipyard ship repair. The Stralsund Volkswerft (now under restructuring) and the Rostock Neptun Werft (now part of Meyer Werft Papenburg) form the major MV shipbuilding cluster. The MV rail network includes the Berlin-Rostock corridor (IC and EC services, 3 hours), the Hamburg-Schwerin-Rostock corridor (ICE 2 hours 45 minutes), the Stralsund-Berlin corridor and the Stralsund-Hamburg-Cuxhaven corridor. The Müritz-Elde Wasserstraße, the Müritz-Havel-Wasserstraße connecting the Müritz to the Berlin Spree-Havel system, the Peene river from the Tollensesee to the Greifswalder Bodden, and the Warnow from Schwerin to Rostock all carry inland-waterway traffic. The Mecklenburgische Bäderbahn Molli (Bad Doberan-Heiligendamm-Kühlungsborn, 900 mm narrow-gauge steam railway operating since 1886 — the world''s oldest narrow-gauge steam railway in continuous operation) and the Rasender Roland on Rügen (Putbus-Binz-Göhren, 750 mm narrow-gauge steam since 1895) preserve regional railway heritage. The Usedomer Bäderbahn UBB runs the standard-gauge electric railway from Wolgast across the Peenebrücke to Heringsdorf and Ahlbeck on Usedom, with cross-border service to Świnoujście in Poland. The MV Autobahn network includes the A20 Ostseeautobahn from Lübeck to Stettin via Rostock-Stralsund, the A19 from Berlin to Rostock, the A24 Hamburg-Berlin, the A14 from Magdeburg currently under extension north to Schwerin (one of the slowest German Autobahn megaprojects with full completion expected after 2030), the A28 to Bremen and the A29 connections. Bundesstraßen include the B96 from Berlin via Neubrandenburg to Stralsund and Sassnitz, the B105 from Lübeck via Rostock to Stralsund, the B104 east-west, the B109 to Stettin, the B193 and the B196 to Sassnitz. The MV cycle network includes the Ostseeküsten-Radweg (EuroVelo 10), the Mecklenburgischer Seenradweg (one of Germany''s top cycling holidays), the Berlin-Kopenhagen Radweg, the Berlin-Usedom Radweg, the Hamburg-Rügen Radweg, the Stettiner Haff Radweg and the EuroVelo 7 (Norway-Malta).',
    economics = economics || ' Further Mecklenburg-Vorpommern economic detail: the MV tourism sector hosts around 8 million visitors per year (the third-highest German state after Bavaria and Baden-Württemberg) with the Baltic Sea coast, the Mecklenburg Lake District, Rügen, Usedom, Heiligendamm, the Hanseatic Old Towns of Stralsund and Wismar, the Müritz National Park and Schwerin all drawing substantial visitor flows. The TUI AG (Hannover-headquartered) has substantial MV operations including the Heiligendamm Grand Hotel resort. The Aida Cruises ships are built at Neptun Werft Rostock (now part of Meyer Werft Papenburg of Lower Saxony). The MV Werften shipyards (Wismar, Stralsund, Warnemünde) built cruise vessels until the 2022 insolvency. The Sassnitz-Mukran Port offshore-wind installation hub at Rügen serves the Baltic offshore-wind farms. The Yacht-Charter sector at Heiligenhafen, Greifswald, Stralsund and across the Mecklenburg Lake District is one of the largest German leisure-yacht markets. The Nordex SE wind-turbine manufacturer at Rostock employs around 2,000 workers building offshore-wind nacelles and rotor blades, with annual revenues of around 6 billion euros. The MV wind-energy and renewables sector is a major growth area; the Baltic 1 (Zingst), the Baltic 2 (Rügen), the EnBW Hohe See, the Wikinger and the planned Sassnitz-Mukran installation hub support the German Baltic offshore-wind cluster. The MV agricultural sector has the largest German cereal-farming area per capita and is the third-largest agricultural state by area, with wheat, rye, oilseed rape, sugar beet, maize, potatoes, oats and barley dominating, plus the Sanddorn (sea-buckthorn) industry around Rügen and Darß-Zingst. The MV food industry includes the Mecklenburgische Schweizerei dairy, the Greifenfeld dairy, the MecklenburgerKüche food processor, the Rostocker Lager, the Müritzer Lebensmittel, the Sanddorn-Storchennest distillery, the Wismarer Brauhaus and the historic Lübzer Bier (technically Mecklenburg but Carlsberg-owned). The MV defence-industry presence includes the Bundeswehr Marine-Hafenkommando Warnemünde, the German Federal Navy''s base at Rostock-Warnemünde, the MV Werften, the historic Volkswerft Stralsund, and the German Federal Police''s Bundespolizei See at Sassnitz. The MV state government is the largest single employer with around 80,000 staff. The MV universities — the Universität Rostock (founded 1419, oldest in northern Europe), the Universität Greifswald (founded 1456), the Hochschule Stralsund, Hochschule Wismar, Hochschule Neubrandenburg and Hochschule für Musik und Theater Rostock — together host around 30,000 students. The Leibniz-Institut für Plasmaforschung und Technologie INP Greifswald, the Max-Planck-Institut für Plasmaphysik IPP Greifswald (home of the Wendelstein 7-X stellarator, the most successful experimental fusion device of the stellarator type), the IOW Leibniz-Institut für Ostseeforschung at Warnemünde, the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut on the island of Riems (the federal animal-disease research institute), the Leibniz-Institut für Nutztierbiologie at Dummerstorf and the Leibniz-Institut für Atmosphärenphysik at Kühlungsborn form the research backbone.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further MV invasive-species detail: the MV state hunters'' association (Landesjagdverband Mecklenburg-Vorpommern) reports annual hunting bags of around 50,000 wild boar, 10,000 raccoons, 15,000 raccoon dogs, 25,000 fallow deer, and large populations of roe and red deer. The MV wolf population in 2024 has around 20 confirmed territorial packs (the second-largest German wolf population after Saxony), spread across the Lübtheen, Müritz, Friedländer Wiese, Anklam, Penkun-Brüssow, Schorfheide-Chorin and Rügen-Putbus areas. The MV state Lupus Office (Wolfsbeauftragter MV) coordinates monitoring. The MV African Swine Fever monitoring at the Polish border has been intensive but no confirmed wild-boar cases have been detected in MV as of 2024 (compared to thousands of cases in Saxony and Brandenburg). The Mecklenburg Vorpommern Pacific Oyster invasion of the western Baltic has been intensively studied by the AWI Bremerhaven and the IOW Warnemünde. The MV Atlantic Comb Jelly Mnemiopsis leidyi invasion has substantially affected the western Baltic plankton ecology. The MV state forestry (Landesforst MV) coordinates the largest German cervid-management programme with around 10 per cent of the state under forest cover. The MV Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut at the island of Riems (founded 1910 by Friedrich Loeffler, the discoverer of the foot-and-mouth disease virus) is the German federal animal-disease research institute, the world''s most secure biosafety-4 animal-disease facility and a leading centre for zoonotic-disease, foot-and-mouth, swine-fever, avian-flu and bluetongue research. The MV state Müritz National Park (Germany''s second-largest national park, founded 1990) and the Western Pomeranian Lagoon Area National Park (Vorpommersche Boddenlandschaft Nationalpark, founded 1990) manage the bulk of MV invasive-species monitoring. The MV state Schaalsee Biosphärenreservat (a UNESCO MAB Reserve) hosts ongoing wolf-monitoring. The historic GDR-era mink farms at the Müritz, the Schwerin and the Cottbus area contributed feral American mink populations to MV waterways. The MV Sea Eagle (Haliaeetus albicilla) recovery, the MV Crane (Grus grus) recovery and the MV Black Stork (Ciconia nigra) recovery are major native-species conservation successes. The MV state has around 350 territorial sea-eagle pairs (the highest German sea-eagle density). The MV NABU and the MV BUND coordinate citizen-science monitoring. The MV Imkerverband has been working with the LUNG on Asian-hornet response, although no confirmed nests have been detected in MV as of 2024.'
WHERE region_name = 'Mecklenburg-Vorpommern';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Niedersachsen transport detail: Hannover-Langenhagen Airport (HAJ, EDDV) handles around 6 million passengers per year. The historic Hannover Hauptbahnhof handles around 250,000 passengers per day with the Bonatz-style facade and 12 platforms. The Hannover S-Bahn (operated by Transdev, the historic Connex-affiliated Hannover S-Bahn) has eight lines totalling 385 kilometres, reaching into Hildesheim, Hameln and Celle, with the central Hannover Hauptbahnhof and the historic Großer Bahnhof junction. The Hannover Stadtbahn (üstra Hannoversche Verkehrsbetriebe) has 12 lines totalling 121 kilometres and around 220 stops, with the central tunnel network under the Kröpcke and Aegi forming the spine. The Hannoversche Verkehrsbetriebe also operates the bus network and the Maschsee ferries. The Braunschweig tram (Braunschweiger Verkehrs-GmbH) has five lines. The Oldenburg, Osnabrück, Göttingen and Lüneburg lack trams but plan returns. The GVH Großraum-Verkehr Hannover, the VBN Verkehrsverbund Bremen-Niedersachsen, the VRBN Region Braunschweig, the VOS Osnabrück, the VEJ Jadeoldenburg, the VGE Göttingen and the historic Heideland-Tarif complete the integrated-tariff network. The ICE corridors crossing Niedersachsen include the Hannover-Berlin NBS (1998 opened at 250 kph), the Hannover-Würzburg NBS (1991 opened at 280 kph with 63 tunnels), the Hannover-Hamburg corridor (currently upgraded to 230 kph), the Hannover-Köln corridor (the historic Cologne-Hannover line currently being upgraded), the new Wolfsburg Süd ICE-Bahnhof opened 1998 on the Berlin-Hannover NBS, and the planned Brussels-Aachen-Düsseldorf-Köln-Hannover-Berlin Trans-European high-speed corridor. The Hannover-Hamburg route is one of the busiest German ICE corridors with up to four trains per hour. The Hannover-Bremen route runs at 200 kph. The Niedersachsen seaport network includes Wilhelmshaven JadeWeserPort (Germany''s only deep-water container port with 18-metre draft for the world''s largest container ships), Cuxhaven (cargo and cruise traffic with the historic Cuxhavener Hafenbahn), Emden (the largest German automotive port handling Volkswagen exports — around 1.4 million cars per year), Brake (lower Weser), Nordenham (lower Weser with the Premium Aerotec Airbus A350 large-fuselage plant and the Steelwind Nordenham offshore-wind monopiles), Stade (lower Elbe), Leer (Ems), Papenburg (Ems, with the Meyer Werft cruise-ship shipyard — the largest cruise-ship builder in the world by tonnage), and Wangerooge. The Mittellandkanal (the longest German artificial waterway at 326 kilometres) connects the Rhine via the Dortmund-Ems-Kanal to the Elbe via Magdeburg. The Niedersachsen cycling routes include the Elberadweg (a top German long-distance cycling route from the Czech border via Hamburg to Cuxhaven), the Weser-Radweg, the Aller-Radweg, the Leine-Radweg, the Ems-Radweg, the Mittelland-Radweg, the Hannover-Münster-Radweg, the Nordseeküsten-Radweg (the German section of EuroVelo 12) and EuroVelo 15. The Niedersachsen Wadden Sea National Park is part of the UNESCO Wadden Sea World Heritage Site (designated 2009 jointly with Hamburg, Schleswig-Holstein, the Dutch and Danish Wadden Seas). The Niedersachsen-Ticket integrated regional fare covers all regional rail and most regional bus operations.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Niedersachsen economic detail: Volkswagen AG at Wolfsburg is by far the largest employer in Niedersachsen, with around 60,000 workers at the Wolfsburg plant alone (out of around 120,000 total VW Group employees in Niedersachsen). The Wolfsburg Autostadt customer-delivery centre and the VW corporate-museum complex attract around 2 million visitors per year. The VW Wolfsburg plant produces the VW Golf, VW Tiguan and VW Touran on the 6.5-square-kilometre Wolfsburg main site, the largest single car plant in the world by area. The VW Plant Hannover-Stöcken produces the VW Transporter T7, VW Multivan and the new ID. Buzz electric VW; VW Plant Emden produces the VW Passat, the VW Arteon and the ID.7 electric saloon; VW Plant Salzgitter produces engines and battery cells (with the new PowerCo battery-cell factory under construction); VW Plant Braunschweig produces battery systems, electric-drive units and chassis parts for the entire VW Group; VW Plant Osnabrück produces the VW T-Roc Cabriolet and Porsche Cayman bodies (the latter as a contract manufacturer for Porsche). VW Financial Services AG at Braunschweig is one of the largest German automotive-financial-services groups. TUI AG (the world''s largest leisure travel group by revenue, headquartered at Karl-Wiechert-Allee in Hannover) has annual revenues of around 16 billion euros and 60,000 employees, operating the TUI Cruises (jointly with Royal Caribbean), Marella Cruises, Hapag-Lloyd Cruises, the TUI fly airlines, the TUI Hotels & Resorts (Robinson Club, Magic Life, TUI Blue) and the TUI travel-agency network. Continental AG (the listed Hannover-headquartered tyre and automotive-supplier giant) has annual revenues of around 40 billion euros across the Continental tyre brands (Continental, Uniroyal, Semperit, General Tire, Barum), the ContiTech rubber-products division and the Continental Automotive electronics-and-systems division. Vitesco Technologies (the powertrain spin-off from Continental in 2021) is at Hannover and Regensburg. Sennheiser electronic GmbH & Co. KG (the family-owned audio-equipment maker founded 1945 at Wennebostel) is one of the world''s leading microphone and headphone manufacturers. Salzgitter AG (Salzgitter-headquartered listed steel and engineering group, the second-largest German steel producer) has the integrated steelworks at Salzgitter producing around 6 million tonnes of steel per year; the SALCOS green-steel transformation is one of the largest German hydrogen-DRI projects. Bahlsen GmbH & Co. KG (Hannover-headquartered family-owned biscuit-and-confectionery maker founded 1889) produces the iconic Leibniz biscuit. Meyer Werft GmbH & Co. KG at Papenburg on the Ems is one of the largest cruise-ship builders in the world. Premium Aerotec, Sartorius AG at Göttingen, Symrise AG at Holzminden, Brötje Heating, Wolters Brauerei and the JadeWeserPort logistics cluster complete the major regional employers. The Hannover Messe (the world''s largest industrial trade fair), the CeBIT (the world''s largest IT trade fair, ran in Hannover from 1986 to 2018), the Agritechnica (the world''s largest agricultural-machinery fair), the EuroTier livestock-equipment fair, the IAA Mobility (ran in Hannover from 1961 to 2019 before moving to Munich), the Hannover Light Festival, and the Hannover Trade and Industry Fair complete the trade-fair complex on the 466,100-square-metre Messe Hannover. The Niedersachsen agricultural sector is the largest in Germany by output, with milk, beef, hops (Hallertau supply), barley, wheat, beer, asparagus and the Cloppenburg-Vechta-Wallenhorst pork-and-poultry cluster (the highest pig-and-poultry densities in Europe). The Wümme-Renaturierung and the Drömling beaver reintroductions are major conservation-and-tourism investments.',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Niedersachsen invasive-species detail: the Niedersächsisches Landesamt für Verbraucherschutz und Lebensmittelsicherheit (LAVES) at Hannover-Wülfel coordinates the state Neozoa register. The Niedersachsen wolf population in 2024 has around 50 confirmed territorial packs (the third-highest after Saxony and Brandenburg), with the famous Lüneburger Heide and Bergen-Belsen training-ground core areas. The Niedersachsen wild-boar African Swine Fever readiness includes the federal-state fencing along the Polish border (Brandenburg) and intensive Niedersachsen culling programmes. The Niedersachsen state hunters'' association (Niedersächsischer Jägerverband) reports annual hunting bags of around 70,000 wild boar, 35,000 raccoons, 12,000 raccoon dogs and 50,000 fallow deer. The Niedersachsen state hosts the largest Asian-Hornet expansion-front in northern Germany, with the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut Braunschweig and the LWK Niedersachsen coordinating monitoring. The Niedersachsen Solling forest park hosts ongoing lynx (Lynx lynx) reintroduction. The historic Lüneburger Heide WildPark Lüneburger Heide at Nindorf hosts captive populations of European bison, brown bear, wolf, lynx, wildcat, otter and beaver — an important conservation-education facility. The Niedersachsen Wadden Sea National Park is part of the UNESCO Wadden Sea World Heritage Site (designated 2009) and supports the most-extensive marine-invasion monitoring in Germany alongside the AWI Bremerhaven. The Niedersachsen Pacific Oyster invasion of the Wadden Sea has substantially altered the intertidal landscape by forming massive reefs on former mussel beds. The Niedersachsen state pond turtle (Emys orbicularis) reintroduction in the Drömling biosphere reserve, the Niedersachsen state beaver population recovery (around 800 confirmed animals from the historic Bayerischer Bund Naturschutz Bayerischer Wald and the Brandenburg-Sachsen-Anhalt source populations), the Niedersachsen state crane (Grus grus) population, and the Niedersachsen state white-tailed sea eagle (Haliaeetus albicilla) recovery are major native-species conservation successes. The Niedersachsen ash dieback (Hymenoscyphus fraxineus from East Asia, the deadly fungal disease that has decimated European ash since the 1990s) is a major Niedersachsen forest-pathology concern. The Niedersachsen oak processionary moth (Thaumetopoea processionea), although technically native to Mediterranean Europe but historically rare in Niedersachsen, has expanded dramatically with climate change and has prompted intensive arboricultural management on Niedersachsen oak avenues. The Niedersachsen Solling Beaver and the Niedersachsen Drömling biosphere reserve host the largest native-species recovery programmes. The Niedersachsen NABU and BUND coordinate citizen-science monitoring; the Tierärztliche Hochschule Hannover (one of Germany''s leading veterinary schools) and the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut at Riems (although technically Mecklenburg-Vorpommern) cooperate on Niedersachsen zoonotic-disease research.'
WHERE region_name = 'Niedersachsen';

UPDATE demo.german_regions SET
    transportation = transportation || ' Further Nordrhein-Westfalen transport detail: the Cologne Hauptbahnhof (with its iconic position immediately beside the Cathedral and the Hohenzollernbrücke) is one of the busiest railway stations in Europe with around 250,000 passengers per day across 11 platforms. It is the terminus of the Cologne-Frankfurt high-speed line (the Köln-Rhein/Main Schnellfahrstrecke opened 2002 at 300 kph with the steepest high-speed grade in Europe at 40 ‰ on the Westerwald), the Cologne-Brussels Eurostar/Thalys service (the Eurostar Group after the 2024 Thalys-Eurostar merger), the Cologne-Frankfurt-Strasbourg-Paris-Est ICE/TGV service, the Cologne-Amsterdam ICE service via the Dutch HSL-Zuid, the Cologne-Stuttgart-Munich ICE/IC corridor, the Cologne-Hannover-Berlin ICE corridor, and the Cologne-Hamburg ICE. The Cologne Messe/Deutz station on the other side of the Hohenzollernbrücke handles overflow ICE traffic. Düsseldorf Hauptbahnhof (opened 1936) handles the Hannover-Düsseldorf-Mainz and Berlin-Düsseldorf corridors. Other major NRW rail nodes are Dortmund Hauptbahnhof, Essen Hauptbahnhof, Duisburg Hauptbahnhof, Aachen Hauptbahnhof, Münster Hauptbahnhof, Bielefeld Hauptbahnhof, Bochum Hauptbahnhof, Bonn Hauptbahnhof, Krefeld, Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof and Hamm (Westfalen). The S-Bahn Rhein-Ruhr (the largest German S-Bahn system by length covering NRW from Aachen to Wuppertal to Münster) has around 700 kilometres on 20 lines. The S-Bahn Köln, the S-Bahn Hannover (extending across the NRW border) and the S-Bahn Rhein-Sieg complete the integrated network. The Cologne Stadtbahn (operated by KVB Kölner Verkehrs-Betriebe) is a converted tramway with 12 lines on 200 kilometres. The Düsseldorf Stadtbahn (operated by Rheinbahn) has 9 lines. The Bochum-Gelsenkirchen-Herne-Recklinghausen Stadtbahn (BOGESTRA), the Essen-Mülheim Stadtbahn (EVAG), the Duisburg-Mülheim Stadtbahn, the Krefeld Stadtbahn, the Bonn Stadtbahn and the Bielefeld Stadtbahn are integrated through the VRR Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Ruhr (the largest German transport association with 7.7 million inhabitants and 13,000 square kilometres), the AVV Verkehrsverbund Aachen-Maastricht, the NVV Nordhessen and the VRS Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Sieg. The Wuppertaler Schwebebahn (the suspended monorail of 1901 by Eugen Langen) is the world''s oldest still-operating suspension railway, running 13.3 kilometres along the Wupper river between Vohwinkel and Oberbarmen with 20 stops. The Port of Duisburg (Duisport, formed at the confluence of the Rhine and Ruhr) is the largest inland port in the world, handling around 130 million tonnes of cargo per year (more than the seaports of Hamburg or Bremerhaven by tonnage). The Port of Cologne (RheinCargo, jointly with Düsseldorf) handles around 12 million tonnes. The Düsseldorf inland port handles bulk and container for the chemical industry. Other inland ports include Krefeld, Bonn, Wesel, Emmerich, Datteln, Hamm, Münster and the Hammer-Hafen on the Lippe. The Rhine, the Ruhr, the Lippe and the Wesel-Datteln-Kanal/Dortmund-Ems-Kanal form the navigable network. The NRW Autobahn network is the densest in Germany; the historic A1, A2, A3, A4, A40, A42, A43, A44, A45, A52, A57, A59 and A555 (Cologne-Bonn, the first German Autobahn opened 1932 as Reichsstraße 25, the world''s first non-Reichsfahrtraße motorway). Cycling: the EuroVelo 15 Rhine Cycle Route, the Vennbahn cross-border cycle path, the 100-Schlösser-Route, the Maas-Rhein-Radweg, the Ruhrtal-Radweg and the Erft-Radweg.',
    economics = economics || ' Further Nordrhein-Westfalen economic detail: NRW has the largest regional GDP among the German Bundesländer at around 750 billion euros, accounting for around 20 per cent of total German GDP, with 35 of the 100 largest German companies headquartered in NRW. The Ruhr Coal-and-Steel cluster (historic European industrial heartland 1850s-1980s) has been largely transformed into a service-and-research economy through the 30-year Strukturwandel programme. The Ruhr coal-mining industry completely closed in December 2018 with the final Zeche Prosper-Haniel at Bottrop. The thyssenkrupp AG Essen corporate headquarters at the Berthold-Beitz-Boulevard employs around 4,500 corporate staff. The thyssenkrupp Stahlwerke Duisburg-Bruckhausen, Duisburg-Hamborn and Duisburg-Hüttenheim integrated steel-and-coke plants produce around 11 million tonnes of steel per year. The RWE AG Essen utility headquarters employs around 5,000 corporate staff. The E.ON SE corporate headquarters at the Brüsseler Platz in Essen employs around 3,500 corporate staff. The Henkel AG Düsseldorf corporate headquarters at the Henkelstraße employs around 8,000 staff. The Bayer AG Leverkusen corporate headquarters at the Bayer Cross campus employs around 9,000 corporate staff and 18,000 production staff. The Currenta Chempark Leverkusen operates 60 square kilometres of integrated chemical-industrial site. The Bonner Bundeskanzleramt der Friedensbewegung, the Bonn UN-Campus (around 1,000 UN staff including the UNFCCC and UNV), the BfArM, the BSI Bonn, the BNetzA Bonn, the Bundesministerien at Bonn, the Bundeszentrale für gesundheitliche Aufklärung (BZgA), the Wissenschaftsrat (the German Council of Science and Humanities), the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD), the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation, the Friedrich Ebert Foundation (Bonn branch) and many other federal agencies still host around 8,000 federal employees at Bonn after the Bonn-Berlin Treaty of 1994. The Cologne advertising-cluster includes the WDR Westdeutscher Rundfunk headquarters at Wallrafplatz (one of the largest German public broadcasters), Deutsche Welle Bonn, Bertelsmann RTL Cologne, the historic Adolf-Grimme-Institut Marl, and the modern Cologne creative-industries cluster around the Mediapark. The NRW media-cluster annual revenue is around 14 billion euros, the largest German regional creative-industries cluster. Ford-Werke GmbH at Cologne-Niehl operates Germany''s second-largest car plant (after VW Wolfsburg), producing the Ford Fiesta until 2023 and now transitioning to the Ford E-Tourneo Custom and Ford Explorer EV with around 13,000 workers. Lufthansa AG corporate registered office and the Lufthansa Group Headquarters Building are at Cologne. Deutsche Telekom AG (the largest European telecommunications operator) at Bonn has around 200,000 employees globally and revenues of around 120 billion euros. Deutsche Post DHL Group (the world''s largest logistics company) at Bonn (Charles-de-Gaulle-Straße in the historic Post Tower by Helmut Jahn). DHL is the global express subsidiary, operating the largest cargo airline in the world by tonnage. Other major NRW corporates include Henkel (Düsseldorf), L''Oréal Germany (Düsseldorf), Vodafone Germany (Düsseldorf), METRO AG (Düsseldorf), Rheinmetall AG (Düsseldorf, the listed defence and automotive supplier producing the Leopard 2 tank gun, the Puma IFV, the GTK Boxer and the PzH 2000 howitzer), Trivago N.V. (Düsseldorf), Uniper SE (the natural-gas utility), Aldi Süd (Mülheim an der Ruhr), Aldi Nord (Essen), Hochtief AG (Essen, the listed construction giant), Brenntag SE (Essen, the chemical distributor), Schenker AG (DB Schenker), Bayer AG (Leverkusen), Lanxess AG (Cologne, the listed specialty chemicals spin-off from Bayer in 2004), Covestro AG (Leverkusen, the polymer-materials spin-off from Bayer in 2015, now part of Adnoc since 2024 acquisition), Vorwerk (Wuppertal, the Thermomix maker), Bertelsmann SE (Gütersloh, the largest privately owned media group in Europe with 17 billion euros annual revenues), Miele (Gütersloh), Claas (Harsewinkel, agricultural machinery), Wilkhahn (Bad Münder), and Tönnies Lebensmittel (Rheda-Wiedenbrück, the largest German meat processor).',
    introduced_species = introduced_species || ' Further Nordrhein-Westfalen invasive-species detail: the LANUV NRW (Landesamt für Natur, Umwelt und Verbraucherschutz NRW) at Recklinghausen is the largest German state environmental authority by staff (around 1,800). The NRW raccoon hunting bag in 2022 reached over 50,000, the highest of any German Land. The NRW Asian-Hornet expansion has been the most rapid in Germany since the 2014 first German breeding record at Aachen-Waldfeucht. The NRW Imkerverband and the LANUV jointly maintain the Asiatische-Hornisse-Meldeportal NRW citizen-reporting platform. The Cologne and Düsseldorf ring-necked parakeet populations are among the largest in Europe, with the Düsseldorf Hofgarten roost hosting several thousand Halsbandsittiche at dusk in winter — a major Düsseldorf urban-wildlife spectacle. The NRW Egyptian goose population is the largest in Germany. The NRW wild-boar urban population is substantial across the Eifel, the Sauerland, and the Bergisches Land, with Cologne and Düsseldorf reporting regular wild-boar encounters in suburban gardens. The NRW Schermbeck Wolfsfamilie (the Schermbeck wolf pack near Wesel) has been a media flashpoint for livestock-predation incidents; the Schermbeck wolf monitoring by the LANUV has been intensive since 2018. The NRW Eifel National Park (founded 2004, the first national park in NRW) hosts substantial native-species conservation programmes including the European wildcat, the lynx (reintroduced 2024), the European pond turtle (reintroduced 2018), and the European mink (planned future reintroduction). The historic Düsseldorf-Kaiserwerth, the Cologne Stadtwald, the Bonn Rheinaue and the Wuppertal Botanischer Garten host distinctive invasive-flora communities. The Bonn Rheinaue is one of the largest German urban-rewilding sites. The Cologne Lentpark, the Düsseldorf Volksgarten and the Bonn Hofgarten host long-term invasive-species monitoring by the local NABU and BUND chapters. The NRW Asian Longhorned Beetle (Anoplophora glabripennis) was recorded multiple times in the 2010s through container-port arrivals in Duisburg and Cologne; emergency containment programmes felled hundreds of trees but the outbreaks have been declared eradicated. The NRW emerald ash borer (Agrilus planipennis) monitoring traps are deployed by the JKI Julius Kühn-Institut Münster at the major NRW container-port logistics centres. The NRW NABU, BUND and Schmetterlinge-NRW citizen-science platforms support comprehensive monitoring. The NRW Köln-Bonn DLR has substantial environmental-monitoring satellite operations. The historic NRW Ruhrgebiet brownfields (the Industriedenkmäler at the Zeche Zollverein UNESCO site, the Landschaftspark Duisburg-Nord, the Gasometer Oberhausen, the Halde Hoheward and the historic Bergehalden) host distinctive ruderal-invasive vegetation communities that have attracted ecological research from the universities of Bochum, Duisburg-Essen and Dortmund.'
